<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0713,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Releases 46 Dissidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with dissidents released, official
comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government released 46 political
prisoners including a prominent dissident Thursday as part of
President Roh Tae-woo's efforts to promote democracy, the Justice
Ministry said.
   Among those freed was Kim Keun-tae, who recently was awarded the
Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights. He was sentenced in 1986
to five years imprisonment for inciting unrest. International human
rights groups campaigned for his release.
   The political prisoners were paroled from prisons throughout the
country along with 453 common criminals, the ministry said.
   ``The political offenders were released in line with the
government's continuing efforts to promote democracy in an
atmosphere of national harmony,'' it said in a statement.
   The statement said Kim and 45 other political prisoners were
granted parole because they had repented for what they had done and
promised not to violate the law again.
   Justice Ministry officials indicated the government would free
more political prisoners in the future if they ``are eligible for
parole and show repentance.''
   Despite the government's announcement Wednesday that it would
release the prisoners, opposition leaders charged that many more
dissidents remained behind bars.
   ``How can we talk about reconciliation and political development
while keeping in prison those patriots, numbering more than 600,
who fought for democracy?'' opposition leader Kim Dae-jung told the
National Assembly.
   Kim Dae-jung also urged the government to punish former
President Chun Doo-hwan and his family for alleged corruption and
confiscate their property.
   He demanded the government meet its promise of full democracy
and accused President Roh Tae-woo of failing to carry out some
promised reforms.
   Some opposition groups claim that 1,000 people are behind bars
because of their political beliefs or opposition to the government.
The government contends jailed dissidents committed violent crimes
or broke national seurity laws.
   About 20 relatives of prisoners demonstrated Wednesday outside
the headquarters of the governing Democratic Justice Party to
demand the release of all prisoners. Police arrested and held the
protesters, but later released them.
   Riot police sealed off roads leading to Seoul's Roman Catholic
cathedral Wednesday and stopped dissidents trying to take part in a
march to Chun's home in western Seoul. A handful of people tried to
attend the rally but were blocked by police.
   The Korean news agency, Yonhap, said about 9,000 riot police
were deployed across the capital to stop the march. About 20
students who sneaked past police lines hurled firebombs and rocks
at police from the cathedral compound, but authorities did not
respond.
   ``Punish Chun!'' and ``Drive out Yankees!'' the students
shouted, but passersby ignored the calls or urged protesters not to
use violence.
   Chun, who stepped down in February after a seven-year term, has
been accused of corruption and brutality against dissidents during
his authoritarian administration.
   Justice Ministry officials said Thursday's release left only 81
political offenders in prison on anti-government charges. There
also are about 480 people awaiting trial for political offenses,
they said.
   Included in the release were 11 South Koreans from Japan charged
with spying for North Korea. The 11, who had resided in Japan, were
arrested while visiting Seoul and other parts of the country in the
late 1970s.
   The release coincided with the first anniversary of the ``grand
declaration for democracy'' by President Roh on June 29, 1987. The
declaration accepted most opposition demands for sweeping
democratic reforms.
   Roh's declaration, issued in the midst of nationwide
anti-government demonstrations, paved the way for the country to
adopt a new constitution and hold the first direct presidential
elections in 16 years.
   Roh, running as the government candidate, beat the divided
opposition in the Dec. 16 elections. He then pledged to bring full
democracy to South Korea.
</TEXT>
