<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DublinMayor     06-29 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dublin Mayor,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Mayor In A Thousand For Dublin's Millennium Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Of the gifts Dublin gave itself for its
1,000th birthday, few have provided as much excitement as the lord
mayor, a woman of great heart who fills the old city with
enthusiasm, charm and grace.
   So successful was Carmencita Hederman in making the Millennium
Year a hit that, although her one-year term ends July 4, an opinion
poll in The Irish Times found 71 percent of Dubliners want her to
have a second.
   Dublin's city elders, the paper said, ``should be encouraged
that such strong views are held about who should be lord mayor; in
most years the majority of citizens couldn't care less.''
   She is a member of the Dublin City Council and its 52 members
choose the mayor, whose duties are largely ceremonial. Mrs.
Hederman, 48, was the first woman to win the office on her own; two
who preceded her were widows of lord mayors.
   The city charter makes no allowance for gender, so she has to be
called lord mayor. Her husband Billy, a surgeon, ``is the first man
to be called lady mayoress,'' says Mrs. Hederman, who trained as a
linguist in Europe and has five children.
   Her married name is a 17th century Anglicizing of an Irish word
meaning ``lightfooted.'' Carmencita acknowledges Spanish ancestry
and her maiden name is Callaghan.
   Mrs. Hederman has been a Dublin councilor for 14 years, always
running as an independent because, she says, ``I like to paddle my
own canoe.''
   She would like a second term, in order ``to see the Millennium
through.'' Her chance appears slim but she has not given up,
declaring to the Irish Times last month: ``All I can say is that if
I do go down, I will go down fighting.''
   The lord mayor has used her entree with the affluent to enlist
commercial sponsors for Millennium events, thus limiting the burden
on taxpayers. Her informal style, whether cycling to an appointment
or chatting with a street crowd, has won the trust of all classes.
   Her impact was felt strongly throughout Ireland in November,
when a bomb planted by the Irish Republican Army killed 12
Protestants at a war memorial service in the Northern Ireland town
of Enniskillen.
   She opened a condolence book that attracted tens of thousands of
signatures. When a Dublin rabbi suggested she take the books to
Enniskillen, she agreed without hesitation.
   ``All these people had come in (to sign), and it was no good
just sort of putting books up on the shelf and saying thanks for
coming,'' she said in an interview. ``We had to do something that
made them feel that their expression of sympathy was reaching its
destination.''
   Irish hearts everywhere were touched by the woman, too choked to
make a speech when she comforted the bereaved of Enniskillen, and
she may have contributed to easing the suspicion Northern Ireland
Protestants have of Roman Catholics in the south.
   Skeptics questioned the wisdom of throwing a year-long birthday
party when the country was in dire economic trouble, and Mrs.
Hederman admits it got off to ``a sluggish start.'' Cynics said
there was no certainty 988 was the year the Vikings founded the
city and suggested it was all a stunt for tourists.
   Mrs. Hederman said her original wish was to delay the
celebration for a year to allow more planning, but added: ``I'm
glad now that we didn't because I think that the Irish are better
at getting things going in a hurry. Our temperament seems to like
the sort of lively rush to boats.''
   So far, the Millennium has given Dublin literary festivals,
regattas, horse races, other sporting events and street theater.
Still to come are fireworks, balloons and a gigantic birthday cake.
   A crash cleanup has scrubbed the grime off such landmarks as the
Post Office, where the 1916 Easter Rising began. A creamy new coat
of paint gleams on the Mansion House, the lord mayor's official
residence.
   ``I think the city and country were at a turning point,'' Mrs.
Hederman said. With record unemployment and tax levels ``we'd
possibly reached an all-time low and the graph was starting to go
up, and so the Millennium has come at a good time.''
   And so, say her fans, has her mayoral term.
   ``In the nicest possible way, she has become the Queen of
Dublin,'' Kevin B. Nowlan, a history professor at University
College, Dublin, said in an interview.
   ``In many ways Irish public life is short of colorful people,
and she combines tremendous intelligence, integrity and great
personal grace.''
</TEXT>
