<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     06-29 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lakers-Pistons Lead Ratings, but Not Enough for CBS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Lakers won with depth and
experience, but NBC prevailed with reruns last week in the A.C.
Nielsen Co. ratings.
   The Lakers' 108-105 victory over the Detroit Pistons was a
runaway winner in the Nielsen survey, with a 21.2 average rating.
The next-best program, NBC's ``Night Court,'' was far behind at
17.1.
   However, NBC placed seven reruns in the top 10 to win the weekly
race with an average rating of 12.1. CBS, also benefiting from a
third-place finish for a first-run ``60 Minutes,'' was second at
11.3. ABC lagged at 8.8.
   For the 40 weeks of the season, NBC's average is 15.4, followed
by CBS with 13.0 and ABC with 12.9.
   A rating point equals 886,000 homes with television.
   The rest of the week's top 10 included a Perry Mason movie,
``The Cosby Show'' and ``Cheers'' on NBC, ``Murder She Wrote'' on
CBS and ``Different World,'' ``Silent Witness'' and ``Golden
Girls'' on NBC.
   ABC's highest-rated show was ``Head of the Class,'' tied with
NBC's ``Amen'' in 16th place.
   The rating for Tuesday night's seventh game of the
Lakers-Pistons series beat the previous mark of 19.3 for the final
game of the 1984 series between the Lakers and the Boston Celtics,
said Michael Eisenberg, director of research at CBS.
   The seven-game series this year, however, averaged half a point
lower than the 15.9 average for the Celtics-Lakers series in 1987,
Eisenberg said.
   CBS had the top-rated news program for the week with an average
rating of 9.2. NBC had 8.2 and ABC 8.1. ABC led the second-quarter
ratings, however, with an average of 9.5, followed by CBS at 9.3
and NBC at 8.5.
</TEXT>
