<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Miniature Animals,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smurf, Smurfette, Moo Moo Become Outlaws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smurf the miniature horse, his
girlfriend Smurfette and tiny Moo Moo the cow are farm animals, not
pets, a court decided in fining the owner $189 for harboring
livestock.
   ``You call this a farm animal?'' asked Calvin Cooledge Lynn of
Sacramento, gesturing to his 85-pound Smurf. ``My whole three
animals wouldn't make up half a horse. Man has bred these horses
down for house pets like they do poodles.''
   But Municipal Court Commissioner William Brigance on Tuesday
found the 63-year-old Lynn guilty of three counts of harboring
livestock in areas zoned for human habitation.
   City Animal Control Director Ruben Mora testified during the
20-minute trial that without the ordinance, there would be ``goats,
roosters, chickens, rabbits and ducks. There would be livestock all
over the city.''
   Lynn offered the signatures of 68 neighbors who said Smurf,
24-inch-tall Smurfette and 28-inch-tall Moo Moo are no bother.
``The horses don't bark, they don't bite, they don't hurt nobody,''
Lynn said.
