<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--`Cinderella' Video,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney To Release `Cinderella' on Video</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Cinderella,'' the 38-year-old Walt
Disney movie long considered one of the studio's crown jewels, will
be released on videotape for sale this fall.
   The release will be available at video stores on Oct. 4, or
about three weeks earlier than Disney rival MCA's planned release
of ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial'' home video.
   ``Cinderella'' will be priced at $26.99 initially, with a price
increase to $29.95 on Dec. 1, and availability ending on April 30,
1989, Disney announced Tuesday. Consumers can order the cassette at
stores beginning July 12.
   ``E.T.'' will be released Oct. 27 at a retail price of $24.95.
   ``Cinderella,'' an adaptation of the ancient story about a
beautiful scullery maid's triumph over her wicked stepsisters, was
first released in 1950. The movie features such songs as ``Bibbidi
Bobbidi Boo'' and ``A Dream Is A Wish Your Heart Makes'' by Mack
David, Jerry Livingston and Al Hoffman.
