<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-ReservationWater     06-29 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Reservation Water,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precious Water in Parched North Dakota</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Indians, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT BERTHOLD INDIAN RESERVATION, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every sweltering
day, folks carrying buckets, thermoses and jugs turn on the outside
tap at the EZ Stop convenience store and fill up.
   To Leone Johnson, providing drinking water to her customers and
neighbors is no big deal. To many living on the Fort Berthold
reservation, Indian and non-Indian, it is a gesture of friendship
deeply appreciated.
   Mrs. Johnson's store gets city water that's been filtered and
chlorinated. Many of the nearby wells, the only reliable source of
water for thousands in northwestern North Dakota, yield brown water
full of salt and foul-tasting minerals.
   ``Chemically, the well water tests safe to drink, but it tastes
almost as bad as it looks,'' said Rich Schilf, natural resources
director of the Three Affiliated Tribes.
   Holding up a jug containing water the color of crude oil, Schilf
said, ``One of my co-workers brought this in from his house this
morning and dared me to drink it. I decided to pass.
   ``Most of the groundwater on the reservation is terrible, full
of sodium,'' added Schilf, who's tried for years to get a
long-promised, federally funded water system installed on the
reservation. ``Almost everybody hauls their drinking water if
they're not hooked up to the New Town system.''
   New Town, the reservation's population center, with 1,300
residents, has doubled its pumping since drought settled on this
high, parched prairie two months ago.
   ``We're pumping 600,000 gallons a day to try and meet the
demand,'' said Bill Folven at the treatment plant. Despite New
Town's being within sight of a huge Missouri River reservoir, the
town gets its drinking water from three deep wells.
   The water plant sells the precious commodity by the
quarter-dollar.
   ``You get 100 gallons for each quarter,'' said Folven, who
empties the coin box and says these days it's usually full.
   Many people on the reservation carry big tanks on their pickup
trucks. They drive to the plant, park under a pipe jutting from the
concrete block building, put quarters in the meter, press a button
and stand back as the water runs.
   Elmer Rambel has run a commercial water delivery service around
New Town for years.
   ``Usually Elmer gets his water from a spring, but his filtration
system broke so he's buying it from the city and hauling it to
us,'' said Myrna Jacobs, a mother of five who deals in real estate
with the Three Affiliated Tribes.
   ``Usually I pay $25 for 2,200 gallons to be delivered to our
cistern, but two weeks ago Elmer had to raise his price to $31,''
she said. ``Despite trying to be real careful and conserve water, I
had to have two truckloads of water delivered to the house last
month and I'm sure it will be the same for June.''
   Mrs. Johnson says she gives her water away in small quantities
``because I've lived here all my life and the people who need my
water to drink are neighbors and friends and customers whose
business I appreciate.''
   She says it doesn't matter how much higher her water bill will
run.
   ``It's something I can do that helps,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-CentralAmerica Bjt   06-29 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Central America, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central America Decisions to Await Completion of Shultz Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman concedes that
efforts to pry concessions from Nicaragua's Sandinista government
have stalled, and the administration's next step won't be decided
until Secretary of State George Shultz returns from Central America.
   Amid increasing reports that Contra rebel troops are returning
to base camps, and with no new peace talks scheduled, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was asked Tuesday whether Reagan had
decided to submit a new aid package to Congress.
   ``We will not have any judgment on the package until sometime
after'' Shultz returns from the region on Friday, Fitzwater said,
``and we don't have a specific schedule, even on that.''
   Shultz was leaving today on a trip that will take him to Costa
Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
   Shultz told congressional leaders on Tuesday that his trip has
the primary purpose of ``shoring up'' the four democracies in the
region by demonstrating long-term U.S. support, according to
participants in the meeting.
   Republican congressional leaders met with Reagan, but House GOP
Leader Bob Michel of Illinois said the president gave no hint of
his plans. He said the issue of another Contra aid package did not
come up.
   ``I'm sure that the administration's position will not be
formulated until after Secretary Shultz makes his trip to Central
America and comes back again with some answers,'' Michel said.
   Asked to assess the status of Reagan administration efforts to
force changes in Nicaragua, Michel replied, ``Well, it's
stalemated, there's no question about that.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged that the
administration's efforts have been thrown off stride.
   ``The administration and the president are certainly concerned
that we've not made any progress in the peace talks,'' he said.
``The question before us is where to go. I suppose stalemated is a
good word in that sense.''
   Ambassador Max Kampelman, whom Reagan reassigned briefly from
U.S.-Soviet arms talks to provide fresh diplomatic impetus to the
Central America policy, joined Shultz in briefing House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, and other members of Congress on Tuesday morning.
   Asked what Kampelman learned from the leaders of other Central
American nations about any new U.S. military moves, Michel said,
``they would not like to see a resumption of the war or military
hostilities, but they thought probably economic reprisals or
pressure'' were needed to bring about democratic reforms in
Nicaragua.
   But, he added, ``then you get into real trouble'' if sanctions
hurt the common people without forcing governmental changes.
   Contra leaders abandoned the peace talks in Managua, which had
been called for under the Central American peace plan.
   A cease-fire has been extended until June 30, but the Contras
have said they do not want to return to any negotiations in
Managua, saying they felt intimidated by the Sandinistas there.
Rebel leaders said the Sandinistas virtually demanded that the
resistance lay down its arms, without any guarantees for democratic
reform.
   Michel said that in the Capitol Hill meeting, Wright ``did
respond that, at some time down the road here, he would honor a
request of the president for whatever move we might want to make.''
   But, he said, ``If I were asked a question, you know, is it
possible to get a military package through the House right now, I
would have to be very negative on that at the moment.''
   Wright, describing the Shultz meeting, said the secretary ``says
what he really wants to do is to shore up and reinforce our
commitment to the success of the four democratic countries in the
region.''
   The speaker called the discussion a sign of a ``shift in
emphasis'' by the administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Aircraft Bjt   06-29 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Aircraft, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Uses FBI Plane 40 Times, Won't Say Why</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators have learned that
Attorney General Edwin Meese III is a frequent flier on FBI
executive aircraft, but the bureau won't say where he goes or what
he does.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., who is directing an inquiry into
Meese's use of FBI aircraft, says the secrecy raises concern that
the administration may be trying ``to keep embarrassing information
from public view.''
   English also says that from what he's learned so far, it appears
at least some of Meese's travel may have violated President
Reagan's mandate to fly on commercial airlines when it is cheaper
for taxpayers.
   At English's request, the General Accounting Office, the
investigative wing of Congress, asked the FBI to supply flight logs
showing where its aircraft had flown and who had been aboard.
   The request was part of a larger review by the English-chaired
Government Operations subcommittee on government information,
justice and agriculture to determine whether the VIP aircraft owned
by various federal agencies could be put to better use in the war
on drugs.
   Instead of the FBI aircraft logs, GAO was given a summary that
provided details about aircraft use by FBI and other Justice
Department officials but only dates and the notation ``USAG'' for
Meese.
   The entire document was stamped ``classified,'' keeping it from
public view.
   The report showed that between June 3, 1986, and May 11, 1987,
Meese used an FBI aircraft 40 times, compared to 37 trips for all
other FBI and Justice officials, according to a committee staffer
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   During this same period, FBI Director William Webster used the
aircraft only six times, one of them a joint trip with Meese,
according to the staffer.
   Patrick Korten, Meese's spokesman, said there were no
improprieties in the attorney general's travels but he would not
comment on why details of the trips are being withheld from
Congress and the public. FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer said the
bureau had no comment.
   English, who has asked the GAO to make another attempt to get
details of Meese's travels, said he has ``serious doubts'' that
classifying all information about the aircraft's use meets the test
of protecting U.S. national defense or foreign policy interests.
   ``The questionable use of the classification system to protect
information relating to the attorney general raises a concern that
classification is being used to keep embarrassing information from
public view,'' he said.
   The committee staffer said the FBI is refusing even to reveal
the aircraft's make and model. However, a separate committee source
said documents indicated that most, if not all, of the trips were
made on the bureau's Sabreliner, a twin-engine executive jet made
by Rockwell.
   The use of such government aircraft is governed by Circular
A-126, an Oct. 5, 1983, White House policy statement that prohibits
use of VIP airplanes when cheaper commercial transportation is
available.
   The circular requires that when an agency uses one of its
aircraft to carry passengers, it must file a written justification
showing that the cost does not exceed the price of flying
commercial.
   English said that ``it is not at all clear that the attorney
general's use of the aircraft conforms to federal regulations. ...
It appears likely that some of the attorney general's travel
utilizing the FBI aircraft could have been accomplished more
economically on commercial airlines.
   ``It does not appear that the Department of Justice has complied
with Circular A-126 in regards to the use of the FBI aircraft by
the attorney general,'' he said.
   Korten said that ``Mr. Edwards is wrong when he suggests that
the attorney general may have violated applicable orders. Whenever
Mr. Meese travels, it is for reasons that comply with the
applicable order.''
   Asked about Meese using the aircraft more than the FBI, Korten
said, ``I don't have anything on that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-MexicoRelations Bjt   06-29 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Mexico Relations, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Cross-Border Relations, Never Smooth, Now Worse</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. relations with Mexico are never
harmonious even in the best of times and a recent episode involving
Mexico's handling of a Puerto Rican separatist wanted by the United
States is bound to deepen mutual distrust.
   Mexico ignored a U.S. request for the extradition of William
Morales, 37, and instead granted him early release last Friday from
an eight-year prison term. He was then deported to Cuba.
   Mexico views Morales as a man who was persecuted in the United
States for his political views. The United States sees him as a
terrorist and says he was involved in more than 50 bombings in the
U.S. that resulted in widespread death and injury.
   Morales had been sentenced to more than 100 years in prison but
escaped from U.S. custody in 1979. He fled to Mexico where, four
years later, he was convicted in the killing of a police officer.
   Despite strong U.S. interest in the case, Mexico did not
formally notify American officials of Morales' release and
deportation until five days after his arrival in Havana, safely
beyond the reach of U.S. authorities.
   The U.S. ambassador to Mexico, Charles Pilliod, has been
recalled to Washington for consultations but it seems unlikely the
administration will take significant retaliatory action against
Mexico.
   The main argument against economic sanctions is that they harm
the United States as much as Mexico by increasing the flow of
undocumented aliens. The administration's options appear to be
limited.
   A key role in the Morales case apparently was played by Foreign
Secretary Bernardo Sepulveda. It was he who formally rejected the
U.S. extradition request, overriding a ruling last December by a
Mexico City judge.
   Sepulveda ranks as perhaps the State Department's most disliked
foreign minister. One official said Sepulveda and Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams have a ``shoot on sight''
relationship.
   Sepulveda is not a favorite of Secretary of State George P.
Shultz either. At one point several years ago, Shultz's aides
considered contriving an excuse for Shultz to back out of a
scheduled meeting with Sepulveda to spare him what promised to be
an unpleasant encounter. But Shultz went ahead with the meeting
anyway.
   Much of the U.S.-Mexican hostility is based on Mexico's support
for Nicaragua's leftist government and, to a lesser extent, the
rebel movement in El Salvador. Mexico and Cuba, and more recently
Panama, are Nicaragua's strongest supporters in the hemisphere.
   Sepulveda is described here as an advocate of selling oil to
Nicaragua at concessional rates even though Nicaragua has a
reputation as a poor credit risk.
   This has put Sepulveda at odds with Mexican ministries
responsible for economic matters. American officials say that on
two occasions, vessels carrying Mexican oil to Nicaragua were
called home before reaching their destination. On both occasions,
Sepulveda was overruled by President Miguel de la Madrid's
financial advisers.
   Sepulveda has maintained that the United States made a big
mistake by supporting an armed insurrection against the Sandinista
government. He has said cooperation with Nicaragua would make it
more likely to pursue moderate policies. He views with disdain
President Reagan's assertion that failure to oppose the Sandinistas
eventually could raise the prospect of a leftist uprising in Mexico
itself.
   Despite the lack of trust, the administration was caught by
surprise when Mexico released Morales and allowed him to go to
Cuba. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called the decision an
``inexplicable affront.''
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Morales' violent
criminal past was so self-evident that his release and deportation
``could only have been taken for political reasons.''
   The two countries can only hope that a change in administration
in both will lead to a more harmonious relationship. Mexico will
elect a new president next month and the United States will do the
same in November. New teams _ and perhaps new approaches _ will be
in place by early next year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
