<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PublicTV     06-29 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Public TV,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Votes Change In Control Over Program Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee wants to curtail the
authority of the presidentially appointed Corporation for Public
Broadcasting and give much of the federal money for public
television directly to the TV stations.
   Senate advocates of the proposal say it would better insulate
program-funding decisions for public TV from politics and address
complaints from independent producers who want more of the public
TV programming money.
   The proposal, part of a package of changes in the way federal
money is distributed to public TV stations, was approved
unanimously by the Senate Commerce Committee on Tuesday as an
amendment to CPB's funding for fiscal years 1991-93. Some of the
changes would take effect earlier.
   The measure now goes to the Senate floor.
   A similar CPB budget bill in the House, expected to be approved
by an Energy and Commerce subcommittee today, contains none of the
Senate panel's proposals. But the House panel may consider changes
that would give independent producers greater access to public TV
funds.
   The Senate committee's proposed changes have divided the public
broadcasting community. CPB says the measure would have dire
consequences, while the Public Broadcasting Service, the private
organization of public TV stations that provides programming to
members stations, supports the bill.
   Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, said he proposed the changes
because of concerns that ``CPB funding decisions are not
sufficiently insulated from political'' influence since CPB board
members are appointed by the president.
   He also said he was concerned about complaints from independent
producers that they lack access to the public broadcasting system.
   But Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said he was concerned about
how the proposal would affect national programming, ``the heart of
the public television system.''
   The changes would fund public television in much the same way
National Public Radio is financed.
   Under the measure, about 80 percent of the $37 million that now
goes into CPB's national programming fund would be distributed
directly to stations for the purchase of national programs. CPB
would be left with about $8.5 million, which it would spend on new
programs.
   Committee staff members say that under the proposal, CPB would
have about $2 million more than it now spends on new programs. The
proposal would not be able to support a program for more than four
years out of this fund.
   After four years, a program would have to find its support from
public TV stations and other sources. The theory is that if the
stations like the program, they will buy it and continue support
for it.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said the changes would give local
public TV stations more control over the programming they broadcast
and allow them to serve their communities better.
   ``These local stations are much more sophisticated than they
were 20 years ago,'' he said.
   But with the end of CPB as a central funding office, the
stations would have to find another mechanism for pooling their
money to support national programming, posing a risk to the entire
public TV system, CPB said.
   CPB said the proposal would leave it with only about $8 million
of the $19 million it had intended to spend in fiscal 1990 on
programs for children and minorities and programs by independent
producers.
   ``We simply won't be able to fulfill promises made in this
bill,'' CPB President Donald Ledwig said in a statement.
   ``There is no guarantee that television program funds going to
stations will be reaggregated at the same level of national program
support, posing a dangerous threat to the long-term identity of
public television in an increasingly competitive environment.''
   But PBS President Bruce L. Christensen said the bill would
``enhance the independence of the programming process.'' He said
the measure reflects ``the ability of local public broadcasting
licensees to make programming decisions that best serve the needs
of their communities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
