<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxBill     06-29 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Bill,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Working up Tax-Change Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax writers are moving toward completion
of a catchall bill that would hand out billions of dollars in tax
breaks, raise corporate levies to pay for them, and fix hundreds of
mistakes in the 1986 income tax law.
   The panel on Tuesday OK'd $5.6 billion in corporate tax hikes
over the next three years to offset tax breaks the panel plans for
farmers and others.
   The committee is scheduled to decide today on another tax hike _
a proposal to take away some of the tax breaks given for
single-premium life insurance.
   Critics say studies show the policies, with tax-free earnings
and interest-free borrowing back from the premium, are a shelter
for the wealthy. But the insurance industry has been lobbying to
limit any crackdown.
   The committee needs to raise taxes to pay for the revenue-losing
provisions it included in the bill, such as repealing the
requirement that farmers and other off-road users of diesel fuel
pay the 15.1 cent per gallon federal tax.
   On Tuesday, the panel voted:
   _To squeeze $2.4 billion from defense contractors and some large
construction companies by repealing an accounting method that
allowed them to delay taxes until long-term projects are completed.
   _To raise $1.5 billion by gradually reducing the tax deduction
for dividends received by corporations owning less than 20 percent
of another company.
   _Speed up tax collection from companies with incomes that vary
widely from year to year, raising $869 million.
   _Repeal tax rules that were designed to benefit corporations of
Alaska natives, but which the committee said were being abused and
would cost the government $825 million over the next three years.
   The committee also voted to extend, with some changes, a tax
formula designed to encourage U.S. corporations to conduct their
research and development in this country.
   The decisions were all made by voice vote, according to
committee staff members who briefed reporters after the session.
   The underlying reason for the tax bill this year is to correct
hundreds of errors included in the massive 1986 tax overhaul. Many
of them are technical, such as incorrect legal citations.
</TEXT>
