<DOCNO> AP880629-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-29 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THREE RIVERS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phyllis Larkin is 72, but that
doesn't stop her from lifting 220 pounds.
   At the 1988 Women's Michigan Open Sub-Masters Tournament in
Grand Rapids on Saturday, Larkin performed a 90-pound bench press,
a 130-pound squat lift and a 220 pound dead lift, said tournament
promoter Gary Morrison.
   ``I don't think anything about it,'' Larkin said of her weight
lifting. ``I have more fun with my senior citizens because they
think I'm nuts, but I do it to be healthy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A longer version moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major defense contractor has developed a
tiny computer chip that can be used to keep track of potential
invaders _ killer bees.
   Engineers for Martin Marietta, known for producing MX missiles
and laser-guided artillery shells, developed the tracking chip at
the Oak Ridge (Tenn.) National Laboratory, the Bethesda-based
company said Tuesday.
   The microchip, about the size of a half-carat diamond and
weighing about as much as a grain of salt, is part of an integrated
circuit that would be attached to captured bees' midsections.
   The device, powered by nine solar cells, can transmit an
infrared signal that can be picked up by a ground station up to a
mile away.
   ``What we've done so far ... is establish that the bee could
indeed fly with the chip'' attached, said Ed Aebischer, a spokesman
at the laboratory. ``The entomologists have looked at it and
they're convinced that it's workable.''
   A working killer bee transmitter is expected to be in the field
by next year.
   Killer bees, which are aggressive but generally not deadly, are
the descendants of Africa queen bees. Since escaping from a
Brazilian laboratory in 1957, they have migrated as far as southern
Mexico, and are expected to cross into Texas as early as next year.
   Scientists hope that by being able to track the insects they can
control the migration without using large quantities of pesticides.
</TEXT>
