<DOCNO> AP880629-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BorderDispute Bjt   06-29 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Border Dispute, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Towns Resort To Old New England Tradition To Settle Border Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instead of spending thousands of dollars
for a surveyor to settle a longstanding border dispute, the towns
of Ashford and Willington plan to resort to an old New England
tradition: walking the line.
   After local officials balked at the $40,000 cost for a survey,
an arbitration panel suggested they resort to the method used for
centuries by New England farmers to re-establish property lines
each spring after winter weather demolished sections of the stone
fences dividing their fields.
   The three selectmen from each town tentatively plan to walk
about 20 acres of disputed land on July 6 and decide among
themselves where the border should be, Ashford First Selectwoman
Paula Faulkner said Tuesday.
   ``What will happen when we walk the line, I'm not sure,''
Faulkner said.
   Poet Robert Frost immortalized the annual ritual among farmers
in his poem ``Mending Wall.'' Connecticut statute once required
that officials from neighboring towns also walk the line every 10
years to maintain boundaries, said Albert Fitzback, a surveyor and
member of the court-appointed, three-member arbitration panel.
   Ashford, which measures 40 square miles, was incorporated in
1714 and has 3,400 residents. Willington, a town of 35 square miles
with 5,000 residents, was incorporated 13 years later. Dairy
farming is the principal industry in the northeastern Connecticut
towns.
   At issue is an 8-mile-long, 1-mile-wide strip that the General
Assembly took from Ashford when Willington was incorporated.
   Ashford authorities contend the border originally was drawn as a
straight line, but Willington officials have relied on markers
placed in 1916 that create a slight jog in the line.
   The crooked line was used for years in countless deeds and other
documents, apparently without argument from either town.
   But in 1985, Ashford ordered an aerial survey of the town as
part of a property revaluation and reverted to the straight-line
border, thereby claiming the 20-acre wedge as its own. The new line
straddles about a dozen properties and some residents are receiving
tax bills from both towns.
   The towns went to court last year and a Superior Court judge
appointed the arbitration panel to settle the dispute.
   The panel spend months poring over land records, including a
1726 map stored in Willington's vault. The map appeared to show a
straight line in the disputed area and the panel eventually
concluded that ``the line has always been and should remain a
straight line.''
   The panel suggested the towns pay for a survey to set the
border, but local officials didn't want to spend $40,000 for it and
asked for another way, Faulkner said.
   Douglas Vonasek, who is now paying taxes to both towns on his 18
acres of land, said he doesn't care which town his property ends up
in, as long as it's only in one of them.
   ``I'd like to see this thing settled once and for all,'' said
Vonasek, who figures the dispute is costing him about $100 a year
in extra taxes.
   It remains uncertain whether walking the line will resolve the
dispute.
   Willington Assessor Joan L. LeBlond questioned the accuracy of
Ashford's aerial survey showing the boundary as straight and said
the crooked border has been accepted since 1916. Such longtime,
unchallenged use should constitute the legal boundary, she said.
   ``I say, let sleeping dogs lie,'' LeBlond said. ``I'm sure there
are many towns where the boundaries jog a little bit. There's
nothing that says it has to be a straight line.''
   But Susan M. Sibiga, a former Ashford selectwoman who has
researched the matter extensively, is just as adamant that the new
straight line should be upheld.
   ``We spent a lot of time on this and the map clearly shows it is
a straight line,'' she said. ``This thing should have been settled
years ago.''
   And if the two towns still can't agree after walking the line?
   ``Then I guess we would have to spend the $40,000,'' Faulkner
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
