<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe     06-29 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Prison Probe,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Site Owners Deny Any Improper Dealings With Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a possible prison site that is the
subject of an FBI investigation for its selection deny any improper
dealings with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis or any member of
his administration.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis, the likely Democratic presidential nominee,
insisted Tuesday the state would not pay ``one dime more'' for the
land in New Braintree, Mass., than it is worth.
   At issue is whether Daniel Striar and Gary Jacobson received
insider information that prompted them to offer to the state for
$9.5 million in 1986 land they had bought a year earlier for $3.2
million.
   Striar and Jacobson said they had no idea until February 1986 _
exactly a year after they signed a purchase and sales agreement for
the 782 acres of property and three months after they bought it _
that the state was interested in the land as a prison.
   New Braintree residents, who have opposed the proposed prison in
their town for two years, have accused Striar and Jacobson of
acting as middlemen between the former owner, the Seventh Day
Adventist Church, and the state, which has a severe shortage of
prison space.
   ``Instead of pursuing it in a legitimate fashion, (New Braintree
residents) chose to take a series of trivial and irrelevant facts
and make them appear as if they were dirty and sinister,'' Jacobson
said.
   Jacobson, 50, lived for several years in Dukakis' neighborhood
in Brookline during his teens. He also has contributed to Dukakis'
gubernatorial and presidential campaigns.
   But Jacobson denied he is a close associate of the governor.
``I'm probably the only citizen of Brookline who is not claiming to
be the closest friend of Governor Dukakis,'' he said.
   Striar, 52, has been linked to Dukakis through a September 1986
dedication ceremony for a Stoughton Jewish community center named
after Striar's parents. Dukakis and Striar attended the ceremony
but Striar said he uttered one word to the governor: ``Hello.''
   Dukakis, appearing at a housing promotion event in Boston, said,
``I didn't know Striar ... I didn't have the slightest interest in
who the owner of the property was.'' He added that, ``I think that
the business of throwing charges around is absurd.''
   Striar defended the $9.5 million asking price.
   ``I looked at this piece of property and I felt it was a
steal,'' said Striar, who has participated in a number of real
estate ventures with Jacobson.
   ``Dr. Jacobson (who is a psychiatrist) and I decided to buy the
property as a real estate speculation,'' Striar said. He said the
town stood in the way of their development efforts, forcing them to
entertain the state's offer a year later to buy the property for a
prison.
   Dorothea Thomas-Vitrac, a New Braintree selectman, said the town
did oppose some of the condominium and recreational development
proposals put forth by Striar and Jacobson. But she said the town
never opposed their original plan to use the land for a psychiatric
hospital.
   Striar and Jacobson also said they have had no contact with the
FBI.
</TEXT>
