<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Thornburgh-Veep     06-29 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh-Veep,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Pennsylvania Governor Seen As Possible Bush Running Mate</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: One in a series of occasional profiles of vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since ending his second term as Pennsylvania
governor in 1986, Dick Thornburgh has hardly retreated from the
public eye.
   Thornburgh, 55, has been heading the Institute of Politics at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government. He has been
asked to head the FBI and the Agency for International Development.
And he has been busier than ever on the political circuit back home.
   All that visibility helps fuel talk of Thornburgh as a potential
running mate for Republican presidential nominee-to-be George Bush.
   Thornburgh also has been said to be considering running for
governor again when Democrat Robert Casey comes up for re-election
in 1990.
   ``He's a politician,'' his longtime aide, David Runkel, said in
a telephone interview. ``He has not closed the door on another
campaign for something.''
   The Bush campaign has said it is too early to speculate about
the search for a running mate. And Thornburgh said there is little
he can do, whether he wants the job or not.
   ``You don't campaign for the office of vice president. There's
only one vote that counts, and that's the vote of the candidate,''
Thornburgh told reporters recently in State College, Pa.
   ``I'm sure the vice president is concentrating on his own short
list of prospective candidates, but I think it's really quite
premature for even speculation to be undertaken because of the fact
that I think he will factor in the choice made by the Democrats in
Atlanta,'' Thornburgh said.
   The Republican convention does not begin until August 15 in New
Orleans. The Democrats meet a month earlier in Atlanta.
   If Thornburgh were asked, he says, ``It would certainly be
something I would give serious consideration to.''
   Thornburgh's recent activity has included two fund raisers that
have netted about $100,000 for the ``Governor Thornburgh
Committee,'' an account he uses to support his travels on behalf of
other candidates, Runkel said.
   In addition, Thornburgh is co-chairman of Pennsylvania's
``Victory '88,'' a fund that distributes money for phone banks and
other Republican campaign efforts.
   ``Victory '88,'' which has $30,000 in the coffers now, is hoping
to raise $600,000 by bringing Bush to Pennsylvania for fund-raising
events in August, Republican officials said.
   The possibility of a Bush-Thornburgh ticket has excited
Pennsylvania's Republican convention delegates, many of whom have
named the former governor as their top choice for the second spot
on the ticket.
   ``He's the most outstanding governor I've served under, and I've
been here for 24 years,'' said Republican State Rep. James Gallen
of Shillington, who won a delegate spot in the April primary.
Gallen said it would make sense for Thornburgh to be picked by Bush
``since he's from Pennsylvania, and it's a key state.''
   U.S. Rep. William Clinger, R-Pa., said Thornburgh would help
neutralize the support of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in the
Northeast and especially in Pennsylvania, where Democrats enjoy a
voter registration advantage of more than 500,000.
   But other delegates said Thornburgh might be too similar to Bush
to form a well-rounded ticket. Both are Yale University graduates
who maintain ties to the Northeast, Thornburgh as a Pennsylvanian
and Bush as a part-time of resident of Maine.
   In 1975, Thornburgh served under President Ford as assistant
attorney general in charge of the Justice Department's criminal
division.
   He was staunchly loyal to the Reagan administration, frequently
testifying on Capitol Hill on behalf of the president's proposal
for line-item veto power and a constitutional amendment to balance
the budget. He turned down offers to head the FBI and AID, and was
considered for Margaret Heckler's health and human services Cabinet
post in 1985.
   As governor, Thornburgh said his budget proposals held spending
increases to less than the rate of inflation for eight straight
years. He championed a controversial welfare reform law that
limited an estimated 68,000 people considered ``able-bodied'' to
three months of cash benefits a year.
</TEXT>
