<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Fountain     06-29 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Fountain,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Groundbreaking' Held on Ohio River for Fountain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Indians, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought may have shrunk the Ohio
River, but it hasn't dried up plans for construction of the
Louisville Falls Fountain, billed as the world's tallest.
   The first of four concrete caissons being implanted in the river
bed was built Tuesday in preparation for the fountain's arrival.
   The structure is being built in Tennessee, and is scheduled to
be floated up the Tennessee and Ohio rivers later this month.
   The fountain, financed by a $2.6 million gift from the Mary and
Barry Bingham Sr. Fund, is intended as a national landmark and a
new symbol for Louisville, reflecting its river heritage.
   It was described as the largest floating fountain in the world
by Louisville Central Area, the downtown planning agency.
   At peak performance, water will jet 375 feet into the air as the
fountain pumps 15,800 gallons of river water a minute.
   Four smaller jets will spray water 75 feet high, and 24 others
will spray 10 feet high, creating a fleur-de-lis, the symbol of
Louisville.
   The drought, which has caused barge backlogs on the Ohio, has
not affected plans for transporting the fountain, said Louisville
Central Area spokesman Errol Frailey.
</TEXT>
