<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeamstersFacts     06-29 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Facts,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Union Goes Back 85 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Teamsters Suit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on the Teamsters union:
   Official name: The International Brotherhood of Teamsters,
Chauffeurs, Warehousemen and Helpers of America.
   Formed: 1903.
   Membership: A general membership of 1.6 million, making it the
largest union in the United States. Besides truck drivers, the
union represents a variety of workers, including flight attendants
and supermarket workers.
   Affiliation: The Teamsters were expelled in 1957 from the
AFL-CIO for high-level corruption. They rejoined the federation
last October.
   Legal troubles: The union's problems with prosecutors go back
decades. Four of the union's past five presidents have been
indicted or convicted.
   _ In 1957, president Dave Beck was convicted of misuse of union
funds.
   _ In 1967, Jimmy Hoffa, who took over when Beck resigned, was
imprisoned on jailed on a 1964 jury tampering conviction. He was
freed in 1971 when President Nixon commuted his sentence, and
disappeared in 1975 and is believed to have been murdered.
   _ The next president, Frank Fitzsimmons, was investigated but
never indicted and died in office in 1981.
   _ In 1983, president Roy Williams resigned after being convicted
of conspiracy to bribe a U.S. senator. He is serving a prison
sentence.
   _ The current president, Jackie Presser, is under indictment in
Cleveland for an alleged ghost employee scheme. He is on leave from
the union following surgery last month for a brain tumor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
