<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     06-29 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Leader Jackie Presser Hospitalized In Serious Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Teamsters Suit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters president Jackie Presser, who is
suffering from brain tumors, was in serious condition early today
after being readmitted to a hospital, officials said.
   Presser, 61, was alert and conscious when he was brought to
Lakewood Hospital's emergency room Tuesday afternoon, said David
Hopcraft, a hospital spokesman.
   Hours earlier, federal prosecutors in New York sued the union in
an attempt to end its alleged domination by organized crime and
force labor reforms.
   WKYC-TV reported Presser was in the hospital's cardiac care unit
and was being watched closely because doctors suspected he had a
pulmonary embolism, a blood clot. The television station reported
that an unidentified source in the hospital said doctors were
trying to determine how to treat the condition and if he should be
moved to another hospital.
   Presser has been tested and treated for brain cancer at the
Cleveland Clinic.
   Hopcraft said doctors did not expect Presser's condition to
change in the near future. Hopcraft would not confirm or deny that
Presser was in the cardiac care unit.
   He said Presser's condition was not related to brain tumors,
which have disabled the union leader.
   U.S. District Court Judge George White, in a ruling June 7,
postponed Presser's July 12 trial on racketeering and embezzlement
charges, citing Presser's bout with brain tumors. Two co-defendants
are to be tried July 12.
   White ruled after Presser's physicians said Presser was
undergoing radiation treatment for brain tumors and might have less
than six months to live.
   Dr. Leslie Sheeler of the Cleveland Clinic, in a May 26 letter,
said Presser had virtually no short-term memory and added, ``I
doubt that he will possibly ever have substantial improvement from
his current status.''
   Presser was released June 13 from the Barrow Neurological
Institute in Phoenix, Ariz., where he had undergone treatment for
the brain tumors.
   He gave up his duties as president of the nation's largest union
for four months on May 4 because of poor health.
   A May 1986 indictment accused Presser of taking $700,000 from
his Cleveland local's union office and paying it to ``ghost''
employees who performed no work.
