<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia-BombAttacks     06-29 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Bomb Attacks,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tigrean Rebels Claim Ethiopians Kill 600 In Air Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tigrean rebels have claimed that Ethiopian
warplanes killed more than 600 civilians in air raids on an ancient
market town during the government's two-month-old counteroffensive.
   The guerrillas said Tuesday that the strikes by four MiG fighter
bombers and two Mi-24 helicopter gunships were unleashed on
Wednesday, June 22 in Hauzien, 340 miles north of Addis Ababa, the
capital.
   Wednesday is market day in Hauzien and hundreds of peasants are
traditionally drawn to the town.
   The attack wounded more than 360 people and killed hundreds of
animals, said the rebel communique, sent to The Associated Press
from the Tigre People's Liberation Front information center in
London,
   There was no way to independently verify the claim. The
government of President Mengistu Haile Mariam rarely comments on
rebel claims, and both sides often exaggerate reports on the war in
northern Ethiopia.
   The communique said much of the town was razed in a six-hour
bombardment.
   ``Most of the buildings _ over 500 including nine stores and 15
shops, the town mosque and the only school _ were completely
destroyed,'' said the rebel report.
   They claimed the Ethiopian government uses rockets and napalm,
phosphorous and cluster bombs in attacks on numerous Tigrean towns.
   Western diplomats based in Addis Ababa say they have heard of
the government using cluster bombs, but not napalm.
   ``The Dergue (government) is committing these atrocities in a
region suffering from starvation,'' the rebels said.
   The U.S. Government and diplomats from other Western countries
have condemned a government counteroffensive begun in May that has
crippled relief operations and jeopardized the lives of 3.2 million
people threatened by starvation from drought in the neighboring
provinces of Eritrea and Tigre.
   The war zone is the most severely affected by a drought that
plagues more than 7 million Ethiopians.
   But diplomats similarly accuse the rebels of pursuing military
objectives with no regard for drought victims. The rebels launched
their offensive at the end of last year after the United Nations
warned of impending famine in the region. Rebels won major
victories in March, capturing several towns and forcing government
troops to withdraw from others.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies when, with a clique of army
officers, he helped overthrow Emperor Haile Selassie in 1974.
   Both the government and rebels are Marxist. Eritrean
secessionists took up arms 27 years ago and are fighting Africa's
oldest civil war. Tigrean rebels went to war 14 years ago demanding
more autonomy.
</TEXT>
