<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tonga-King'sParty     06-29 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tonga-King's Party,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Decrees Five-Day Party for 70th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NUKU'ALOFA, Tonga (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tongans plan to feast, dance, march in
parades and race longboats in a five-day party fit for a king _ and
decreed by the monarch of this South Pacific archipelago.
   King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV ordered the bash for Friday through
Tuesday to celebrate his 70th birthday on July 4.
   The capital will be shut down and the king will be honored with
a naval review, a black-tie ball, native dancing, rugby matches and
two traditional feasts each inviting 1,200 people.
   There will be church services across the islands 1,500 miles
north of New Zealand where nearly all residents are Christian.
   Tonga, discovered by Dutch explorers in 1616, is the region's
sole surviving monarchy. Tupuo has reigned for the past 23 years.
   The country is part of the British Commonwealth. Its Parliament
is loosely based on the British model but only nine of its 28
members are democratically elected as ``people's representatives.''
Nine are noblemen voted in by aristocratic families, and the rest
are appointed by the king.
   The king's brother, Prince Fatafehi Tu'ipelehake, is prime
minister.
   Generations of bloody tribal warfare ended last century when the
present king's great-great grandfather, Siaosa Tupou I, established
the throne. He freed commoners from a system of feudalism among
Tonga's 169 islands, spread over 290 square miles.
   The authorities are determined that this weekend's celebrations
will demonstrate solidarity with the monarchy. But in recent years,
there have been rumblings of discontent in this country of 104,000
people.
   Many Tongan families now find themselves relying on money sent
back from relatives who have migrated to the United States,
Australia and New Zealand.
   Tired of the constraints of a rigid class system, thousands of
young Tongans continue to migrate rather than face growing
unemployment and few opportunities at home.
</TEXT>
