<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Rehabilitation 1stLd-Writethru a0460 06-29 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Rehabilitation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0460,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Remarkable Turnaround, Ousted Local Leader Back In The
Limelight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `Official reports ...,' to delete reference
to official reports. PICKS up 15th graf, ``During my ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official disgraced three years ago for
alleged corruption is back in the limelight as one of Canton's
rising stars, yet another example of China's penchant for reviving
its politically dead.
   Lei Yu, 54, earned nationwide notoriety in 1985 when, official
media accounts said, he and other top-ranking officials on southern
Hainan island were accused of abusing power by importing vehicles
and consumer goods and reselling them at high profits to the rest
of China.
   Lei was demoted from his leading party and government posts on
the undeveloped, tropical island between Vietnam and the
Philippines and become a county-level party deputy secretary in
southern Guangdong province.
   But on March 31, the official Xinhua News Agency announced that
he had been promoted to vice mayor of Canton in charge of foreign
economic relations and trade. Assisting economic growth in two
counties, Lei had learned, among other things, ``never to loaf on
the job,'' the report said.
   On Monday, the Canton People's Congress voted Lei one of six
vice mayors of the Guangdong capital, a leading city in China's
economic reform program.
   He received the second most votes of the nine candidates,
newspaper reports appearing in the nearby British colony of Hong
Kong said Tuesday.
   Four days earlier, the congress chose Yang Ziyuan as mayor by a
318-153 tally over Lei, according to newspaper reports in Hong
Kong. Before the vote, Lei reportedly reminded the congress of his
mistakes in the Hainan affair in a well-received speech and threw
his support Yang.
   In an interview at Canton's municipal offices two weeks ago, it
was clear why Lei is back. He displayed an agile no-nonsense mind
and enthusiastically espoused the market-oriented economic reforms
of senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Wearing a well-tailored Western suit and exuding confidence, Lei
seemed cut in the mold of Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang, who
has taken the lead in promoting Deng's reforms.
   Deng and Zhao also have experienced disgrace and rehabilitation.
Both were purged during the chaotic 1966-76 ultra-leftist Cultural
Revolution, accused of being `capitalist roaders' and paraded
through the streets in dunce caps. Countless others were purged
during the decade of disaster.
   Lei's disgrace was different, however. It resulted not from a
political power struggle but from economic scandal.
   According to official Chinese reports, the scandal involved the
illegal trade of 3.3 million cars, color televisions, video
recorders and motorcycles, which were imported to Hainan island in
1984 and 1985 then resold throughout China.
   Under a program to spur development, Hainan had been allowed to
import automobiles and 16 other ``luxury goods''. The items were
intended for use only on the island, but Lei and others decided to
resell them, resulting in millions of dollars in profts, the
reports said.
   A Western source in Canton said he believed Lei thought the
importation scheme could raise money to build up Hainan's
infrastructure, which is woefully lacking. As such, many believed
Lei was punished more for his unorthodox methods than for economic
corruption.
   ``During my stay in Hainan, I wanted to boost the island's
economy,'' Lei was quoted as saying in the Xinhua report. ``But
things went contrary to my wishes because I did not take hold of
the state policies.''
   Lei reiterated during his interview with The Associated Press
that he did not get ``one cent'' out of the importation scandal.
Still he acknowledged that he let things get out of hand.
   ``At that time, we were short of experience, so it was not
strange that we sometimes made mistakes,'' he said, adding with a
smile, ``I believe I'll be a little smarter than before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Drought-DeadWheat Bjt   06-29 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Dead Wheat, Bjt,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Of Minnesota's Spring Wheat Dies Of Thirst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHCOTE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald Olsonawski plowed under all but
300 of the 1,700 acres of wheat he planted in the spring. The crop
struggled then withered on Minnesota's thirsty prairie, the upper
section of America's breadbasket.
   ``We've gone through all that work, and now the whole year is
shot,'' said Olsonawski, 39. ``It's like a wasted year. It's like
we never turned a wheel.
   ``You should see beautiful fields. All you see is black dirt.
I've given up on the grain crop,'' said Olsonawski.
   Last year, Minnesota produced about 100 million bushels of
spring wheat worth $246 million, second only to North Dakota's 189
million bushels, according to the state's Agricultural Statistics
Service. Spring wheat is the high protein variety, ground into
flour for yeast breads and hard rolls.
   This year, 85 percent of the crop is rated poor to very poor,
the state said Monday. Damage is even worse in parched Kittson
County, in the northwest corner on the Canadian border.
   County officials estimate a loss of 7 million bushels, 90
percent of the crop. Already, 60,000 acres have been plowed under.
An acre that should yield 40 to 50 bushels of wheat is projected to
produce half a bushel, according to insurance appraisers.
   Lush, solid waves of grain should be filling fields. Now, they
look like desk tops dotted with stubbly stalks and revealing bare
spots. Wheat that should be 8 to 12 inches high with grain-bearing
heads have wilted to half that size.
   ``This crop has failed,'' said Kelly Turgeon, the county's
executive for the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation
Service. ``It's not even feasible to try to harvest it. It's
devastating.''
   A majority of the county's farmers have federal crop insurance.
They are paid damages for what their land is producing and what it
should have yielded, but the payments probably will just cover
expenses for fertilizer, fuel and time.
   For grain farmers, the nation's worst drought in 50 years was
the last straw in a hectic year. They had a killing frost May 13,
and then saw high winds blow away seeds and injure crops.
   After a farmer has invested time and money on plowing, seeding
and fertilizing, plowing a crop under is hard.
   But Harold Younggren, 61, was told his wheat harvest would be
half a bushel per acre instead of 45 to 60 bushels. He and his sons
looked at the scraggle in the arid fields, figured it would cost
more in fuel and time than it was worth, and then plowed under all
but 40 acres of the 1,550 acres of wheat they planted in late April.
   ``There wasn't anything there. There's a few spears of grain
here and there,'' Younggren said.
   ``We've never torn up grain like this before,'' said Younggren,
a farmer for 40 years. ``The heat burned it right off. It dwindled
to nothing.''
   Statewide, the picture is a little brighter, but not much.
   A 50 percent loss has been projected, amounting to $200 million
to $300 million, according to Fred Hejduk, head of the Minnesota
Wheat Growers Association in Red Lake Falls.
   ``The overall situation is very serious and almost beyond
repair,'' said Hejduk. ``Some fields are totally devastated. It
doesn't pay to crank up the combine.''
   A wheat farmer may have spent $150 an acre to plant, seed and
fertilize. That acre should return a $75 profit.
   ``Plowing it under means they've failed,'' said Bernie Penner,
conservation service agent in Crow Wing County. ``How would you
feel as a surgeon if all your patients died? A farmer's expertise
is raising crops. He only gets one chance each year.''
   Wheat is such a part of the lifestyle in the fertile grain belt
that wallpaper in offices and restaurants is decorated with wheat
stalks.
   And a drought seems incongruous in a state with a license plate
slogan of Land of 10,000 Lakes, and where the mighty Mississippi
begins.
   But hot winds and a dry spring meant grain cooked under a
sweltering sun.
   Farmers plow under their fields to control weeds, get their land
ready for next season and keep unprofitable plants from using up
nutrients.
   Some farm officials wish the farmers would just let the wheat
stay in the fields instead of risking wind erosion remindful of the
1930s Dust Bowl.
   ``We're advising them to just leave it there,'' said Marlin
Schieffert, conservation service agent in Clay County. ``It's so
dry, it's susceptible to be blown by the wind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
