<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AMA-Glance     06-29 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA-Glance,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary Of Day's Events At AMA House of Delegates Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AMA Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the major issues considered
Tuesday by the American Medical Association's 420-member House of
Delegates. The AMA is the nation's largest group of doctors,
representing 295,000 physicians. The convention ends Thursday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MERCY KILLING</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates approved a policy statement stressing the AMA's
opposition to euthanasia. A proposal to restrict the AMA's
publication, the Journal of the American Medical Association, from
publishing articles about the subject was rejected.
   The vote came in the wake of a controversy spawned by the
January publication of a first-person article in JAMA entitled
``It's Over, Debbie,'' in which an anonymous doctor claimed he
ended a cancer patient's life at her request.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>TOBACCO</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates continued their fight against tobacco by voting to
call on the federal government to end price supports and help needy
tobacco farmers begin growing other products.
   Delegates postponed action until today on a proposal to call for
the doubling of the federal tobacco tax from 16 cents per pack to
32 cents.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>HANDGUNS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates approved a proposal to work for a ban on the
manufacture and sale of realistic-looking toy guns.
   They also voted to seek manufacturing and sales bans on real
``firearms'' made from plastic or small amounts of metal that make
them undetectable by screening devices.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DRUG POLICY</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates were scheduled to vote on a measure seeking to
shift the focus of the nation's war on drugs from drug traffickers
to users, but postponed action until today. A committee that took
testimony on the policy recommended adoption.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PRODUCT LIABILITY</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The delegates were scheduled to vote on a proposal to call on
state and federal governments to limit the amount of money awarded
in product liability lawsuits. The vote was postponed until today.
   According to a report prepared by AMA trustees, biomedical
companies have slowed development of new vaccines, drugs and other
``potentially life-saving technologies'' because of the fear of
litigation.
</TEXT>
