<DOCNO> AP880629-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Romania     06-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Romania,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Orders Hungarian Diplomat to Leave in Escalating Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rift between two East bloc allies
grew to unprecedented proportions when Romania ordered a Hungarian
diplomat expelled in a dispute over Romania's treatment of its
ethnic Hungarians.
   Romania on Tuesday ordered Hungary's consul general in the city
of Cluj-Napoca to leave the country within 48 hours and declared
the consulate closed, the official Hungarian news agency MTI said.
   The decision apparently was prompted by a demonstration of about
50,000 Hungarians in Budapest Monday to protest the planned
demolition by the year 2000 of half of Romania's villages,
including ethnic Hungarian communities.
   It was the largest street demonstration in Hungary since Soviet
troops put down a 1956 rebellion.
   Cluj-Napoca is in Transylvania in northwestern Romania, where
most of that country's 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians live.
Hungarians know it as Kolozsvar.
   Ethnic Hungarians in Romania, the largest minority group in East
Europe outside the Soviet Union, long have complained that they
suffer discrimination and are denied ethnic rights.
   Romania and Hungary, neighbors and military allies in the
Soviet-led Warsaw pact, have waged a war of words over the issue.
   Official Hungarian media have given considerable coverage to
protests by political, social and artistic groups against Romania's
village demolition program.
   President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania on Tuesday rejected
criticism of the plan and accused Hungarian authorities of actively
supporting the unofficial protest.
   The resettlement plan calls for 7,000 of Romania's 13,000
villages to be torn down and replaced with agricultural-industrial
centers.
   Romanian state-run media said the goal is to gain more farmland
for use by the country's collectivized agriculture, which is
plagued by lack of incentives for farmers and livestock fodder
shortages.
   Romania also maintains the plan will raise the living standards
of villagers who would have access to health care and social
facilities.
   MTI said Foreign Minister Ioan Totu of Romania summoned
Hungarian Ambassador Pal Szuecs Tuesday and told him of the
expulsion order.
   ``All responsibility for this violation of the valid consulate
agreement between Hungary and Romania devolves upon the Romanian
government,'' MIT said. It said the Hungarian government would work
to improve relations with Romania and the 20,000 ethnic Romanians
in Hungary.
   Hungary has given refuge to thousands of ethnic Hungarians who
have fled Romania and also taken in other Romanians escaping
economic hardship.
   Romania began an austerity program in 1981 that has led to food
and energy shortages. It has reduced its foreign debt from more
than $11 billion in 1981 to less than $5 billion, but at the
expense of its people.
   Earlier Tuesday, Hungarian Foreign Ministry spokesman Istvan
Komoroczky told journalists that Hungarian authorities had told the
Romanian Embassy in advance of Monday's demonstration.
   The demonstrators marched silently past the Romanian embassy
building, which was guarded by Hungarian police, and there were no
incidents.
   The Hungarian government and speakers at Monday's rally stressed
that a change of existing borders is out of the question. Under the
1920 Trianon Treaty, predominantly Hungarian Transylvania became
part of Romania.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
