<HEAD>How to Squeeze 35,000 Credentialed Bodies into Space for 11,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats are trying to figure out how to get
35,000 people slated to attend the party's national convention into
a hall that will seat only 11,000 people.
   The Democratic National Convention Committee is hoping to
peacefully resolve the problem by putting the overflow from the
Omni Coliseum into the adjacent World Congress Center, but admit
the feelings of party hotshots may be hurt in the process.
   ``We'll have fewer spectator seats in the Omni, and there are
going to be people who are disappointed they aren't going to be in
the Omni,'' said Ruth Berry, press secretary for the DNCC, which is
in charge of organizing the July 18-21 event.
   The seating problem is one of a series of difficulties in
preparations for the nominating convention, but officials are
certain all will be right when the opening gavel sounds.
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk said, ``We knew there
would be limited space. But it is adequate to accommodate all the
delegates and additional guests. It will be a little difficult for
the media. This is not a sprawling complex (The Omni), but it's not
a theater in the round.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Michigan Panel Votes to Restore Presidential Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Michigan House Elections Committee has
voted to reinstate a presidential primary election in 1992.
   Under the bill passed Tuesday to the full House, voters would
have to declare in advance whether they wanted to vote on the
Republican or Democratic side.
   The provision was added by lawmakers to meet the Democratic
National Committee rules which don't recognize results of ``open
primaries'' allowing members of each party to cross over and vote
for another party's candidate.
   In Michigan, the 1976 primary marked the last time that both
major parties participated in the open primary. The Republicans had
a primary in 1980 but opted for a multi-tiered convention system in
the past two elections.
   Leaders of both parties have supported the return to a primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Oregon Governor To Stay Home and Work During Dems Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon Gov. Neil Goldschmidt, citing the
press of state business, says he will skip the Democratic National
Convention, foregoing a slot as a ``super delegate.''
   Goldschmidt's office issued the statement Tuesday while the
governor was vacationing in Hawaii.
   State Sen. Grattan Kerans, who served as a consultant to
Dukakis' Oregon primary campaign, said Goldschmidt's announcement
is ``not a big deal.''
   Kerans noted that Goldschmidt is recovering from a recent
operation to relieve chronic sinus infections.
   Goldschmidt's decision will reduce the Oregon delegation in
Atlanta from 54 to 53 members.
</TEXT>
