<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Goetz     06-29 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Goetz,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Judges Reverse Goetz's Sentence; Order Resentencing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernhard Goetz's six-month jail sentence was
declared illegal by an appeals court, which ordered that he be
resentenced for criminal possession of a gun in the 1984 subway
shootings of four teen-agers.
   The state Supreme Court's Appellate Division voted 5-0 on
Tuesday to vacate the jail sentence Justice Stephen Crane imposed
on Goetz on Oct. 19, 1987, after he was convicted of third-degree
criminal possession of a weapon.
   The appeals court let stand the $5,000 fine, 280 hours of
community service, five years' probation and psychiatric counseling
for Goetz ordered by Crane.
   Goetz, a 40-year-old electronics specialist, was acquitted last
June of all but the gun charge in the Dec. 22, 1984, shootings.
Goetz, who is white, said he shot the four blacks after they tried
to rob him. The youths claimed they were just panhandling money.
The case stirred a national debate about vigilantism.
   Defense attorneys said they were pleased the sentence had been
rejected but would appeal other issues to the Court of Appeals, the
state's highest court.
   ``We will be asking the judge at this point to grant Bernie
Goetz the right of probation,'' defense lawyer Barry Slotnick said.
   ``Hopefully,'' he added, ``the public will write some letters of
indignation to Judge Crane indicating that Bernie Goetz doesn't
belong in jail, whether it be for one day, two months or six
months.''
   Slotnick said Goetz cannot come out worse-off under resentencing
by Crane, scheduled for July 18.
   The prosecution and the defense contended that the punishment
was illegal and that Goetz should have been sentenced to a year in
prison.
   The defense wanted a year sentence because that would have made
Goetz eligible for release after two months. Under the six-month
sentence, he would not have been eligible for parole until four
months because of a quirk in the law.
   The prosecution argued that the law mandated a minimum sentence
of one year for third-degree criminal possession of a weapon.
   The appeals court judges agreed in part with the prosecutor,
Assistant District Attorney Gregory Waples.
   ``An individual who is convicted of this offense must be
sentenced to an indeterminate period of imprisonment, or in the
alternative, a definite sentence of no less than one year,'' the
judges said.
   Crane could have imposed a shorter legal sentence if he had
explained why the sentence required by law ``would be unduly
harsh,'' the judges wrote.
   ``Since the court expressly stated on the record that a definite
one-year term or an indeterminate term would not be unduly harsh,
the split sentence was unauthorized and illegal,'' the judges said
in an unsigned three-page opinion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
