<DOCNO> AP880629-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     06-29 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Command Meets With Officers As Truce Expiration Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, NICARAGUA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry said its high
command was meeting with army officers to discuss potential actions
once a truce with Nicaraguan rebels expires Thursday night.
   The end of the government-declared truce coincides with a series
of consulations between Secretary of State George Shultz and U.S.
allies in Central America.
   The ministry called the meetings between Defense Minister
Humberto Ortega and his commanders ``extremely important,'' but
provided no details. It said such meetings were held only in
extraordinary circumstances.
   The Sandinista government did not announce whether it would
extend its unilateral truce. The U.S.-supported Contra rebels said
they would continue to abide by the cease-fire indefinitely, but
rejected a government offer to resume peace talks this week.
   Each side has accused the other of violating the truce that took
effect March 21. The government claims 3,000 Contra fighters
recently re-entered Nicaragua from Honduran base camps in
anticipation of renewed fighting.
   A series of peace negotiations broke down June 9 over
differences on democratic reforms and a timetable for rebel
disarmament.
   The United States has funded the Contras since 1981, two years
after the Sandinistas took power, but Congress cut off military aid
to the rebels in February.
   The 6{-year war has killed more than 26,000 people and caused an
estimated $3 billion in economic damages.
   Shultz arrives today in Guatemala City and is to consult with
officials in Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador before the trip
ends Friday.
</TEXT>
