<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-29 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar and share prices scored strong gains in
mixed trading in Tokyo Wednesday.
   The dollar opened the day's dealings at 132.80 yen and managed
to break past the 133-yen barrier during the morning session. It
fluctuated mainly between 132.40-133.40 yen during the day before
closing at 132.40 yen, up 1.45 yen from Tuesday's 130.95-yen finish.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a slight 36.92-point loser Tuesday, won back
209.24 points, or 0.76 percent. It finished the day at 27,607.33
points.
   Traders attributed the climb to strong buying interest centered
on large-capital steels and heavy industrials which also led the
market recovery Tuesday after heavy morning losses.
   Traders said the dollar's bullish rise was fueled by comments
from Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, who ruled out the
possibility of foreign exchange intervention by the Bank of Japan
to support the yen.
   ``The statement prompted a lot of dollar-buying,'' said a dealer
at a local securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``As long as the central bank continues with this attitude, the
dollar may even rise to the 135-yen level this week,'' he said.
   Miyazawa told reporters during a regular press conference on
Tuesday that the central bank had no intention of intervening in
the market to stem the dollar's rise unless necessary. He dismissed
the current market gyrations as ordinary fluctuations.
   The dealer also said intervention in Europe, where the business
day begins as Tokyo trading ends, had cast a slight worry on the
local market Tuesday. The dollar had dropped a slight 0.75 yen to
finish at 130.95 yen Tuesday, down from Monday's six-month high of
131.70 yen.
   The U.S. currency last traded on the 133-yen level in early
December when it opened at 133.05 yen on Dec. 8. The dollar closed
last Friday at 129.70 yen, a four-month high.
</TEXT>
