<HEAD>Justice Employees File Suit Against Random Drug Testing Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trial attorneys and supervisors in the Justice
Department are asking a court to halt Attorney General Edwin Meese
III's plan to conduct random drug testing of department officials.
   A lawsuit was filed by 42 employees on Tuesday, a day after the
Justice Department announced random testing of workers in sensitive
jobs would begin in two months.
   The suit contends the plan is unconstitutional and is being
implemented ``without any factual showing of a problem of drug use
in the department.''
   The 42 plaintiffs named in the suit were mostly Justice
Department trial attorneys plus several supervisors, including
three deputy chiefs of the civil rights division's criminal
section: Barry Kowalski, Daniel L. Bell and Norajean M. Flanagan.
   Arthur Spitzer, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney
involved in the case, said he had spoken to a number of other
Justice Department officials who privately supported the lawsuit
but didn't want to join it for fear of hurting their careers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Approves Bill To Crack Down on Telemarketing Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is calling on the Federal Trade
Commission to crack down on fraud in telemarketing _ sales over the
telephone _ which is estimated to cost consumers at least $1
billion a year.
   By a voice vote, the House passed a measure on Tuesday directing
the FTC to draft rules governing sales by telephone and to make it
easier to sue telemarketing companies.
   The bill says the agency should consider including provisions
that establish refund rights for customers and a period during
which consumers can withdraw their order and set a time of day when
unsolicited calls can be made.
   The FTC estimates that telemarketing sales in 1986 amounted to
more than $100 billion. The agency, however, has been able to get
back only about $25 million for defrauded consumers over the past
four years, Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said.
   ``No piece of legislation is going to end fraud,'' Luken said
during debate on the bill Monday. ``But I think this bill will
significantly reduce the losses now being suffered by American
consumers.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Approves Fishing Vessel Safety Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after Peggy and Robert Barry lost
their son at sea, the House has passed a measure calling for safety
equipment aboard fishing vessels that the couple says could have
helped save their son's life.
   The legislation passed Tuesday calls for safety equipment such
as life rafts and survival suits aboard the vessels. Northwest
lawmakers who fought for the bill called it a memorial to those who
have lost their lives at sea.
   ``This was an important first-step in making the industry
safer,'' said Robert Barry, who lobbied for the bill after his son
died when the fishing vessel Western Sea sank off the Alaska coast
in 1985.
   Barry, who lives in Washington, D.C., said the 70-year-old
Western Sea, which was registered out of Seattle, did not contain
life rafts, survival suits or an emergency locator when it went
down with six crewmen aboard.
   ``The crew of the Western Sea would have had a chance of
surviving if they had had such things as life rafts,'' said Barry.
``Without them, they didn't have a chance.''
</TEXT>
