<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TeamstersSuit-Reax     06-29 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Suit-Reax,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds' Lawsuit Against Teamsters Assailed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Teamsters Suit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal racketeering lawsuit accusing
Teamsters leaders of making a ``devil's pact'' with the Mafia is a
``shameful attempt'' at union-busting, Teamsters officials charged.
   Federal prosecutors filed the civil lawsuit against the 1.6
million-member union Tuesday, seeking to oust members of the
Teamsters general executive board for allegedly allowing mob
infiltration during the past 30 years.
   The lawsuit also sought appointment of a union trustee to ensure
free and fair union elections.
   ``We are not seeking overall control of the Teamsters union,''
U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani said, adding that his office was
using the racketeering laws ``in a surgical way to attempt to take
back from the Mafia the Teamsters union.''
   William Doran, head of criminal division for the FBI's New York
office cautioned: ``This is not a case of union-busting but instead
a case of mob-busting.''
   But Teamsters leaders quickly denounced the lawsuit.
   ``It's pure myth that this organization is in any way influenced
or controlled by organized crime,'' Teamsters' lawyer John Climaco
told a news conference in Montreal, where the union's general
executive board is holding its quarterly meeting.
   ``It's totally un-American and it's wrong.''
   The union's acting president, Weldon Mathis, called the lawsuit
``a vicious anti-labor attack'' and ``a shameful attempt to destroy
a democratic union. It will not be tolerated.''
   The lawsuit also was denounced on Capitol Hill, where Sen. Orrin
Hatch, the ranking Republican on the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee, said it sets ``a terrible precedent.''
   ``If there are union officers who are corrupt or are connected
with the Mafia, then the government should come down on them with
dispatch,'' Hatch, R-Utah, said in a speech on the Senate floor.
``But I have great difficulty in the trusteeship of an entire
international union. I don't think the government or any court in
this nation is capable of being a trustee over a union.''
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., echoed Hatch's remarks. ``I think we're
getting on very, very thin ice here,'' he said.
   Two years ago, the government used a similar lawsuit to place
Teamsters Local 560 in Union City, N.J., under the control of a
court-appointed trustee.
   The former head of that local called the current lawsuit a
groundless attempt by the Reagan administration to break the
American labor movement.
   ``They want to cripple the Teamsters like 560. I don't think
they'll be successful,'' said Michael Sciarra, president of the
9,000-member local from December 1984 to June 1986.
   ``It's a dark day for labor,'' he said. ``I believe the
Republicans are out and they're looking for jobs for their friends.
It's all political. They always go after the strongest.''
   Dave Beck, who preceded Jimmy Hoffa as Teamsters president from
1952-57, said if there is corruption in the union it has ``no
influence over the great mass of the Teamster organization.''
   Beck, 94, now living in Seattle, denied the allegations of
pervasive corruption in the union.
   ``I don't think there's any merit to that at all and if so
there's been a terrific amount of inefficiency by the factors of
government from the national level clear on down,'' said Beck, who
served 2{ years in prison for embezzlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
