<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-RiverWatch     06-29 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-River Watch,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shrinking Mississippi River Attracts Curious Crowds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Indians, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents are flocking to the levee these
days to watch as the mighty Mississippi River slowly dries up.
   ``I've lived here all my life and I've never seen anything like
this,'' J.C. Bailey, a 66-year-old carpenter said Tuesday evening
as he gazed at the shrinking river.
   Bailey and his wife, Letha, were among about 200 people who had
gathered at John Edgar Point, just below downtown, to gawk.
   ``It's amazing,'' Bailey said as he surveyed the crowd. ``My
wife and I come here all the time to watch the barges. Usually,
we're the only ones here, but this time I had a hard time just
finding a place to park.''
   Like many of the gawkers, Vernon Reed brought along binoculars
and a camera.
   He pointed to a large sandbar in the middle of the river and
said, ``That sandbar wasn't there until three weeks ago. Now, it's
100 yards long and getting bigger every day.''
   Reed, a dentistry school professor, said he has been watching
the river daily for the past three weeks or so.
   ``The river has been dropping almost a half a foot a day,'' he
said. ``You can almost see it drying up right before your eyes.''
   According to the U.S. Corps of Engineers, the Mississippi is at
a record low. The water level at Memphis is 9.8 feet below sea
level, more than 20 feet lower than it was at this time a year ago.
   ``People are starting to find artifacts and other things that
have been under water for years,'' said Dorothy Gross, a
camera-toting Memphis bookkeeper. ``A woman recently found a fossil
on the riverbank that turned out to be a mastodon bone.''
   She and the others in the crowd watched intently as an Ultra
Light aircraft suddenly swooped down and landed on the newly formed
sandbar in the middle of the river. The on-lookers oohed and ahhed
as the craft paused on the sandbar for a moment and then took off,
looking like a huge dragonfly as it hovered just a few feet above
the water.
   An almost festive mood prevailed as the crowd combed the bank
for souvenirs or peered across the water, trying to spot a trace of
a sunken wreck purported to have been sighted on the Arkansas side
of the river.
   ``It's supposed to be over there, on the far side of the
sandbar,'' said Billie Ann Owen, who came down to look at the river
with her husband and 2-year-old son.
   ``I'm here to make sure they don't fall in,'' she said, laughing.
   James Owen, an insurance agent, said he was hoping to find an
artifact to commemorate the visit.
   ``Like everybody else here I'd be happy to go home with a belt
buckle or an arrowhead, something that hasn't been seen for a
couple of hundred years,'' he said.
   Owen added that he had come to the river to view history in the
making.
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime thing,'' he said. ``Or, at least
I hope it is.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is The Associated Press'
Southeastern states regional writer based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
