<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Rights 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-29 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Rights, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0472,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls For Free Expression But Police Drag Away
Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS two grafs for 5th graf pvs, `Just a ... better
respected.' with UPDATE on arrests. PICKS up 6th graf pvs, ```I
would ...' SUBS graf 17-end, bgng, `A spokesman ...,' with 5 grafs
to UPDATE with details.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after Mikhail S. Gorbachev said citizens
should be able to freely express their opinions, police broke up
two demonstrations in Moscow in a scene reminiscent of traditional
Soviet intolerance.
   ``Homeland'' was what protesters shouted Tuesday as 200 Crimean
Tatars gathered to demand they be allowed to return to their
homeland.
   Police moved in twice to drag off members of the disgruntled
ethnic group, carting them away in buses.
   On Pushkin Square, police arrested seven members of a group
called the Democratic Union, witnesses said. The group advocates a
multiparty system and an end to the Soviet military presence in
Eastern Europe.
   Today, participants in the demonstrations said the seven had
either been fined, jailed or summoned to court. The fate of the
arrested Tatars was unknown.
   In the Kremlin on Tuesday, Gorbachev told the first nationwide
Communist Party conference in 47 years that the civil rights of
Soviet citizes need to be better respected.
   ``I would like to dwell particularly on the political freedoms
that enable a person to express his opinion on any matter,'' he
said in his keynote address. ``The implementation of these freedoms
is a real guarantee that any problem of public interest will be
discussed from every angle.''
   But the Soviet leader warned that activities such as redrawing
borders and establishing political parties to challenge the
Communists' political monopoly would not be tolerated.
   He also said the Soviet legal system should ``guarantee strict
observance of the citizens' rights to the inviolability of private
life and the home, privacy of correspondence, postal and telegraph
messages.''
   The system must also ensure, he said, that a person is innocent
until proven guilty and that all people get equal treatment before
the law.
   Those rights and the right to speak out on the issues before
Soviet society have been violated since the time of dictator Josef
Stalin and must be restored, he said.
   After police carried away about 200 demonstrating Crimean Tatars
on Tuesday, a sobbing woman said: ``They took my husband!''
   The woman, in her 20s, was arrested a few minutes later.
   Two officers told a reporter the protesters were not being
arrested or taken to a jail, but merely removed from the area
because they were ``violating public order.''
   Stalin ordered all Crimean Tatars deported to Soviet Asia in May
1944 from their homes in the Ukraine. They were accused of
betraying their country while the Crimean peninsula was occupied by
the Nazis.
   The government dropped the collective war crimes charges in
1967, but the Crimean Tatars, who number about 300,000, were not
allowed to return home.
   On Pushkin Square, after police rounded up members of the
Democratic Union, several remaining group members addressed
separate crowds to promote their platform.
   Yevgenia Debrianskaya, a group member, said today that two of
those arrested were ordered jailed for 15 days, two were imprisoned
for 10 days and two were summoned to court in a few days. She said
she was fined $161.
   In addition, a leading Democratic Union member was arrested
Monday and sentenced to 15 days in jail for taking part in an
earlier demonstration, a spokesman for the group said Tuesday.
   Yuri Mityunov said the arrest of Igor Tsarkov was aimed at
keeping the group quiet during the party conference.
   Reshat Dzhemilev, a Crimean Tatar who lives in the Uzbekistan
capital of Tashkent, said today that he did not know what became of
countrymen arrested during Tuesday's protest.
   Moscow dissident Valery Senderov said that in previous cases,
the Tatars have been shipped home from Moscow and no legal action
taken against them.
   Dzhemilev said Crimean Tatars met Tuesday in Tashkent and
decided to strike at their workplaces after a reported
demonstration in the city by about 5,000 Tatars on Sunday.
</TEXT>
