<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Dissidents     06-29 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Dissidents,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Announces Release Of 46 Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced today the
release of 46 political prisoners, including prominent dissident
Kim Kun-tae, and said it would review the cases of other jailed
radicals.
   The Justice Ministry, in a brief statement, said the 46 would be
released Thursday from various prisons on parole. Ministry
officials said 453 common criminals would also be paroled.
   Opposition groups have been demanding the release of hundreds of
jailed dissidents they contend were imprisoned for political
beliefs or anti-government activity.
   Top opposition leader Kim Dae-jung told the National Assembly
today that more than 600 political prisoners remain in jail. He
called the continued detention of dissidents the main barrier to
political peace in South Korea.
   ``How can we talk about reconciliation and political development
while keeping in prison those patriots, numbering more than 600,
who fought for democracy?'' he said.
   About 20 relatives of political prisoners demonstrated earlier
today outside the headquarters of the governing Democratic Justice
Party to demand release of all prisoners. They were taken away by
police and released a short time later.
   Some opposition groups contend there are more than 1,000
political prisoners serving sentences or awaiting trial for
anti-government activity. Government officials say most of the
prisoners committed violent crimes or violated national security
laws.
   The dissidents to be released Thursday either demonstrated
repentence or served a third of their sentences, ministry officials
said. They said the cases of other dissidents will be reviewed on a
monthly basis for possible releases.
   Kim Kun-tae appeared to be the only prominent figure among those
to be released Thursday.
   Sentenced in 1986 to five years in prison for inciting unrest,
he recently received the Robert F. Kennedy award for human rights
and international human rights groups have been campaigning for his
release.
   Kim Dong-chul, a senior Justice Ministry official, said Kim
Kun-tae had demonstrated repentence because he told officials he
would continue his political activities, but would follow the law.
   Among those to be released are five people arrested in December
after opposition supporters staged a demonstration in Seoul over
alleged government vote rigging in presidential elections.
   Five labor activists and a number of members of a radical
student group are among the other dissidents, officials said.
   Also to be released are six men, former Korean residents of
Japan, who were convicted of spying for communist North Korea, the
officials said.
   Hundreds of political prisoners have been released in several
amnesties since last summer after the government of former
President Chun Doo-hwan bowed to demands for democratic reforms.
   President Roh Tae-woo said today in a speech to government and
governing party officials that his administration has made
considerable progress toward achieving full democracy. He said
there had been a dramatic improvement in political and human rights.
   Roh, a former general, backed opposition demands for direct
elections and democratic reforms exactly one year ago after
nationwide unrest. He won election in December after two opposition
candidates split the opposition vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
