<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0515,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 10th graf, `In 1985...' to ADD background. Pick up 11th
pvs, `Meanwhile, on...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar soared past the 133-yen mark today for
the first time in nearly seven months before falling back in active
trading in Tokyo. Share prices on the stock exchange also scored
heavy gains.
   The dollar closed the day at 132.40 yen, up 1.45 yen from its
130.95 yen finish on Tuesday. It broke the 133-yen level during the
morning session and briefly peaked at 133.40 yen before falling
back. The currency fluctuated mostly between 132.40-133.40 yen.
   ``It was a carbon copy of what happened yesterday (Tuesday),''
said King Ogino, a dealer at Goldman Sachs.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, during a regular news
conference Tuesday, ruled out the possibility that the Bank of
Japan would intervene in the market to prop up the yen.
   Ogino said the governor of the Bank of Japan, Satoshi Sumita,
also pushed the dollar up when he said the bank would not change
its monetary policy for now but would act ``flexibly'' if
necessary. He told reporters it was unlikely the dollar would
appreciate.
   ``The market moved up and down like a yoyo,'' Ogino said. Unless
the Bank of Japan is ready to step in, he said, currency dealers
were likely to test new highs.
   ``There is spare room for the dollar to go up,'' Ogino said.
   The U.S. currency last traded at the 133-yen level in early
December when it opened at 133.05 yen on Dec. 8. It closed that day
at 132.78 yen. Just last Friday, the dollar finished the week at
129.70 yen, its highest level in about four months.
   With Wednesday's gain, the U.S. currency has won back 3.45 yen
so far this week in two trading days. On Tuesday, it fell a slight
0.75 yen.
   The yen was trading as high as 242 to the dollar in September
1985 when the major industrial nations agreed to push the dollar
lower to help reduce the massive U.S. trade deficit, including its
large deficit with Japan. A lower dollar theoretically makes U.S.
goods cheaper and more competitive abroad.
   Meanwhile, on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the main market
barometer surged 209.24 points, or 0.76 percent, to close the day
at 27,607.33 points.
   Traders said steel issues led the Nikkei climb, but buying
interest also focused on heavy industrials and electricals.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 2.5 billion shares,
unchanged from Tuesday's figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
