<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CancerScreening     06-29 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cancer Screening,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Avoiding Cancer Screening Tests, Federal Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-two percent of women age 40 or older have
never had a breast X-ray to detect cancer, including 17 percent who
have never even heard of the test, a federal survey suggests.
   Only 17 percent of women in the age group had gotten the test
during the past year, although federal authorities recommend
getting one every year or two starting at age 40, and annually
after age 50.
   The test, called a mammogram, and other cancer screening tests
are not being used enough, said Maryann Roper, acting deputy
director of the National Cancer Institute.
   She described preliminary results of the federal survey Tuesday
at a seminar sponsored by the cancer institute and the
pharmaceutical firm Hoffmann-La Roche Inc.
   The survey, which asked a variety of questions about cancer,
included interviews with 3,297 women and 2,426 men.
   Among the results:
   _ 23 percent of women 18 or older had not had a Pap smear for
detecting cervical cancer in the previous three years. The
institute says all sexually active women in that age group should
have the test annually, or less frequently at a physician's
discretion if three consecutive Pap smears showed no problem.
   _ 72 percent of women 40 or older reported having a physical
screening exam for breast cancer, a number Roper said should be
higher because the exam is easily included in a routine physical.
   The most common reasons people gave for not getting tests were
that they had not heard of them, that they felt they did not need
screening, and that they had experienced no problems that would
prompt them to get such a test.
   Screening tests are supposed to be taken before any symptoms
develop, to catch cancers early.
   Roper said researchers were surprised to find that the cost of
mammograms was rarely cited as a reason for not getting one done.
She also said the use of mammograms appeared to decline with age,
even though the risk of breast cancer increases with age.
   Screening must become more widely used to cut overall cancer
death rates in half by the year 2000, a cancer institute goal,
Roper said. For example, some 80 percent of women will have to
follow the guidelines for breast cancer screening, she said.
</TEXT>
