<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-29 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls for 10 Percent Federal Minority Set-Asides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says the federal government
should set aside 10 percent of all contracts for minority-owned
businesses and put a Cabinet-level administrator in charge of
enforcing affirmative action programs.
   The Democratic presidential contender, speaking Tuesday night at
the annual convention of Operation PUSH, the civil rights
organization he founded, said laws on the books to help minorities
in contracting are empty without enforcement.
   ``That's the proclamation without the emancipation,'' he said.
   Jackson, who ran second in delegates in the primaries to
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, said an enforcement official
should be ``an economic ombudsman whose job it must be, fully
staffed, to demand affirmative action in every phase of government,
every contract.''
   Meanwhile, Operation PUSH officials at the convention said they
will examine the hiring and promotion practices of at least six
companies, beginning a process that could lead to an economic
boycott unless minorities are put in management and ownership
positions.
   The Rev. Willie Barrow, PUSH executive director, said officials
have targeted firms which she claimed appear to have few blacks in
top positions and that negotiations will be launched with the
companies.
   ``Boycott is the last resort,'' she said.
   Mrs. Barrow said PUSH will examine Red Lobster restaurants,
Payless Shoesource shoe stores, Carson Pirie Scott & Co. department
stores, and Toyota automakers.
   She also said the organization would ``look into'' makers of
Cadillac and Mercedes-Benz autos, and would continue action against
Revlon cosmetics, which has been the target of a PUSH boycott.
   Spokesman for the companies were not available for comment
Tuesday night.
   Jackson has led battles for agreements with private firms in the
past in which affirmative action timetables were established. He
told reporters at the convention that he believes strongly in
negotiating with companies over hiring and promotion practices.
   ``Boycotts only occur when negotiations break down,'' he said.
</TEXT>
