<HEAD>Six Army Officers Killed In Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army helicopter plunged into a canal
near Bangkok during a rain storm and killed six army officers,
including two close aides of army chief Gen. Chavalit Yongchaiyudh,
officials said today.
   Col. Anusorn Krisanaserani said the U.S.-made UH-1 Bell
helicopter was returning to the capital late Tuesday from the
Thai-Cambodian border when it crashed just north of Bangkok's Don
Muang International Airport.
   Anusorn identified the two aides as Col. Suppachai Rodpothong
and Col. Konthee Suvannarat.
   He said preliminary investigations indicated that bad weather
conditions may have been caused the crash.
   Local newspapers quoted police as saying that the helicopter's
rotor blades struck a power line before it plunged into the canal.
</TEXT>
