<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0605EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaymateKilled     06-29 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Playmate Killed,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Youth Admits Killing Playmate, Staging his Disappearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKWALL, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy who shot a playmate hid
the body beneath his bedroom closet and helped police in a weeklong
search before admitting that he accidentally killed him in an
argument, authorities said.
   ``He put his body down in the scuttle hole and then he came back
out and cleaned up the blood,'' said police Sgt. Mark Chamberlain
said Tuesday. ``He even told his mother later that he had spilled
some Kool-Aid.''
   The June 20 disappearance of Jason Daniel Powell, 10, drew
together hundreds of residents of this community of about 10,000.
Police had searched the other boy's house where Jason's body was
found, but were unaware of the crawl space beneath the flooring.
   ``At the time we were searching with the idea that he was still
alive somewhere. We thought maybe he was hiding out and that his
friends were protecting him,'' Chamberlain said. ``We were looking
for a boy, not a body.''
   The youth moved his friend's bicycle to a field two blocks away
from his home and joined in searches in the area, Chamberlain said.
   The search ended Monday when Carol Cade found Jason's badly
decomposed body beneath a closet in her home after smelling a
stench.
   After the discovery, the 10-year-old admitted to authorities
that he had shot Jason, but said he did not know the gun was
loaded, authorities said. The Dallas County Medical Examiner said
Jason suffered a single .22-caliber gunshot wound to the head.
   The boy, whose name was withheld by authorities, was questioned
and released to his mother, police said. The case has been turned
over to the district attorney's office, Police Chief Bruce Beaty
said.
   Officials would not elaborate on Mrs. Cade's relationship to the
boy, but friends said he was her son.
   ``They were in the living room playing video games and he wanted
to go outside and play but Jason said, no, that he wanted to stay
inside,'' said Jason's 18-year-old brother, Sean Powell, in an
account confirmed by police.
   ``He went into another room and came back with a pistol where
Jason was lying on the floor and said, `If you don't go outside to
the playhouse I'm going to shoot you,''' Sean said. ``And he shot
him once in the head. He died instantly.''
   Tuesday night, the single-story brick home where authorities
removed Jason's body after cutting away a section of flooring was
empty. Mrs. Cade had permission to return Tuesday afternoon, but
stayed away, Chamberlain said.
   Authorities and acquaintances said Mrs. Cade lived alone with
her two sons after a separation from her husband. The gun used was
found in her dresser drawer with one spent shell, Chamberlain said.
   ``He just panicked. He was scared. That's the only explanation I
can have for it, but I do believe him,'' said Powell, who returned
from his Navy station in Norfolk, Va., to help lead the search for
his brother.
   ``It must have been hell for a 10-year-old kid to kill his own
friend and not even know the gun was loaded.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
