<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Bring Some Welcome Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms and cooler weather soothed parts of the
drought-parched central United States early today, after setting at
least one record for rainfall.
   Madison, Wis., received 1.67 inches of rain on Tuesday, breaking
a 60-year-old mark of 1.62 inches.
   Despite a break in the 100-degree temperatures, health officials
in St. Louis reported another death Tuesday from Saturday's torrid
heat. An 87-year-old woman died of heat stroke, bringing to nine
the number of weather-related deaths there in a recent heat wave.
   In Colorado, a flash flood warning was issued Tuesday night for
parts of Gunnison County as the Ohio Creek flooded its banks and
water up to 4 feet deep surrounded homes north of Gunnison.
   Other heavy rainfall totals early today included 3.1 inches at
Oklahoma City, 2.14 inches at La Crosse, Wis., and 1.19 inches at
Laramie, Wyo.
   Severe weather accompanied the rain in some areas. Thunderstorms
in northwestern Oklahoma produced gusts to 62 mph that downed
trees. Strong thunderstorm winds also downed tree limbs and damaged
a mobile home and a barn.
   A thunderstorm in eastern Nebraska hurled gusts to 65 mph, while
thunderstorms in Montana dropped golf ball-size hail.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from the high
Plains to the middle Mississippi Valley early today, with
thunderstorms most numerous in eastern Nebraska and western Iowa,
two of the states worst hit by the drought.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms also dampened the
Rocky Mountain region, the Northeast and the Florida peninsula.
   The heat wave continued to break, with temperatures dropping to
the 40s and 50s in the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes
region and the northeastern states early today. Highs were in the
80s in parts of Kansas, Missouri, Iowa and Nebraska.
   The forecast for today called for widespread showers and
thunderstorms from the northern Rockies through the Missouri Valley
into the middle Mississippi Valley and Florida; showers and a few
thunderstorms scattered over much of New England; and mostly sunny
skies over the rest of the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected in the 60s from the upper Great
Lakes through the upper Ohio Valley into New England; in the 70s
from the upper Mississippi Valley into the lower Ohio Valley and
northern sections of the Middle Atlantic Coast region; in the 60s
and 70s in the Pacific Northwest; 100 to 105 degrees across parts
of the lower Mississippi Valley, the plains of the Rio Grande
Valley, the northern California valleys and the desert Southwest;
and in the 80s or 90s across the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 90 degrees at Las Vegas, Nev.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 65 partly cloudy; Buffalo 48
fair; Charleston, S.C. 66 fair; Cincinnati 69 cloudy; Cleveland 60
fair; Detroit 59 fair; Miami 80 fair; New York 72 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 72 cloudy; Pittsburgh 62 partly cloudy; Portland,
Maine 62 cloudy; Washington 74 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 62 showery; Dallas-Fort
Worth 77 fair; Denver 71 cloudy; Des Moines 82 thunderstorm;
Indianapolis 69 fair; Kansas City 84 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 65 cloudy; Nashville 71 fair; New Orleans 81 hazy; St. Louis
79 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 62 fair; Anchorage 55 fair; Las Vegas 90
windy; Los Angeles 65 partly cloudy; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake
City 76 cloudy; San Diego 64 fair; San Francisco 55 windy; Seattle
52 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 fair; Toronto 43 fair.
</TEXT>
