<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-StudentSlaying     06-29 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Student Slaying,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Sentenced In Student Slaying That Prompted Protests, One Gets
Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beijing court today sentenced one youth to
death and gave a second a suspended death sentence in the slaying
of a student whose death triggered protests for democracy and
better treatment of intellectuals.
   Three other youths got prison terms, and a sixth defendant was
found guilty of hooliganism but ``escaped criminal punishment,''
the official Beijing Evening News said.
   All six were tried in the Beijing Intermediate People's Court in
connection with a June 1 attack on several Beijing University
students outside an off-campus snackshop and liquor store.
   One of the students, 22-year-old Chai Qingfeng, was shot in the
head with BB gun pellets and beaten with a shovel. He died of his
wounds the following day.
   Nearly 1,000 fellow students marched that night from campus to
central Beijing's Tiananmen Square to demonstrate their sorrow and
demand tighter security for students.
   Over the next week, the target of the students' anger broadened.
Hundreds of posters, most anonymous, went up at Beijing University
denouncing government corruption and demanding democracy and more
funds for education.
   The unrest subsided after police sealed off Tiananmen Square and
intimidated the students into cancelling a second planned march.
   The six suspects were arrested within 48 hours of Chai's death
in an obvious effort to calm the students. The trial, which began
June 18 and was closed to the foreign media, also started with
unusual speed. There have been no official media reports on the
testimony.
   As had been expected, the court ordered the death penalty for
Wang Jian, an unemployed young man with a record of theft who was
identified as the ringleader. He was convicted of deliberate murder.
   In China, executions generally are carried out by a bullet to
the back of head.
   Ha Enming, also unemployed with a theft record, was convicted of
deliberate murder and given a suspended death sentence, to be
reevaluated at the end of two years of labor reform. The report
said he and Wang Jian hit Chai with an iron shovel.
   Wang Jianming and Wang Yonglian were convicted of hooliganism
and sentenced to 15 and seven years in prison, respectively.
   Wang Li, 22, the only woman defendant, was convicted of
harboring a criminal and sentenced to three years. Original press
reports claimed she took part in the attack on Chai and was charged
with hooliganism. The Beijing Evening News did not say if she was
cleared of this charge or give details of whom she hid. The sixth
defendant, Liu Bin, was convicted of hooliganism but not sentenced.
   Wang is a common name in China, and reports have not said if any
of the Wangs are related.
   The attack was the second killing of a university student in
Beijing in the past year. A student at the University of Foreign
Economic Relations was killed in December in a fight with two local
youths. They also were speedily arrested and tried, and one was
executed.
   About 1,000 students marched to government offices in central
Beijing to protest that killing.
</TEXT>
