<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Bomb, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>November 17 Claims U.S. Attache's Killing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with November 17 statement.
PICKS up 14th graf, `The killing ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek terrorist organization blamed for
previous assassinations of American diplomats claimed
responsibility today for a car-bomb blast that killed the U.S.
military attache as he drove to work.
   In a five page statement published in the left wing Athens
afternoon daily Ethnos, November 17 said it would attack more
Americans ``until the last Turkish soldier leaves Cyprus and the
last American soldier leaves our country.''
   U.S. Navy Capt. William Nordeen, 51, was killed Tuesday when a
booby-trapped car blew up next to his armor-plated automobile just
100 yards from his suburban Athens home.
   The blast ripped off the car's roof and flung Nordeen's
decapitated body into the yard of an unoccupied house.
   Many Greeks blame the United States for failing to prevent
Turkey's 1974 invasion of Cyprus after an Athens-inspired coup
there.
   About 30,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the northern third
of the eastern Mediterranean island, divided into northern Turkish
Cypriot and southern Greek Cypriot sectors.
   The November 17 statement described the 3,500-strong American
military presence in Greece as ``a force of occupation'' and said
``we will strike against anyone of its members or agent of its
secret services.''
   Police said the statement appeared to be genuine.
   ``I don't think anybody except November 17 had the expertise to
pull off something like this,'' a senior police officer said on
condition of anonymity.
   Nordeen and his British wife, Patricia, were due to leave next
month after completing a three-year tour at the U.S. Embassy in
Athens.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou said ``he was deeply grieved'' over
the killing and pledged to fight terrorism.
   ``We really cooperate with the countries of the European
Community and others to face terrorism, which we condemn
unequivocally,'' Papandreou said.
   In the past, Papandreou's socialist government has been
criticized by the United States for laxity in battling terrorism.
   Police said the car-bomb attack was immaculately planned and
detonated by a remote controlled radio device.
   Witnesses told police they saw two dark-complexioned men roaring
away on a motorbike immediately after the explosion. A police
spokesman said a stolen motorcycle was later found in the area.
   November 17 is named for the day in 1973 that troops and tanks
crushed a student rebellion against the 1967-74 dictatorship. The
group has claimed responsibility for the assassinations of Athens
CIA station chief Richard Welch in 1975 and of U.S. Navy Capt.
George Tsantes in 1983.
   The group also claimed responsibility for a failed car-bomb
attack last October against a bus carrying American servicemen.
   None of its members has ever been arrested.
   The killing came four days after Greek and American negotiators
wrapped up a seventh round of slow-moving talks for a new bases
accord. Officials have said the talks are making little progress
but haven't reached an impasse.
   A five-year accord signed by the Papandreou government expires
in December this year. Papandreou has said he is willing to
negotiate a new agreement, but that it must be approved in a
referendum before taking effect.
   Since the 1950s, the United States has operated two bases near
Athens and two on the island of Crete along with a dozen
mountain-top communications installations. In return, Greece gets
military credits totalling more than $340 million every year.
   Neighbors said Nordeen set out for work around 8 a.m. every day,
driving down the tree-lined street where several Western diplomats
live to the main Athens highway.
   The Minnesota native had earlier served as Assistant Naval
Inspector in Washington and with the U.S. Fleet in the Pacific
Ocean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
