<HEAD>Bombs Kill Seven In Assam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded in the northeastern
state of Assam, killing seven people and injuring 59, the United
News of India said today.
   Police blamed the blasts Tuesday on extremists from the Bodo
tribe who are fighting for a separate Indian state for Bodos.
   The explosions occurred near Barpeta Road, a town 85 miles north
of Dispur, capital of Assam, a tea-growing state bordering
Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   Two suspects have been detained in connection with the blasts,
UNI said.
   Authorities banned public assembly in the area in an effort to
prevent further trouble.
