<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChainSawMurder     06-29 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chain Saw Murder,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Teen Killer to Seek New Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former university professor convicted of
murdering a teen-age male prostitute and dismembering his body with
a chain saw will seek a new trial, his attorney says.
   Max Bernard Franc, 58, was found guilty of first-degree murder
Tuesday by a jury that deliberated less than three days.
   ``I've never been as disappointed in a verdict as I've been in
this verdict,'' deputy public defender Mark Kaiserman said, adding
he would appeal the conviction.
   Franc was accused of shooting Tracy Leroy Nute, 18, cutting up
the body in a bathtub and distributing the parts across 200 miles
of California. Franc claimed a man named Terry Adams committed the
gruesome killing last August. The prosecution contended Adams does
not exist.
   ``I think the jury did the right and justifiable thing,'' said
Deputy District Attorney Sterling Norris.
   Sentencing was scheduled for July 29.
   The prosecutor said he would seek the maximum possible sentence
of 25 years to life in prison, which would make Franc eligible for
parole in 12{ years.
   After the verdict, Kaiserman said he remains convinced of
Franc's innocence.
   ``I would describe him as a very passive individual who does not
have an assaultive bone in his body and would not be able to commit
this type of crime,'' the attorney said.
   A ruling by Superior Court Judge John H. Reid excluded critical
evidence from the trial regarding a potential suspect, Kaiserman
said.
   Jurors were never told that the man, Peter Krizek, had been
charged in a similar dismemberment case eight years ago. The last
of his four trials ended in a jury deadlock. Krizek testified
during Franc's trial that he had nothing to do with the Nute
killing.
   Franc, a native of De Pere, Wis., was a public administration
professor at California State University in Fresno until his arrest
last August.
   Jurors were told Franc lived a double life _ a conservative
professor in Fresno but a homosexual voyeur about 210 miles away in
West Hollywood, who paid young men to be photographed in sexual
poses.
   Nute, a runaway from Kansas City, Mo., who came to California to
be a movie star, wound up working as a prostitute.
   Franc was arrested after a chain saw he rented was returned with
blood and flesh in its works.
   The case against Franc was circumstantial. Forensic experts
found traces of blood throughout his West Hollywood apartment as
well as in his car. The murder weapon was found in Franc's
university office. A motorist identified Franc as the man he saw
sitting in a car near a freeway offramp where body parts were found.
</TEXT>
