<2ND_LINE>PM-Gas Explosion,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Kills Self, 82-Year-Old, Injures Nine Others; Toddler Found In
Rubble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who ignited a gas explosion that
leveled two row houses, killin himself and an elderly neighbor, had
threatened suicide for weeks and warned his teen-age daughter not
to come home, acquaintances said.
   Nine people were injured in Monday night's explosion, including
a 3-year-old boy who was found nine hours after the blast buried
under 10 feet of shattered brick and splintered wood. Onlookers
applauded as rescuers carried Harry Mertz out on a stretcher
Tuesday.
   The boy was listed in guarded condition today with second- and
third-degree burns on 11 percent of his body, said Phyllis Propert,
spokeswoman for St. Christopher's Hospital for Children.
   Richard Litostansky, a handyman neighbors say was distraught
over his wife's plans to leave him, ignited a gas line he opened in
his basement and set off the explosion, authorities said.
   ``Friends and neighbors have said he threatened suicide. For the
past several weeks, he's been talking it up pretty good. Apparently
he was in the basement, opened the gas line and blew it,'' police
Detective Mike Boyle said.
   Litostansky, 45, and Bernard Fink, 82, who lived in the
connecting row house, died in the blast. The injured included two
police officers.
   Litostansky stopped in two doors away at the corner bar, the
Stock Exchange, for a beer Monday night.
   ``When he came in, he was acting crazy and all. So I flagged him
for the night. He went up to the corner with his daughter. I could
hear him say, `I'm going to kill myself. Don't come home
tonight,''' bartender Dan Wallace said.
   Earlier in the day, Litostansky had said he would kill himself
because of plans by his wife, Penny, to leave him, said a friend,
Robert W. Jenkins.
   Jenkins, 36, said he tried to persuade Litostansky to leave the
gas-filled house and even offered him money.
   ``He just kept backing up. I knew something was going down,''
Jenkins said.
   ```I'm taking you with me, Bobby! You're my only friend!'''
Jenkins said Litostansky screamed to him from the basement. Jenkins
said he ran for the door and was on the top step when the blast
blew him onto the sidewalk.
</TEXT>
