<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForeignBorn-Health     06-29 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Born-Health,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign-Born Americans Spend Less Time Hospitalized Or Sick at
Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Native-born Americans spend more time in
hospitals or sick in bed at home, and visit doctors more
frequently, a federal study says.
   The National Center for Health Statistics compared the health of
native-and foreign-born residents of the United States, aged 18 and
over, and found that the newcomers appear to be the healthier group.
   Dr. Gerry E. Hendershot, author of the report ``Health of the
Foreign-Born Population: United States, 1985-86,'' said a number of
possible reasons could account for this difference.
   ``One factor that certainly is involved is the selectivity of
immigration to this country,'' he said in a telephone interview
this week.
   ``People with higher educations and professional skills have a
better opportunity to migrate to this country, so people coming
here tend to be from groups that have good health,'' he said.
   In addition, the Immigration and Naturalization Service does
some health screening, Hendershot said. Plus, ``immigrants tend to
be younger, on average, than the general population, and younger
people in general tend to be healther than older people.''
   Finally, he noted that the study was based on interviews with
58,682 households. By looking at household groups, the analysis
would not include transients, such as migrant workers, who may tend
to be in poorer health, Hendershot commented.
   He added that he hoped to undertake another study in the future
aimed at detailing the reasons for health differences.
   According to the survey:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Some 10.8 percent of native Americans had been hospitalized in
the previous year, compared to 9.5 percent of the foreign-born.
   _Reporting six or more contacts with a doctor or other health
professional in the year were 18.5 percent of natives and 16.2
percent of the foreign-born.
   _When it came to spending four or more days in the year staying
home sick in bed, native-born people led 22.8 percent to 18.8
percent.
   The difference between native-born and foreign-born people in
being sick in bed for four days or more covered all age groups up
to 65. Over age 65, however, the groups were similar to one another
_ 26.3 percent for natives and 27.6 percent of foreign borns.
   By sex, 18.5 percent of native-born males were sick in bed four
days, compared to 15.3 percent of foreign-born men. For women, the
figures were 26.8 percent for natives and 22.0 percent for those
from overseas.
   Turning to hospital stays, the 10.8 percent of natives
hospitalized in the prior year included 8.6 percent of men and 12.8
percent of women. Foreign-born people were hospitalized at a 9.5
percent rate, 7.0 percent for men and 11.8 percent for women.
   Six or more physician contacts during the year were reported by
13.3 percent of native men and 23.1 percent of women. The figures
for those born elsewhere were 10.6 percent for men and 22.5 percent
for women.
   The survey also asked if people were limited in any of their
activities by chronic physical problems.
   Some 17.6 percent of native-born Americans aged 18 and over
reported some such limitation. This included 16.9 percent of men
and 18.2 percent of women.
   Among the foreign born, 13.2 percent reported chronic health
problems limiting their activities. This included 11.9 percent of
men and 14.5 percent of women.
   Finally, people were asked to generally rate their own health.
   In this category, the share who said they considered themselves
in only fair or poor health was identical in both groups at 12.9
percent.
   However, the fair and poor category included 11.9 percent of
native men compared to 11.0 percent of foreign-born men. For native
born women, 13.8 percent said they were in fair or poor health,
compared to 14.6 percent of the foreign born.
   Of the approximately 156.6 million Americans aged 18 and over at
the time of the survey, about 14.9 million were listed as foreign
born.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
