<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArtTheft     06-29 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Theft,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Painting Stolen From Dutch Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTERLO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves stole a self-portrait of the
20th-century Dutch painter Charley Toorop from an isolated museum
in the woods, the Culture Ministry said today.
   The theft at the Kroller-Muller museum, about 10 miles north of
the eastern city of Arnhem, was the fifth reported in the
Netherlands in as many weeks.
   A museum guard reported Toorop's 1934 ``Self-Portrait'' missing
at about 4 p.m. on Saturday afternoon.
   The value of the 24-by-18-inch canvas is estimated at $20,000.
   Culture Ministry spokeswoman Annemarie Stordiau said there were
no suspects in the theft.
   Charley Toorop was born in 1891, the daughter of Dutch
impressionist Jan Toorop. Her work, which includes numerous
self-portraits, is marked by its brown and gray coloring. She died
in 1955.
   The Kroller-Muller museum, whose collection includes 19th- and
20th-century art, is in a nature reserve.
   Among the five recent thefts, the most spectacular occurred on
May 20, when three paintings worth up to $52 million _ including a
Van Gogh and a Cezanne _ were stolen from Amsterdam's Municipal
Museum. They were recovered by police 10 days later.
</TEXT>
