<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Politics,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Walks into Florida GOP Primary Fight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0453 to change category code to `p'; Speech
1:45 p.m. EDT; text prospect uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan finds himself inadvertently
in the middle of a Republican primary fight in Florida as he
launches what aides say will be an active campaign season on behalf
of GOP candidates.
   Reagan was flying to Miami today for a fund-raising spech on
behalf of third-term Rep. Connie Mack III, grandson of the
legendary baseball manager, who is seeking the seat of retiring
Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles.
   The president, who follows a policy of not interfering in
primary contests, accepted the speaking date weeks ago on the
assumption that Mack would be unopposed in the Sept. 6 Florida
primary.
   On Monday, however, U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, the prosecutor
who obtained a drug indictment against Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, resigned his federal post and jumped into the race.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked whether this made
the Miami speech inconsistent with Reagan's hands-off policy in
primaries, said, ``Well, circumstances have made it a little
inconsistent.''
   ``The president has campaigned for Connie Mack in the past and
stated his support for him,'' Fitzwater said. ``And so
circumstances simply created this situation.''
   Mark Mills, communications director for the Mack campaign, said,
``The president gave his word and his commitment to support Connie
Mack and I just think the president is following through on that.''
   Mills said the president's visit is expected to garner about
$600,000. He said Reagan would pose for photographs with people who
have raised at least $10,000 for the campaign or the state
Republican Party, and then speak at a luncheon. Luncheon tickets
were $500 or $1,000, depending on where the seats were.
   The spokesman said the money raised will be split evenly between
the Mack campaign and the state GOP. Merkle, who said he would not
come to the luncheon because he was not invited and didn't want to
be rude, said Monday the money should be put in escrow and held for
the winner of the primary.
   Reagan also planned to meet privately with leaders of Miami's
large Cuban-American community. Cuban-Americans have generally
supported Reagan although some have argued that he is softening on
Fidel Castro by negotiating on immigration, human rights and Angola.
   It is the president's fourth visit to Miami and his 10th to
Florida during his second term.
   Republicans would need a net gain of five seats to regain
control of the Senate. Although the president has appeared at
fund-raising events in Washington for GOP Senate candidates, this
is his first political foray out of the capital in the 1988
campaign.
   Fitzwater said there will be more.
   ``The political activities haven't been fleshed out yet, but as
a general matter, you will have fund-raisers attended by the
president _ some for the party, some for specific candidates,'' he
said.
   The White House spokesman said the extent of Reagan's
campaigning for Vice President George Bush, the apparent GOP
nominee for president, ``will all be firmed up in the next few
weeks.''
   Most Florida Republicans predicted that Merkle, starting late
with little financing, would have trouble catching up with the
well-financed Mack. Democrats have four candidates slugging it out
for their nomination _ U.S. Reps. Dan Mica and Kenneth ``Buddy''
MacKay, Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter and State Sen. Pat Frank
of Tampa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
