<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Gas Arab Schoolgirls Protesting Outside U.S. Consulate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials today said Israeli police hurled
tear gas at a group of Arab teen-agers staging a peaceful sit-in
outside the U.S. Consulate to protest the closing of their school.
   The officials said that they had asked that tear gas not be used.
   In the occupied West Bank, soldiers shot and wounded two
Palestinian youths, including one who was in serious condition,
hospital officials said. The army said it was checking the reports.
   American officials said the tear gas was thrown after the
schoolgirls left the consulate parking lot and as the half-hour
demonstration appeared to be breaking up.
   A consulate spokesman said the girls, mostly 13- and
14-year-olds, didn't throw stones and only held up handwritten
signs saying, ``Please Open Our Schools.'' About 30 police and riot
police were at the scene, said the official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. He said there were about 75 protesters.
   Police spokesman Rafi Levy put the number of demonstrating
schoolgirls at 200 and said tear gas was used only after the
students were warned to disperse.
   ``The use of tear gas is based on operational considerations of
the moment,'' Levy said. ``If there are official complaints about
police behavior, I would be glad to check them and respond.''
   Several Arab schoolgirls were arrested outside a school in east
Jerusalem after they tried to incite fellow students to protest,
Levy said.
   Israeli officials have closed 34 schools in Arab east Jerusalem
and the occupied West Bank, contending schools are a central spot
for anti-Israeli demonstrations since the Arab uprising began
nearly seven months ago.
   Since Dec. 8, 211 Palestinians and four Israelis have been
killed.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded two Palestinians, one 17 and the
other 22, in clashes near the casbah, or Arab marketplace, in the
West Bank city of Nablus, officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad and St.
Luke hospitals said.
   The teen-ager, shot in the stomach, was reported in serious
condition.
   In the West Bank city of Hebron, troops welded shut 24 stores on
a street where a Jewish settler was stabbed Friday, Palestinian
witnesses said.
   Israel radio said the army had detained members of a guerrilla
unit believed to be responsible for recent attacks in the Hebron
area.
</TEXT>
