<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Missiles     06-29 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Missiles,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Leaders Vow To Counter Arab Arms Buildup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said today that
Israel will bolster its military might to counter the buildup of
sophisticated missiles among Arab nations.
   Shamir's comments, carried on Israel radio, came a day after the
United States promised to help Israel develop an anti-ballistic
missile in response to ``ominous new military developments in the
region.''
   The new technology, designed to shoot down ballistic missiles,
will cost $120 million to $130 million dollars, the daily Jerusalem
Post said. The White House said the United States will pay about 80
percent of the costs.
   Recent reports have said that China is preparing to sell Syria
its most advanced surface-to-surface missile, the M-9. The M-9 has
a range of 375 miles.
   Speaking in the coastal city of Caesaria, Shamir said the
planned sale meant Israel would step up efforts to find a response.
   ``It obliges us ... to increase our eforts in preparing answers
to this threat. We are working in this field. There are answers and
we have to improve them,'' Shamir said.
   In Jerusalem, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres expressed concern
about ``the production of ground-to-ground missiles with chemical
warheads in the hands of governments that occasionally have lost
their balanced judgment and want to attack Israel just because they
have a weapon.''
   ``I'm sure and I know what I'm speaking about that (we)...will
find a reply to it,'' Peres said.
</TEXT>
