<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearAlert 1stLd-Writethru a0445 06-29 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Alert, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs first 2 grafs to CORRECT 37 plants to 37 reactors; adds
27 grafs with list of affected reactors.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is ordering
operators of 37 nuclear reactors to review safety procedures after
power levels fluctuated erratically at an Illinois plant.
   The alert for operators of boiling-water reactors was prompted
by a March 9 incident in which two pumps used to circulate water
through a Commonwealth Edison Co. reactor were shut off, triggering
an uncontrolled fluctuation of power, the NRC said Tuesday.
   The incident, at Edison's LaSalle Unit 2 near Ottawa, Ill.,
ended without harm after the reactor exceeded its rated capacity
and shut down automatically, the commission said.
   Although Commonwealth Edison handled the situation properly, the
problem could have been serious, NRC spokesman Frank Ingram said.
   ``The power was oscillating like mad, from 25 percent one minute
to something else the next,'' added Michael Mariotte, director of
the Nuclear Information and Resource Service, a private
clearinghouse for information about nuclear energy and radiation
effects.
   ``Then, it suddenly burst up to 118 percent of power before an
automatic setpoint finally shut the plant down,'' he said. ``We're
real concerned about what would have happened had that one
automatic setpoint failed.''
   However, an NRC official said there was no threat of a meltdown.
   ``We didn't know how much worse the situation could get,'' said
Ashok Thadani, its assistant director of engineering and systems
technology. ``There was the potential _ not likely, but the
potential _ of fuel damage. But a whole lot of other things have to
go wrong before you worry about a (radiation) release.''
   The incident was the first of its kind in the United States,
although engineers had calculated that such an event could occur
without warning at any of 37 U.S. plants using boiling-water
reactors, the NRC said. Most of the nation's 110 licensed plants
use pressurized water, rather than boiling water, to turn their
turbines.
   Edison spokeswoman Deborah Vestal said both pumps inadvertently
were shut off at the same time during routine calibration of
instruments, and the mixture of cold and hot water in the reactor
system when the pumps started again caused the power fluctuation.
   ``It was a one-in-a-million thing,'' Ms. Vestal said. ``At the
instant, we knew what was occurring and we knew what to do to cease
it. That's what was done. There was no damage to the fuel. There
was no release of radiation. There was no suffering at the plant.''
   Ingram called the incident a fluke but said the NRC is advising
utilities using similar reactors about what happened at LaSalle.
   He said the commission would make sure plant operators are
briefed so they can recognize the conditions leading up to
uncontrolled power changes and know what to do about them.
   ``The NRC is admitting it does not yet know of a hardware way to
fix the problem,'' Mariotte said. ``We would like to see them come
up with some sort of solution rather than telling the operators
simply to watch out for it.''
   These are the 37 reactors affected, listed first by the name of
the operating utility, followed by the name of the plant and then
its location.
   In some cases, the location name may vary from the name in
common use in the area. The Pilgrim, Peach Bottom and Browns Ferry
plants are not operating while their owners try to improve
management to satisfy the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   Boston Edison Co., Pilgrim, Plymouth, Mass.
   GPU Nuclear Corp., Oyster Creek, Forked River, N.J.
   New York Power Authority, Fitzpatrick, Scriba, N.Y.
   Niagara Mohawk Power Corp., Nine Mile Point units 1 and 2,
Scriba, N.Y.
   Northeast Utilities, Millstone 1, Waterford, Conn.
   Pennsylvania Power & Light Co., Susquehanna units 1 and 2,
Berwick, Pa.
   Philadelphia Electric Co., Peach Bottom units 1 and 2, Peach
Bottom, Pa.
   Philadelphia Electric Co., Limerick units 1 and 2, Pottstown, Pa.
   Public Service Electric & Gas Co., Hope Creek 1, Salem, N.J.
   Vermont Yankee Nuclear Power Corp., Vermont Yankee, Vernon, Vt.
   Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co., Perry 1, North Perry, Ohio.
   Commonwealth Edison Co., Dresden units 2 and 3, Morris, Ill.
   Commonwealth Edison Co., LaSalle Units 1 and 2, Seneca, Ill.
   Commonwealth Edison Co. and Iowa-Illinois Gas & Electric Co.,
Quad Cities units 1 and 2, Cordova, Ill.
   Consumers Power Co., Big Rock Point, Charlevoix, Mich.
   Detroit Edison Co., Fermi 2, Newport, Mich.
   Illinois Power Co., Clinton 1, Clinton, Ill.
   Iowa Electric Light & Power Co., Duane Arnold, Palo, Iowa.
   Nebraska Public Power District, Cooper, Brownville, Neb.
   Northern States Power Co., Monticello, Monticello, Minn.
   Carolina Light & Power Co., Brunswick units 1 and 2, Southport,
N.C.
   Georgia Power Co., Hatch units 1 and 2, Baxley, Ga.
   Gulf States Utilities Co., River Bend, St. Francisville, La.
   Middle South Utilities Corp., Grand Gulf 1, Port Gibson, Miss.
   Tennessee Valley Authority, Browns Ferry units 1, 2 and 3,
Decatur, Ala.
   Washington Public Power Supply System, WNP 2, Richland, Wash.
