<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Shultz     06-29 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Shultz,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz May Visit The Middle East In July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz may visit the
Middle East in July to try to push his regional peace initiative, a
senior American official said today.
   Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost said he discussed the
possibility of a Shultz visit during two days of talks with Israeli
leaders. Armacost spoke to reporters at Ben Gurion International
Airport before leaving Israel.
   Shultz has made three unsuccessful tours of the Middle East
since October in an effort to try to persuade Israel and Arabs
states to adopt his peace plan before American and Israeli
elections in November.
   The plan calls for convening an international conference under
the auspices of the United Nations to serve as a launching pad for
direct bilateral talks between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
   The conference would be attended by the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China.
   The idea is favored by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres but opposed
by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who fears the international body
would be hostile toward Israel.
   The Israeli daily Maariv reported that a decision on the Shultz
visit would be made after a meeting between Assistant Secretary of
State Richard Murphy and Vladimir P. Polyakov, head of the Middle
East desk in the Soviet Foreign Ministry. The two are to meet in
Europe next month.
   Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said the two-day
meeting would be devoted to ironing out U.S.-Soviet differences
over the role of superpowers in the proposed international forum.
   While the United States favors a largely ceremonial role, the
Soviet Union has insisted on more active involvement.
   The Kremlin also supports the participation of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. Israel views the PLO as a terrorist group
and refuses to negotiate with it, and the United States backs
Israel's position.
</TEXT>
