<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CluckingVisitors     06-29 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clucking Visitors,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Dozen Roosters Come To Roost ... And Roost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMSBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald and Sandy Smith's feathers aren't
exactly ruffled over their unexpected houseguests, but the visitors
are nothing to crow about either.
   For one thing, the Smiths are waking up earlier now, 4 a.m. to
be exact, because of the dozen roosters that mysteriously appeared
on their lawn and haven't left yet.
   The fowl visitors arrived in the dead of night and announced
their presence in the customary way: with loud crowing to greet the
dawn.
   ``Dawn comes earlier for roosters than it does for humans,''
Mrs. Smith noted.
   After their first rude awakening, the couple called the police,
but the only advice they could offer was, ``Make soup.''
   For the past 12 days, the chickens _ who appear to be all
roosters _ have resisted all efforts to get them to fly their
newfound coop. They roost among trees along the road at night and
wander over the Smiths' three-acre spread during the day.
   They even _ no jokes, please _ cross the road to explore the
woods and fields on the other side.
   The Smiths have taken the invasion good-naturedly, although to
Smith, it is becoming about as humorous as the old joke.
   ``It's funny, but when you're awakened at 4:30 every morning, it
loses its charm fast,'' he said.
   The Smiths have enlisted the aid of the Connecticut Humane
Society and a local 4-H Club, but the chickens have managed to
elude any attempts at capture. Now, the couple is offering free
chickens for the taking.
   If no one takes them up on the offer, nature will probably solve
the problem in its own manner.
   ``What's going to happen eventually is that they'll be picked
off by predators _ foxes, raccoons,'' Mrs. Smith said. ``And that
will be it.''
   Already, she said Tuesday, there appear to be only about seven
chickens left from the original dozen.
   But all things considered, she said, ``it's not a bad way to go.
They're probably having the time of their life, eating bugs,
roaming free. And then they come back and find bread under the
tree.''
   The Smiths have been feeding the birds. ``I don't know whether
we should be doing that,'' Smith said. ``But we felt sorry for
them.''
   Where the chickens came from in the first place remains a
mystery.
   If it was a prank _ the chickens arrived on the weekend that
many high schools staged graduation ceremonies _ the Smiths have no
clue as to who is responsible, or why.
   Wherever they came from, the chickens appear to like their new
home, and the Smiths are adjusting.
   ``If you don't like it, you shouldn't live in the country,''
Mrs. Smith said philosophically. ``I'm sure a lot of city people
wouldn't like it at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
