<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lefebvre     06-29 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lefebvre,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishop Ordains Priests On Eve of Bishop Consecration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre today
ordained 16 new traditionalist priests and urged them to join the
fight against the ``cancer of liberalism'' in the Roman Catholic
Church.
   The ordinations came on the eve of the consecration of four
bishops by Lefebvre, a move that will cause the first schism, or
split in the Church, in more than a century and lead to Lefebvre's
excommunication.
   At least 5,000 sympathizers watched the four-hour ceremony.
Several traveled up to 16 hours to reach this Swiss hamlet, the
birthplace of Lefebvre's St. Pius X fraternity.
   In his homily, the French-born prelate did not make any
reference to his threatened excommunication. The Vatican said it
will take effect as soon as he goes ahead with the consecrations
without papal approval.
   Lefebvre, whose movement is fighting reforms of the Second
Vatican Council, said it was since the Council in 1962-65 that
``the cancer of liberalism is spreading in the church.''
   ``Join the fight against liberalism, that false notion of
freedom,'' he said. ``And be prepared to suffer persecution.
Whatever you may be told, you will remain Catholic.''
   The Vatican announced it was canceling a symphony concert to
express its ``deep pain''' over the impending schism.
   The concert of Ludwig van Beethoven's ``Missa Solemnis'' was
scheduled for Thursday evening in the Vatican's Paul VI Auditorium,
as part of a series of cultural events marking the current Marian
Year.
   ``In anticipation of the grave act that will take place tomorrow
to the damage of the unity of the church, the president of the
Committee for the Marian Year announces that the concert is
canceled,'' a Vatican statement said.
   Today's ceremony brought to 220 the number of priests ordained
by Lefebvre in defiance of an earlier Vatican sanction imposed in
1976 that bars him from celebrating Mass or giving the sacraments.
   Many knelt during the ordination Mass, celebrated in Latin
according to the 16th century Tridentine rite. The Vatican Council
replaced it with the Mass in vernacular.
   Many in the crowd were seen buying a dossier on Thursday's
consecration that contained the text of a letter Lefebvre had
addressed to the four future bishops. In it, he charged that ``the
chair of Peter and the posts of authority in Rome are occupied by
antichrists.''
   That was why, he said, he felt obliged to proceed with the
consecrations ``so that the Catholic Church and priesthood will
continue to exist for the glory of God.''
   ``History will prove that he is right,'' said Mark Simmons, a
29-year-old accounting clerk who flew over from London for the
occasion. ``The threat of excommuncation does not impress me at
all. It cannot be valid. It would mean condemnation of 2,000 years
of church history.''
   Pierre Papay, a 43-year-old French businessman from Angers, said
he had come to demonstrate his ``total support'' for Lefebvre.
``I'm not worried at all by these threats.''
   Dominique Bochatay, a 30-year-old Swiss teacher, said ``there
will be no schism, certainly not by us. Schismatic are those who
break with the tradition, who break with Jesus Christ.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
