<DOCNO> AP880629-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraArms     06-29 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Arms,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long-Expected Indictment Draws Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors are keeping sealed a long-anticipated
federal indictment for illegally shipping arms to the Nicaraguan
Contras, but defense attorneys already are criticizing it for
penalizing soldiers, instead of the generals.
   The indictment was returned Tuesday by a Fort Lauderdale grand
jury that had called witnesses to testify about illegal arms
flights to El Salvador and private training for Nicaraguan rebels.
   A source close to the investigation, who spoke under condition
of anonymity, said the charges may not be made public for a week or
more.
   Among those expected to be charged are Tom Posey and some who
worked for him at the private Civilian Material Assistance group,
which claims to have collected $3 million for the Contras, said
Posey's attorney Doug Jones.
   He said the charges will be based on the Neutrality Act, which
bans private citizens from interfering in foreign affairs.
   ``I have a real hard time understanding why this will be a
violation of the Neutrality Act now when it wasn't three years
ago,'' Jones said.
   Posey and the organization were ``absolutely, totally''
encouraged by the Reagan administration to help the Contras and did
so openly, Jones said.
   Posey, who testified before the grand jury, said, ``Everything
we have done is legal.''
   ``We have never provided lethal weapons to the Contras,'' he
added.
   Critics of the investigation say it charges those who carried
out plans to aid the Contras, but not those who designed the plans.
   John Mattes, a federal public defender in Miami, says the U.S.
attorney's office dragged its feet in the investigation for
political reasons and tried to keep him from investigating the case
of his client, Jesus Garcia.
   Garcia, now out on parole from a minor weapons conviction, tried
to get a reduced sentence by saying he had participated in a
government-backed arms-smuggling operation out of Fort Lauderdale.
Mattes claimed prosecutors and FBI agents tried to convince him to
drop the defense investigation.
   Then-U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner, along with prosecutors later
called before a congressional committee, strongly denied the charge.
   Mattes said there is little likelihood the indictments will
include higher-ups who ordered the illegal arms shipments.
   ``It was coordinated by Robert Owen on behalf of Oliver North,''
Mattes said Tuesday. Owen, the State Department liaison to the
Contras, worked closely with North.
   ``The foot soldiers are never charged in wars, it is the people
that ordered them, that directed them.''
   The arms shipment that sparked the investigation was flown out
of Fort Lauderdale in March 1985 after supporters of the rebels
gathered 20mm cannons, M-60 machine guns, mortar shells, automatic
rifles and ammunition at various points around Miami.
   Steven Carr, a Civilian Material Assistance member who later
died of an apparent drug overdose in California, told The
Associated Press that the plane landed at Ilopango Air Force Base
in El Salvador. The arms were stored there for several weeks, he
said, and then sent on to Contra troops in northern Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
