<DOCNO> AP880629-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kuwait-Arms     06-29 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Arms,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwait Will Seek Jets Elsewhere If Congress Blocks F-18 Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait will seek arms from other countries if U.S.
lawmakers refuse to sell 40 F-18 jet fighters to the Arab nation,
Kuwait's foreign minister said today.
   ``We have a variety of alternatives in case the U.S. Congress
blocks the deal,'' Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah told reporters. ``We are
not obliged to purchase our needs from the United States. But what
we seek is good quality.''
   The tiny, oil-rich Persian Gulf state, which borders the
Iran-Iraq war zone and is seeking to upgrade its air defenses, has
been attacked and threatened by the fundamentalist regime of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, which accuses it of aiding Iraq.
   Sabah's statement coincided with a report that Kuwait was
drawing $5.5 billion from its petrodollar reserves to buy new
weapons.
   He added: ``Kuwait's policy is based on the diversification of
weaponry sources regardless of the manufacturing country.''
   Kuwait bought Strela anti-aircraft missiles from the Soviet
Union in 1984 after Congress blocked the sale of U.S.-made Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles.
   Congress has blocked other plans by the administration to sell
advanced fighter jets, missiles and other hardware to Arab
countries on the grounds they could be used against Israel.
   Congress is expected to decide next month whether to approve or
reject the $2 billion sale.
   The sale of the F-18, the United States' most sophisticated
fighter-bomber, would be the first to an Arab country. Only Canada,
Australia and Spain have purchased the aircraft.
</TEXT>
