<DOCNO> AP880629-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Tito     06-29 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Tito,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Call For Reappraisal of Late President's Role</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of prominent intellectuals
has issued the strongest statement yet calling for a reappraisal of
Josip Broz Tito's role in leading the country into its worst social
and economic crisis.
   The 19-member Committee in Defense of Intellectual Freedoms, in
a statement to the Yugoslav leadership, also called for an end to
official veneration of the late president, the founder of Communist
Yugoslavia who died in May 1980.
   A copy of the statement, received by the Associated Press on
Wednesday, said Tito is responsible for creating an undemocratic,
repressive political system ``which has thwarted progressive
development of the society.''
   ``Tito's role in making crucial political decisions and his
absolute power in shaping Yugoslav policies were so great that the
present-day position of the country _ and particularly its current
deep social crisis _ cannot be understood or explained without a
comprehensive and objective, scientific and critical reappraisal of
his historical responsibility,'' the statement said.
   Tito was the undisputed leader of Yugoslavia for 35 years until
his death. In spite of growing public disapprobation, criticism of
his policies is still considered a criminal offense.
   In addition to rising ethnic tensions, Yugoslavia is faced with
a $21 billion foreign debt, 170 percent inflation, 15 percent
unemployment, dropping living standards and growing labor unrest.
   The influential unofficial group, consisting of a number of
prominent university professors, authors, artists and scientists,
issues regular statements on political issues, but observers said
they could not recall previous instances where Tito's policies were
questioned in such a way.
   ``There can be no way out of the present economic, political and
moral crisis affecting Yugoslav society without a thorough critical
evaluation of past Yugoslav policies,'' the statement said.
   The constitution adopted in 1974 under Tito is generally blamed
for the country's woes. It granted wide autonomy to the six often
factious republics and two provinces.
   The statement called for a ``dispassionate'' assessment of
Tito's role in the government's repressive measures against
dissidents, particularly against those incarcerated on ``one of
modern Europe's most sinister prison camps _ Goli Otok.''
   Goli Otok, an island off the central Adriatic coast, was used as
an internment camp for alleged opponents of the government after
Yugoslavia's break with the Soviet bloc in the late 1940s.
   Several thousand are said to have died in detention from ill
treatment by prison authorities.
   The statement criticized Tito's non-aligned foreign policy for
having ``isolated our country from its natural cultural,
historical, economic and political surrounding'' in Europe.
   Tito was one of the founders of the non-aligned movement in the
late 1950s and early 1960s.
   Instead of paving the way for Yugoslavia's political and
economic integration in western Europe, the focus of Tito's foreign
policies remained exclusively on Africa and Asia, the statement
said.
   The forum also criticized Tito's lavish lifestyle, demanding to
know ``the real costs of his rule.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Wonder-Mayor     06-29 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Wonder-Mayor,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stevie Wonder Mulls Run for Detroit Mayor _ Someday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stevie Wonder says he is serious about becoming
mayor of Detroit.
   Not right away, mind you, but whenever Coleman Young, the
long-serving mayor, is ready to step aside, the Motown recording
star says he could step into the world of big-city politics.
   ``I think he could do a good job, too,'' Young, a Wonder fan,
said when told of the singer's political aspirations during an
appearance in Boston with likely Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis.
   The one-time child prodigy floated the Wonder-for-mayor idea in
an interview Tuesday on Detroit radio station WJLB-FM.
   ``I hope someday, and this is really going to shock you, ...
someday I probably will think about running for mayor of this city,
straight out,'' Wonder, 38, told talk show host John Mason.
   Mason, a friend of Wonder who ran into the singer in Detroit at
the closed circuit airing of the Mike Tyson-Michael Spinks
heavyweight boxing fight, laughed and asked Wonder if he was
serious.
   ``I'm very serious,'' he replied.
   Wonder, however, said he has no immediate plans to challenge
Young, whose term expires in 1989.
   ``Coleman, don't worry,'' Wonder said. ``Not yet.''
   Young, 70, has been mayor since 1974 and has shown no
indications of relinquishing the job. Asked if he had decided
whether he would run again, Young said, ``If I have, I haven't
announced it.''
   Wonder said he believes solutions exist to the problems of drug
abuse, teen-age gangs and the breakdown of the family structure,
but ``people really have not attacked those problems. I do believe
problems have solutions.''
   Wonder, who was born in Saginaw and raised in Detroit, achieved
his first success in the music business in Detroit and still
records for the Motown label, now based in Los Angeles. Its sale to
MCA Inc. was announced Tuesday.
   His hits include ``Sir Duke,'' ``Isn't She Lovely?'' and ``You
Are the Sunshine of My Life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary     06-29 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Opens With Reform On Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's parliament, expected to make
significant changes in the government and discuss economic reforms,
began meeting for the first time today under new Premier Karoly
Grosz.
   Grosz led a new generation of communist leaders into power
during a national party conference last month.
   During the opening day of its spring session, members of
parliament elected Bruno F. Straub as president, a largely
ceremonial post. Straub had been virtually assured parliamentary
approval after he was nominated last week by the communist party's
Central Committee.
   The conference marks the end of Janos Kadar's 32-year leadership
of Hungary and paves the way for sweeping economic reforms Grosz
and other officials say are necessary to overcome economic
stagnation and cope with the highest per capita foreign debt in
Eastern Europe.
   Grosz replaced Kadar as party chief last month.
   ``The Central Committee of the Hungarian Socialist Workers'
party and the National Council of the Patriotic People's Front
forwarded joint personnel proposals on filling leading posts of the
presidential council,'' the news agency MTI said in a terse report
in announcing the session opening.
   Grosz became premier in June 1987 and won international
recognition for his determination to push through a program of
unpopular austerity measures, including the introduction of
personal income and value-added taxes.
   However, Grosz has said in recent interviews that his government
has failed so far to revitalize the stagnant economy.
   Proposed government changes at the current session include the
creation of a new Cabinet position, minister of state, for Imre
Pozsgay, a key advocate of political change to accompany economic
reforms.
   He is to be entrusted with as yet unspecified tasks that are
likely to include overseeing reforms.
   Soviet bloc parliaments traditionally rubber-stamp party
decisions, but Hungarian parliament sessions have increasingly been
marked by intensive debate since some non-party candidates were
allowed to run for the assembly in 1985.
   Straub, 74, replaced Karoly Nemeth, 67, who has been officially
on sick leave since June 1. Nemeth was dropped from the Politburo
in May.
</TEXT>
