<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Victims 1stLd-Writethru a0583-a0584-a0586-a0591
06-29 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Victims, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583-a0584-a0586-a0591,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, refusing to give new
protection to crime victims, today severely limited state efforts
to shield young sex abuse victims when they testify at criminal
trials.
   The justices, voting 6-2, overturned the conviction of an Iowa
man sentenced to 10 years in prison for sexually molesting two
13-year-old girls.
   The court said the defendant's rights to a fair trial and to
confront his accusers appear to have been violated by the use of a
one-way screen that was placed in front of him at trial to prevent
the children from seeing him.
   The decision could jeopardize other efforts to protect
witnesses, such as videotaped testimony.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the court, said such one-way
screens violate a defendant's right to confront his accusers.
   ``It is difficult to imagine a more obvious or damaging
violation of the defendant's right to a face-to-face encounter,' he
said.
   Scalia said the defendant's rights were not outweighed ``by the
necessity of protecting victims of sexual abuse.''
   Most states have approved the use of some form of protective
device in child abuse cases when young witnesses testify.
   Today's case stems from the conviction of John Avery Coy on sex
molesting charges.
   A screen was placed in front of Coy in court to shield the girls
from seeing him when they testified. Prosecutors said the device,
which allowed Coy to see the girls, was intended to safeguard the
children from possible emotional trauma.
   A state law presumed children under 14 would be traumatized in
such situations.
   But Coy's lawyers said the screen made a guilty verdict
practically inevitable by creating a presumption he was guilty.
They also said the screen deprived Coy of confronting the girls
face to face, violating a constitutional right intended to yield
honest testimony.
   The lawyers said the screen was particularly prejudicial because
in order for it to function properly the courtroom was darkened and
a panel of bright lights was directed at the device.
   Coy's lawyers said there was no evidence the girls were in
danger of being traumatized.
   They also argued that the judge in the case mistakenly may have
believed the state law compelled him either to order the one-way
screen or to have the girls testify outside the courtroom on
closed-circuit television.
   Prosecutors initially asked the judge to permit the girls to
testify via closed circuit TV. Coy's lawyers objected to the
request. The judge overruled the objection but then ordered the
screen used.
   The screen resembled an oversize school blackboard.
   The Iowa Supreme Court, in upholding Coy's conviction, said the
judge was not obligated to determine that the screen was necessary
or that it served a compelling state interest.
   The children were attacked while they were in a makeshift tent
in their backyard, adjacent to Coy's home. They were unable to
identify their assailant, who was masked and shined a flashlight at
them.
   There was circumstantial evidence that led police to charge Coy
with the attack, including testimony by the girls that their
attacker wore his watch midway up his arm with the face turned
inward. Coy was under arrest on an unrelated charge when police
came to suspect him of the attack on the girls.
   The Supreme Court has ruled previously that stigmatizing
defendants in certain ways may violate their rights. For example,
the court has struck down such practices as requiring defendants to
wear shackles, leg irons or prison uniforms while appearing in
court.
   But the justices have held even inherently prejudicial courtroom
procedures may be allowed when they promote an essential state
policy.
   The court sent today's case back to the Iowa courts for further
hearings.
   The justices said the conviction against Coy could be reinstated
only if the lower courts determine that the use of the one-way
screen was a ``harmless error'' and there is proof beyond a
reasonable doubt Coy would have been convicted even if the screen
had not been used.
   Dissentimg were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Harry A.
Blackmun. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not take part in the case.
   The case is Coy vs. Iowa, 86-6757.
</TEXT>
