<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Politics, Hold-for-Release Ld-Writethru, a0560,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release at 1:45 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Hits Dukakis Record on Taxes and Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with material from Reagan's prepared speech at
fund-raiser for Rep. Connie Mack, FOR RELEASE at 1:45 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today branded likely Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis a ``true liberal'' who would
raise taxes and ``restore the heavy hand of government'' in
American lives.
   In his most direct attack yet on the Massachusetts governor who
is virtually assured of opposing Vice President George Bush in the
fall election, Reagan told a Republican Party fund-raising event
``the sad truth is that whenever liberals talk about `reducing the
deficit,' it's just a code word for boosting taxes.''
   ``The $64 billion question is this: Should we expect that if the
Democrats' all-but-certain presidential candidate is elected that
he would raise taxes?'' the president asked. ``In fact, he just
did.''
   Reagan, making an appearance on behalf of Rep. Connie Mack III,
who is seeking the Republican nomination for the Senate seat being
vacated by Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., said that in the last five
years, Dukakis ``has increased Massachusetts' state spending at
double the rate of federal spending.''
   Although the growth in federal spending has been slowed during
the Reagan years and the deficit has been cut, largely through the
Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing act and a deal Reagan struck with
congressional leaders last fall, the president has presided over
the largest federal budget deficits in history. Reagan has blamed
Congress for that, even though he has never submitted a balanced
budget to Capitol Hill.
   In making the trip to Miami today, Reagan inadvertently put
himself in the middle of a Republican primary fight in Florida.
   The president, who follows a policy of not interfering in
primary contests, accepted the speaking date weeks ago on the
assumption that Mack, grandson of the legendary baseball manager,
would be unopposed in the Sept. 6 Florida primary.
   On Monday, however, U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, the prosecutor
who obtained a drug indictment against Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, resigned his federal post and jumped into the race.
   In his speech to the fund-raising luncheon, Reagan noted Mack's
connection to baseball and said that ``next year, thanks to you,
Washington will have a new winning team, and I mean real major
leaguers: Sen. Connie Mack and President George Bush.''
   ``What the 1988 elections are all about is whether we continue
to build on that progress and move ahead to an even brighter
future, or whether he hesitate and return to those worn-out
policies that bring high taxes, low growth and a loss of direction
and purpose,'' he said.
   ``And each time the people have made the same decision: to
continue in the direction of economic freedom, entrepreneurship and
individual opportunity,'' he said. ``And to move away from the
heavy hand of government which seeks to control the people and the
economy.''
   ``So, yes, the man expected to head up the Democratic ticket
that Connie faces is a true liberal who, instead of controlling
government spending, raises taxes,'' Reagan said.
   On another subject, the president vowed that he would make no
concessions with Cuba's Fidel Castro to warm relations between the
United States and the island nation.
   ``There is an unbridgeable gulf between the governments of the
United States and Cuba,'' he said. ``It is the gulf between freedom
and tyranny. And as far as this administration is concerned,
freedom for Cuba, liberty for her people, is a non-negotiable
demand.''
   Mark Mills, communications director for the Mack campaign, said
Reagan wanted to go ahead with his appearance despite Merkle's
entry into the GOP primary race.
   ``The president gave his word and his commitment to support
Connie Mack and I just think the president is following through on
that,'' he said.
   The president's visit is expected to garner about $800,000.
Mills said Reagan would pose for photographs with people who have
raised at least $10,000 for the campaign or the state Republican
Party, and then speak at a luncheon. Luncheon tickets were $500 or
$1,000, depending on where the seats were.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the extent of
Reagan's campaigning for Bush, the apparent GOP nominee for
president, ``will all be firmed up in the next few weeks.''
</TEXT>
