<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Haiti     06-29 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four More Aides to Deposed President Manigat Released</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Four aides to deposed President
Leslie Manigat were released from jail after a one-week
incarceration, Radio Haiti Inter reported today.
   Roger Savain and his son Roger Jr. were set free from the
political prison Fort Dimanche on Tuesday afternoon, the station
reported. It said two other other former Manigat aides, Jean-Yves
Noel and Narcaisse Lescouflair, also were freed.
   The elder Savain had been Manigat's information minister. The
station didn't say what roles the others held in Manigat's
government.
   The four said in an interview on state-run television that they
were treated well in jail. It was unclear whether charges ever were
filed, whether the four were interrogated, or whether they were
simply locked up.
   Capt. Isidore Pongnon, commander of Fort Dimanche, told Haiti
Inter that ``seven or eight'' more aides to the deposed president
still were being held but would soon be released.
   More than a dozen aides and advisers to Manigat, including at
least three U.S. citizens, were arrested in the hours after Lt.
Gen. Henri Namphy installed himself in the National Palace on June
19.
   Two days earlier, Manigat had fired Namphy, at the time the
army's commander-in-chief, and placed him under house arrest.
   On Tuesday, the government announced the release of four former
Manigat aides. The government identified them as U.S. citizens
Robert Benodin, Frantz Jean-Louis and Jean Bogart; and Harry
Carrenard, a Haitian-Canadian with double nationality.
   Carrenard was Manigat's minister of social affairs.
   Those still under arrest include Lionel Desgranges, Manigat's
former chief of staff.
</TEXT>
