<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0607 06-29 0954</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0607,960</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Reagan remarks for release at 1:45 p.m. EDT; updates with
Reagan, Bush in top 8 grafs, picking up in 2nd graf pvs, The
Massachusetts</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Blasts Dukakis; Dukakis Talks Over Veep Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis got down to serious talk about a
running mate today, beginning private meetings at the Capitol with
senators including some mentioned as possible candidates, while
President Reagan joined the campaign fray by blasting Dukakis as a
liberal sure to raise taxes.
   Vice President George Bush, the likely Republican presidential
nominee, said today in a foreign policy speech in San Francisco
that sweeping changes being proposed by Soviet Leader Mikhail
Gorbachev should be viewed with optimism, but he added, ``The cold
war is not over.''
   In a speech to the World Affairs Council, the vice president
credited America's military buildup for a change in Soviet
thinking. ``My point is that it was eight years of American
strength that confronted the Soviet Union with the true costs of
aggression and the necessity of reform,'' Bush said.
   Reagan, in remarks prepared for delivery at a GOP fund-raising
event in Miami, referred to Dukakis, though never mentioning him by
name, as a ``true liberal.'' And he said, ``The sad truth is that
whenever liberals talk about `reducing the deficit,' it's just a
code word for boosting taxes.''
   ``The $64 billion question is this: Should we expect that if the
Democrats' all-but-certain presidential candidate is elected that
he would raise taxes?'' the president asked. ``In fact, he just
did.''
   Dukakis recently signed a cigarette tax designed to head off a
deficit in the Massachusetts state budget.
   Reagan, taking credit for the 1980s economic revival in
Massachusetts, said Dukakis ``has spent every dime and more of the
revenue generated in his state by the eagan-Bush recovery. And
since 1986, while the federal budget deficit has been cut sharply,
his deficit in Massachusetts has ballooned.''
   The Dukakis administration says the state budget will in fact be
in balance, as mandated by law, at the end of the fiscal year on
Thursday.
   The Massachusetts governor and certain Democratic presidential
nominee also planned to travel to the Midwest late today and, like
Bush, highlight the hardships caused by the long dry spell.
Dukakis, who earlier said he was ``enjoying the process'' of
selecting a running mate, said nothing to reporters as he arrived
at the Capitol today.
   Bush, previewing the foreign policy speech he was to give to the
World Affairs Council in San Francisco today, said Tuesday that
Americans should be ``very, very wary'' about whether Gorbachev's
call for sweeping changes in the Soviet Union actually will lead to
``a fundamental departure from their Marxist system.''
   On the other hand, Bush said Gorbachev should be encouraged to
move ahead with his twin programs of glasnost, or opennesss, and
perestroika, or restructuring.
   In interviews Tuesday, Bush said he was not worried about a
Gallup Poll for the Times Mirror Corp., released this week, which
showed him running 13 points behind Dukakis.
   ``I like to come back,'' he said. ``I think I'm going to win.''
   Bush was heading back to Washington after a brief stopover in
Appleton, Wis.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, was spending today on Capitol Hill in
meetings with as many as 30 Democratic senators. Among them,
perhaps, will be his eventual choice for a vice presidential
nominee.
   Sources say the Dukakis campaign is seeking exhaustive
background information, even driving records, from potential
candidates, to avoid any embarrassing surprises after the ticket
has been set.
   The most recent among the possible candidates reportedly
declining to be considered is Rep. Thomas Foley of Washington, the
House majority leader.
   At a joint appearance Tuesday in Boston with Dukakis, Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., said the ``betting on Capitol Hill seems to be
John Glenn and Lloyd Bentsen as the front-runners'' for the No. 2
spot.
   Dukakis laughed when told that the Ohio or Texas senator was the
sure winner. ``I'm not a betting man,'' he said.
   Republican party sources, meanwhile, said Tuesday that New
Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean has been chosen to deliver the keynote
speech at the Republican National Convention in August in New
Orleans. The selection could be announced as early as today, the
sources said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Bush was
attracted to the governor's views, outlined in his book ``The
Politics of Inclusion,'' on ways to reach beyond the GOP's
traditional wealthy, white-collar base.
   Although Kean has also been mentioned as a potential running
mate for Bush, Kean said Tuesday, ``I'm doing everything I can to
make sure he doesn't come to me.''
   Former U.N. Ambassador Jeane J. Kirkpatrick will be a featured
speaker at the GOP convention, it was announced Tuesday.
Kirkpatrick had endorsed Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole for
president during the primaries.
   Republican party chief Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. said there was no
link between the announcement and the Democrats' choice on Monday
of Texas Treasurer Ann Richards as their convention keynote speaker.
   While in California, Bush endorsed the recommendation of
President Reagan's AIDS commission that victims of the deadly
disease should have federal protection from discrimination on the
job, in schools and elsewhere.
   Reagan has yet to take a position on the recommendation, and
Bush supported the president, adding: ``I've got a different role
here. I want to say what I think.''
   Jesse Jackson, in a speech Tueday at the 17th annual convention
of his operation PUSH, said the federal government should be
required to set aside 10 percent of all contracts to businesses
owned by minorities. He also said a Cabinet-level administrator
should be put in charge of making sure affirmative action programs
are enforced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
