<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0468 06-29 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 1 graf in 3rd section to update</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developments at a glance in the investigation
into allegations of fraud and bribes paid by defense contractors
and consultants to procurement officials at the Defense Department:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEESE BLAMES CONGRESS FOR EXCESSIVE REGULATIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III said defense contractors that
are targets in the current probe may have adopted an attitude of
``We've got to get ours now'' due to congressionally imposed
``layers of requirements'' on Pentagon officials dealing with the
contractors. But Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., disputed Meese's contention,
saying, ``I don't know of any rule or law that's passed that would
entice someone to sell a government secret for money.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEESE RECUSES HIMSELF FROM INVESTIGATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Meese, who answered reporters' questions about the investigation
Tuesday, had recused himself from the probe the previous day
because his own defense lawyers are representing clients involved
in the case, Justice Department officials acknowledged Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PENTAGON'S TOP PROCUREMENT OFFICIAL SOUGHT TO LIMIT SEARCHES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Robert Costello, undersecretary of defense for acquisition,
wrote a memo to Carlucci last month asking that top Pentagon
officials be given the authority for prior approval of search
warrants for defense contractor facilities. Costello sought the
authority after investigators on Feb. 25 searched the Electronic &
Space Division of Emerson Electric Co. near St. Louis in a separate
fraud investigation, but Carlucci rejected the idea.
   Testifying today before a House committee, Costello defended the
memo. He said the search he complained about should not have been
undertaken without prior review at the Pentagon. ``The people at
the local level had taken, perhaps, overly aggressive actions,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FORMER NAVY SECRETARY KNEW OF PROBE BUT KEPT SECRET FROM CARLUCCI</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Former Navy Secretary James Webb said the Naval Investigative
Service told him last fall that a member of the Navy headquarters
staff and Melvyn Paisley, a former assistant Navy secretary, were
under investigation in the defense fraud case. Webb said officials
told him Paisley was a ``central figure'' in their investigation.
But Webb said he consciously decided not to tell Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci about the probe because he figured authorities
would tell Carlucci when and if they wanted him to know about it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEINBERGER KEPT CRITICAL PENTAGON STUDY AWAY FROM CONGRESS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger refused for six
months to send Congress a study done by the Defense Investigative
Service that was highly critical of the way most defense
contractors handled classified documents, sources said. The report
was completed in April 1987 but not sent to Congress until October.
</TEXT>
