<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JPLAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0594 06-29 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-JPL Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0594,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Researchers Burned In Jet Propulsion Lab Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with workers still in serious
condition today, quote from spokeswoman. Pickup 3rd graf, `The
lab...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two researchers were seriously burned
when a piece of equipment broke and sprayed them with a corrosive
chemical at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, officials said.
   Stanley P. Sander and Valerie Lang, both chemists, were listed
in serious condition today at Sherman Oaks Burn Center, said
spokeswoman Johna Rogozin. ``Their condition really has not changed
at all since yesterday,'' she said.
   The lab was evacuated and sealed following the accident, said
lab spokesman George Alexander. He said results of an inspection to
determine the accident's cause were expected to be completed
sometime today.
   The Jet Propulsion Laboratory runs America's unmanned space
exploration program under contract to the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration. It is operated by the California Institute of
Technology.
   The two researchers were burned by the chemical bromine as they
tried to free a stopped valve in a glass-tubing network. The valve
broke and drops of the chemical splashed onto the skin on their
forearms, hands and wrists, Alexander said.
   The two were working under a safety hood at the time of the
accident in JPL's Atmospheric Chemistry Laboratory.
   The researchers were conducting an experiment into the roles of
bromine and chlorine in formation of the ozone hole in the Earth's
upper atmosphere, Alexander said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
