<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Medicaid     06-29 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Medicaid,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Says Federal Judges May Settle State-Federal Medicaid
Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in an $11.3 million victory
for the state of Massachusetts, ruled today that federal judges
have the power to settle disputes between states and the federal
government involving Medicaid funds.
   The 6-3 ruling reinstated a federal judge's decision that
Massachusetts may recover $11.3 million in Medicaid money to care
for the mentally retarded that the federal government had withheld.
   Medicaid is a joint federal-state program to provide medical
care to the financially needy. States administer the day-to-day
operations and the federal government pays part of the costs,
``reimbursing'' the states in advance.
   From 1978 through 1982, Massachusetts received several hundred
million dollars in federal money as partial reimbursement for
providing medical assistance to the mentally retarded.
   Under regulations adopted by the secretary of Health and Human
Services, Medicaid reimbursements are not available for
``vocational training and educational activities.''
   In two separate audits, federal officials determined that
Massachusetts had obtained Medicaid reimbursements for various
``special education'' services provided to mentally retarded people
living in intermediate care facilities.
   The federal officials disallowed $11.3 million in reimbursements
paid for the five-year period in question, and recovered the money
by withholding some advance Medicaid reimbursements in subsequent
years.
   Massachusetts officials sued HHS Secretary Otis Bowen in a
federal trial court, seeking to recover the $11.3 million and to
bar his agency from failing to reimburse such services in the
future.
   U.S. District Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. of Boston ruled in
1985 that the government must make up the $11.3 milion withheld
from Massachusetts.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last March 31 overruled
part of Garrity's decision.
   The appeals court said that, under a federal law called the
Tucker Act, any claim against the federal government for more than
$10,000 in monetary damages must be settled by the U.S. Claims
Court based in the nation's capital.
   But the appeals court upheld Garrity's decision regarding future
reimbursement.
   The Reagan administration asked the Supreme Court to step in to
decide which court has jurisdiction in such disputes.
   The justices today ruled that Garrity, rather than the claims
court, had authority to decide the case.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the court, said federal
judges rather than the claims court are empowered to review final
orders by the secretary of Health and Human Services refusing to
reimburse states for Medicaid expenditures.
   Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices
Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   The case is Bowen vs. Massachusetts, 87-712.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
