<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0597 06-29 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0597,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Revs Up Veep Selection Process With Washington Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 with 5 grafs new to UPDATE with Bentsen,
Mitchell, Kerry and Moynihan meeting with Dukakis; picks up 4th
graf pvs, bgng, `Press secretary'; SUBS grafs 17 and 19 to delete
now-redundant first references to Brountas and Bentsen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, ``enjoying the process,''
took his search for a running mate to the Capitol today while aides
ran extensive background checks on even the driving records of
potential candidates.
   The Massachusetts governor and certain Democratic presidential
nominee entered the Capitol without saying a word today and headed
to a room to conduct meetings all day with as many as 30 or more
Democratic senators _ among them, perhaps, his eventual choice for
a vice presidential nominee.
   Dukakis met first with most of the 16 senators up for
re-election this fall, including Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York.
   Two other senators who met with Dukakis, George Mitchell of
Maine and John Kerry of Massachusetts, said the subject of the vice
presidency came up but that the likely nominee did not discuss the
names of potential candidates.
   ``He said the process is still open, and he's enjoying the
process of getting to know people,'' Kerry said. ``No names were
mentioned.''
   Paul Brountas, Dukakis' senior adviser who is leading the search
for a vice presidential candidate, sat in on the meetings, Kerry
said.
   Press secretary Dayton Duncan said Dukakis might also meet with
some House members before the day was out but planned a return
visit on July 13 to meet with House Democrats.
   He said Dukakis felt no pressure to make or announce a decision
on a running mate soon, despite suggestions the campaign would like
to make the choice before the Democratic National Convention opens
July 18.
   ``He doesn't feel like he's under any timetable or deadline,''
Duncan said.
   Dukakis planned a late-afternoon departure on a campaign swing
through the Midwest, starting in Des Moines, Iowa, where he
scheduled an event to highlight the hardship farmers face on the
drought-stricken plains.
   Dukakis dismissed speculation about his search for a running
mate, saying at an appearance Tuesday in Boston: ``There's only one
guy who knows what's going on and that's the guy you're looking at.
   ``I'm enjoying the process and I hope you are too,'' he added.
   Dukakis refused to rule out Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia for the No.
2 spot on the ticket despite Nunn's insistence that he is not
interested. The Georgia senator said he had no plans to provide the
background information being requested of prospective running mates.
   Dukakis also said Sen. Bob Graham of Florida remained in
contention.
   Campaign spokesmen were providing few details of his Washington
meetings.
   ``All that does is lead to tea-leaf reading,'' said Duncan.
   Duncan said only that the campaign would release a list of
senators he had met with by the end of the day. Dukakis was to use
an office in the Capitol where senators would drop by to see him,
Duncan said.
   Dukakis' campaign, according to sources, has asked for an
exhaustive amount of information from several potential Democratic
vice presidential contenders.
   Officials said Dukakis' campaign has requested detailed
background information, including income tax returns, academic
records, driving records, military records and health records among
other material.
   Brountas is even delving into details of Sen. John Glenn's 1984
presidential campaign. Sources said they sought information about
the Ohio senator's lingering $2.4 million campaign debt and a staff
upheavalat a critical time in that ill-fated campaign.
   The campaign wants to avoid any embarrassing surprises once the
choice has been made. Past campaigns have been damaged by
controversy over the running mate, such as in 1984 when financial
questions were raised about the husband of nominee Geraldine
Ferraro, and in 1972 when revelations about Sen. Thomas Eagleton's
psychiatric treatment led to his withdrawal from the ticket.
   Dukakis' aides have solicited information from several
prospective candidates, including Jesse Jackson and Glenn, as well
as Sens. Graham, Nunn and Bentsen and Reps. Thomas Foley of
Washington, former rival Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Lee
Hamilton of Indiana. The names of Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas and
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee also have cropped up.
   Foley has reportedly declined to provide the requested
information. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey also has taken himself
out of the running, and Dukakis said Friday, ``I respect that.''
   Dukakis appeared in Boston with Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., at
an event where he promised to spend $3 billion on subsidized
housing.
   Cranston said the ``betting on Capitol Hill seems to be John
Glenn and Lloyd Bentsen as the front-runners'' for the No. 2 spot.
   Dukakis laughed when told of Cranston's assessment. ``I'm not a
betting man,'' he said.
</TEXT>
