<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dungeons&Dragons     06-29 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dungeons & Dragons,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Convicted in Parents' Murders Despite Fantasy Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today convicted a 20-year-old
schizophrenic of the murders of his parents, rejecting a defense
claim that he believed he was under the spell of a character in the
fantasy game ``Dungeons and Dragons'' at the time.
   The jury found Daniel Kasten guilty of shooting his parents as
they lay sleeping in their Lake Ronkonkoma home in May 1987.
   In closing arguments yesterday, Kasten's lawyer, William Nash,
said that the case was not about ``Dungeons and Dragons.''
   ``This case is about psychoses, delusions and schizophrenia,''
Nash said. ``Dungeons and Dragons is the game Mr. Kasten decided to
make his own reality.''
   The lawyer said Kasten believed he was under the control of the
``Mind Flyer'' character when he shot his parents, Edith and Joseph
Kasten.
   But Assistant District Attorney Randall Hinrichs, said: ``No one
is saying that Kasten is a normal, well-adjusted individual. A
normal, well-adjusted individual wouldn't kill his parents.''
   But he added, ``At the time that he killed both his parents, he
was aware that he had a gun in his hand and it could cause harm.''
   Hinrichs also played part of Kasten's videotaped confession in
which he said that he had thought about murdering his parents for
years but had hesitated because he knew it was wrong.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
