<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   06-29 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,1101</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: who will?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 26
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Knoxville (Tenn.) News-Sentinel, on line-item vetoes:
   If the president had a line-item veto, would it be easier for
him to fight spending excesses on Capitol Hill? Though common sense
says yes, opponents of the idea cite discouraging evidence from
states that already have this budget device. They say that on the
average these states have no more success in restraining outlays
than other states.
   But George Mason University economist Mark Crain, currently on
leave to the White House budget office, has conducted a more
detailed analysis. He reports that not all line-item vetoes are
created equal: The most effective type seems to be the
``item-reduction veto,'' which allows a governor to substitute a
lower dollar figure than the one sought by the legislature for a
particular item. Only 10 states have this budget device.
   Crain finds that when all other variables are held constant, the
item-reduction veto slashes average annual spending increases by
more than half _ from 4 percent to 1.3 percent.
   Over the years that adds up to enormous savings ... Crain's
findings make the case for a strong line-item veto more convincing
than ever.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 26
   The Orange County (Calif.) Register on tougher drug laws:
   The law authorizing the seizure of vehicles involved in drug
transactions was intended to punish smugglers and big-time dealers
by taking trucks or dope-laden tugboats at the same time the drugs
themselves were confiscated. ... Now the authorities claim the
right to confiscate a vehicle with a few marijuana seeds on or in
it, and sell it at auction unless the owner takes the initiative of
contesting the seizure. The owner doesn't need to be convicted of
selling, buying or possessing an illicit drug to lose the vehicle.
   Such a penalty for a minor crime for which punishment is already
prescribed by law is intended to frighten small-timers, not bother
big dealers.
   The drug law Catch-22 is on display here. The more drug laws
drive up the price of illicit drugs, the more tempting the trade
will be, and the more violent and utterly unscrupulous people will
dominate it...
   Drug laws do not keep drugs away from those who want them, and
they have unfortunate side-effects, like massive increases in real
crimes such as mugging and robbery. The latest escalation simply
illustrates the point. It should be abandoned, and we should move
to something constructive, like a spirited debate about drug
legalization.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 26
   Fond du Lac (Wis.) Reporter on federal drought aid:
   We agree wholeheartedly with Gov. Thompson that Wisconsin's
drought-stricken farmers deserve better treatment from the federal
government.
   Thompson, in Chicago ... with other governors to discuss the
Midwest drought, got in a brief word with U.S. Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng but received less than total attention.
   The governor told Lyng that dairy states deserve better
representation on the administration's drought study commission.
Lyng responded that he had to see the president and left the
session after only a short appearance. In Washington,
administration spokesmen said Lyng expects it to rain within two
weeks and make emergency help unnecessary.
   Thompson was insulted by the treatment. Wisconsin farmers should
be, too. A good deal of damage is already done but Lyng is playing
weatherman and predicting rain. He says that will make aid unneeded.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 25
   Evening Express, Portland, Maine, on baseball manager Billy
Martin's firing:
   Let's start with an undeniable premise: Billy Martin is a loose
cannon and George Steinbrenner is the weirdest owner of a
professional baseball team since Charlie Finley. That probably
explains why Martin is the ex-manager of the New York Yankees for
the fifth time.
   What remains inexplicable is why Steinbrenner keeps hiring
Martin back only to fire him again and again. Or why Martin, who
knows he's going to be sacked the next time Steinbrenner gets up on
the wrong side of the bed, keeps taking the job. ...
   Not that anyone in these parts really cares. Actually, from the
standpoint of Red Sox fans, Steinbrenner's ability to keep the
much-loathed Yankees in turmoil _ and thus from winning pennants _
can be classified as a Good Thing. If Boston doesn't win a pennant,
there is at least some small solace in the knowledge that the
Yankees won't either.
   Keep up the good work, George.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 25
   The Lewiston (Maine) Daily Sun on the Hollywood writers' strike:
   The writers' strike may be the best thing that has happened to
the American family since dogs were invented. Brothers, sisters,
mothers and fathers may be forced to use their time for better
purposes. Who knows, maybe your neighbors will stumble on a
previously unknown offspring who got lost in the couch crowd that
was formerly routinely planted before the tube.
   Yes, TV turmoil may eventually translate into family unity and
an aid to education. Public and-or informative television,
mind-expanding entertainment alternatives and even quality,
relations-enhancing discussions are all part of the 1988 prime-time
home agenda.
   If the strike continues into the fall season, the denizens of
Hollywood may have to lower themselves from cruising around in
Rolls Royces and Porsches to driving American cars, and family
counseling services around the country may fall on hard times as
well.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 24
   The Seattle Times on the Contras:
   Pink slips are flying at Contra headquarters as the Nicaraguan
rebels go through a political version of a Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization.
   Without a steady supply of dollars from Washington, the Contras
cannot sustain their challenge of the Sandinista government in
Managua. Largely a creation of the Reagan administration, the
Contras never stirred a loyal following outside the United States.
   Finally, Congress lost interest. Last March a compromise aid
package of $47.9 million was approved to cushion the implosion of
the rebel movement.
   As the military forces bicker, the political resistance effort
is going through its own period of deflation and dissent. In better
times, the Miami-based Contras had a worldwide budget of $5 million
and offices or representatives in Honduras, Costa Rica, Spain,
Italy, France, Britain and West Germany.
   To save money, the plenary session of the Contra network will be
held in the Dominican Republic, not Miami.
   The Contra dissidents, timid on the battlefield and jealous of
their perquisites, may inspire a hostile takeover only in a resort
convention hall.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
