<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0635 06-29 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0635,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Don't Be Too Quick To Trust The Soviets, Bush Warns</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 9th graf, bgng, `Bush promised,' to UPDATE with Bush
omitting phrase from speech.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today that
sweeping changes being proposed by Soviet Leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev should be viewed with optimism, but cautioned, ``The cold
war is not over.''
   In a speech to the World Affairs Council, the all-but-certain
Republican nominee credited America's military buildup with being
responsible for the change in Soviet thinking. ``My point is that
it was eight years of American strength that confronted the Soviet
Union with the true costs of aggression and the necessity of
reform,'' Bush said.
   He said that President Reagan's summit in Moscow with Gorbachev
late last month was the result of ``eight years of moral
determination and hard work rebuilding American might. But this
said, we must remember the cold war is not over.
   ``We must be bold enough to seize the opportunity of change, but
at the same time prepared for, as one pundit titled his column,
`the protracted conflict.'''
   Bush spoke in San Francisco at the wrap-up of a 24-hour visit to
northern California chiefly intended to raise money for GOP coffers
at two private fund-raisers. On his return to Washington today,
Bush planned to stop in Appleton, Wis., to highlight the plight of
farmers hurt by the drought.
   In discussing America's military buildup, Bush took note of the
investigation of alleged bribery, fraud and corruption at the
Pentagon.
   ``If the news stories are true,'' he said, ``the accused have
done more than steal from the public treasury. They have undermined
America's security and broken faith with the American people.''
   In the prepared text of his speech released earlier, Bush
promised ``we will throw the book'' at guilty parties. However, in
delivering the address, he omitted that phrase.
   The vice president cautioned, however, about over-reacting to
the alleged corruption.
   ``The first reaction in Congress to the scandals _ to increase
the regulatory bureaucracy at Defense _ though understandable, will
only add to the complexity and worsen the problem,'' Bush said.
``The answer is to reduce, cut and simplify, including staff and
executive overhead.''
   The vice president said that Congress and the executive branch
should make a compact ``to take the patronage and pork out of
defense.''
   In a series of interviews Tuesday, Bush said he was not worried
about a Gallup Poll for the Times Mirror Corp. that showed him
running 13 points behind Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis. The survey was released Monday.
   ``I don't make too much of it,'' Bush said, adding that polls
had shown him trailing then-rival Bob Dole before the New Hampshire
primary, which he won handily. ``I look at it as something that can
be taken care of.
   ``I like to come back. I think I'm going to win,'' he said.
   Bush offered a preview of his foreign policy address in
responding to reports about Gorbachev's opening remarks Tuesday to
a Communist Party conference that is expected to produce a showdown
this week between reform and conservative forces in the Soviet
Union.
   The Soviet leader urged a redistribution of power in the Soviet
Union to give new authority to the president and legislature. He
said his country must break with the ``ossified system'' of the
past.
   Asked his view of Gorbachev's speech, Bush said he had not been
briefed on the Soviet leader's remarks, but that ``it seems to me
that (the address) is quite encouraging.
   ``I am one who views perestroika as manifestation of change _
some of that change is real. I'm also one that feels that as they
go about reforming their country, we should look for opportunities
to do more with the Soviet Union in terms of investment or
exchanges of people or whatever it is.''
   However, Bush said, ``we ought to be very, very wary and not
jump to the conclusion that a call of that nature be confused with
fundamental, permanent change in the Soviet Union's approach to
other countries and indeed whether it's a fundamental departure
from their Marxist system.''
   As to whether the Soviets are moving toward democracy, he said:
``I don't see the evidence of it yet.''
   He urged the Soviets to strive for fuller compliance with the
Helsinki accords which prescribe how nations should respect human
rights.
   Specifically, Bush called for more Jews and divided families to
be allowed to leave the Soviet Union.``I think that would be the
most visible manifestation of real glasnost, openness, and real
reform, perestroika. And that's what we ought to be looking for and
encouraging in every way possible,'' the vice president said.
   On another subject, Bush said carriers of the deadly AIDS virus
should be protected by the federal government from discrimination
on the job, in schools and elsewhere.
   ``I think it is needed,'' Bush said, embracing the key _ and
most controversial _ recommendation of President Reagan's AIDS
commission.
   ``I think it is important to do a lot to lay to rest some of the
fears. There is a lot of misunderstanding,'' Bush said.
   Reagan has not taken a position on the recommendation.
</TEXT>
