<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--FreakAccident     06-29 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Freak Accident,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Truck Hits Man It Sent to Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are trying to determine if a
man who was found sprawled in a street was killed by a fire engine
that was summoned to help him.
   Antonie Nolan, 24, may have been dead before he was hit by the
12-ton fire engine on Sunday, police said Tuesday.
   The cause of death may not be known for several weeks when the
Alameda County Coroner's office releases autopsy results.
   Traffic Officer Mike Oliveira said police received an emergency
call that a man was lying motionless in the street.
   A fire engine, ambulance and police car were dispatched.
Firefighters, trained in first aid, are routinely sent on medical
emergencies, said Oliveira.
   The fire engine was moving at about 20 mph, using its headlights
and searchlight on the street, which is very poorly lit and
littered with debris, he said.
   Oliveira said a firefighter spotted the man in the road, but
before the engine driver could stop, the truck ran over the man.
</TEXT>
