<1ST_LINE>u w PM-MinimumWage     06-29 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Approves Increase In Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor Committee voted 11-5 today to
approve legislation that would increase the current $3.35 an hour
federal minimum wage by $1.20 over the next three years.
   The legislation, sponsored by committee Chairman Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., would raise the wage rate to $4.55 per hour over
three years, identical to a proposal being considered by House
leaders.
   Although several Republican senators earlier had said they would
offer amendments to the bill, none was introduced at the meeting.
   ``There was no reason to take on those issues in committee,''
said Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah. ``There will be amendments when
the bill gets to the floor.''
   An earlier proposal, introduced in both the House and Senate,
would have increased the wage to $4.65 per hour over three years
and indexed it to 50 percent of the average national wage
thereafter.
   The House, during subcommittee and full committee action,
dropped the indexing provision and boosted the rate to $5.05 per
hour over four years.
   When the legislation goes to the House floor, there is expected
to a bipartisan substitute proposal to bring the minimum wage to
$4.55 per hour over three years.
</TEXT>
