<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Festival     06-29 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Festival,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Festival Makes Interim Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No AMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With 12 days remaining of the First New York
International Festival of the Arts, the festival's chairman gave it
a glowing interim review on Wednesday.
   ``I would say it (attendance) is in excess of 75 percent of the
total number of seats,'' Martin E. Segal, the festival chairman,
told a news conference.
   However, Segal said he disliked speaking in terms of attendance
percentages, since the sizes of halls vary.
   ``The judgment of the success of the festival we believe should
be around its artistic merit,'' he said.
   To a question whether too much is going on _ one night lists 68
events _ Segal said, ``We don't know the answer. We wound up with
140 composers of over 1,000 composers that are known in this
century. We wanted to be sure we were representing the scope of the
wonders of the art form of this century.''
   The festival began June 11 and will end July 11.
   Paul Libin, producer of ``Juno and the Paycock,'' said lines of
people hoping for cancellations are longer than lines outside ``The
Phantom of the Opera.'' The play, presented by the Gate Theater of
Dublin, is appearing for two weeks.
   Jacques d'Amboise, who heads the National Dance Institute, which
teaches dance in schools, said the institute's concert sold out for
two nights instead of one for the first time in 12 years.
   Robert Jones, a producer of the JVC Festival, which also is
regularly in New York in June and this year is part of the
International Festival, said, ``We have experienced what we feel is
an almost 12 percent increase in our overall business.''
   On Sunday afternoon, Segal said he attended the New Stockholm
Orchestra's U.S. debut. ``We learned about a new orchestra. They
should come back. We're presenting a number of artists for the
first time.''
   The festival will bring the city $400 million in spending, Segal
said, adding, ``Many theaters are closed at this time of year. The
festival has created a situation where events are going on.
   ``We believe the city is going to become increasingly a
12-month-a-year place for entertainment and the performing arts,
which is consequential for the city economically and for artists.''
   The festival will end July 11 with superstar opera tenor Placido
Domingo singing a free concert in Central Park. Gloria Estefan will
sing a solo and a duet with him and Linda Ronstadt will join him
for Mexican songs. The festival will then end with a fireworks
display.
</TEXT>
