<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0645,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Wants New Direction in War on Drugs
^Eds: UPDATES throughout with approval of Medicaid proposal,
recommendation to limit product liability awards, edit to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association today approved a
report calling for expanded treatment of drug abusers and other
major changes in the nation's war against drugs.
   Also today, the nation's largest organization of doctors called
for reform of the nation's Medicaid health insurance system for the
poor to establish uniform nationwide eligibility standards and
uniform payments for medical care.
   The AMA's House of Delegates, its policymaking body, voted to
lobby the government to expand Medicaid to cover an additional 27
million poor people at an estimated cost of $24 billion at 1988
spending levels.
   On the drug issue, delegates called for shifting the main point
of attack from trying to catch drug traffickers to working to
reduce demand for their illegal products by expanding treatment of
abusers.
   ``We are saying this nation does have the will to overcome the
drug problem, but it simply has the wrong game plan,'' said Dr.
Lonnie Bristow, an AMA trustee from Berkeley, Calif.
   The delegates today also approved a recommendation intended to
encourage biomedical companies that may be hesitant about
developing new products for fear of lawsuits.
   It urged that state and federal governments reform the nation's
court system to limit the amount of money awarded in product
liability lawsuits.
   Worry about being sued by patients and having to pay
multimillion-dollar awards is leading the companies to hold off on
developing new vaccines, drugs and other ``potentially life-saving
technologies,'' according to a report presented to the group.
   On Tuesday, the House of Delegates rejected a ban on publishing
articles about euthanasia, but held firm against mercy killing.
   It also called for bans on toy guns that can be mistaken for the
real thing and on real, non-metallic firearms that can slip through
metal detectors and other screening devices.
   The policy-making arm of the 295,000-member group voted to urge
the federal government to end price supports for tobacco and help
tobacco farmers begin growing other crops, but postponed action on
a proposal for doubling the federal tobacco tax.
   The 420 delegates were to vote later today on a proposal calling
for creation of a new class of hospital worker.
   The drug policy approved today recommends that the federal
government expand drug abuse treatment programs, ease regulations
to permit private doctors to treat opiate addicts with methadone
and strengthen drug education programs aimed at adolescents.
   The policy also calls on the president to appoint ``a
high-ranking official of the Executive Branch to coordinate federal
drug policy'' to reduce rivalry among different agencies and keep
them from working at cross purposes.
   The policy stresses the AMA's opposition to widespread random
drug testing and to the legalization of outlawed drugs.
   The delegates reiterated their opposition to mercy killing in
the wake of an uproar over the Journal of the American Medical
Association's publication earlier this year of an article by a
doctor describing how he ended a cancer patient's life at her
request.
   The article, ``It's Over Debbie,'' touched off widespread
criticism of the journal for not publishing the author's name and
for not including a clear statement of the AMA's opposition to
mercy killing.
   However, the delegates rejected a proposal from the Nebraska
delegation to require the AMA to ``refrain from publishing articles
which involve the taking of human life without'' also printing the
association's stand against mercy killing.
   The debate over euthanasia ``will be with society for the
foreseeable future,'' said Dr. Alan Nelson, chairman of the AMA
board of trustees. ``The position of the AMA has been consistent
and it was restated today so there won't be any confusion.
Euthanasia is wrong ... and the medical profession will continue to
deplore it.''
   The delegates also are considering a proposal to organize a new
class of hospital bedside worker, called a ``registered care
technologist,'' in an effort to offset the nursing shortage.
   As envisioned in the doctors' proposal, these workers would
receive from two months to 18 months of training and would handle
such chores as bathing patients, taking vital signs and changing
bandages.
   The plan is opposed by the American Nurses' Association, which
says the answer to the shortage is increased salaries and better
working conditions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0581 06-29 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Linger In Montana, Wyoming, Indiana</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Sonoma County fire still
burning and containment of San Luis Obispo fire, picks up 3rd graf
pvs, `The Montana-South Dakota...'; SUBS 21st graf pvs, `In
the...', to increase number of acres burned to 600 sted 150 and
INSERTS new grafs 22-23 to UPDATE with more fires in northern
California; picks up 22nd graf pvs, `In South...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters today battled a blaze in Wyoming's Shosone National
Forest while a 60,000-acre timber and grass fire was brought under
control along the Montana-South Dakota border and an Indiana peat
fire smoldered for a fifth day.
   A stubborn fire that destroyed four homes and more than a dozen
farmbuildings kept firefighters busy today in rural Sonoma County,
north of San Francisco, where a wind-whipped blaze nearby destroyed
most of the historic community of Preston on Tuesday.
   A 200-acre wildfire in southern California's San Luis Obispo
County that forced the evacuation of a campground and closed a
highway was contained today, while brush fires in Riverside County
east of Los Angeles were nearly contained.
   The Montana-South Dakota and Wyoming fires were contained
Tuesday, and the border fire was delared under control early today.
   In Montana, information officer Sandi Sacher said some of the
1,034 firefighters were preparing to return home. The fire burned
over about 58,300 acres in southeastern Montana and northwestern
South Dakota, including parts of the Custer National Forest.
   ``They have delayed demobilization from what they normally do
because of the severe weather conditions and severe dryness just to
make sure sparks of the fire are well out and, if the winds pick
up, none of them will flare up,'' Sacher said.
   The fire, which began June 20 during a lightning storm, was
fought in temperatures sometimes exceeding 100 degrees. The fire
cost upwards of $2 million to battle and caused an estimated $4
million damage, officials said.
   About 22 ranchers had permits to graze cattle in the Custer
National Forest, and the fire forced them to seek other grazing
land for their herds.
   Benny and Dorothy Padden, who ranch about 7,000 acres in the
Long Pines area, had about 550 head of cattle on forest land. So
far, nine head have been found dead and nearly half of those who
survived were burned.
   ``The drought was bad enough without the fire,'' said Padden.
``There's too many adversities at one time. We're infested with
grasshoppers, also. They didn't leave any out this year.''
   In Wyoming, the 390 firefighters battling the 1,150-acre fire in
the Shoshone National Forest completed a fire line around the blaze
Tuesday.
   The fire, discovered Friday, was burning inside the Wolf Creek
Timber Sale and had threatened critical grizzly bear and bald eagle
habitats.
   Forest spokesman Tom Portice said firefighters were able to
protect bald eagle nesting sites. The fire should not severely
affect the grizzly bear habitat, he said.
   In northern California's Sonoma County, dry, hilly terrain and
gusty winds hampered firefighters who battled a stubborn fire that
burned four houses and a dozen outbuildings Tuesday. The fire raged
for hours several miles south of Sebastopol and scorched between
200 and 300 acres before firefighters contained it, said Bob
Gloeckner, a director of the Hessel Fire Protection District.
   ``The wind kept picking up hot embers and spotting them ahead of
the fire itself, a quarter mile, half a mile ahead, and starting
additional fires,'' Gloeckner said.
   Earlier in the day, gusts fanned a fire from a downed power line
into an inferno that destroyed a 17-room mansion built 112 years
and an art colony in Preston, a hamlet two miles north of
Cloverdale on the border between Sonoma and Mendocino counties.
   After the flames were quenched, only chimneys and bathtubs
remained of the mansion. The fire also destroyed the textile
artworks of Christina Buffalo Larkin and the paintings of artist
Robert Thomas, album designer for the Grateful Dead.
   Also lost in the fire was Thomas' 30-year collection of antique
and unusual folk music instruments.
   ``This has been a double tragedy,'' said Lisa Ellis, wife of a
ranch manager. ``Not only have we lost the historic buildings, but
the artists colony has been wiped out, an incalculable loss.''
   In southern California, three brush fires broke out in the
afternoon as arid regions sweltered under temperatures that topped
the 100-degree mark. All burned in steep, brushy terrain and were
fanned by winds.
   In San Luis Obispo County, 175 miles northwest of downtown Los
Angeles, a 200-acre brush fire forced the evacuation of Cerro Alto
Campground and closed Highway 41 between Atascadero and Morro Bay,
said Kim John with the California Department of Forestry. She did
not know how many people had to flee.
   In the desert country near Cabazon, 95 miles east of downtown
Los Angeles, a 125-acre fire burned in Millard Canyon near the
Morongo Indian Reservation. Another blaze, south of Interstate 10
near Cabazon Peak, burned 600 acres and was nearly contained today.
   Firefighters said flames charred about 400 acres of grass and
brush in northwestern Calaveras County and an unknown number of
acres just north of Lakeport in Lake County.
   The Calaveras County blaze for a time threatened the small
community of Paloma, according to the Tuolumne-Calaveras Ranger
Unit. But no buildings were lost, and no injuries were reported.
   In South Bend, Ind., a fire in a wooded area reached a level of
peat moss running from 12 feet to 15 feet deep.
   ``You can't put it out. All you can do is contain it,'' said
state police Sgt. Tom Rubesha. ``This peat is buried. Peat fires
have been known to burn for years.''
   The blaze discovered Saturday had spread to 40 to 60 acres by
Tuesday, authorities said.
</TEXT>
