<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-TeenChastity 2ndLd-Writethru a0632 06-29 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Teen Chastity, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0632,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Government May Finance Religious Groups' Chastity
Programs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs, Chief Justice, to elaborate on how
religious group receiving federal money could violate Constitution</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ruled the federal
government may give money to religious groups to promote chastity
among America's teen-agers.
   The 5-4 ruling said a 1981 federal law that funnels taxpayer
money to private groups to counsel adolescents against premarital
sex is not unconstitutional on its face.
   But the justices ordered further lower court hearings to
determine whether the statute, as it is being applied, ever may
violate the constitutionally required separation of church and
state.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, writing for the court, said
if there is evidence that some recipients of federal funds are
violating the Constitution by teaching religious doctrine the
remedy is to ban them from getting further money. The solution is
not to kill the law, Rehnquist said.
   Rehnquist said the so-called teen chastity law has a valid
secular purpose in seeking to eliminate or reduce economic problems
caused by pre-marital sex among young people.
   He said the statute also does not have the primary purpose of
advancing religion and does not create an excessive entanglement
between church and state.
   ``We note, as is proper given the traditional presumption in
favor of the constitutionality of statutes enacted by Congress,
that our conclusion that the statute does not violate the
establishment clause (requiring separation of church and state) is
consistent with the conclusion Congress reached in the course of
its deliberations,'' Rehnquist said.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Harry A. Blackmun said, ``As
the record developed thus far in this litigation makes all too
clear, federal tax dollars appropriated (under the law) have been
used with government approval to support religious teaching.''
   He was joined by Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall
and John Paul Stevens.
   The law, officially the Adolescent Family Life Act, was passed
by Congress soon after President Reagan took office.
   Former Sen. Jeremiah Denton, R-Ala., sponsored the law; it was
ushered through Congress by fellow conservatives. The act provided
millions of dollars for care, prevention and research.
   Care services include pregnancy testing, maternity counseling,
and adoption and referral help.
   Prevention services are those aimed at discouraging adolescent
sexual relations and include programs offering counseling and
family planning.
   Opponents of the law said religious groups were using the money
to promote Christianity. For example, they said some groups advised
young girls to practice sexual abstinence by pretending that
``Jesus is their date.''
   Supporters of the law said it is in line with federal aid to
religious organizations that sponsor other worthy social services
such as hospital care, drug abuse programs, orphanages and
emergency shelters.
   In seeking funds, applicants are required to describe how they
will ``involve religious and charitable organizations, voluntary
associations and other groups in the private sector.''
   U.S. District Judge Charles Richey in Washington struck down key
provisions of the law in April 1987. Richey said the law had a
primary effect of advancing religion and fostered an excessive
entanglement between government and religion.
   The judge left intact provisions of the law that did not involve
giving money to religious groups.
   The administration said the law is needed to combat teen
pregancy. More than one million teen-age girls become pregnant each
year and about 500,000 have abortions.
   The law was challenged by a group of taxpayers, clery members
and the American Jewish Congress. They were represented by the
American Civil Liberties Union.
   Planned Parenthood, the American Psychological Association, the
National Organization for Women and the National Abortion Rights
Action League were among the groups that attacked the law.
   Supporters of the statute include the U.S. Catholic Conference,
the Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights and United
Families of America.
   The case is Bowen vs. Kendrick, 87-253.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
