<HEAD>N.C. Doctor Takes Over As AMA President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AMA Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 6:15 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James E. Davis, the new president of the nation's
largest doctors' organization, on Wednesday called for a renewed
emphasis on the service ethic in medicine.
   Davis, a surgeon from Durham, N.C., was to be sworn in Wednesday
as president of the American Medical Association during the group's
annual policy-making convention.
   In a speech prepared for delivery at his inauguration, Davis
proposed that county and state doctors' associations organize and
staff _ free of charge _ medical ombudsman offices to serve the
public.
   ``They will receive the public's questions, concerns,
suggestions and recommendations about health matters and follow
through on consumer complaints,'' he said.
   ``We must get a handle on the high cost of health care,'' Davis
said. ``We must find solutions to the drug crisis and other
frightening conditions that plague so many American adolescents. We
must develop ways to reach out and care for the medically
indigent.''
   Davis is a history buff, fascinated by the Civil War. He became
involved in the leadership of organized medicine partly through his
interest in parliamentary procedure.
   After serving as president and speaker of the House of Delegates
of the North Carolina Medical Society, he was elected vice speaker
and then speaker of the AMA's House of Delegates.
   In his spare time, he is writing a brief reference manual on
parliamentary procedure for presiding officers.
   Davis succeeds Dr. William Hotchkiss of Chesapeake, Va., as
president of the AMA.
</TEXT>
