<HEAD>Czech Dissident Author Denied Permission to Travel to Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czech dissident author was denied
permission to attend an international disarmament conference that
opened Wednesday in Sweden, according to a news report.
   Vaclav Havel said in a letter to the organizers that his latest
application for a passport was ``rejected on the grounds that my
traveling abroad was not in the state's interest,'' the TT Swedish
news agency said.
   It said Havel wrote that he has not been issued a passport for
19 years.
   About 900 peace activists and academics are in the southern city
of Lund for the four-day conference, organized by the European
Nuclear Disarmament movement.
   Last week, the leader of a banned Polish peace group also was
denied a passport to attend the conference. Allowed to attend the
meeting, however, was Jacek Kuron, an adviser to the outlawed
Solidarity trade union.
