<DOCNO> AP880629-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Migrants Bjt   06-29 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Migrants, Bjt,0944</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Or No Drought, Migrant Laborers Toil Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORHEAD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each morning, Israel Zamora reports to
the job exchange hoping a farmer needs him and his family to hoe
weeds competing with the lucrative sugar beet crop.
   Migrant laborers are in demand in the Red River Valley between
Minnesota and North Dakota, even more so this year as farmers try
to salvage a cash crop that could determine if they survive or fail.
   ``It's too hot. There's not enough rain. A lot of the fields are
too dry, so it's dirty,'' said Zamora, 40, of Weslaco, Texas,
showing his calloused, nicked-up hands.
   ``But we're poor. This is how we make our living. We never know
what's going to happen the next day.''
   Zamora was given the name of a farmer and directions to his
place. Then he headed off with his family in a tattered white Ford
van that survived the three-day journey from Texas. For the next 12
hours, they hoed weeds for $30 an acre.
   Hundreds more migrants than usual, almost all of them from the
parched lands of Texas, made the 1,500-mile trip in pickups and
vans to find seasonal work in Minnesota. Thanks to unusual weather,
they found more work than normal.
   ``Everybody's working, and I have 50 farmers waiting for more
laborers. Weeds don't know there's a drought,'' said Armando
Cuellar, counselor for the state's Job Service Division in
Crookston.
   ``I've never had this much labor available, but this is the year
I'm shortest on labor. I'm hearing from growers who never used
migrant laborers,'' Cuellar said.
   The worst drought in 50 years is only one problem facing the
beets, which ripen into tannish-white bulbs that produce sugar. A
May 13 frost killed much of the first planting, so farmers had to
try again. High winds hampered the second seeding, and survivors
are enduring the drought and an onslaught of weeds.
   Farmers spray chemicals to control weeds, which suck up moisture
from the ground and keep it from the beets. But the herbicides
don't work unless it rains. If it rains now, the weeds grow twice
as fast as the beets.
   ``If the chemicals don't kill the weeds, the laborers will.
They're like insurance to an automobile owner,'' said Pablo
Guajardo of the Job Service Division in Moorhead.
   The Red River flows north into Canada through a lush
200-mile-long valley that was once the bed of a glacial lake. The
heavy, rich soil is among the most fertile in the world.
   Sugar beets are a $1 billion industry in the valley, which
produces about 20 percent of the sugar made in the United States.
About 12 percent of the U.S. total comes from an 1,800-member
cooperative called the American Sugar Crystal Co., which expects
the yield to be down substantially this year because of the drought.
   Crop projections are 16 tons per acre on 366,000 acres, down
from last year's yield of 19 tons per acre, according to Ron Hayes,
president of American Crystal.
   But the beets have fared better than wheat, barley and other
light grains on the parched prairie, so growers are concentrating
on them.
   ``You can't dare abandon the sugar beets at this point,'' said
Evert Schumacher, Polk County executive of the state's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service. ``That's all the hope these
farmers got.''
   About 4,400 migrants are in Moorhead, including 1,400 who are
laborers. They arrived in April and May but had no work early
because of the weather.
   However, with the late start and and the drought, they'll
probably have work into August.
   The migrants normally get paid $22 an acre, or a minimum of $5
an hour. Because of the increased demand, some are getting $30 to
$35 an acre, and a good hoer can work two acres per day, seven days
a week.
   At the job exchange, men with folded arms sat in chairs against
a wall at a former high school, looking like anxious students
waiting to see the principal. They waited for word on work and
talked about the weather. Barefoot children scurried about or drew
pictures on papers.
   ``It's a pretty bad year. Too many weeds,'' said Rodolfo
Gonzalez, 46, wearing a Los Angeles Dodgers baseball cap. ``One
good thing about the drought, though. No mosquitoes.''
   Bennie Hernandez had just driven 14 hours from Wyoming because
he heard there were jobs here. After this job, he'll go to Iowa to
hack weeds with a machete in the soybean fields.
   ``You don't know from one day to the next. We just move and hope
to find work,'' Hernandez said.
   The work is exhausting. Workers chop at knee-high weeds along
straight rows of beets, stopping occasionally for water. The lunch
break lasts 30 minutes.
   The migrants took a chance on the drought-stricken north because
job opportunities are scarcer in Texas.
   ``At least up here they have hope. The economy in Texas is not
the best. There's nothing down there to begin with,'' said Guajardo.
   The migrants don't harvest the beets. That's done by machine in
October, when the crop is cut into slices like french fries and
mixed with water to remove the sugar.
   Farmers who have given up on their grain crops are keeping their
fingers crossed on sugar beets.
   Gerald Olsonawski of Kittson County, who plowed under 1,400
acres of failed wheat. He has 321 acres of beets. ``That's my last
hope. That's all I got to go on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
