<2ND_LINE>PM-Kean-Keynote, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Jersey Governor To Give Keynote Speech At GOP Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Kean comments; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng
``The sources...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's popular Gov. Thomas Kean, known
for his call to bring women and minorities into the GOP mainstream,
said today he will deliver the keynote speech at the Republican
National Convention.
   ``The Republican Party, if it's going to be successful, has to
appeal to everybody,'' Kean said. ``That's the message'' he said he
will present to GOP delegates Aug. 15 in New Orleans.
   Kean, 53, one of the party's rising stars, was picked to give
the high-profile speech by Vice President George Bush, the expected
Republican presidential nominee, sources told The Associated Press.
   The Democrats, whose convention is next month in Atlanta,
announced the selection of their keynote speaker, Texas State
Treasurer Ann Richards, on Monday.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Bush
decided on Kean in large measure due to the governor's
party-expanding philosophy, outlined in Kean's recent book, ``The
Politics of Inclusion.'' In the book, Kean talks about ways to
reach beyond the GOP's traditional wealthy, white-collar base.
   Kean, one of New Jersey's most popular governors, was
resoundingly re-elected in 1985 with an unprecedented 60 percent of
the black vote. Four years earlier, he had squeaked into the
governor's job by the slimmest margin ever.
   The re-election victory in an otherwise dull political year cast
Kean into his party's limelight and put him in demand around the
country as a speaker. In 1986, Republican governors chose Kean to
head their national association.
   The sources said Kean clinched the sought-after speaking role at
a meeting with Bush in Ohio last week, when the governor delivered
a talk outlining strategy against Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, the expected Democratic nominee.
   Bush and Kean have met privately several times to discuss
strategy in recent months.
   Kean's spokesman, Carl Golden, declined Tuesday to comment on
the selection of the governor as keynote speaker.
   New Jersey's state Assembly Speaker Charles Hardwick, a
Republican, called Kean's selection ``great news for New Jersey and
the Republican Party.
   ``The governor's message is one that will be well received
around the country,'' said Hardwick, who also serves as
vice-chairman for the GOP convention's platform-writing committee.
   Kean has also been mentioned as a potential running mate for
Bush. But Kean, on a unrelated trip here Tuesday, said, ``I'm doing
everything I can to make sure he doesn't come to me.''
   A Kean-Bush ticket would match two millionaires, both with Ivy
League educations, and both from the Northeast. Kean has said,
however, he would be hard pressed to decline a place on the ticket
if asked.
</TEXT>
