<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentCouncils     06-29 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Councils,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Delegates Surveyed At Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Making a contribution to society is far
more important than earning a hefty salary, a poll of U.S. high
school student leaders has found.
   Delegates to the National Association of Student Councils
conference in Albuquerque were asked Tuesday what would be most
important to them at age 40.
   Fifty-two percent selected ``having made a contribution to
society;'' 20 percent chose ``a successful first marriage;'' 18
percent picked ``being a better parent than the generation that
raised me;'' and 10 percent reported ``making a lot of money.''
   The conference's sponsors say the findings show a definite shift
in values among America's youth.
   ``During the past three years students have been moving away
from money as a measure of success and focusing upon societal
contributions as their prime measure of achievement as an adult,''
said Dale Hawley, director of student activities for the National
Association of Secondary School Principals, the conference sponsor.
   ``When we asked this question at a similar conference four years
ago, students indicated making money was their primary measure of
success,'' Hawley said.
   The 1,500 delegates from across the county also cited alcohol
overwhelmingly as the most frequently used drug by their peers.
Eighty-nine percent chose alcohol, 9 percent chose cigarettes, 2
percent chose marijuana, and less than 1 percent cited hard drugs
like cocaine. Figures were rounded off so they totaled more than
100 percent.
   Delegates reported they see considerable cheating in school.
Sixty-six percent said they see cheating frequently, 33 percent
said infrequently and 1 percent said they never saw any cheating.
</TEXT>
