<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Transportation     06-29 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Transportation,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes $10.8 Billion Transportation Measure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This includes material in AM-Manassas Battlefield, a0715</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved a $10.8
billion transportation appropriations bill for fiscal 1989 that
boosts spending for the Coast Guard and aviation, and seeks to
shield a Civil War battlefield from development.
   The measure, sent to the Senate on a 371-40 vote, has been
threatened with a veto by administration officials who say it is
too expensive. The bill would pour $2 billion more into
transportation programs for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 than
President Reagan has proposed.
   Besides $10.8 billion in new spending, the legislation would
allow the government to spend up to another $15.4 billion next year
from special funds set aside for aviation, highway and mass transit
projects.
   Overall, the measure would give the Coast Guard a budget of $3.1
billion, of which $492 million would have to be spent on anti-drug
programs. The Federal Aviation Administration would receive $6.6
billion. Both agencies' coffers would be boosted by about 16
percent over 1988 levels.
   The legislation also would make it harder for a developer to
build a proposed shopping mall on a Manassas, Va., site where the
Second Battle of Bull Run was fought in 1862. The provision would
forbid the federal government from allowing highway interchanges to
be built to serve the area.
   The measure also provides $3.3 billion for mass transit
programs, $13.8 billion for highway projects and $590 million for
Amtrak, the passenger railroad. Reagan has repeatedly proposed
ending federal subsidies for Amtrak, and slashing mass transit
assistance virtually in half.
   The legislation, as always, also contains some money for road
construction and other projects that benefit the districts of
particular lawmakers.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee approved a $10.6 billion
version of the bill last Friday. The two chambers will have to work
out their differences before the legislation is sent to the White
House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
