<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-29 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one in this smokestack suburb of
Chicago ever clamored for a poet laureate, so when a rhymster who's
never worked or lived here assumed the title, it ticked off a few
locals.
   They don't want James Underdown and they're not too fond of his
poetry either.
   ``It's kind of cruddy, if you ask me,'' says Mayor Robert
Stefaniak.
   ``For someone to be a poet laureate of a community he should at
least be a resident of the community,'' city librarian Vickie Novak
said Wednesday. ``I've been a lifelong Calumet City resident, and I
don't think he knows the city very well.''
   But Underdown, who recites what he calls Calumet City-inspired
poetry at an off-beat Chicago nightclub, disagreed with Ms. Novak's
assessment.
   ``I've just introduced a new perspective to it (Calumet City)
and she may be blind to what she's been living in her whole life,''
said Underdown, who wears a tuxedo and a black ``Andy Capp'' hat
and smokes a fat ``Black Jack'' cigar while he performs.
   Underdown, who grew up in the affluent suburb of Wheaton, said
only one of his poems is written about Calumet City itself, but
he's written 30 ``from a Calumet City Perspective.''
   He said his favorite line is:
   ``They've said in the past we ain't got no class and we watch TV
all day to see Vanna. But we know it's worse in the back of a
hearse or anywhere in Indiana.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may be a trashy way to win $500 or more, but
Seattle's faithful recyclers probably won't complain.
   The city is launching a ``garbage lottery'' contest to reward
those who turn in bottles, cans, newspapers and other recyclable
goods.
   Lottery applications will be distributed in community
newspapers, grocery stores and other outlets, and once a month city
employees will draw two applications, one each from Seattle's north
and south ends.
   When a name is drawn, utility workers will check the person's
garbage to see if it contains any bottles, cans, newspapers or
other recyclable goods. If none is found, the person gets $500.
Otherwise, the money is added to the next month's garbage jackpot.
   ``It's just like the real lottery,'' said Tim Croll of the
city's Solid Waste Utility. The program should start by early
August.
</TEXT>
