<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--ColoradoPoll     06-29 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Colorado Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis Ahead in Colorado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado voters favor likely Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis over Republican George Bush by nearly a
double-digit margin, a recent poll shows.
   The telephone poll, conducted by The Denver Post and KCNC-TV,
shows Dukakis with the support of 45 percent of the 553 people
randomly surveyed across the state. Bush, the all-but-certain GOP
choice, has the backing of 36 percent of the voters while 19
percent remain uncommitted.
   If the poll results hold up in the general election in November,
it would be an historic state first _ Colorado voters have not
supported a Democratic candidate in 24 years.
   The poll indicates that Colorado's leaning toward the Democratic
candidate comes from a voter desire to change the political party
in power. The poll shows that Dukakis would be favored by about the
same margin even if the Republicans nominated Kansas Sen. Bob Dole,
who is popular among Colorado residents.
   The poll was conducted June 5-7 by Talmey Research & Strategy of
Boulder. It has a margin of error of 4.2 percent.
</TEXT>
