<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Long-RangeForecast     06-29 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Long-Range Forecast,310</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's drought-plagued upper Midwest
faces warmer than normal temperatures and normal to below-normal
rainfall during July, the National Weather Service reported
Wednesday.
   The 30-day forecast calls for above-normal temperatures
throughout the Midwest as far west as Montana, Colorado and
Wyoming, south through Arkansas and east to the Appalachian
Mountains.
   Below-normal temperatures are expected in the Pacific Northwest
with the remainder of the country expected to be near-normal.
   July rainfall is expected to be below-average for Michigan,
Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Kentucky and most of California.
Above-normal rainfall is expected in portions of Arizona, New
Mexico and in the Puget Sound region. The rest of the country is
likely to have about normal rain for the month.
   The National Weather Service Long Range Predictions Group also
released a 90-day outlook for July, August and September.
   That projection calls for below-normal rainfall in California
and along the Atlantic coast from Washington, D.C., to northern
Florida. Above-normal rainfall is likely in some of the currently
drought-plagued areas, including Montana, Wyoming, southern South
Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, New Mexico and the western portions of
Iowa, Missouri, Oklahoma and Texas.
   The rest of the country did not fall into either the above- or
below-normal categories.
   The 90-day temperature outlook is for above-normal readings east
of Iowa, Missouri, Arkansas and Louisiana, with the highest
likelihood of hot weather in the Tennessee Valley and the southern
Appalachians.
   The mountain states were expected to have below-normal readings
during the 90-day period while the rest of the country and New
England could go either way.
   The agency issued a short-range, 6-to-10-day forecast calling
for above-normal temperatures in most of the country except the
southern Atlantic coast and the Puget Sound area. Below-normal
rainfall is expected in the Great Lakes region, Chesapeake Bay
area, Texas and from the mountain states westward to the Pacific.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
