<DOCNO> AP880629-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tito     06-29 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tito,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Question Tito Legacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident intellectuals blame the
late President Tito for most of Yugoslavia's current troubles and
are demanding an end to official veneration of the man who
personified the nation for 35 years.
   The 19-member Committee In Defense of Intellectual Freedoms said
in a statement dated Monday and addressed to the Yugoslav
leadership that Tito built an undemocratic, repressive political
system that ``has thwarted the progressive development of society.''
   A copy was received Wednesday by The Associated Press. It is
believed to be the strongest statement to date for what is called a
``critical reappraisal'' of Tito, the undisputed leader of this
Communist nation from the partisan days of World War II until his
death in 1980 at age 87.
   Tito is still revered by Yugoslav authorities and criticizing
his policies is a criminal offense. The intellectuals described
many instances of public veneration as ``primitive rituals.''
   The group making the statement is led by Dobrica Cosic,
Yugoslavia's most popular author, who was dismissed from the
Communist Party Central Committee in the late 1960s for criticizing
Tito's policies. Its members include university professors,
artists, authors and scientists.
   ``Tito's role in making crucial political decisions and his
absolute power in shaping Yugoslav policies were so great that the
present-day position of the country _ and particularly its current
deep social crisis _ cannot be understood or explained without a
comprehensive and objective scientific and critical reappraisal of
his historical responsibility,'' the statement said.
   ``There can be no way out of the present economic, political and
moral crisis affecting Yugoslav society without a thorough critical
evaluation of past Yugoslav policies.''
   Yugoslavia has a $21 billion foreign debt and an annual
inflation rate of about 170 percent. Growing labor unrest is
threatening the Communist Party's leadership.
   In their statement, the intellectuals traced the crisis to
Tito's last decade in power, when the foreign debt rose from $2
billion to $20 billion.
   They also said he ``intentionally invented political opponents
in order to nurture the ghost of permanent civil war, thus
preventing the meaningful democratization of society.''
   Although Yugoslavia, which left the Soviet bloc in 1948, was
considered the most liberal communist country, Tito was intolerant
of opposition.
   The statement was issued one day before the 40th anniversary of
the day Yugoslavia was formally kicked out of the Soviet bloc after
Tito broke with Josef Stalin. On June 28, 1948, the Informbureau, a
Soviet-dominated grouping of all Communist nations and parties,
voted unanimously to expel Yugoslavia for ``deserting the
principles of Marxism-Leninism.''
   Moscow and its allies, which accounted for more than 80 percent
of Yugoslavia's foreign trade, immediately imposed a trade boycott
and Tito turned to the West.
   According to the intellectuals, a ``dispassionate'' assessment
is needed of Tito's role in measures against dissidents,
particularly those sent to ``one of modern Europe's most sinister
prison camps _ Goli Otok.''
   Goli Otok, or Bare Island, is a rocky island off the central
Adriatic coast that was an internment camp for 13,000 alleged
opponents of the regime after Tito's break with Stalin.
   Several thousand are said to have died because of maltreatment
by prison authorities.
   The intellectuals said Tito's foreign policy ``isolated our
country from its natural cultural, historical, economic and
political surroundings'' in Europe. He was a founder three decades
ago of the organization of nations professing non-alignment.
   That focused his foreign policy on Africa and Asia, the
statement said, instead of on political and economic integration
into Western Europe.
   It also criticized Tito's lavish lifestyle, demanding to know
``the real costs of his rule.''
   Tito's salary was never disclosed, but the statement said the
lengthy court battle over his estate indicated his personal wealth
was substantial.
   His widow, Jovanka, sued the state for title to several
mansions, vineyards, limousines and boats she claimed were his
personal property.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
