<DOCNO> AP880629-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SocialInventions     06-29 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Inventions,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twelve Cited For Building A Better World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Graham wanted to break down the
traditional British reserve and get to know his neighbors a bit
better. So he hung up a sign outside his door.
   ``Unofficial Community Cafe,'' it said. ``Open and Free to All
Local Residents as Long as the Sign is Up.''
   He got more than visitors. He won an award for helping make the
world a better place.
   ``I think you have to be slightly brave to put up a sign saying
`Knock on My Door,' but it could catch on,'' said Nicholas Albery,
founder of an organization called the Institute for Social
Inventions.
   Graham was among 12 people singled out this year by the
institute, a London-based group that annually awards cash prizes to
creative people who think of new ways to improve the quality of
life.
   Graham, a television soundman, hung up his sign when he moved
into his new row house in Cardiff, Wales, last winter. The first
day alone, 13 people dropped by for coffee or tea.
   ``I have a humanist bent and I say all people are worth
something, even the most boring of them. But you have to be ready
to do a lot of listening,'' he said in a telephone interview
Wednesday.
   A young mother up the road even borrowed the sign to host the
homespun cafe for awhile.
   The institute divides its $1,700 cash prize among the winners,
who will be feted at a ceremony on July 12.
   Launched in 1985, the institute publishes a Social Inventions
quarterly for about 400 subscribers, said Albery, 39, a
psychotherapist.
   ``I think there are plenty of ideas that are worthy but dull,
and should be worthy but imaginative,'' he said.
   Similar institutes have formed in Sweden, Denmark and the Soviet
Union, and one is planned for the United States among interested
parties in Philadelphia, San Francisco and Oregon, Albery said.
   He said the Soviet Foundation for Social Inventions has been
swamped with 15,000 ideas from the public since it was set up last
fall by geophysicist Gennady Alferenko.
   Other award winners this year include 65-year-old Ilya
Nikolayevich Savin of the Soviet Union, who proposed a network of
regional and school botanical gardens grown from her own 30-year
stock of fruit and berry plant seeds.
   Also among this year's winners is Margie McGregor, whose
Friendship Trust in Oxfordshire encourages adults to help problem
teen-agers take up hobbies.
   British Biochemist John Hart is cited for a proposal to deal
with juvenile delinquents by postponing their age of majority to
21, thus denying them driving licenses or credit cards.
   The Best Third World Social Invention award went to Dr. Thomas
Lovejoy of the Smithsonian Institution in Washington.
   In 1984, he suggested that Western conservation groups could
offer to redeem part of a Third World country's debt in return for
that country providing funds to protect a conservation area, such
as a tropical forest.
   Debt-for-nature swaps have already been arranged in Bolivia,
Ecuador and Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
