<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-UnionNod     06-29 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Union Nod,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wins First Formal Union Endorsement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democractic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis got his first formal union endorsement on Wednesday from a
group that represents mostly federal Internal Revenue Service and
Customs Service workers.
   The 59,000-member National Treasury Employees Union said its
endorsement of the certain Democratic nominee was based on his
commitment to beef up support for the Customs Service's drug
interdiction programs and revenue agencies such as the IRS as a way
to reduce the federal deficit.
   ``The Reagan administration has been long on empty words and
false perceptions but very, very short on good deeds,'' said the
union's president, Robert Tobias.
   ``It proposed reductions of funds to support Customs Service
drug interdiction by 23 percent and whacked drug education
expenditures by 36 percent,'' Tobia said.
   ``The Reagan-Bush romance with Noriega was the capper,'' he
said, referring to Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega, who was
indicted by a federal grand jury in Florida on drug smuggling
charges.
   Tobias also praised what he called Dukakis' commitment to
collective bargaining as evidenced by his relations with
Massachusetts state employees over the past decade.
   The only other union to formally endorse a presidential
candidate so far is the 23,000-member, black-dominated National
Union of Hospital and Health Care Employees. It endorsed civil
rights leader Jesse Jackson early in the primary campaign.
   The Treasury Employees and Hospital Employees unions are not
affiliated with the 14-million member AFL-CIO, which has put off a
formal endorsement until after the Republican National Convention
in August.
</TEXT>
