<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BiloxiCurfew     06-29 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biloxi Curfew,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biloxi Officials Place Curfew On High-Crime Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-block area in a middle-class
neighborhood is off limits after 10 p.m. to children under 16 as
the city tries to keep young people away from drug dealers and
other criminals.
   Police Chief Tommy Moffett said the area is ``a No. 1 hangout
for drug users and peddlers of stolen property. We have seen some
gang activity. And juveniles are being recruited by drug pushers.
   ``We need to separate the youths from that element,'' he said.
   Officials said the emergency 10 p.m. curfew, approved
unanimously by City Council on Tuesday, will continue until Sept.
30. For the rest of Biloxi, a southern Missippi city of 49,000
people on the Gulf of Mexico, the curfew for those under 16 is 1
a.m. to 5 a.m.
   The curfew area is a well-kept neighborhood of modest homes with
several nightclubs and a park. Officials said street corners, open
lots and parking lots have become gathering places for criminals
who hide in the crowds of young people at night.
   The police chief said young people idolize the criminals and
drug pushers in the area, and they have helped criminals escape
from police. Officers are less aggressive because of the presence
of young people, he said.
   Officials said it will be easier for police to fight the city's
drug and crime problems with the youths off the street.
   City Councilman William Stallworth said he proposed the curfew
after pleas from residents. Without juvenile ``shields,'' criminals
will be forced out of the neighborhood, he said.
   ``If you can break up the hub, then everything disperses,'' he
said. ``The situation has become critical.''
   Over the last 18 months in the curfew area, officials said there
have been four homicides, 10 shootings and 246 assaults, including
three assaults on police officers. More than a third of the city's
juvenile problems were reported from that area during the same
period.
</TEXT>
