<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpecialProsecutor-Effect 1stLd-Writethru a0726 06-29
0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Special Prosecutor-Effect, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Ruling on Special Prosecutors Clears Way for Deaver
Sentencing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS last graf to UPDATE with Morrison comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court decision upholding the
validity of independent counsels clears the way for the sentencing
of former White House aide Michael K. Deaver for lying under oath
about his lobbying business.
   The trial judge in Deaver's case had stayed further proceedings
in the case after a federal appellate court in Washington struck
down the constitutionality of the independent counsel law last
January.
   But the Supreme Court's decision Wednesday removes an important
element of Deaver's challenge to his prosecution, though his
lawyers say they have other issues to raise when they appeal the
conviction.
   The decision also means that former White House political
director Lyn Nofziger will have to rely on other issues to appeal
his conviction and 90-day sentence for illegally lobbying former
Reagan administration colleagues.
   And the decision dispels any doubt about the legal authority of
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh to prosecute former White
House aide Oliver L. North and other defendants on charges stemming
from the Iran-Contra arms and money affair.
   ``The independent counsel statute provides a workable solution
to a difficult problem,'' Walsh, who had accepted a back-up
appointment, said in a statement. ``We are gratified that the
Supreme Court has upheld the constitutionality of that statute.''
   The prosecutor in Deaver's case, independent counsel Whitney
North Seymour, said in a brief statement Wednesday that he would
ask U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to reschedule the
sentencing ``at an early date, so the Deaver case can then move on
through the appeal to its final conclusion.''
   Seymour, who declined to accept a parallel appointment from the
Justice Department to blunt the effect of contitutional challenges
to the statute, called the high court's decision ``a major victory
for the public interest.''
   Deaver could receive a five-year sentence for each of three
felony convictions of lying to a grand jury and the House Energy
and Commerce investigations subcommittee about the lobbying
business he formed after leaving President Reagan's staff in 1985.
   Deaver was found guilty of lying when he denied or said he
couldn't recall lobbying former administration colleagues on behalf
of private clients.
   When questions about the propriety of his lobbying business were
raised in 1986, Deaver requested the appointment of an independent
counsel to investigate the allegations in the hopes of clearing his
name.
   His lawyers later tried to stop his indictment on the perjury
charges by challenging Seymour's constitutional and legal authority
to prosecute the case.
   Randall J. Turk, one of Deaver's lawyers, said the conviction
could have been overturned had the law been struck down. But he
said the defense still had other avenues to pursue.
   ``We have a number of issues still pending before the trial
court and if we don't prevail there, we plan to pursue an appeal,''
Turk said.
   Deaver's lawyers have asked Jackson to set aside the verdict on
the ground that the judge made improper rulings and gave erroneous
jury instructions.
   E. Lawrence Barcella, who defended Nofziger, also contended that
the independent counsel decision is not a big setback for his
client.
   ``While we don't agree with the opinion, it doesn't
significantly affect our challenge to the charges that were lodged
against Mr. Nofziger,'' Barcella said.
   ``Our challenge has always been focused on the post-employement
sections of the Ethics in Government Act, the vagueness of that
statute and the application of the facts to that statute,''
Barcella said.
   Nofziger was convicted earlier this year of three counts of
violating the law by lobbying former Reagan administration
colleagues, including then-White House counselor Edwin Meese III,
within a year of leaving the president's staff.
   He has been allowed to remain free pending appeal to the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington, which is scheduled to hear
arguments in November.
   Had the high court struck down the statute, however, Nofziger's
conviction might have been put in jeopardy. Some of the evidence
independent counsel James C. McKay used to convict Nofziger was
obtained before McKay accepted a dual appointment from the Justice
Department last year.
   McKay, meanwhile, is investigating Meese to determine whether he
used his government office for financial gain.
   The high court's ruling also revives the long dormant
investigation of independent counsel Alexia Morrison to investigate
allegations that former Assistant Attorney General Theodore B.
Olson obstructed a congressional investigation of the ``Superfund''
scandal at the Environmental Protection Agency.
   Olson and two other former high-ranking Justice Department
officials had challenged Morrison's power to subpoena them. Their
efforts to resist the subpoenas led to the Supreme Court ruling
Wednesday.
   ``Obviously we are very pleased with the opinion and
particularly at the fact that it was reached nearly unanimously by
the court,'' Morrison said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
