<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Students     06-29 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Students,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Court Sentences Six Students In Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Wednesday sentenced six students
convicted in the slaying of a classmate that triggered campus
riots, a newspaper reported. One of the students was sentenced to
death.
   On June 1, a group of students attacked several of their Beijing
University classmates outside an off-campus food store and killed
Chai Qingfeng, 22. Chai, who was shot in the head with BB gun
pellets and beaten with a shovel, died the following day.
   The court ordered the death penalty for Wang Jian, 26,
identified as the gang leader who shot Chai. Wang, unemployed and
with a record of theft, was convicted of deliberate manslaughter
and hooliganism, the Beijing Evening News said.
   In China, executions usually are carried out with a gunshot to
the back of the head.
   Ha Enming, 18, also unemployed and with a theft record, was
convicted of deliberate manslaughter and given a suspended death
sentence, which is to be reevaluated at the end of two years of
reform labor. The official Xinhua News Agency reported that Ha had
started the brawl and hit Chai with an iron shovel.
   Wang Jianming, 21, and Wang Yonglian, 19, who injured two other
students, were convicted of hooliganism and sentenced to 15 and
seven years in prison, respectively.
   Wang Li, 22, was convicted of sheltering a criminal and
hooliganism, and sentenced to three years in prison. The agency
reported she encouraged her friends to beat the students, gave
false testimony to police, and helped the other five flee by giving
them money.
   The agency reported that Liu Bin, 22, was not punished because
he had tried to stop his classmates from attacking their fellow
students.
   The reports did not say if any of the sentenced students named
Wang _ a common name in China _ are related.
   On the night of Chai's death, nearly 1,000 fellow students
marched from the campus to central Beijing's Tiananmen Square to
demonstrate their sorrow and demand tighter security for students.
   Within the next week, hundreds of posters were posted at the
university, denouncing government corruption and demanding
democracy and more funds for education. The unrest subsided after
police sealed off Tiananmen Square.
   In an effort to calm the students, police arrested the six
suspects within 48 hours of Chai's death. The trial of the six
began June 18 and was closed to the foreign media. No official
reports were available on the testimony.
   Chai was the second university student murdered in Beijing in
the past year. A student at the University of Foreign Economic
Relations was killed in December in a fight with two local youths.
They also were arrested and tried, and one was executed.
</TEXT>
