<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1739EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Budget     06-29 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Final Appropriations Bill Earlier Than Usual</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed the last of its 13 annual
appropriations bills on Wednesday, the earliest that feat has been
accomplished in 28 years.
   ``Hell has indeed frozen over,'' quipped Rep. Silvio Conte of
Massachusetts, senior Republican on the House Appropriations
Committee.
   After the House overwhelmingly approved its last two money bills
_ covering transportation and interior programs _ House Speaker Jim
Wright halted deliberations to hail ``a historically significant
occasion.''
   The last time the House approved all of its spending bills
before June 30 was in 1960, when the new fiscal year began July 1.
This year's bills are for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1.
   This year's process has been immensely easier than in recent
years because of last fall's deficit-reduction agreement between
President Reagan and congressional leaders. That pact decided in
advance next year's overall spending levels for military, foreign
aid, and domestic agency programs.
   ``We have kept the total of appropriations bills below the
president's requests, although we made rearrangements of priorities
of the various bills to continue essential domestic programs,''
said Rep. Jamie L. Whitten, D-Miss., the chairman of the
Appropriations Committee who received a round of applause.
   Because of the House's changes in spending plans, some of which
the White House contends are too costly, there are veto threats
hanging over several of the bills.
   But even if just one of the regular spending bills is eventually
signed by the president, the record will be better than in the last
two years.
   For last year and the current fiscal year, all of the
government's spending authority has been wrapped into huge,
catchall money bills. The president has promised never again to
sign one of those omnibus measures, and many in Congress vowed
never to vote for one again.
   The Senate has approved its version of four spending bills. The
House and Senate have reached agreement on one of those, and it
could be sent to the White House in the next few days.
</TEXT>
