<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MilwaukeeMovie     06-29 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Milwaukee Movie,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baseball Movie Casting Draws Players, Scouts and Dreamers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of amateur baseball players flocked to a
city park Wednesday to try out for a major league team that will
compete only on the silver screen.
   But some of the men who showed up wearing baseball caps and
lugging bats and gloves hoped that, even if they didn't catch the
eye of the casting director, they might be noticed by the
professional scouts who were on hand.
   ``If there's some major league prospects out there, you can bet
your pants I'll be there to sign them,'' said scout Emil Belich, of
the Major League Baseball Scouting Bureau. ``You never know.''
   The movie, titled ``Major League,'' will be filmed in Milwaukee
later this summer.
   ``It's been a dream of mine to be in the movies and to play
ball. I get on this (cast) and it's a dream come true,'' said Dan
Steffan of Milwaukee, one of the nearly 200 men who turned up at
the daylong tryouts at Washington Park.
   ``I can hit, I can pitch and I can do anything they want to....
It just depends on what they're looking for,'' added William Pucci,
24, of suburban Brookfield, who plays semi-professional baseball in
the Milwaukee area.
   Dan Barrett, a Marquette University student from Cincinnati,
said he would be willing to sacrifice his college soccer season to
make the movie.
   ``I'd love to make a summer of it. I'd maybe even bypass the
soccer season if it help me'' get on the squad, Barrett said.
   The movie, produced by Major League Productions, will focus on a
professional team from Cleveland that sheds its losing ways during
a championship season, said Lisa Beasly, head of the casting crew.
   The filming of ``Major League'' comes on the heels of the
release this summer of a baseball romance story, ``Bull Durham''
about a minor league catcher. ``Major League'' is expected to be
released next spring.
   Most of the movies will be filmed between the end of July and
mid-September at Milwaukee's County Stadium, home of the Milwaukee
Brewers professional baseball team.
   ``It's a great city and everybody's wonderful and they've got
that wonderful ball park,'' Beasly said.
   Other scenes will be shot in Tucson, Ariz., and Mexico, Beasly
said.
   Beasly and her assistants said about 50 men will be selected to
play on the teams featured in the movie. Five will travel with the
regular cast, which includes Charlie Sheen as the team's star
pitcher and Tom Berenger as a catcher.
   ``They have to look like major league ball players,'' Beasly
said. ``If nothing else, they get to wear the major league uniforms
of their dreams.''
   To help with the tryouts, Beasly asked former Cleveland Indians
great Ken Keltner to come to the field. Keltner's diving catch at
third base helped snap Hall of Famer Joe Dimaggio's 56-game hitting
streak in 1941.
   ``That's my alma mater (Cleveland) and this is my home town,
Milwaukee, so I guess I had to be here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
