<DOCNO> AP880629-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PatrickKennedy     06-29 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patrick Kennedy,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Kennedy's Son Files For First Political Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick J. Kennedy, the 20-year-old son
of Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy, said Wednesday he will run
for office, challenging a long-time legislator in Rhode Island,
where he attends college.
   Kennedy will face five-term state Rep. John M. Skeffington Jr.
in the Sept. 14 primary. The winner is virtually assured of
election in the heavily Democratic district.
   ``I think I offer new ideas and especially important, the energy
to put those ideas to work,'' Kennedy said, appearing slightly
nervous before the television cameras as he filed his candidacy
papers.
   Skeffington said he was surprised that a Kennedy would decide to
begin his political career by challenging a member of his own party.
   ``I did not think they would come in running against an
incumbent Democrat holding office,'' Skeffington said. ``I don't
think they've ever done that before, with the exception of (Patrick
Kennedy's) father running for president.''
   Skeffington, in an interview, stressed his family's ties to the
working- to middle-class Mount Pleasant neighborhood where his
grandfather established the family funeral home 75 years ago.
   ``I'm 50 years old. My roots are here. I'm not going anywhere,''
he said. Under Rhode Island law, anyone who is 18 and has lived in
the state for 30 days may run for the General Assembly.
   Kennedy, who will be a junior at Providence College this fall,
said he plans to make the state his home after graduation. ``My
community is Mount Pleasant and my future is Rhode Island,'' he
said.
   In 1986, Skeffington won renomination by just 165 votes over
Brian Reddy, a political newcomer.
   Kennedy's name has appeared on a Rhode Island ballot once
before. In the March presidential primary he spent $12,000 and won
more votes than any other delegate for Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis in the state's 2nd Congressional District except for
Providence Mayor Joseph R. Paolino Jr.
   ``Because of the money he can put into this race, it will be an
interesting contest,'' Skeffington said. ``I've never hired a
polling association before, but I've been forced to this year.''
   Kennedy said he had not drawn up a budget yet, but does not plan
to spend any more than ``you would spend in any hotly contested
legislative race.''
   Kennedy is the youngest of Edward Kennedy's three children. Two
of his cousins, both children of the late Robert F. Kennedy, have
also run for office. Joseph P. Kennedy II was elected to Congress
from Massachusetts and Kathleen Kennedy Townsend lost a
congressional race in Maryland.
</TEXT>
