<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Secrecy 1stLd-Writethru a0778 06-29 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Secrecy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0778,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Annouces Proposals to Liberalize Secrecy Laws</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Raises 6th graf to 3rd graf to raise reference to opposition
to proposals.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced proposals Wednesday to
liberalize Britain's sweeping secrecy laws by decriminalizing
trivial leaks and giving journalists more legal protection.
   Another key clause would confine secrecy mainly to defense,
intelligence and foreign affairs.
   The opposition Labor Party denounced the proposals as
``draconian and unacceptable.'' They also were criticized by
proponents of freedom of information, and by at least one Tory
legislator.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said the Conservative government,
long accused of being obsessed with secrecy, aimed to ``clip the
wings of any possible abuse of the criminal law by the Executive.''
   ``This should dispel any notion that the criminal law is being
used to protect information simply because its disclosure would
embarrass the government,'' Hurd told the House of Commons.
   However, the reforms would reinforce the lifetime gag on
intelligence agents and make them automatically liable for criminal
prosecution for any disclosure.
   Hurd said the move was the most radical plan yet to reform the
Official Secrets Act, which makes it a criminal offense to reveal
any official information, however trivial, without formal
authorization.
   The act, passed hastily during a 1911 German spy scare, has
helped give Britain a reputation as the most secretive of the
Western democracies.
   The new proposals restricted secrecy to six categories: defense;
security and intelligence; international relations; information
obtained in confidence from other governments; information useful
to criminals; and information about bugging, telephone surveilance
and the reading of mail.
   However, officials would face internal disciplinary measures for
disclosing confidential material such as Cabinet documents.
   ``From a freedom of information point of view, this is dismal,''
said Des Wilson, chairman of the Campaign for Freedom of
Information pressure group.
   ``This gives no greater access to information. It simply narrows
the number of categories in which disclosure is a criminal
offense.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has ruled out a U.S.-style
Freedom of Information Act.
   The proposals, outlined in a policy document presented to
Parliament, followed a series of secrecy-related controversies.
   These included a 1986 police raid on British Broadcasting Corp.
studios to seize tapes of a documentary about a spy satellite, and
the government's losing two-year court battle to ban publication of
``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs of retired intelligence officer Peter
Wright.
   Under the new proposals, Wright, who lives in Australia, could
be pursued with the same vigor and be charged if he returned to
Britain.
   The proposals also stipulated that people charged under the
Official Secrets Act cannot plead in their defense that the leak
was in the public interest, commonly known as whistle-blowing, or
that the material had been already published elsewhere.
   In 1985, a jury acquitted Clive Ponting, a former senior civil
servant, on grounds that his exposure of a goverment cover-up of
facts surrounding the sinking of an Argentine cruiser in the 1982
Falkland Islands war was in the public interest.
   ``I would probably have been found guilty under these new
proposals,'' Ponting commented Wednesday.
   However, the proposals offer journalists a new protection by
shifting to the prosecution the onus of proving that a disclosure
gravely harmed national interests.
   Courts alone, and not government ministers, would be able to
rule on what is secret.
   Richard Shepherd, a Tory legislator whose more liberal reform
bill was defeated last January on Mrs. Thatcher's instructions,
called the government proposals ``repressive.''
   But analysts said a parliamentary revolt by Tory dissidents who
backed the Shepherd bill appeared to have helped liberalize the
government proposals.
   Two major previous attempts at reform, in 1971 and 1979,
foundered largely on criticisms they did not go far enough.
   Newspaper editors said the new proposals were less restrictive
than anticipated, but complained that publication of secret
material in the public interest or because it had already been
published elsewhere should be legitimate defenses.
   ``We believe they (the defenses) would have helped avert
nonsenses such as we have recently had to endure in the guise of
protecting official secrets,'' said James Bishop, chairman of the
Association of British Editors.
   Several prestigious national newspapers are fighting
prosecutions for publishing material from or about ``Spycatcher.''
Wright's book, banned from sale in Britain, has been a best-seller
worldwide.
</TEXT>
