<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman-Surgery,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Lawmaker Undergoes Heart Surgery, Doing Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Glenn Anderson, chairman of the House
Public Works and Transportation Committee, had multiple bypass
heart surgery Wednesday and was doing well, his office said.
   Surgery was performed on the 75-year-old California Democrat at
Good Samaritan Hospital in Los Angeles, Anderson spokesman David
Smallen said. The congressman was expected to return home to San
Pedro, Calif., by July 4, Smallen said.
   Anderson succeeded Rep. James Howard, D-N.J., as chairman of the
public works committee after Howard died last March 25 following a
heart attack.
   Smallen said the surgery on Anderson, who had no history of
heart problems, was ``elective'' and ``routine.'' He said the
lawmaker had planned to have the procedure performed during the
congressional recess in August, but moved up the date after
learning that his surgeon would be taking a long vacation beginning
later this week.
   Anderson probably will miss the Democratic national convention
in Atlanta next month, Smallen said, which he was scheduled to
attend as a delegate for the likely candidate, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis. He is expected to return to Washington after the
convention.
   Anderson has been in Congress for 20 years. Known as a quiet
legislator who is happy to sidestep controversy, he was lieutenant
governor of California from 1959 to 1967, and a member of the state
Assembly from 1943 to 1951. He began his political career when he
became mayor of Hawthorne, Calif., in 1941.
