<DOCNO> AP880629-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WeatherOutlook     06-29 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weather Outlook,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Cheer in Store for Dry Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government weather forecasters offered scant
cheer to drought-plagued areas Wednesday, issuing a series of
forecasts that call for more of the same, at least for the next
month.
   ``It's likely to get worse before it gets better,'' said Dr.
Michael Hudlow, director of hydrology for the National Weather
Service.
   The overall outlook calls for little change in the weather for
the next week or two. Hot, dry weather will continue but shift its
emphasis eastward and southward over the next one to three months,
said Dr. Donald L. Gilman, head of the agency's Long Range
Predictions Group.
   The lone bit of good news, if it comes in time, was a chance of
above-normal moisture in some western sections of the Great Plains
sometime in the next 90 days.
   ``Unfortunately, reliable predictions of the drought's end, its
geographic spread or changes in severity cannot be made today,''
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration cautioned in a
statement issued at a news briefing.
   High-altitude jet stream winds that normally sweep across the
northern tier of states have split to the north and south, Gilman
said, holding the drought conditions in place between them.
   The 6-to-10-day outlook is ``very close to holding stationary
the pattern of the last few weeks,'' Gilman said.
   In that short time span, the outlook calls for much-above-normal
temperatures in Montana, Wyoming, the Dakotas, Nebraska, Wisconsin
and Iowa.
   In addition, above-normal readings are expected in much of the
rest of the nation except the Columbia River valley, West Texas and
along the Atlantic Coast from North Carolina through Georgia and
northern Florida.
   In the short range, the rain forecast is ``patchy,'' said
Gilman. He said no precipitation is likely in Oregon, California,
Nevada, southern Idaho, western Utah, western Arizona and Texas.
   There is a chance of some scattered moisture from the Gulf of
Mexico causing rain here and there in the Midwest. But only Kansas,
South Carolina and Georgia seem likely to have more rain than
normal for the period.
   Turning to the 30-day forecast for July, above-normal heat is
expected throughout most of the northern Plains and upper Midwest,
Gilman said, while the outlook for rain is ``very uncertain.''
   The greatest chance of hot weather is in Illinois, Indiana,
Ohio, Kentucky and Tennessee, Gilman said. He gave that region a 65
percent chance of being hotter than normal for July, an unusually
high ranking for a summer forecast. Outlooks for 30 days normally
carry only a 55 percent probability.
   In addition, July has a chance of warmer-than-normal weather
from Pennsylvania west through the Great Lakes states to Montana,
south to Oklahoma and Arkansas and east to the Appalachian
Mountains.
   The rest of the country should expect near-normal readings in
July except the Puget Sound region, where is it expected to be
cooler than normal.
   The outlook for rain in July shows below-normal readings
expected for California, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio and
Kentucky. Above-normal precipitation is expected only in Puget
Sound and along the Arizona-New Mexico border.
   Other regions are likely to be close to normal, Gilman said, but
the below-normal region could expand back into the Plains.
   Gilman said that if it were earlier in the year, he would have
predicted a larger dry area, but there may be breaks in the jet
stream which could allow some rain to move north from the Gulf of
Mexico.
   The Weather Service also issued a 90-day forecast for July,
August and September.
   That outlook anticipates above-normal temperatures along the
Pacific Coast, in southern Arizona and in Iowa, Missouri, Arkansas,
Louisiana, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania, West Virginia,
Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia, Maryland, Delaware, the Carolinas,
Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia and Florida.
   Below-normal temperatures are expected in Idaho, Montana,
Wyoming, Colorado, Utah and New Mexico, with near-normal readings
elsewhere.
   The three-month rain outlook is for below-normal amounts in
California, Maryland, Virginia, the Carolinas, Georgia and parts of
West Virginia, Tennessee and Kentucky.
   The lone bit of good news may be the chance of above-normal
precipitation for Montana, Wyoming, southern South Dakota,
Nebraska, Kansas, Colorado, New Mexico, West Texas and western
Oklahoma over the 90 days.
   For the rest of the nation the chances are too close to call
over such a long period, Gilman said.
</TEXT>
