<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NunAbducted     06-29 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nun Abducted,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Takes Woman From Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old woman, taken from a New York
convent by her family, will be free to return after she hears her
family's concerns about the institution, a brother said.
   Mary Susan Greve, known as Sister Mary Cecelia, was walking with
two nuns on a street in a Catskill Mountains town Sunday when her
father and her three brothers pushed her into a car and took her
away.
   New York state police have said they would not press charges
unless the woman wants to file them.
   John Greve, 16, declined Tuesday to say where his sister and the
rest of the family were staying.
   The family, he said, opposed his sister's decision to become a
novice at St. Joseph Novitiate Convent in Roundtop, N.Y., after the
family broke with a traditionalist Catholic church in Sharonville,
a Cincinnati suburb.
   The Rev. Michael A. Farano, chancellor of the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of Albany, N.Y., said the St. Joseph Novitiate Convent
calls itself a traditionalist Roman Catholic convent.
   However, he said, it is not recognized by the Catholic Church.
Its services are in Latin and it has rejected all of the teachings
of the Second Vatican Council of the 1960s, he added.
   ``The reason we did this was to give her the facts,'' John Greve
said, referring to the incident Sunday.
   If she wants to return to the convent after she hears her family
out, she is free to do so, he said. ``But we know that will be the
last time we will probably ever see her again,'' he said.
   Sunday was the second time the family has taken the woman from
the convent, John Greve said. His mother, he said, went to the
convent in April, tricked her daughter into getting into the car
and flew her back to Cincinnati, where a nun from the convent was
waiting for them. The nun succeeded in persuading the woman to
return to the convent.
   A sister-in-law, Gina Greve, said the convent's spiritual
adviser, the Rev. Clarence Kelly, has forbidden Mary Susan Greve
from seeing or talking to family members.
   ``He said they cannot let her go back to her family because we
would be an evil influence and jeopardize her vocation,'' she said.
   Kelly said Tuesday that his concern was for the young woman. ``I
hope the parents come to their senses, leave her be and let her
live her own life.''
   John Greve said he and two brothers, Dave and Mark, and his
parents, James and Susan Greve, participated in the most recent
incident. The father and the brothers took the sister from the
convent, while the mother waited in a motel, he said.
</TEXT>
