<DOCNO> AP880629-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lefebvre Bjt   06-29 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishop Ordains Priests, Followers Are Defiant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ECO3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre ordained 16
priests Wednesday, the day before a consecration of four bishops
that will automatically expel the rebel traditionalist from the
Roman Catholic Church.
   He urged the new priests to fight the ``cancer of liberalism''
in the church, which the 82-year-old archbishop says has been
infiltrated by ``wolves and thieves.''
   Organizers estimated the ceremony attracted at least 7,000
people to a rolling meadow in front of Lefebvre's seminary in this
Swiss hamlet.
   Sympathizers came from all over Western Europe, many in buses.
More than 1,000 cars were parked around the huge tent, which also
will be the scene of Thursday's consecration.
   Lefebvre says bishops must be consecrated so his traditionalist
movement will continue after he dies. Church law provides automatic
excommunication of those involved if bishops are consecrated
without papal approval.
   Pope John Paul II said Tuesday he was ``very saddened'' by
Lefebvre's ``breaking the unity of the church (and) taking with him
a large number of followers into schism.''
   Vatican officials said a performance of Beethoven's Missa
Solemnis, scheduled for Thursday evening in the Paul VI Auditorium,
was canceled because of the ``deep pain'' felt by the church over
the Lefebvre affair.
   The last major schism, or split in the church, occurred when the
so-called Old Catholics broke with Rome in 1870 after the First
Vatican Council proclaimed the doctrine of papal infallibility.
   Repeated pleas by the pontiff have failed to impress the French
archbishop, who has said excommunication is ``without value'' and
ignored previous Vatican sanctions.
   Before Wednesday's ceremony, he had ordained more than 220
traditionalist priests since Pope Paul VI suspended him from
priestly functions in 1976. The Vatican considers all the
ordinations illegal.
   Most of the 16 new priests are French graduates of the seminary
of Lefebvre's St. Pius X Fraternity, which he founded 18 years ago
in Econe and named for the pope who condemned modernism in a 1907
encyclical.
   Also among the new priests were West German, Italian, Spanish,
Australian and British nationals and an American, James H. Doran,
25, son of an automotive designer in Detroit.
   Lefebvre's rebellion began with the Second Vatican Council of
1962-65, whose liberal reforms included modernizing the liturgy. He
continued celebrating Mass in Latin, using the 16th century
Tridentine rite, and dismissed the ``bastard rites'' in the
vernacular that took its place.
   He speaks of the ``satanic influence'' of liberalism in the
church, preaches against ``neo-modernist and neo-Protestant
tendencies'' and proclaims: ``Our future is the past.''
   In his homily Wednesday, Lefebvre did not refer directly to the
impending excommunication but repeated his argument that he is not
the one causing schism.
   ``He who breaks with tradition breaks with the church,''
Lefebvre told the new priests, and urged them to fight ``the cancer
of liberalism'' he says has been spreading since the Second Vatican
Council.
   They will suffer ``persecution,'' he added, but ``whatever you
may be told, you will remain Catholic.''
   Antonio de Castro Mayer of Campos, Brazil, who is 84 and the
only bishop to support Lefebvre publicly, assisted him at the
ceremony.
   Among the spectators were nuns in white, Dominican monks in
yellow robes and 50 supporters of Lefebvre from Gabon, dressed in
African garb and mingling with the crowd. Lefebvre was a missionary
in Gabon for 13 years and later was named archbishop of Dakar,
Senegal.
   About a dozen people questioned at random said the Vatican
warnings left them unshaken in their loyalty to Lefebvre view.
   ``History will prove that he is right,'' said Mark Simmons, a
29-year-old London accountiong clerk who was among about 200
British sympathizers.
   Some supporters said they expect an eventual settlement with the
Vatican.
   ``Sooner or later, Rome will recognize the fruits of Monsignor
Lefebvre's work,'' said Doran, the American ordained.
   Speculation about a new last-minute appeal from the pope stirred
when a priest arrived in the official car of the Vatican ambassador
to Switzerland but would not say why he had come.
   Edoardo Rovida, the ambassador, was reached by telephone at his
office in Bern and asked whether his aide brought a letter from the
pope. ``There are always letters to be brought,'' he replied, and
refused to elaborate.
</TEXT>
