<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0786 06-29 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0786,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel, U.S. Agree To Joint Development Of New Missile</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 1 graf with Shultz not planning Middle East visit in
July</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Israel agreed Wednesday
to work together on the development of a new tactical missile
designed to shoot down Arab ballistic rockets which could be fired
at Israeli population centers.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin called the Arrow project
a response to ``push-button'' warfare in which Arab foes were
relying on Soviet and Chinese rockets to try pierce Israeli
defenses.
   He said the missile should be ready for testing in two to three
years, with a decision on production depending on the results.
   The agreement was signed at a Pentagon ceremony by Maj. Gen.
David Ivry, director general of the Israeli defense ministry, and
Lt. Gen. James Abrahamson, who is in charge of the U.S. Strategic
Defense Initiative.
   Israel is collaborating with the United States in the search for
a space-based defense against Soviet ballistic missiles. The
program, known popularly as Star Wars, anticipates using kinetic
energy, lasers and other sophisticated technology to destroy the
rockets before they could reach their U.S. targets.
   Rabin stressed in a speech at the National Press Club that
Israel's objectives were much more limited. He said if the Arrow
proved effective in the tests the missile might be used as a
defensive weapon at short-range.
   The Israeli official said Israel had to find a way to cope with
the new missiles the Soviets had supplied to Syria and the Chinese
to Saudi Arabia. He said the Syrian missiles could reach almost
every target in Israel.
   For the Arabs, who have fought six major wars with Israel since
1948, the rockets offer a chance to accomplish what Arab armies and
air forces could not achieve, Rabin said.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, at a separate news
conference, said the Arrow ``would make a contribution to our SDI
program, and have application, as well, in other areas.''
   He said the joint project ``fits in very well with our concept
of deterrence based on defense.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who appeared with Carlucci
at the windup of separate talks with Australian officials, said
``if you happen to be sitting in Israel, with shorter-range
ballistic missiles around you that are very hard to defend against,
you feel very strongly the importance of learning how to defend
yoursevles against them.''
   A Pentagon statement said 80 percent of the cost would be borne
by the United States and 20 percent by Israel.
   The signing followed a statement of concern Tuesday by President
Reagan after a meeting at the White House with Rabin. The president
said he was troubled by ``ominous new military developments'' in
the area.
   Rabin, during two days of talks here, has stressed Soviet
deliveries of new missiles to Syria and Libya, and Chinese
shipments to Saudi Arabia.
   ``If the United States could not persuade China and Saudi
Arabia, I doubt Israel would be able to persuade the Soviet
Union,'' to refrain from the deliveries, Rabin said.
   Israel has had a series of diplomatic meetings recently with
Soviet officials that indicate a warming by Moscow to the Jewish
state, with which it broke relations in 1967.
   On another subject, Rabin criticized American television
networks and other media for giving much less coverage to missile
attacks by Iran and Iraq on each other's cities and other war
atrocitiies than to the beatings of Palestinian Arabs on the West
Bank.
   Rabin said he was used to having a ``double-standard'' applied
to Israel, but he believed the networks should have devoted more
than a few minutes to what he said was the slaying of 5,000 Kurds
by Iraq with chemical weapons.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said Shultz had no
plans to visit the Middle East in July. The possibility of such a
trip was raised when Michael H. Armacost, undersecretary of state
for political affairs, told reporters in Israel he discussed the
issue with Israeli leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Teamsters Bjt   06-29 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters, Bjt,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Union A Test Case For National Suit Against Teamsters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A test case has shown that a government
takeover can restore some democracy to a corrupt Teamsters local,
but the battle is far from over, the local's court-appointed
trustee said Wednesday.
   And labor observers stressed that the experience of Teamsters
Local 560 in Union City does not mean the Justice Department will
be able to meet the far more ambitious goal it announced Tuesday _
wresting control from the union's international leaders.
   The success of a government takeover could depend on how much
power a judge grants to a trustee, said Herman Benson, director of
the Brooklyn, N.Y.-based Association for Union Democracy, a
non-partisan union rights group.
   To eliminate union corruption, ``you have to have massive
government interaction,'' said Benson.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in New York filed suit Tuesday
describing the Teamsters as dominated by the Mafia, seeking to have
a federal judge remove from office any union officials who violated
racketeering laws and appoint a trustee to supervise free elections.
   In 1984, U.S. District Judge Harold A. Ackerman ruled that a
takeover of Local 560 was necessary because of a quarter-century of
brutal organized crime domination at the hands of the Provenzano
family. Ackerman appointed a trustee to clean up the local and
bring on free elections.
   It was the first time a union had been placed under government
control.
   Benson points to recent improvements in allowing the 8,500
members of Local 560 a voice in their union. He said the changes
have come under stewardship of Edwin Steir, a former federal
prosecutor on the job about a year.
   ``I see enormous change since I've gotten here,'' said Steir,
citing discussion of past corruption among the rank and file.
   ``People say things they've never said before,'' he said.
   However, ``there's still fear here and there's a lot of
uncertainty'' about how to assert dissenting views, he said.
   Attorney Harvey Weissbard, who represents Local 560's last
president, Michael Sciarra, said Giuliani's office is going to face
some ``high-powered (legal) talent'' and the prospect of lengthy
appeals, which could also bog down the process.
   Sciarra dismissed Tuesday's lawsuit as a politically motivated,
union-busting move that signaled a ``dark day for labor.'' Sciarra
has the support of a large and vocal group of Local 560 members.
About 2,000 people appeared at a recent rally for him.
   Two candidates have emerged to oppose Sciarra, who rose to power
under the deposed leadership.
   Weissbard said he plans to file a motion later this week to
overturn Ackerman's 1984 decision based on a recent Supreme Court
ruling. A group of 260 truckers who joined the union after 1984
have also sued to end the trusteeship.
   The trustee took over Local 560 in 1986, after an appeals courts
upheld Ackerman. But only in recent months have forces organized to
oppose the former allies of jailed ex-president Anthony ``Tony
Pro'' Provenzano, who authorities say is a captain in the Genovese
crime family.
   He has been linked to the unsolved disappearance of national
Teamsters leader Jimmy Hoffa in 1975.
   Steir says he has had trouble building democracy because of a
tradition of suppression of dissent that made fear and cynicism his
main enemies.
   Benson said the very size of the international union could be an
asset in allowing more open discussion among the rank and file.
``The international, at least, is not one monolithic block of
crooks,'' he said.
   On the other hand, said labor law expert Michael Goldberg, a
University of Pittsburgh law school associate professor, a trustee
of the international will have to contend with thousands of local
leaders who may not cooperate.
   New York University law professor James Jacobs pointed out that
the function of a local and the international are different, and it
is difficult to draw conclusions from Local 560's experience.
   ``There you're really running a union at the grass roots,'' he
said. In the international's case, ``you're talking about an
overarching management of the whole administration.''
   Whether Local 560 has been freed from the taint of organized
crime is still an open question.
   Federal prosecutors earlier this year questioned Sciarra and
former vice president Joseph Sheridan at a deposition where they
sought to find out whether reputed Genovese crime family captain
Matthew ``Matty the Horse'' Ianniello influenced union decisions.
   On a tape of a secretly recorded conversation in 1984, Ianniello
is heard saying to a Local 560 official, ``I think Mike Sciarra
should take over there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
