<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InsiderTrading-Wang     06-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading-Wang,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Analyst Remembered As Bright, Ambitious Schemer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Insider Trading-Lee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen Wang Jr., a young investment analyst
trainee charged in the second-biggest insider-trading scandal in
Wall Street history, was always a ``make-a-buck kind of person,''
recalled his high school sweetheart.
   ``He said he wanted to make his first million by (age) 30,''
said Gloria Lowry of north suburban Skokie, Ill. ``He was always
scheming _ coming up with ways to make money.''
   Ms. Lowry dated Wang, 24, as a teen-ager in Arlington Heights,
the northwest suburb in which both were raised.
   Other acquaintances remembered Wang as a bright, driven young
man who left the University of Illinois just two credits shy of an
undergraduate degree to pursue his ambitions with a major New York
investment firm.
   Wang, a junior investment analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co., was
accused Monday in a civil case of participating in an illegal
insider-trading scheme that allegedly netted $19 million. Wang
received at least $200,000, according to the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   ``My wife and I said someday he'd be a millionaire, but this is
a shock,'' said Tom Walsh, 33, a neighbor of Wang's father, Stephen
Sr., a Taiwan-born engineer and stepmother, Pat, who still live in
the house where Wang, his brother and two sisters grew up.
   Wang's parents have an unlisted telephone number and could not
be reached Wednesday. But an account in The Wall Street Journal on
Wednesday quoted his father as saying his son remains hopeful he'll
be cleared of wrongdoing.
   The father also was quoted as saying his son denied breaking any
laws and was taken advantage of by the man alleged to be his
co-conspirator, Taiwan-born businessman Fred C. Lee, a Morgan
client.
   ``He might have let one or two things slip that (Lee) made money
on,'' the elder Wang was quoted as saying. ``But he didn't mean
to.''
   Wang was an active youth who mowed lawns and shoveled snow to
earn money and often organized other children to do chorse for him,
said Kathleen Paul, a neighbor who has known him for 20 years.
   ``Money was a very high priority for him when he was a child,''
she said.
   After graduating with good grades from Buffalo Grove High
School, where he played on the basketball and baseball teams, Wang
enrolled in 1982 at the University of Illinois. He first studied
political science but switched his major to finance and accounting,
according to school records.
   As a freshman, Wang developed and sold a coupon book called
``The Student Survival Kit.'' He persuaded retailers to place
coupons in the book, which he sold to students for $2.
   In a 1983 interview with the Illini Times, a weekly newspaper
distributed on campus, Wang said he had derived more satisfaction
from the experience of the coupon project than from the undisclosed
amount of money it made.
   ``We're put on this earth to achieve,'' Wang said. ``If you love
what you do, money comes along with it.''
   Wang left college in the spring of 1986 and was hired by Morgan
for a two-year internship. The firm usually recruits college
graduates for the program but made an exception for Wang.
   ``I can't tell you two years back what went into the decision
but we were well aware that when he came here, Mr. Wang didn't have
a degree,'' Morgan spokesman Lawrence Friedman said.
   Nevertheless, Wang circulated a resume on Wall Street last year
in which he claimed he had graduated magna cum laude with a finance
degree from the university, according to an account in The New York
Times.
   Wang, who was paid about $31,000 last year, would have finished
the two-year Morgan training program Friday, Friedman said. Wang
has been suspended pending an investigation of the SEC charges.
</TEXT>
