<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthInsurance     06-29 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Insurance,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Require All Employers to Offer Medical Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All employers would be required to offer
medical insurance to their workers under a bill introduced
Wednesday by Rep. Fortney H. Stark, who said the measure would
``move us a long way'' toward universal health insurance.
   The Employee Health Benefit Act is similar to a minimum health
bill awaiting Senate floor action.
   There are about 37 million Americans without health care
coverage, and two-thirds of them have jobs or are dependents of
people with jobs. In 1985, hospitals provided $7.4 billion in
charity care.
   The bill from Stark, chairman of the House Ways and Means health
subcommittee, would require employers to offer coverage of the same
services as Medicare plus maternal and child health benefits. It
would set up state risk pools to keep costs reasonable and put a
cap on the cost of group insurance purchased by small employers.
   Its enactment ``would move us a long way towards the target of
assuring every American's basic right to high-quality health
services,'' Stark, D-Calif., said in a floor statement submitted
for the record.
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee in February
approved a similar bill sponsored by its chairman, Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass. But it is unclear when or if the full Senate will
consider it during this Congress. The same bill is pending in the
House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Expanded health care coverage is expected to be a priority in
the next Congress starting in January.
</TEXT>
