<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Morales     06-29 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Morales,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decision Called Example of Mexican Sovereignty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government remained silent about
Washington's anger over the release of a Puerto Rican separatist,
but local editorials Wednesday praised the decision as an example
of national sovereignty.
   ``The Mexican government denied the extradition of William
Morales, and that is a decision that merits all the support of the
citizenry because it strengthens national sovereignty against
external pressures,'' the leftist newspaper Uno Mas Uno, or One
plus One, wrote.
   Morales, 37, is wanted in the United States for terrorist
activities.
   The daily La Jornada, a competing leftist paper, wrote that the
United States tried ``to magnify a diplomatic-political matter
whose limits are clearly defined'' and ``has taken the case of the
patriot William Morales as a new pretext for confrontation with
Mexico.''
   The editorial said that course ``can be risky for both
countries, especially because of the time and space in which the
conflict is introduced.''
   Both newspapers have followed the Morales case closely. La
Jornada broke the story earlier in June that the Foreign Ministry
decided to grant political asylum to Morales, who was in a Mexican
prison at the time.
   Last Friday, Morales was released after serving five years of an
eight-year sentence for murder and allowed to fly to Cuba. The
Cuban government has not made any statement about his presence on
that Caribbean island.
   As a sign of its displeasure, Washington recalled Ambassador
Charles J. Pilliod Jr. from Mexico City for consultations.
   ``This decision is an inexplicable affront to otherwise
excellent U.S.-Mexican relations and a great blow to U.S. and
Mexican efforts to combat the scourge of international terrorism,''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   Pilliod last week wrote to La Jornada objecting to its editorial
praise for the Foreign Ministry's decision and its description of
U.S. policy on Puerto Rico as ``colonialism.''
   ``Mr. William Morales was tried, found guilty and sentenced by
state and federal courts in New York on the charges of possession
of explosives (homemade bombs and dynamite),'' Pilliod wrote.
   ``It concerns us very much that an individual with his criminal
record and who is a convicted criminal in both countries might be
considered worthy of the status of a political refugee,'' he added.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Tuesday that Mexico waited five days before informing the
United States of Morales' release.
   The newspaper Excelsior, which generally reflects government
positions, said Washington's announcement that it was recalling
Pilliod was ``accompanied by the Reagan administration's typical
language, which doesn't bode well.''
   In a front-page column, Excelsior said the news produced ``a
silence in all the country's political circles'' and now ``the
inevitable response that this announcement provoked must be
awaited, above all in these times on the eve of presidential
elections.''
   General elections are scheduled for July 6, with unusually
strong competition facing the Institutional Revolutionary Party
that has governed Mexico since 1929.
   Morales was sentenced to more than 100 years in prison in New
York but escaped from U.S. custody in 1979. He fled to Mexico,
where in 1983 he was convicted in the killing of a police officer
and for entering the country illegally.
   Tensions about the Morales case come at a time when both
governments have been emphasizing cooperation. The most recent
meeting between Presidents Reagan and Miguel de la Madrid in
February in the Pacific coastal resort of Mazatlan even minimized
the longstanding disputes over drug trafficking.
   U.S. officials at the State Department are making no secret of
their dislike for Foreign Minister Bernardo Sepulveda, whose
department issued the decision on Morales' political asylum.
   The resolution signed by Sepulveda granting asylum said Morales,
who was badly disfigured in an explosion at a clandestine bomb
factory in New York, ``did not arrive at producing harm to society
or any individuals in particular, escept those he inflicted upon
himself.''
   In one of Morales' last interviews before leaving Mexico, he
told The Associated Press by telephone from the Northern
Penitentiary in Mexico City that the government's decision was ``a
political recognition of our fight'' for independence.
   He said he would not return to Puerto Rico ``because political
persecution continues over there. But I can say that the Mexican
government's decision reflects a very Latin American position.''
   Puerto Rico is a commonwealth of the United States whose
residents have American citizenship but cannot vote in U.S.
presidential elections. Some Puerto Rican nationalist groups
advocate independence for the island but are split over whether to
use violence to attain their goal.
</TEXT>
