<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JetCrashes     06-29 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Crashes,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two F-16s Collide, Another Crashes; One Pilot Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FRA5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BODENHEIM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. Air Force F-16 fighters
on a training flight collided and crashed Wednesday near this
southwestern town less than two hours after another went down in
the Black Forest, officials said.
   Police said one pilot was killed in the collision.
   A Pentagon spokesman said it was the first time F-16s had
collided and that three of the single-engine jets had been lost in
one day.
   Identities of the pilots were not released.
   The collision near Bodenheim, a town of 6,000 about six miles
south of Mainz, occurred at 1:30 p.m. (7:30 a.m. EDT), said Capt.
Gail Hayes, an Air Force spokeswoman. The planes were assigned to
the 50th Tactical Fighter Wing at Hahn Air Base in West Germany.
   ``There was one person aboard each aircraft. The condition of
those on board is unknown,'' Ms. Hayes said in a telephone
interview from U.S. Air Force European headquarters at Ramstein Air
Base near Kaiserslautern, about 95 miles southwest of Frankfurt.
   Hugo Lenxweiler, a spokesman for West German police, said by
telephone that one pilot was killed.
   ``The other pilot was able to eject safely'' but it was not
known whether he was injured, Lenxweiler said from his office in
Bingen, about 30 miles west of Frankfurt. He said both planes
crashed several hundred yards from a populated area.
   Preliminary information indicated one F-16 rammed the other from
behind and exploded, the police spokesman said.
   The ZDF television network showed videotape of the wreckage
burning in a field just outside Bodenheim. Debris was scattered
over a wide area and the smoking tail of one jet sat upright in the
field.
   It also showed the intact ejection seat used by the surviving
pilot. Police said no one on the ground was hurt.
   In the first accident, an Air Force F-16 crashed in the Black
Forest south of Karlsruhe at about noon. The pilot ejected safely
and was taken to Ramstein Air Base for medical evaluation, Air
Force officials said.
   The identities of the pilots were not immediately released.
   Teams of military investigators would examine the wreckage and
determine the cause of both accidents, Capt. Hayes said.
   Capt. Matt Durham, an Air Force spokesman at the Pentagon, said:
``We've never had three go down in one day. There haven't been any
mid-air collisions with F-16s.''
   Durham reported 17 Class A accidents involving F-16s this year
compared with 12 in all of 1987. Those are accidents in which there
is either a fatality or damage to aircraft exceeding $500,000.
   Even with Wednesday's accidents, ``the F-16 is still the safest
single-engine aircraft in U.S. Air Force history,'' he said.
   Two other other Air Force F-16s have crashed in West Germany
this year.
   One went down April 18 near an ammunition depot and hospital
south of Trier near the Luxembourg border. The pilot was slightly
injured when he ejected.
   On March 31, an F-16 crashed into the town of Forst north of
Karlsruhe, killing the pilot and a resident.
   The F-16, nicknamed the Fighting Falcon, is made by General
Dynamics and can fly twice the speed of sound. The $13.5 million
aircraft became operational with the U.S. Air Force in 1979 and is
considered one of the most popular jet fighters in the world based
on exports,
   More than 940 are in service with the Air Force and it still
buys the plane.
</TEXT>
