<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLOReax     06-29 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO Reax,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Hails U.S. Court Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO Mission-Suit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization's
ambassador to the U.N. hailed as a victory for international law a
federal court ruling issued Wednesday that permits the PLO to keep
its mission in New York.
   ``The United Nations now has no fear that the host country, or
any host country, can violate its legal obligations and get out
scot-free,'' Zehdi Labib Terzi told The Associated Press.
   U.S. District Judge Edmund Palmieri ruled that the
Anti-Terrorism Act passed by Congress does not supersede U.S.
obligations under its 1947 Headquarters Agreement with the United
Nations.
   Palmieri also said the language and legislative history of the
Anti-Terrorism Act, which branded the PLO a terrorist group, do not
indicate Congress meant to abandon America's obligations under the
Headquarters Agreement with the United Nations.
   The U.S. Mission to the United Nations said it would have no
comment on the ruling.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he was
``gratified by this judgment, which demonstrates the respect of the
U.S. courts for the international obligations of the country.''
   Terzi said the ruling is ``a great relief, because to add insult
to injury by the United States and have those injuries coming from
the judiciary would be very damaging.
   ``But now that the judiciary ... has come out with an opinion
which is supportive of international legal minds, including the
International Court of Justice, we are satisfied.''
   In April, the International Court of Justice at The Hague,
commonly known as the World Court, decreed that the United States
is obligated under the 1947 Headquarters Agreement to submit the
dispute to arbitration.
   The court has no enforcement power over its rulings.
   Dr. Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League's permanent observer to the
United Nations, said: ``We welcome the decision of the judge. We
consider it to show the integrity of the judicial system.
   ``The judgment goes to show respect for the Headquarters
Agreement and we consider this to be a victory for the United
States (judicial system) over the recklessness of the Israeli lobby
and their unquestioning supporters,'' said Maksoud in a telephone
interview from Washington.
   ``We welcome this decision and believe that this will facilitate
the work of the U.N. (General) Assembly,'' he said. ``It shows
judicial respect for United States' treaty obligations and the
healthy independence of the judiciary.''
</TEXT>
