<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0731 06-29 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Joins Presidential Fray, Attacks Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New grafs 3-5 with Dukakis response</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plunged into the 1988 White House
campaign on Wednesday, attacking Michael Dukakis as a liberal bent
on ``worn-out policies'' of tax raises and runaway government
spending.
   ``Should we expect that if the Democrats' all-but-certain
presidential candidate is elected that he would raise taxes? In
fact, he just did,'' Reagan said, mocking the recent cigarette tax
Dukakis signed in an effort to head off a state budget deficit.
   Dukakis, told of Reagan's remarks, told reporters: ``With all
due respect, I think the president's confused.''
   He defended his own economic record, contrasting it with that of
the administration.
   ``The next president will inherit a fiscal mess _ I think we all
know that...And one of my jobs as president of the United States
will be to straighten out this mess,'' said Dukakis.
   Reagan, in an address prepared for a Florida GOP fund-raising
event in support of Rep. Connie Mack III's Senate bid, fired his
harshest barrage yet at Vice President George Bush's likely
opponent. The speech marked his first political foray outside the
capital this campaign season.
   The president said of Dukakis, ``Not only has he hiked taxes as
governor of Massachusetts, but in the last five years he has
increased Massachusetts' state spending at double the rate of
federal spending.''
   Dukakis ``has spent every dime and more of the revenue generated
in his state by the Reagan-Bush recovery,'' Reagan said. ``So yes,
the man expected to head up the Democratic ticket ... is a true
liberal who, instead of controlling government spending, raises
taxes.''
   The Dukakis campaign was quick to fire back.
   ``There he goes again,'' said campaign spokesman Mark Gearan.
``The fact of the matter is that the Massachusetts budget will be
balanced and that tough choices on spending have been made,
something that we have seen nothing of during the past eight
years.''
   ``This administration has piled up more red ink than the
presidencies of George Washington to Jimmy Carter combined,''
Gearan said. ``Michael Dukakis has balanced nine and soon to be 10
budgets, a track record that should be the envy of this
administration.''
   Reagan appeared to relish his role as a surrogate for Bush. In
addition to his clear effort to debunk the ``Massachussets
miracle'' of economic recovery Dukakis has touted, the president
also seemed intent on raising the tax-hike issue, which helped foil
Walter Mondale's bid for the White House in 1984.
   Hitting at critics who have attacked his own record on federal
deficits, which reached record levels during his administration,
Reagan asserted that when liberals talk about reducing the deficit,
``it's just a code word for boosting taxes. And once they raise
taxes, they raise spending even more.''
   The president boasted about the nation's robust economy and
said, ``What the 1988 elections are all about is whether we
continue to build on that progress and move ahead to an even
brighter future or whether we hesitate and return to those worn-out
policies that bring high taxes, low-growth and a loss of direction
and purpose.''
   Reagan also lashed out at another prominent Democrat _ and
favorite target _ Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy, charging that
the senator's health care proposals amount to disguised taxes on
corporations.
   ``Sen. Kennedy has tried for years to pass an exorbitantly
expensive program of socialized medicine,'' Reagan charged, adding,
``It hasn't happened, so he is proposing _ and the expected
Democratic nominee has endorsed this plan _ that the government
pass a law requiring private companies to directly pay for a
federally mandated health insurance program.''
   ``What is euphemistically called government-corporate
partnership is just government coercion, political favoritism,
collectivist industrial policy and old-fashioned federal
boondoggles nicely wrapped up in a bright colored ribbon _ and it
doesn't work,'' Reagan said.
   ``Yes, soaring prices and a sinking economy _ that's what the
other fellows with all their lip service about compassion'' have
inflicted and have in store for the American people, Reagan
asserted.
   Reagan, who met privately with a group of some 30
Cuban-Americans before his address, also tried to reassure them
that his administration was not warming up to Fidel Castro, terming
Cuba ``an inhuman Communist dungeon.''
   Although Reagan's support has been strong in the Cuban-American
community here, some leaders have argued that he is softening his
anti-Castro stand by negotiating with Cuba on immigration, human
rights and the issue of Cuban troops in Angola.
   ``There is an unbridgeable gulf between the governments of the
United States and Cuba; it is the gulf between freedom and
tyranny,'' Reagan said.
   In his address, Reagan also offered a renewed plea for aid to
the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   ``Connie Mack and I stand with the Nicaraguan resistance; we
will not rest until we have won for them the full support they need
_ and until they have won for themselves the genuine democracy and
freedom for which they have so bravely struggled.''
   En route to Miami aboard Air Force One, Reagan spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said the White House has no package prepared for
congressional consideration on renewing aid to the rebels.
   ``We're waiting for (Secretary of State George) Shultz to
return,'' Fitzwater said. Shultz left Wednesday on a three-day
swing through Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras on a
trip billed by the administration as an attempt to reinforce U.S.
support for the Central American democracies.
   Reagan's appearance in Florida put him in the middle of a
Republican primary fight. Mack, the conservative third-term
congressman, is seeking the seat of retiring Democratic Sen. Lawton
Chiles.
   The president accepted the speaking date weeks ago. Then, on
Monday, U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who successfully prosecuted a
major Colombian-drug case, launched his own bid.
</TEXT>
