<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuonicontiSuit     06-29 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buoniconti Suit,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Citadel $5,000 For Contempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined The Citadel $1,000
Wednesday for violating a gag order during the trial of an injured
football player's $16.5 million suit against the military college.
   Circuit Judge John Hamilton Smith ruled the college had
willfully disobeyed the gag order he issued in March requiring that
parties to the suit ``make no purposeful dissemination'' of
information about the case.
   Meanwhile, Bill Holthouser, the former linebacker coach at the
military school, denied in testimony Wednesday he pressured the
injured student, Marc Buoniconti, to play against East Tennessee
State during the 1985 season.
   Buoniconti, the son of former Miami Dolphins star Nick
Buoniconti, was the starting middle linebacker for The Citadel when
he suffered a broken neck while making a tackle in that game. He
was left a quadriplegic.
   Citadel public relations director Ben Legare admitted he was
aware of the gag order when he approached The News and Courier and
suggested the Charleston newspaper run a previously published
column about the case.
   The column by a Miami sportswriter was syndicated by the Knight
Ridder newspaper chain and appeared in the June 19 edition of The
(Columbia) State.
   ``I had no input into the creation of that story,'' Legare said,
adding, ``In my opinion it was a public domain story.''
   He said the column brought out ``points that had not been
brought out before.'' The trial opened June 13; the defense began
its case Monday.
   Citadel attorney Dawes Cooke said Legare did not view his
actions as dissemination of information by The Citadel itself and
said the intent was not to influence the jury.
   But Smith noted that it was The Citadel that initially requested
the gag order. He fined the school $5,000, but when he returned to
court in the afternoon he said that upon reflection he decided to
reduce the fine.
   The column quotes a University of Miami official as saying
Buoniconti speared an opposing player in the tackle that left him
paralyzed. Spearing is hitting head first rather than with the
shoulder; it is illegal under football rules.
   That has been the defense's contention in the suit against The
Citadel, the team's trainer and doctor.
   Buoniconti alleges the defendants were negligent in treating a
neck sprain he suffered several weeks earlier. The suit also
charges they failed to warn him a congenital neck condition made it
dangerous for him to continue playing football.
   Holthouser, now defensive coordinator at Virginia Military
Institute, testified Wednesday that he put no pressure on
Buoniconti to play. ``I did not have a conversation in which I said
we need you to play to win,'' he said.
   He added Buoniconti seemed normal in warmups before the game,
did not complain about pain or say special equipment to protect his
neck didn't feel right.
</TEXT>
