<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Cold War Not Over But Hails Gorbachev's Proposals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 7 grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng, `Bush spoke,' to
UPDATE with Bush criticism of Dukakis' policy on strategic nuclear
weapons, remarks in drought area.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush declared
Wednesday ``the cold war is not over'' between Washington and
Moscow, but said sweeping changes proposed in the Soviet Union by
Mikhail S. Gorbachev sound ``revolutionary.''
   Bush, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee,
credited the Reagan administration's $1 trillion military buildup
with helping push the Soviets toward democracy and openness.
   And, in a speech, he said he hoped the investigation of fraud,
bribery and corruption in the Pentagon procurement process would
not undermine the consensus for military strength or provoke an
over-reaction.
   ``The first reaction in Congress to the scandals _ to increase
the regulatory bureaucracy at Defense _ though understandable,
that's only going to add to the complexity and worsen the problem.
   ``The answer is to reduce, cut and simplify, including staff and
executive overhead,'' Bush said, adding that Congress and the White
House should agree ``to take the patronage and pork out of
defense.''
   Bush spoke before the World Affairs Council, a foreign policy
group, at the conclusion of a 24-hour visit to northern California,
where he spent most of his time at private fund-raisers for
Republicans.
   On his return to Washington on Air Force Two, Bush attacked
Dukakis' policy on strategic nuclear weapons.
   Dukakis has voiced opposition to the MX missile and Midgetman
missiles, and also has said he would replace the administration's
Strategic Defense Initiative with a buildup in conventional forces.
   ``He wants to do away with a lot of these systems and I think to
negotiate an arms control agreement with the Soviet Union, it would
be ridiculous to do that,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said it was the United States' refusal to
make unilateral concessions on arms that persuaded the Soviets to
sign an agreement to abolish U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range
nuclear missiles.
   En route home, the vice president stopped in Appleton, Wis., and
then drove nearly 50 minutes to the farming community of Marion to
watch a cattle auction and talk about the drought.
   Standing at the auctioneer's podium amid the mooing of cows,
Bush said, ``I want to say that, leave aside the politics of the
moment and my ambitions for the fall _ what we want to do as a part
of the administration is do as much as possible under the
circumstances.''
   Upward of three-quarters of an inch of rain fell on the parched
area Tuesday, and Bush said, ``I just hope we get more rain. I hope
that will save some of the corn crop we passed by and may take a
little of the pressure off the families.''
   Bush's speech earlier followed by one day an address in Moscow
by Gorbachev to an extraordinary party council in which the Soviet
leader proposed creation of a powerful new post of president and a
partial transfer of power away from the Communist Party.
   ``Some of the dramatic reforms that General Secretary Gorbachev
proposed just yesterday would truly if implemented be revolutionary
and should the reforms ... be put into practice it would represent
historic change,'' he said. The vice president said that such moves
should be watched with ``guarded optimism.''
   However, Bush said, ``We've got to remember the cold war is not
over. We must be bold enough to seize the opportunity of change,
but at the same time, as one pundit titled his column, be prepared
for `the protracted conflict.'''
   He said the changes of glasnost, or openness, and perestroika,
or restructuring of the Soviet economic system, ``didn't take place
in a vacuum but in the context of reinvigorated American strength.''
   Bush added, ``My point is this _ it was eight years of American
strength that confronted the Soviet Union with the true costs of
aggression and necessity of reform.''
   He called Reagan's recent summit in Moscow with Gorbachev the
result of eight years ``of moral determination and hard work
rebuilding America's strength, its might.''
   Highlighting his concern about the alleged corruption in the
Pentagon purchasing system, Bush said, ``The greatest tragedy out
of all of this would be if the conduct of a few individuals were to
be used to undermine the consensus on rebuilding America's
strength.''
   He spoke warmly of reforms proposed several years ago by a
presidential commission headed by David Packard for changes in the
procurement process. He said the panel concluded that far more
defense money is lost because of the bureaucracy than because of
fraud and corruption.
   ``Even if every one of Dave Packard's recommendations were
implemented tomorrow, it would not eliminate human greed,'' Bush
said. ``That is why we must be constantly vigilant, bring in the
best people and hold them to the highest standards.''
   In raising the subject, Bush said the alleged scandal involved
Congress, the Pentagon and the defense industry. ``If the news
stories are true, the accused have done more than steal from the
public treasury. They have undermined America's security and broken
faith with the honest American people,'' the vice president said.
</TEXT>
