<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Savimbi     06-29 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Savimbi,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Savimbi Says Aid Should Continue Until Reconciliation Accepted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi, claiming
control of more than one-third of Angola, appealed Wednesday for
continued U.S. aid to force Angola's communist government to deal
with his movement.
   ``Support should not be cut before we have concluded with the
MPLA (government) a deal, for negotiations, formation of a
government of national unity and elections,'' Savimbi told a forum
on southern Africa.
   The bearded guerrilla fighter takes his message to the White
House Thursday, where he has an appointment with President Reagan.
He met Secretary of State George Shultz on Tuesday and has been
talking to members of Congress and private groups during an
extended visit to the United States.
   Savimbi has been lobbying against views of some Democrats who
favor restoring the ban lifted two years ago against aid to his
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA, and
of U.S. civil rights advocates troubled by UNITA's acceptance of
arms from white-ruled South Africa.
   Savimbi's proposals for national reconciliation were sharply
opposed here this week by an Angolan MPLA government delegation
that discussed with Reagan administration officials the ongoing
negotiations about the removal of Cuban forces from Angola.
   The Angolan officials rejected talks with UNITA or elections,
repeated demands for the guerrillas to lay down their arms and
branded them ``ancillary forces of South Africa.''
   Declaring he is against apartheid, the South African system of
racial segregation, Savimbi said UNITA has always ``accepted
support from wherever we get it'' _ earlier in the independence
struggle against Portugal, and now against the Marxist government
and its supporting Cuban, Soviet, East German and North Korean
forces.
   ``No one is saying that Churchill or Roosevelt by supporting
Stalin were communists,'' he added, referring to the allied
British, American and Soviet leaders during World War II.
   Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.S. ambassador at the United Nations,
introduced Savimbi to the forum sponsored by the American
Enterprise Institute, a private business-sponsored, conservative
policy group as ``one of the authentic heroes of our time, a poet,
revolutionary, theoretician and survivor.''
   Savimbi said 12,000 more Cuban troops entered Angola the past
two months, raising the total to 57,000, which is about 25 percent
over U.S. estimates.
   Except for increased Cuban strength, ``the situation has turned
very favorable'' for UNITA, Savimbi said, with the Cubans moving
from Northern to Southern Angola. This has ``given us the intiative
in the North, we are closer to the capital and MPLA is feeling much
more pressure than ever before,'' he said.
   ``U.S. support has made a tremendous difference, we have
neutralized Cuban and MPLA air power, and we got a very powerful
transmitter which is allowing us to pass our message to the whole
nation.''
   U.S. aid to UNITA since the ban was lifted is classified but has
been unofficially estimated at about $16 million a year.
</TEXT>
