<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0714 06-29 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Palestinian Teen-Ager; Police Tear-Gas Arab
Girls</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops killed a 15-year-old Palestinian
boy Wednesday and police fired tear gas at Arab schoolgirls
protesting peacefully outside the U.S. Consulate in Arab east
Jerusalem, witnesses said.
   In a third incident, troops shot and wounded two young Arabs
near the open-air market in the West Bank city of Nablus, hospital
officials said.
   The army confirmed one Palestinian was wounded there Wednesday
and said it was checking the report of a second shooting.
   The Palestinian boy who died, Ibrahim Ghassan Aranka, was shot
during a clash in the Arab village of Taiyiba, near Ramallah in the
West Bank, said officials at Jerusalem's Mukassad Hospital.
   The fatality brought to 212 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel captured from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
war. Four Israelis also have died in the violence.
   Salem Suleiman Khoriyeh, 42, the son of the village elder, told
The Associated Press that villagers spotted a Jewish settler
setting fire to olive trees near Taiyiba Wednesday.
   He said hundreds of villagers rushed to the grove and battled
the blaze, which destroyed about 15 acres of olive trees.
   Soldiers in five jeeps watched but did not help, Khoriyeh said.
   Angered by the indifference, villagers began stoning the
soldiers, who responded by opening fire, Khoriyeh said. He said
Aranka was shot from a distance of about 150 feet.
   An army spokesman said an officer opened fire in Taiyiba after
his unit was pelted with stones and bottles and that two soldiers
were slightly injured. He said the army was investigating whether
Aranka was killed by army gunfire.
   The spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said he could not
immediately confirm villagers' claims about a Jewish settler's
arson.
   The protest near the U.S. Consulate involved about 75 girls,
most of them 13 to 14 years old, who were holding up handwritten
signs saying: ``Please Open Our Schools,'' said the U.S. official,
who spoke on condition his name not be used.
   He said American officials had requested that tear gas not be
used. He said the United States would raise the incident with
Israel.
   The official said about 30 police officers hurled tear gas after
the schoolgirls left the consulate parking lot and the half-hour
demonstration appeared to be breaking up. He said the girls did not
throw stones.
   The girls were seen fleeing the gas, many of them coughing and
covering their faces with their hands.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Rafi Levy put the number of
demonstrators at 200 and said tear gas was used only after the
students were warned to disperse.
   Levy said several Arab girls were arrested outside a school in
east Jerusalem for allegedly trying to incite fellow students to
protest. Israel radio said seven were arrested.
   Israeli officials have closed 34 schools in Arab east Jerusalem
and the West Bank, contending schools are a central source of
anti-Israeli protests.
   The radio also quoted the head of Israel's military
intelligence, Maj. Gen. Amnon Shahad, as saying that although the
Arab uprising spawned a new local leadership in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, Palestinians still accept the Palestine Liberation
Organization as their undisputed leader.
   Shahad's statement marked a rare Israeli acknowledgement of PLO
influence in the occupied territories.
   Hospital officials said Wednesday's clash in Nablus began when
youths threw bottles and rocks at troops accompanying Israeli tax
officials who were checking Arab shops.
   Soldiers fired tear gas and rubber bullets and then fired live
ammunition, seriously wounding a 17-year-old in the stomach and a
22-year-old in the right arm, the hospital officials said.
   In Hebron, on the West Bank, a military spokesman said the army
arrested members of a guerrilla cell believed responsible for
stabbing a Jewish settler last Friday and other attacks.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charles Redman in Washington
denied on Wednesday a report from Israel that U.S. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz might make another trip to the Middle East
in July to seek a peace agreement.
   Redman said Shultz was not ruling out another visit to the
region later this year, but not in the time period mentioned.
</TEXT>
