<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-TrainCrash     06-29 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Train Crash,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Look for Clues to Why Train Lost Brakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators searched for clues Wednesday to why a
train lost its brakes and ended its journey in a disastrous
collision at a Paris station that killed nearly 60 people.
   Police said dismembered bodies had caused confusion in
establishing a death toll in the accident, which occurred Monday,
and it probably was 56 rather than the 59 announced earlier. Of 38
people injured, 13 still were hospitalized.
   All the 55 dead identified by Wednesday were French.
   The runaway commuter train careened into the busy Gare de Lyon
station at 7:10 p.m. Monday and hit a full train waiting to depart.
   Most of the victims apparently were in the stationary train.
Witnesses said most passengers had left the incoming train at an
unscheduled 26-minute stop.
   Three separate investigations are being conducted, by police,
the state-run railway company and the Transport Ministry.
   Officials of the rail company said Tuesday the veteran engineer
on the runaway train realized more than a mile from the Gare de
Lyon that his brakes were gone and warned passengers to move to the
back of the train.
   They also said the engineer, Daniel Saulin, 42, first realized
there was a brake problem after the eight-car train had been
stopped five miles from the station by a passenger who pulled the
emergency cord.
   Louis Lecor, a company spokesman, said authorities had not yet
identified the passenger who committed the ``act of malicious
mischief.''
   Saulin had problems resetting the brakes and the train did not
move for 26 minutes, the company said. Most passengers boarded
another Paris-bound train that passed, the French press quoted
witnesses as saying.
   About a mile from the Paris station, when Saulin realized he had
no brakes, he alerted the station controller and then his
passengers. His train sped into the Gare de Lyon at 40-50 mph,
through a stop signal 600 yards from impact.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said investigators
were questioning both Saulin and the controller and listening to
``black boxes'' containing technical information on train movements.
   Quoting ``well informed sources,'' it said there was a conflict
in the accounts of the engineer and station controller. According
to the agency report, Saulin said the controller told him to
proceed despite brake problems but company policy is that such a
decision rests with the engineer.
</TEXT>
