<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Military     06-29 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Military,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Officers Sentenced In January Rebellion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court sentenced nine
army lieutenants Wednesday to jail sentences ranging up to 90 days
for their roles in a January mutiiny, the government said.
   They were among several hundred officers and non-commissioned
officers who sided with former Lt. Col. Aldo Rico in the brief
rebellion involving the Monte Caseros Infantry Regiment in
northeastern Corrientes Province and five other army camps.
   It was one of the most serious threats to the civilian
government government of President Raul Alfonsin since it replaced
a military dictatorship in December 1983.
   The rebellion ended Jan. 18 with the surrender of 328 officers
and non-commissioned officers. Three loyalist soldiers were wounded
by a mine explosion.
   Rico and his followers were protesting the trials of military
officers accused of human rights violations under military juntas
that ruled from 1976 to 1983.
   He contended the military should have been thanked for winning
the ``dirty war'' on leftist subversion, in which a government
panel says at least 9,000 people disappeared and are presumed dead.
Human rights groups 30,000 is a more accurate figure.
   About 60 officers, including Rico, are being held pending trial
in a military jail in Magdalena, 60 miles southeast of Buenos Aires.
   Rico, 44, led a similar revolt in three army camps in April
1987. He faces a possible 25 years to life in prison.
   The nine men sentenced Wednesday have been under arrest since
January. In ordering sentences of 30-90 days, the army's Permanent
War Council recognized the time served.
   The detainees were returned to their original camp in the
southern province of Chubut, close to the Chilean border.
</TEXT>
