<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Bhopal     06-29 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Bhopal,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Direct Union Carbide Settlements with Bhopal Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district judge blocked the Union Carbide
Corp. on Wednesday from settling directly with victims of the
Bhopal gas leak, the world's worst industrial disaster.
   Judge M.W. Deo issued an interim injunction against direct
settlement in response to a June 16 request by the Indian
government, which has made itself sole legal representative of
victims of the Dec. 3, 1984, gas leak.
   Nearly 3,000 people were killed and more than 20,000 seriously
injured in the leak at a Bhopal pesticide plant owned by an Indian
subsidiary of Union Carbide, which is based in Danbury, Conn.
   The company says the leak was caused by employee sabotage. India
says poor maintenance and low safety standards were to blame.
   India filed a $3 billion suit against Union Carbide that is
still being heard.
   ``It's disturbing that the Indian government, which claims to be
the sole representative of Bhopal victims, continues to prevent
those victims from resolving their own claims expeditiously and to
their own satisfaction,'' the company said Wednesday in a statement
released at its headquarters.
   Union Carbide, saying there was ``no political will'' in the New
Delhi government to settle, began dealing directly with lawyers who
filed suit in the United States on behalf of gas claimants.
   Nearly 150,000 claimants are represented by lawyers seeking
damages in courts in Connecticut and Texas. The Indian government
has received claims from about 500,000 people.
   Deo said his order was not to stop proceedings but only to block
a settlement in the United States before he gives his final
judgment on July 29.
   Union Carbide argued that any injunction would be an affront to
the Connecticut court that is judging the case with private lawyers
of gas victims.
   Indian government lawyers say any settlement reached in the
Connecticut court would be null and void.
   They quoted a Union Carbide spokesman as saying the company was
seeking to reach a settlement providing less than $350 million for
the victims.
</TEXT>
