<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Soviet     06-29 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Soviet,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Confirms Subs In Swedish Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unidentified Soviet government
official was quoted as saying Wednesday that Soviet submarines may
have regularly violated Swedish waters until 1985, when Mikhail S.
Gorbachev took power, but have not done so since.
   The Aftonbladet daily quoted the official as saying the Soviets
distrusted Sweden's ability to keep neutral in wartime and feared
it would be forced to help the North Atlantic alliance.
   The Soviet military wanted to chart Swedish waters and convinced
the Kremlin to go along in what was one of a series of foreign
policy errors during the regime of Leonid Brezhnev, the newspaper
quoted the official as saying.
   ``I cannot exclude that Soviet submarines operated in Swedish
waters. On the contrary, it is probable, considering our previous
foreign policy,'' he was quoted as saying in an interview in Moscow.
   According to Aftonbladet, he said ``the military could easily
convince the Soviet party leadership that this or that was
necessary. The control over the army was not so strict. Since then
it has been tightened.''
   Aftonbladet called the man an expert on Scandinavian affairs.
   It said the official reported that the Soviet violations
continued until 1985, when Gorbachev became general secretary of
the Soviet Communist Party.
   It was the closest to an admission of territorial violations
since a Soviet submarine ran aground off Karlskrona naval base in
1981. Last week, Soviet spokesman Gennady Gerassimov said reports
of continued intrusions reminded him ``of the Loch Ness story.''
   Swedish defense staff spokesman Evert Dahlen declined to comment
on the Aftonbladet story since ``we do not know who the source is.''
   But Dahlen said incursions were continuing as they have every
year this decade. Sweden has not identified the nationality of the
intruders since making a diplomatic protest to Moscow in 1983. The
Soviets rejected the accusations, and Swedish-Soviet relations were
virtually frozen until last year.
   The Soviet official was quoted as saying Soviet foreign policy
has ``changed fundamentally,'' and that he ``without doubt can say
there are no Soviet submarines in Swedish waters today.''
   ``We know that the slightest mistake or another grounding will
cause a new conflict with Sweden, and not only Sweden, there will
be an outcry all over the world,'' he was quoted as saying, adding
that a new scandal could be ``fatal to Gorbachev's new foreign
policy which is based on showing we are not aggressive.''
</TEXT>
