<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Contract     06-29 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Contract,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>IG Reconsidering Decision To Drop Investigation Stemming From
Telephone Tip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon inspector general's office has
reopened its investigation into a disputed contract in the wake of
the separate criminal investigation of bribery and fraud in Defense
Department weapons purchases, according to Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich.
   The IG probe was renewed June 16, two days after the
two-year-old criminal investigation became public when search
warrants were served on Pentagon officials, contractors, and
private consultants.
   The investigation was reopened because of the possible
involvement of Melvyn R. Paisley, a former top Navy official who
has emerged as a key figure in the bribery investigation.
   The contract in question involves a Navy radar-warning system,
said Dingell, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Dingell, in a letter Tuesday to Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci, asked for all documents relating to the decision by June
Gibbs Brown, the Pentagon inspector general, to take another look
at the case.
   Dingell's letter said Brown's office received information from a
telephone tip in which the tipster alleged that Paisley conspired
with officials of two companies to limit competition for the
AN@ALR-67 radar receiving sets. The two companies were identified
as Litton's Applied Technologies Division and Dalmo Victor, a
subsidiary of the Singer Corp.
   The Navy reportedly planned to open competition for a $121
million part of the contract to several companies, but the
unidentified tipster said Paisley ordered that a less-competitive
process known as ``leader@follower'' be used.
   That would permit Litton to remain the lead contractor and allow
it to train a second company to produce the system. The second
company would be Dalmo Victory, the tipster said.
   Litton had been the sole-source contractor for the system, which
includes a sophisticated display and warning system which tells a
Navy pilot that his plane is being tracked by enemy radars.
   Dingell's letter said the contract ``may ultimately be worth $1
billion to the recipients.''
   The tip was telephoned to the General Accounting Office, the
congressional watchdog agency, which passed it along last Aug. 27
to the Pentagon inspector general's office. The Pentagon office
investigated and told the GAO on Feb. 18 that the charges were
``unsubstantiated,'' Dingell said.
   Dingell said he wants to know ``what facts led the DoD-IG to
label the charges as `unsubstantiated.'''
</TEXT>
