<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Cardinals 1stLd-Writethru a0862 06-29 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Cardinals, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0862,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Bestows Rings on 24 New Cardinals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs with 1 graf to restore dropped word
`including' and fix typo in Catholic.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II placed gold rings on the
fingers of 24 new cardinals Wednesday and told them to be
``tireless promoters and constructors of peace and harmony'' in the
church.
   He also gave a sacred vestment known as the pallium to each of
15 new archbishops, including Eugene Marino of Atlanta, the first
black Roman Catholic archbishop in the United States.
   About 20,000 people filled St. Peter's Square for the ceremony
late Wednesday afternoon, many with umbrellas to ward off the
glaring sun.
   When the new cardinals marched to the altar at the start of the
2{-hour Mass, the crowd burst into applause and waved yellow and
white handkerchiefs, the Vatican's colors.
   Among the 24 churchmen formally installed Tuesday as ``princes
of the church'' were two U.S. archbishops, James Hickey of
Washington, D.C., and Edmund Szoka of Detroit.
   The cardinals knelt one-by-one before the red-robed pontiff
Wednesday to receive the rings, a sign of their espousal to the
church.
   All the cardinals, except Anthony Padiyara of Ernakulam, India,
wore maroon robes trimmed with gold. Padiyara, a member of the
Siro-Malabaresi rite, was dressed in a glittering silver robe
decorated with bright pink.
   John Paul called on the new cardinals to emulate Saint Peter and
Saint Paul, the patron saints of Rome, whose feast day fell on
Wednesday.
   ``We expect these cardinals to be, like Peter, tireless
promoters and constructors of peace and agreement among the people
of God _ models, like Paul, of the generous and incessant
dedication to the proclamation of the Gospel in every part of the
world,'' the pontiff, speaking in Italian, said in his homily.
   Delegations from different countries applauded after the
cardinals received their rings.
   The 15 archbishops knelt before the pontiff earlier to receive
the pallium, a thin white wool band decorated with black crosses
that symbolizes union with the Holy See.
   ``Peace be with you,'' the pope told each archbishop in Latin as
he placed the pallium over his head.
   Asked what he thought about as he received the vestment, Marino
said after the Mass: ``The universality of the Church.''
   ``Having been born and raised in Biloxi, Miss., and my idea of
the church having been conditioned by being in small communities, I
suddenly found myself a bishop, then an archbishop, then here. It
was very exciting for me to kneel there,'' he said.
   Archbishop Anthony Bevilacqua of Philadelphia also received the
pallium, as did archbishops from Italy, Tanzania, the Philippines,
Ireland, Brazil, Haiti, Algeria and India.
   The rings given to the cardinals bear a gold rectangle, slightly
larger than a man's thumbnail, with a raised image of Christ on the
cross.
</TEXT>
