<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland-Police     06-29 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland-Police,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Action Against Police Chief Over Shooting Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A watchdog panel of police and
civilians said Wednesday no disciplinary action will be taken
against Northern Ireland's police chief over allegations his force
murdered unarmed guerrilla suspects.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, called it a cover-up. The Social Democratic and
Labor Party, the province's leading Roman Catholic party, said the
chief and his deputies should resign.
   The 20-member Northern Ireland Police Authority criticized
certain police operational procedures but said no action was needed
against Sir John Hermon, chief constable of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary.
   Nor will his two top deputies, Deputy Chief Constable Michael
McAtamney and Assistant Chief Constable Trevor Forbes, face
disciplinary action, it said.
   It was the latest chapter in a conflict that has bedeviled the
British province since late 1982, when police killed six unarmed
Catholics, five of them acknowledged guerrillas, in three separate
incidents.
   The killings led to allegations of an illegal shoot-to-kill
policy against guerrillas fighting to rid Protestant-dominated
Northern Ireland of British rule and unite it with the
predominantly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   The panel said it based its decision on findings of an inquiry
which reported no evidence of illegalities. It said its decision
was by a majority of one, but did not give the exact vote or say
how many members voted.
   Hermon and his deputies said in a statement: ``We always knew we
had nothing to fear from any investigation. Nevertheless we are
pleased the Police Authority has vindicated our position.''
   Herman, who turns 60 in November, has said he will retire next
year.
   On Monday, the London-based human rights group Amnesty
International demanded a judicial inquiry into the killings, saying
existing procedures were inadequate for preventing illegal police
shootings.
   John Stalker, a British detective assigned to investigate the
shootings, claims he was obstructed by Hermon and eventually forced
off the case because he was close to proving murder had been
committed.
   In January, the British government announced that although there
was a police conspiracy to obstruct justice, no one would be
prosecuted.
   Stalker's inquiry was completed by another British officer,
Colin Sampson, whose report has not been published.
   But the Police Authority quoted Sampson as concluding: ``I have
found no evidence that there were instructions to any police
officers in Northern Ireland to use other than legitimate methods
to bring offenders to justice.''
   Kevin McNamara, the opposition Labor Party's Northern Ireland
spokesman, said: ``There have been two casualties: the first is
confidence in the administration of the rule of law in Northern
Ireland. The second is Britain's good name in the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
