<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Teamsters     06-29 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Teamsters,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters' Lawyer Says New Jersey Test Case Was Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Newark-Teamsters Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer for the Teamsters union on Wednesday
said a U.S. Justice Department plan to stop alleged Mafia influence
of the union through a court-appointed trustee is an idea that was
tried in New Jersey and failed.
   Teamsters chief counsel John Climaco, in a telephone interview
from the Ritz Carlton Hotel where the Teamsters' executive is
holding its quarterly meeting, told The Associated Press the
trustee plan was ``a very real threat.''
   But he said union leaders were ``ready to fight anything.''
   On Tuesday, U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani filed a racketeering
lawsuit in Manhattan federal court in what he said was an attempt
to break Mafia domination of the Teamsters.
   The government wants a federal judge to remove from office any
Teamsters officers found to have violated racketeering laws, and to
appoint a trustee who would ensure the fair election of new
officers in the 1.6-million member union.
   A test case for the move occurred in Teamsters Local 560 in
Union City, N.J., where court-appointed trustees have been in
charge since 1986.
   The second trustee appointed, former federal prosecutor Edwin
Steir, has reported some progress but also says union members are
reluctant to get involved because of past intimidation.
   ``Everyone who has been connected with 560 has said it's a
failure, including the first trustee,'' Climaco said.
   He said the union executive will conclude its meeting behind
closed doors Thursday but may not immediately reveal its plans
against the federal lawsuit.
   The lawsuit named all 18 members of the union's executive board,
including the Canadian representative, Edward Lawson, 59, of
Vancouver, a member of Canada's appointed Senate. It also named 26
alleged members or associates of the Mafia, 25 of whom already have
been convicted of extortion, embezzlement and other crimes.
   Lawson was angered by the sweeping nature of the suit, noting
the specific allegations involve only six U.S. locals out of 620
and no charges against the union in Canada.
   He claimed the suit was aimed at taking the heat off a
scandal-plagued Reagan administration, including allegations of
wrongdoing against Attorney General Edwin Meese and corruption at
the Pentagon.
   ``This is the most corrupt administration in the history of the
United States,'' said Lawson, head of the Teamsters in Canada and a
vice-president of the international union.
   ``They've decided they have to get all of that (scandal) out of
the news and do something like attack an easy target like the
Teamsters.''
   He said it was not clear if the suit was aimed at appointing a
trustee for union elections in Canada.
   ``Whether they have the right to extend their tentacles into
Canada is a very serious question,'' Lawson said. ``We're going to
defend this vigorously. They're going to find that the Teamsters
are not so easy a mark.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
