<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Rocard     06-29 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Rocard,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Says Wealth Tax Not Meant As Revenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Premier Michel Rocard said Wednesday his
new government's proposal to re-establish a wealth tax was intended
to knit society together, not to soak the wealthy.
   ``The wealth tax is a contribution to solidarity, not a revenge
against the rich,'' Rocard told the National Assembly in a speech
describing the outlines of his government's policies.
   Rocard, appointed premier just after the May 8 re-election of
Socialist President Francois Mitterrand, named an expanded
49-member Cabinet on Tuesday with Socialists in all key positions
but with several more centrist or non-political figures in
ministerial posts.
   The Socialists have just 277 seats in the 577-member assembly,
and so will need support from Communist or center-right deputies to
pass legislation.
   But Rocard's minority government should be in no immediate
danger of falling. He is under no obligation to call a vote of
confidence, either on his statement of general policy or on other
issues.
   In his speech, the premier did not provide any specifics of the
planned wealth tax, which will replace a levy imposed by the
Socialists after their election in 1981 and repealed by the
conservatives under Premier Jacques Chirac in 1986.
   Rocard said too high a tax on accumulated wealth would risk
accelerated capital flight at a time when France needs business
investment.
   ``On the other hand, a symbolic tax _ which would be purely
ideological _ would not produce the necessary amounts for the
solidarity desired by all,'' he said.
   The wealth tax, as Mitterrand promised in his re-election
campaign, is to provide part of the funds for a mininum guaranteed
income, the amount of which has also not been set.
   Rocard said legislation on both proposals would be adopted by
his Cabinet on July 13 and sent immediately to the assembly for
consideration.
   The premier said his government hoped to provide ``a new hope''
for France by increasing spending on research, restoring
dilapidated public housing and making education and training
priorities.
   Government agencies will be asked to improve and simplify their
service to the public, said Rocard, who promised to pay a visit
exactly a year from now to those departments that make the greatest
improvements.
   He said France would remain committed to building a united
Europe and increase its development aid gradually until it amounts
to 0.7 percent of the gross national product.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
