<DOCNO> AP880629-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TeamstersSuit     06-29 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters Suit,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Behind the Feds' Lawsuit Against the Teamsters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive memorandum accompanying a government
suit to seize control of the Teamsters outlines hundreds of
Teamster-related prosecutions since 1970 to back up charges the
union made a ``devil's pact'' with the mob.
   The government filed suit Tuesday, seeking to oust the top
leadership of the nation's largest union.
   In support of its request, the government claimed in a detailed,
105-page document that a recent series of successful criminal and
civil prosecutions demonstrates the Mafia has gained control over
the Teamsters.
   The court papers noted that four of the last five Teamsters
presidents have faced federal felony charges and three were
convicted: David Beck for embezzlement; Jimmy Hoffa for obstructing
justice and mail fraud, and Roy Williams for trying to bribe a U.S.
senator.
   ``Since approximately 1970,'' according to the memo, ``the
government has successfully prosecuted well over 300 persons
associated with the Teamsters for Teamsters-related crimes.''
   Among 26 alleged mob figures named as defendants in the lawsuit,
25 have been convicted of Teamsters-related crimes such as
extortion through threats of union problems, embezzling union funds
and taking labor payoffs.
   From 1970 until now, the government contended, the Teamsters'
executive board ``has rarely taken disciplinary action against, or
even investigated, corrupt Teamsters officials or subordinate
entities.''
   The union leadership, the government charged, ``has made a
devil's pact with La Cosa Nostra,'' or the Mafia.
   The Teamsters' executive board, which is holding its quarterly
meeting in Montreal, criticized the lawsuit as ``a vicious
anti-labor attack'' and said allegations of ties to organized crime
were ``pure myth.''
   After the suit was filed, U.S. District Judge David Edelsten
barred the board from making large expenditures of union funds or
destroying records, and banned the 25 convicted mob defendants from
participating in union affairs.
   In announcing the lawsuit, U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani quoted
the President's Commission on Organized Crime's description of the
Teamsters as ``the union `most controlled' by organized crime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
