<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-F16s     06-29 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-F16s,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Begins Debate On Transfer Of F-16s To Italy
^with AM-Jet Crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties argued in the legislature
Wednesday that the planned transfer of U.S.-made F-16 fighter jets
to Italy from Spain would harm chances for peace.
   The government, responding to a request from the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, announced June 4 it would accept 72 F-16s that
will be expelled from the Torrejon air base near Madrid within
three years.
   NATO asked Italy to accept the warplanes, which comprise the air
force's 401st Tactical Fighter Wing, so they could remain part of
NATO strategy for the defense of southern Europe.
   The Chamber of Deputies, the lower house, opened debate on the
transfer Wednesday and is expected to vote Thursday on a motion by
four opposition parties to reject it.
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita's governing coalition holds a
comfortable majority and is expected to win parliamentary approval
for the transfer.
   The government says Italy must honor its commitments to NATO and
that Italy and the allies cannot make what would amount to a
unilateral act of disarmament.
   The United States wanted Spain to keep the planes, but after
lengthy negotiations, Spain declined to renew a base agreement.
   Italy's opposition parties argued Wednesday that accepting the
planes would alter the strategic balance between East and West and
hinder efforts to reduce tensions.
   Deputy Maria Teresa Capecchi, a Communist, said relocating the
fighter-bombers in Italy ``shapes up as dangerous act that risks
being misinterpreted by the East.''
   However, Christian Democratic Deputy Bartolo Ciccardini argued
that failure to relocate the planes in southern Europe ``would
reduce NATO's military power in the area by 30 to 50 percent.''
   The government has decided to station the American planes at a
military airport near Crotone, a city of 50,000 about 400 miles
south of Rome.
</TEXT>
