<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-InsuranceTaxes     06-29 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insurance Taxes,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Says Tax Panel ``Rolled'' By Insurance Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee voted
Wednesday to limit the tax break for single-premium life insurance
policies, but chairman Dan Rostenkowski said his panel did not go
far enough because of industry pressure.
   The committee, meeting in closed session, approved by voice vote
an amendment offered by Rep. Barbara Kennelly, D-Ct., whose
Hartford district is an insurance industry stronghold, to raise
about $300 million over the next three years by shrinking the
loophole.
   Rostenkowski wanted to raise twice as much, but shrinking the
loophole still more.
   Under the 1986 tax law, the growth in value in the policies is
untaxed and the purchaser can borrow back the large single premium
interest-free, making what critics say is a tax dodge for the
wealthy who are able to afford such policies.
   Under the Kennelly version that prevailed, people who take
advantage of that mechanism would incur subsequent tax penalties if
they borrowed against policies held less than seven years.
   Rostenkowski had wanted penalties to apply if interest-free
loans were taken against a policy held less than 20 years. His plan
would have raised more than $600 million, but over his objections
the panel went with the industry-supported Kennelly plan.
   In a statement released when committee staff briefed reporters
on the session, Rostenkowski told the committee it was getting
``rolled by the insurance industry,'' and promised to fight the
issue again on a future tax bill.
   ``We're only kidding ourselves _ and the industry is completely
naive _ if they think this ... does the job,'' he said.
   Mrs. Kennelly, in a telephone interview, said she was confident
her plan would end abuses. She said the current tax bill was not
the place for a broad revamping of insurance taxes.
   ``I think what we probably did was close down the single premium
loophole,'' she said. Brokers promising a quick buck ``will be out
of business,'' she said.
   The provision was added to a grab-bag tax package which started
as a series of technical corrections to the 1986 bill, but which
also includes a wide range of other tax changes.
   About $6 billion in new taxes, mostly on corporations, have been
approved by the committee to offset tax breaks, such as repeal of
the requirement that farmers and other off-road users of diesel
fuel pay the 15.1 cent-per-gallon federal tax.
   The committee was scheduled to continue work on the bill on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
