<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DefenseProbe-Documents 1stLd-Writethru a0899 06-29 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Documents, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0899,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Reveals Documents Destroyed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Gardner's first name from Robert to Charles in graf
8 bgng ``Among those'';Instants in 5th graf, `In an ...' is cq, as
is full quote from Hudson in 11th graf, `As the ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors in the Pentagon bribery and fraud
investigation have learned of several instances of documents being
destroyed by people implicated in the probe, according to court
papers released Wednesday.
   The revelation was contained in a brief submitted by the office
of Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney in Alexandria, Va., to a federal
judge in Brooklyn who has been asked by Newsday to unseal certain
documents.
   ``In the short time since the execution of the search warrants
became public, the government has already become aware of several
incidents of destruction of documents related to this case,''
Hudson said in arguing against disclosure of the sealed documents.
   Hudson, chief prosecutor in the Pentagon investigation, provided
no details on who destroyed documents, how they were destroyed or
how they might have been related to the probe.
   In an affidavit attached to Hudson's brief, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Joseph Aronica said prosecutors had learned of ``two
incidents of document destruction by persons who are implicated in
the investigation which in two separate instants required the
securing of premises to prevent further destruction and the
emerging application for search warrants.''
   The application by Newsday, a Long Island-based newspaper, seeks
to unseal search warrants and supporting affidavits executed by
Andrew Maloney, the U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of New
York, on June 14 as part of the larger investigation into defense
contract procurement.
   Under investigation are allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former military men, bribed Pentagon
officials for inside information useful in winning contracts worth
billions of dollars.
   Among those targeted by Maloney's office are the Unisys Corp.
plant in Great Neck; Charles Gardner, a consultant to Unisys and
former Unisys employee; Dennis Mitchell, an employee at the plant,
and the Hazeltine Corp. in Greenlawn.
   In April, Gardner met with Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., and Unisys
engineers to discuss several defense programs in which Unisys was
involved, including Aegis, a multi-billion dollar shipboard combat
system for the Navy. Dyson reportedly is under scrutiny in the
investigation.
   Newsday's lawyer, Robert Raskopf, has argued to U.S. District
Judge Edward Korman that the seal should be lifted because the
investigation has been extensively reported in the media.
   In response, Hudson said disclosure would jeopardize the probe,
``which is in many respects still in a formulative and most
vulnerable stage.''
   ``Revealing the precise contours of the government's intentions
and current information may well encourage document destruction and
other acts would have the practical effect of putting major felons
beyond the reach of justice,'' Hudson said.
   Hudson disputed Newsday's position that much of what is in the
documents is public knowledge.
   ``In fact, previous news stories have not disclosed significant
portions of the material recited in the affidavit, particularly the
wiretap information,'' he said.
   Some of the affidavits detail targets of the investigation,
information suggesting the direction of the probe and the
government's theory of the case, he said.
   Hudson also said that the disclosure of Hazeltine's affidavit
would reveal the identity of a confidential source cooperating in
the investigation.
   Korman has yet to rule on the application for disclosure.
Raskopf said he would ask the judge on Thursday to give him until
Friday to respond to Hudson's brief.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
