<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Shultz     06-29 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Shultz,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say `Chain of Combat' is Message to Shultz</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels battling the
U.S.-backed government said Wednesday that ``a chain of combat
sweeping the entire country'' is a message of defiance to Secretary
of State George P. Shultz.
   Shultz is to spend several hours here Thursday as part of a
three-day, four-nation tour of Central America.
   The rebels, on their clandestine Radio Venceremos, described an
attack carried out Tuesday on an army base and a cotton cooperative
in La Paz province. They also mentioned other smaller attacks,
ambushes and skirmishes staged Tuesday.
   ``Attention: A chain of combat is sweeping the entire country to
tell Shultz and (President) Reagan's haggard eunuchs that here in
El Salvador a people in arms does not kneel before imperialist
arrogance,'' said the broadcast.
   The radio did not say whether there would be any military
actions Thursday.
   In another development, a leftist university student union
announced a march for Thursday morning. The march ostensibly is to
demand more government funds for the National University.
   But the union, which has participated in most anti-American
demonstrations here, was considered likely to emphatically denounce
Shultz's presence.
   Shultz left Washington on Wednesday for Guatemala City, his
first stop. He was to travel also to Costa Rica and Honduras before
returning to Washington Friday.
   The presidents of the four countries and Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega signed a regional peace accord on Aug. 7, 1987. The
accord has contributed to an easing of hostilities in Nicaragua but
has had no effect on civil wars in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Shultz's visit comes as President Jose Napoleon Duarte is in
Washington for treatment of liver cancer. Duarte is to return to El
Salvador early next month.
</TEXT>
