<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugBust     06-29 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bust,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Seize 990 Pounds Of Cocaine, Arrest Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents posing as the captain and crew
of a drug smuggling ship helped seize $36 million worth of cocaine
and arrest three people in the biggest such bust in Louisiana,
officials said Wednesday.
   J. Robert Grimes, regional Customs commissioner, said the case
demonstrates that drug lords are sending more and more cocaine into
the Gulf Coast area around New Orleans as authorities turn up the
heat in Florida and Texas.
   ``The major organizations are starting to move into this area,''
Grimes said at a news conference.
   About 990 pounds of cocaine in brick-like packages were stacked
on a table as officials announced the seizure, made Tuesday near
Lafitte.
   It was the largest seizure from a vessel officials in Louisiana
have ever made, said U.S. Attorney John Volz.
   Arrested Tuesday were Louis Castro, 49, a Cuban who lives in
Miami; Alejardo Ramos, 62, of New Orleans, and Miguel Diaz, 57, of
Gretna. Maurice Sudheimer of New Orleans, a crew member aboard the
vessel, escaped and is being sought, Customs officials said.
   All four could face sentences of life in prison if convicted of
the drug smuggling charges.
   Grimes said informants provided agents with enough information
to infiltrate the smuggling operation. Agents posing as a vessel
captain and crew sailed with smugglers to international waters off
Colombia, where they took a load of cocaine from another vessel
then sailed to Lafitte, Grimes said.
   Earlier this month, an indictment unsealed in Lafayette alleged
that drug smugglers linked to Panamanian leader Manuel Noriega
conspired to import more than $1 billion worth of cocaine and
marijuana into the United States.
   The indictment accused 170 people of smuggling 500,000 pounds of
drugs, some of it through southern Louisiana, and of plotting to
smuggle in at least an additional million pounds.
   U.S. Attorney Joe Cage called it perhaps the largest U.S.
narcotic smuggling ring ever.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
