<HEAD>Three More Marines Fired In Alleged Pornographic Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more Marines implicated in a
pornography ring were discharged this week for ``lewd and
lascivious conduct for compensation,'' camp officials said.
   A Marine was discharged last week on the same grounds. The names
of those discharged were not released.
   The firings resulted from an investigation of a pornography ring
allegedly headed by Thomas Francis McGrath of Oceanside,
authorities said.
   McGrath was jailed last week for investigation of pimping,
pandering and running a house of prostitution after police seized
33 videos and hundreds of pictures from his house, police said. He
was freed on $10,500 bail.
   Many photos showed men, some in partial military uniform, posing
nude or performing sex acts. A catalog believed to have been
distributed nationally advertised some of the non-homosexual
material for sale, authorities said.
   Some Marines may have been paid up to $1,000 a month as the
live-in partners of other men, according to police.
   Police have said 15 to 25 Marines are under investigated for
possible involvment. Mitchell refused to say how many Marines may
be involved.
   Maj. Tom Mitchell, a base spokesman, refused to say whether
those disciplined Tuesday had appeared in videos and photographs of
men engaging in homosexual acts.
   Pentagon policy dictates that military personnel who engage in
pornographic or homosexual acts will be discharged and could face
court martial.
