<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz-CentralAmerica 3rdLd-Writethru a0turerandnowmakesproductsrangecretaryofStateBeginsCentralAmericaTour
06-29 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Central America, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0847,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Begins Central America Tour</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz arriving in
Guatemala City, delivering remarks. PICKS up 2nd graf pvs bgng, A
senior official .... Minor editing throughout to TRIM and conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Wednesday that Nicaragua's government systematically has refused to
engage in good faith negotiations, compiling instead a record of
``evasions and non-compliance.''
   Opening a four-nation Central American visit, Shultz hailed the
democratic gains made in the region in recent years, but singled
out Nicaragua's lefist Sandinista government as an exception to the
trend.
   The tone of Shultz's remarks as he arrived here Wednesday night
suggested he hopes that Central American countries will bring
pressure to bear on Nicaragua to move toward a democratic system.
But he offered no specific proposals.
   The Sandinistas, Shultz said, ``have not democratized. They
continue to suport subversion in neighboring countries. Theirs is
not a record of honest negotiations.
   ``It is a record of negotiations corrupted by the Sandinistas'
efforts to destroy those who do not agree with them.''
   Instead of negotiating fairly, Shultz said, the Sandinistas have
engaged in ``evasions and non-compliance'' in talks dating back to
the revolution in 1979.
   Shultz's trip is aimed at giving Central American leaders
forceful assurances of U.S. support and at seeking common
approaches for dealing with Nicaragua.
   A senior official who briefed reporters earlier said the
administration's plan to seek renewed aid for the Nicaraguan
Contras will not be a major focus of the trip, but Shultz is
expected to hold a strategy session with rebel leaders in Guatemala
Thursday night.
   In addition to Guatemala, Shultz will visit El Salvador,
Honduras and Costa Rica, returning to Washington Friday night. No
stop in Nicaragua is planned, consistent with the Reagan
administration's policy of shunning contacts with Sandinista
government leaders until they show what Washington regards as
serious interest in moving toward a democratic system.
   The official, who insisted on anonymity, said Shultz hopes to
encourage the leaders of the four countries to pressure Nicaragua's
government to show more flexibility in efforts to achieve a final
settlement to its conflict with the pro-U.S. guerrillas, known as
Contras.
   Negotiations for a settlement broke down earlier this month and
no new talks have been scheduled. The Sandinistas and the Contras
have blamed each other for the collapse of the negotiations.
Meanwhile, a fragile cease-fire remains in place but some
insurgents, impatient with the negotiating impasse, are reported
prepared to resume the fighting.
   The Contras have received no military aid since Feb. 29 and the
consensus among both Democrats and Republicans in the House is that
any administration request for additional military aid would have
little chance for approval.
   The administration has said no decision has been made as yet on
an aid package, but some Contra supporters on Capitol Hill are
weighing the possibility of seeking approval for additional
military aid that would be released only if certain, but still
undefined, conditions are met.
   One Senate source said the military aid package likely would be
offered only if Shultz signals Congress upon his return that such a
move would be welcomed.
   But several congressional sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they thought it more likely that Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias would emphasize to Shultz the prospect of
increasing economic pressure on Nicaragua as a substitute for
Contra military pressure.
   Arias has spoken to U.S. officials about asking the handful of
European countries now giving economic aid to the Sandinista regime
to cut off that aid, and possibly about seeking a broadened trade
embargo against the regime.
   At the same time, the Sandinistas might be offered U.S. economic
aid if they meet certain targets for democratic reforms, the
sources said.
   Some hard-line congressional backers of the Contras said they
feared Shultz might go along with such suggestions. ``I detect a
diminution of zeal,'' one House Republican said.
   But Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., a leader of House pro-Contra
forces, said nothing short of a total economic boycott of Nicaragua
would have any effect. ``I see no sign Arias is willing to go that
far.''
   The countries Shultz will visit are among the largest recipients
of U.S. aid in the hemisphere. Shultz will tell leaders in each
country that U.S. support for them will continue regardless of the
outcome of the November election, the official said.
   Among the countries Shultz will visit, El Salvador appears to be
the one facing the the gravest difficulties. A leadership vacuum
has been created by the illness of President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
who is believed to have only a few months to live.
   The country also has become increasingly polarized between the
left and right, with the FMLN guerrilla movement pledging to step
up their campaign against government forces and the rightist ARENA
party scoring impressive electoral gains at the expense of Duarte's
Christian Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
