<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TVALayoffs 1stLd-Writethru a0874 06-29 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TVA Layoffs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0874,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA To Lay Off 7,500 Workers To Keep Utility Competitive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 7th graf pvs, `We fully ...' to ADD
history of TVA.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority, the
nation's biggest supplier of electricity, said Wednesday it will
lay off 7,500 of its 34,000 workers to keep the federal utility
competitive and ensure its survival.
   ``It's very important for all of us to realize that we're not
just going through another reorganization or another reduction in
force simply to achieve a one-time budget goal,'' said general
manager Bill Willis. ``We're fundamentally restructuring TVA and
getting it in shape for the future.''
   The 22 percent reduction, to be completed by Oct. 1, is in line
with TVA chairman Marvin Runyon's goal of converting TVA from a
bloated, top-heavy organization to a businesslike structure capable
of competing with privately owned utilities.
   Runyon, formerly chief executive officer of Nissan Motor
Manufacturing Corp. USA and a vice president of Ford Motor Co.,
became TVA chairman in January. In April he announced a program to
restructure the agency.
   He said at the time the restructuring would include substantial
layoffs.
   TVA's goal is to keep its rates the same for the next three
years. The cuts and other changes announced Wednesday are an effort
to avoid an increase of about $300 million in the budget year that
begins Oct. 1.
   ``We fully believe ... (these measures) will allow us to go into
next year with no rate increase,'' Willis said.
   The government-owned utility was founded during the Depression
in 1933 to help develop the Tennessee River basin. TVA built dams
and power plants and also undertook health, education and
conservation programs.
   Runyon said at a board meeting Wednesdasy that the number of
jobs created in the Tennessee Valley by the availability of
reasonably priced electricity eventually will more than offset the
loss of 7,500 TVA jobs.
   Those laid off will include about 4,000 full-time salaried
employees, 1,800 contract employees, and 1,700 paid on an hourly
basis.
   Runyon said 889 managers are among those let go, reducing the
ratio of supervisors to employees from 1-to-7 to about 1-to-13.
   ``We know that these decisions will be painful for our employees
who are being asked to leave through no fault of their own,''
Runyon said. ``But we are convinced, and we hope you understand,
that these actions are absolutely necessary for the survival of TVA
and for the long-term economic vitality of our region.''
   Runyon repeatedly has said TVA cannot survive unless it becomes
more efficient and competitive with utility companies outside its
seven-state region. He has said the agency can be of more help to
the region's economy by luring industry with cheap electric power
than by being an employer itself.
   More than 1,200 jobs will be lost in TVA's headquarters city of
Knoxville, 775 jobs in Chattanooga, and 329 in Muscle Shoals, Ala.
Runyon said TVA would inform every affected employee by late
Wednesday.
   Runyon said he does not believe the layoffs violate the agency's
contracts with any of the five unions that represent some of its
employees.
   There was no immediate response from the unions to Wednesday's
announcement.
   The board also approved a more moderate pace for TVA's nuclear
power program, which began in the early 1970s with an ambitious
plan to build 17 reactors. TVA has gotten as many as five reactors
in operation, but currently only one is running. The agency is
paying off $8 billion on eight plants that were canceled, Runyon
said.
   The board agreed to defer indefinitely construction at
Bellefonte Nuclear Plant near Scottsboro, Ala., until projections
indicate a need for the power. The board also agreed to reschedule
operational dates for five other reactors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
