<DOCNO> AP880629-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     06-29 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Chief Says Substantial Reforms Necessary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia is in urgent need of bold
reforms to overcome deep economic and social problems and any delay
will be fatal, the country's Communist Party chief said Wednesday.
   Speaking at a session of the party's Central Committee, party
chief Bosko Krunic also indicated there will be no change in
one-party rule in Yugoslavia. He said the single-party system will
be defended ``by all means, including legal measures.''
   Delegates at last month's national party conference sharply
criticized the ruling Central Committee and demanded replacement of
leaders who have led the country into its worst crisis in history.
   Yugoslavia has been grappling with a $21 billion foreign debt,
soaring inflation, now at 170 percent, and growing labor unrest.
   The Communist leadership is moving to revive the ailing economy
by planning to introduce an open market economy with a substantial
private sector.
   ``Courageous changes, without sentimentality or illusions, are
imperative, and any delay would be fatal,'' Krunic said in his
speech.
   He said economic changes should include the immediate
introduction of a market-oriented economy. But he added the state
would continue to exercise a measure of control.
   ``If we allow the uncontrolled functioning of the market, we
would face even greater difficulties,'' Krunic said.
   During a discussion that followed Krunic's speech, Central
Committee member Radovan Radonjic submitted his resignation,
claiming the body was ``largely responsible'' for the country's
problems.
   ``The reforms cannot be implemented by those who created the
present system,'' Radonjic was quoted as saying by the official
Tanjug news agency. ``The reforms can only be carried out by new
and able men.''
   Ante Markovic, President of Croatia, Yugoslavia's second largest
republic, said the country's reforms should be implemented by those
leaders who ``carry the reforms in their souls, and that is why the
choice of the next party president is of crucial importance.''
   He was referring to the upcoming annual selection of the party's
president. The selection, to be made by the party presidium early
next month, will pit Stipe Suvar, long considered the official
party ideologist, against Ivica Racan, a liberal reformist.
   In another development, the election of a new president for the
official Slovenian Socialist Youth Union was postponed for two
months because a leading candidate is under arrest, Tanjug reported.
   Journalist Janez Jansa, one of three candidates for youth union
president, is being held by military authorities on charges of
possessing a classified army document.
   Jansa and another reporter, David Tasic, who frequently attacked
the military in their articles, were arrested last month after a
police search of their homes and offices. Military officials said
the search uncovered photostat copies of a top secret report.
   An army sergeant-major was also detained on suspicion of having
leaked the document, which reportedly dealt with the combat
readiness of Yugoslav border forces.
   The arrests sparked a wave of protests in Slovenia, where 60,000
people have so far signed a petition for the journalists' release.
About 400 church groups, companies, trade union chapters and even
Communist Party cells have donated funds toward a special defense
fund for the trio.
</TEXT>
