<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Paisley 1stLd-Writethru a0852 06-29 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Paisley, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0852,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Asks FBI For Former Navy Official's File</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs bgng, `Paisley was,' to UPDATE with date of
full Senate confirmation of nomination; INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th
graf pvs bgng, `I am,'' and ADDS 4 grafs to end to UPDATE with
statement by Sens. Nunn and Warner on records held by committee on
Paisley nomination, new procedures for nominee reviews instituted
by them in January 1987</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator asked the FBI on Wednesday to give
Congress its file on a former Pentagon procurement official under
investigation in connection with alleged fraud and bribery in
defense purchasing.
   The former official, Melvyn Paisley, was assistant secretary of
the Navy for research, engineering and systems from 1981 through
1987.
   He had worked for Boeing Corp., a major defense contractor, for
28 years before taking the Defense Department job and became a
defense consultant after resigning in March 1987.
   Paisley's consulting office was bugged and his phone tapped
during the two-year investigation into allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former military men,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could be
vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Paisley was approved for the Navy job after a nine-minute
hearing Nov. 18, 1981 attended by two members of the 17-member
Senate Armed Services Committee. The full Senate confirmed his
nomination Nov. 23, 1981.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., in a letter to the FBI, said press
accounts of Paisley's activities indicated the FBI knew of
allegations of improper conduct by him while the committee was
considering the nomination.
   ``As a member of that committee, I believe it is important to
determine just what the FBI knew about Mr. Paisley at the time of
his Senate confirmation and the extent to which that information
was made available to the Senate Armed Services Committee,'' Levin
wrote.
   There have been allegations the FBI was told during a background
check for the appointment that Paisley had been involved in making
questionable payments or gifts while he was at Boeing. The
allegations were made by a former associate of Paisley's at Boeing,
by one of his three ex-wives and by a former sister-in-law.
   The transcript of the confirmation hearing gives no hint of any
controversy.
   The FBI has refused to release results of the background check,
citing privacy restrictions.
   Levin's staff asked the FBI by telephone last week for access to
the Paisley file. The request was passed to the White House, which
denied the request Tuesday, Levin said.
   ``I am therefore now requesting the entire FBI file from you,''
Levin said in his letter to the bureau.
   The current chairman and ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and John Warner, R-Va.,
said in a statement Wednesday night that the committee has
researched the records it currently holds on Paisley's nomination.
   ``Those records contain a copy of Mr. Paisley's biography, his
completed financial disclosure forms and associated memoranda, and
the standard letter from him required by the committee concerning
his financial situation,'' the statement said. ``The committee's
records of the Paisley nomination contain no other information.''
   Levin was a member of the Armed Services Committee in 1981 but
did not attend the hearing.
   ``Although he was not there, his staff was there because he had
a conflict in schedule,'' said Willie Blacklow, a Levin aide.
   Asked if the senator believed he had done his duty in
scrutinizing the nomination, Blacklow said: ``If you're assertion
is this was not viewed as a major appointment, you're absolutely
right. We're finding out a bit differently now.''
   The only two senators present at the confirmation hearing were
the late Sen. Henry Jackson, D-Wash., and Roger W. Jepsen, the Iowa
Republican who was acting as chairman of the committee. Jepsen was
defeated for re-election in 1984 by Democrat Tom Harkin.
   The statement by Nunn and Warner notes that they instituted new
procedures for reviewing nominees when they took their present
positions in January 1987.
   The new procedures require ``all nominees to complete an
extensive questionnaire that requests not only financial
information, but also personal background information,'' according
to the statement.
   ``The staff director and general counsel are required to advise
the chairman in writing, as well as any other interested members,
as to whether the nominee has a conflict of interest or the
appearance of a conflict of interest.... We also require a letter
from both the Office of Government Ethics and from the Department
of Defense General Counsel that any nominee does not have a
conflict of interest,'' the statement said.
   ``We require the counsel to the president to submit a letter to
the committee that describes the extent of the FBI background
investigation, the conflict of interest review, and the tax record
check. The chairman and the ranking minority member review such
information as the FBI elects to make available when any question
has been raised and that information may shed light on the issue,''
Nunn and Warner said in the statement.
</TEXT>
