<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoppeTrial     06-29 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hoppe Trial,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mistrial Declared In Ex-Football Star's Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge declared a mistrial Wednesday
in the murder trial of former Auburn University football star Bobby
Hoppe after the jury said it could not reach a verdict in the
31-year-old case.
   ``I think that further deliberation would be fruitless,''
Hamilton County Judge Joe DiRiso said after foreman David N.
Reynolds reported the jury was hopelessly deadlocked after four
hours of deliberations.
   Hoppe, 53, is accused of using a shotgun to kill moonshine
runner Don Hudson on a dark street in 1957. He was indicted in
March after an investigation reopened at the request of Hudson's
mother.
   Hoppe testified during the seven-day trial that the shooting was
self-defense. He said he fired only after the bootlegger drove up
beside his car and pointed a pistol at him.
   Prosecutors argued that Hoppe, then a 22-year-old college
student, was angry because Hudson, 24, had beaten Joan Hoppe
Voiles, Hudson's ex-girlfriend and Hoppe's sister.
   Two jurors told reporters that the jury had voted 10-2 for
acquittal.
   A date for a new trial was not immediately set. Prosecutor Tom
Evans said he will retry the case.
   Hoppe could receive up to 20 years to life in prison. He is
charged under the law as it existed in 1957, when there was no
capital punishment.
   At the time of the slaying, Hoppe was preparing for his senior
year at Auburn, then known as Alabama Polytechnic Institute. That
fall, with Hoppe at halfback, the team went 10-0 and won their only
national championship.
   Hoppe is on leave from his position as athletic director at
Chattanooga State Technical Community College.
</TEXT>
