<HEAD>Krishnas Roses Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW VRINDABAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Rose Society has
awarded its highest honor to the Hare Krishna community here for
its rose garden.
   The Krishnas' roses showed no signs of disease or insects and
had ``lots of healthy growth'' despite the drought, Rose Society
spokesman Archie Brant said Tuesday.
   The judges, in bestowing the society's national award for public
gardens, were also impressed with the garden's unusual backdrop, a
gold Indian-style palace built by Krishna devotees, Brant said.
   The devotees pamper the roses with hand watering but like most
gardeners use pesticides, despite the Hindu doctrine of respect for
all forms of life, said New Vrindaban garden director Betty Hickey.
   ``Well, that doesn't apply when you want a nice showy garden,''
Hickey said. ``You have to use some chemicals.''
