<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Amnesty-Somalia     06-29 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Somalia,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Calls Torture In Somalia Systematic And Routine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torture is systematically used against hundreds of
political prisoners in Somalia, Amnesty International charged
Thursday in a report on the Horn of Africa country.
   The London-based human rights organization said Somalia was
subject to a ``persistent pattern of gross human rights
violations,'' including ``routine'' torture of suspected political
foes of the government and their long-term and often arbitrary
detention.
   Some torture victims were as young as 12 or 14 and were arrested
for collecting money for the Somali National Movement, which
opposes the government of President Mohamed Siad Barre, the report
said.
   According to testimony of victims, torture methods of the
National Security Service included bending people double and
severely beating them; electric shock; wounding with knives;
suspension upside down; sexual assault; death threats and tying
people in sacks and submerging them in water until they nearly
drowned _ either in the sea or a water tank.
   Numerous testimonies spoke of the Security Service headquarters
at Godka prison in the capital, Mogadishu, as a place of torture.
It is known as ``The Hole,'' a place from which it was extremely
difficult to escape, the report said.
   Somalia, a pastoral country with a population of 5.3 million,
has had to act as host for about 1.5 million refugees from drought
and guerrilla war in neighboring Ethiopia. It became an independent
republic in 1960, created from territories colonized by Italy and
Britain.
   Siad Barre, an army major general, seized power in a 1969 coup.
   Amnesty won the 1977 Nobel Peace Prize. It conducts worldwide
campaigns for the release of non-violent political prisoners and
opposition to torture and the death penalty.
   The report said although previous Amnesty appeals to end torture
and other grave violations of human rights in Somalia ``received
little response,'' it was again appealing to Siad Barre to stop
torture which it added probably went on during the whole of his 19
years in power.
   Amnesty said it was also asking the president to investigate
recent ``unlawful killings'' in Hargeisa, northern Somalia, where
the government is fighting rebels.
   The report, ``Torture in Somalia,'' was based on testimony by
torture victims, corroborated in some cases by medical examination,
AI said.
   The report said that in most testimony of torture, the victims
asked their identities be kept secret. However, it printed the
testimony of an architect, Seleiman Nuh Ali, who was arrested in
1982, tried last February and sentenced to 24 years' imprisonment
after a death sentence was commuted.
   Nuh Ali described how he was driven from Godka prison to a beach
and subjected to four types of torture: first being punched; then
``framed into a small ball, almost breaking my back'' and having
his testicles squeezed; having water poured into his mouth while
his nose was clasped so he could not breathe, and finally being
kicked all over his body with heavy boots.
   Nuh Ali said torture continued for two weeks until he agreed to
confess to political opposition activities.
   The report included testimony by an unidentified woman who said
that after her husband fled to Ethiopia and joined an opposition
movement there, she was arrested in 1978 and tortured for ``about a
year'' by being raped repeatedly in Godka prison, beaten, burned
with cigarettes, given electric shocks and submitted to the
sack-in-water torture.
   ``I was later put in solitary confinement for four years,'' the
woman said.
   ``Thousands of people have fled from Somalia in recent years
because of political persecution or on account of their opposition
to the government,'' the report said.
   It said some who have gone back under offers of amnesty have
been arrested, tortured and detained without trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
