<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Loans     06-29 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Loans,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Vote To Exempt Small Business Loans From Inflation
Adjustments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers rewriting the constitution
voted Wednesday to exempt small business and farm loans from
adjustments to inflation, which ran nearly 550 percent since the
loans were made.
   Legislators doubling as a constituent assembly voted 286-163 for
the exemption on debts incurred between Feb. 28, 1986 and Feb. 28,
1987.
   The article could still be defeated when the complete
constitution is voted on later this year.
   Not more than $50,000 owed by each business will be pardoned
under the measure and debtors must pay the principal within three
months after the constitution goes into effect.
   The loans were made under a 1986 government program which was
aimed at stimulating the economy.
   During the program, many Brazilians believing in a sustained
economic boom expanded their businesses to meet soaring demand. But
when the program ended as inflation soared, Brazilians once more
found themselves mired in a government austerity program, pushing
many small businesses into bankruptcy.
   Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega has said if the exemption
goes ahead, the government will pay the costs partially by raising
taxes. The rest, he has said, will push up the public sector
deficit, now running at about 6 percent of the gross national
product, and fuel inflation, which is 20 percent monthly.
   The government will cover 80 percent of the cost and private
banks will cover the balance.
   Lawmakers are writing the constitution that will replace the
authoritarian document handed down by military generals in 1969.
Brazil returned to civilian rule after 21 years of military
government in march of 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
