<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Northrop-Korea     06-29 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northrop-Korea,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northrop Discloses Subpoenas Served on Firm and Three Executives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has subpoenaed Northrop
Corp. and three top executives for information on a $6.5 million
payment the company made to South Korean businesses, the defense
contractor said Wednesday.
   The subpoenas were served Tuesday and Wednesday, said Tony
Cantafio, a Northrop spokesman.
   Cantafio said the executives ordered to appear before the grand
jury were Thomas V. Jones, Northrop chairman and chief executive
officer; Welko E. Gasich, an executive vice president, and William
C. McGagh, former chief financial officer.
   Although McGagh's retirement was announced in April, he has been
working with the company during a transition period, the company
said.
   The Justice Department and a Congressional subcommittee is
investigating Northrop's payment of more than $6.5 million to
Korean businesses in connection with attempts to sell its F-20
Tigershark jet fighter to the Korean military.
   Eventually, Northrop's program to develop the F-20 jet fighter
failed, with development costs estimated at $1.2 billion and
without a single plane being sold.
   The House Energy and Commerce subcomittee on investigations is
investigating whether the payment was intended to buy influence
rather than build a hotel and office project in Seoul, as Northrop
contended.
   Cantafio said in May that the 1984 payment was part of a
so-called offset program in which Northrop was to invest in Korea's
economy in return for receiving the fighter contract. Such
arangements are common among aerospace companies dealing with
developing companies and are allowed by U.S. law., he said.
   Northrop, denying it violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act,
has portrayed itself as a victim of fraud by its Korean partners in
the hotel venture.
   ``We made this investment in 1984 in good faith and to show our
commitment to Korea on the F-20 project,'' Cantafio said Wednesday.
``We made several attempts to get the hotel built, but our partners
delayed the project. When it became clear we weren't going to get
the hotel built, we tried to get our money back by going to
arbitration in Korea.''
   A call to the U.S. attorney's office went unanswered after
business hours.
</TEXT>
