<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Delivers Reagan Message To Emir Of Bahrain
^With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. envoy Richard Murphy delivered a
verbal message from President Reagan to the emir of Bahrain on
Wednesday dealing with U.S.-Bahraini ties, the Gulf News Agency
reported.
   It said Murphy and Sheik Isa Bin Salman Al Khalifa discussed the
Persian Gulf conflict, Middle East problems and the improvement of
relations between Bahrain and the United States. It gave no details.
   U.S. ties with this island state have improved in the past year.
The U.S. naval task force that patrols the war-troubled gulf enjoys
commercial facilities in Bahrain.
   The Reagan administration recently announced it planned to sell
four F-16 jet fighters and spare parts to Bahrain for about $90
million. Bahrain previously bought 12 of the sophisticated
warplanes.
   The United States also supplies Bahrain with Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles.
   Murphy has been touring the region to discuss with leaders means
of ending the nearly 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war; Secretary of State
George Shultz's plan for ending the Arab-Israeli conflict, and the
recent superpower summit in Moscow.
   His tour included Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, the United
Arab Emirates, North Yemen and Qatar.
