<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-29 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Brings Some Relief to Iowa, Nebraska</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the Central Plains
across the Mississippi Valley and northern Arkansas on Wednesday,
bringing some relief to drought-stricken sections of Iowa and
Nebraska.
   A cold front pushing slowly southward across the Midwest brought
much cooler air to the Midwest and the Northeast, with early
afternoon temperatures mostly in the 60s from the Dakotas through
the Great Lakes and into northern New England.
   A tornado touched down in the early afternoon 10 miles northwest
of Sidney, Neb., thunderstorm winds blew the roofs off barns near
Fourche Junction, Ark., and marble-size hail and 2{ inches of rain
fell in less than 20 minutes at Davenport, Neb.
   Much of northern and western Iowa received 1 to 2 inches of rain
overnight. A flash flood watch was in effect for eastern Wyoming
and a flash flood watch for small streams was posted over the Pikes
Peak region of Colorado. An inch and a third of rain fell in less
than an hour in the foothills northwest of Colorado Springs.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the southern
Rockies, Florida and southern sections of Alabama and Mississippi.
Showers dotted the Ohio Valley and showers were also scattered from
eastern Washington state into northwest Montana.
   Cool weather prevailed in the Northwest, but temperatures
climbed into the 90s to around 100 degrees from the southern half
of the Plains to the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Mullan, Idaho, to 104 at Little Rock, Ark., and Needles,
Calif.
   The forecast for Thursday called for more showers and
thunderstorms extending from the northern and central Plains across
Missouri, Arkansas and the Tennessee Valley into the Carolinas.
Thunderstorms will also be scattered over New Mexico, Western
Texas, Oklahoma, Florida and southern sections of Georgia and
Alabama.
   Much of the nation can expect high temperatures in the 70s or
80s, with highs only in the 60s from the Great Lakes across New
York State and northern Pennsylvania into New England. Temperatures
will reach the 90s to around 100 from the southern Plains through
Florida and southern Georgia and across the Great Basin.
</TEXT>
