<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0866 06-29 1168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0866,1,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls Dukakis `True Liberal'; Dukakis Screens Veep
Candidates</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, Bush made, with 3 grafs to include second
poll; picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: In another</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis screened vice presidential running mates on
Wednesday, telling reporters afterward: ``We're making progress.''
President Reagan, meanwhile, tore into the likely Democratic
presidential nominee as a ``true liberal'' bent on more taxing and
spending.
   Vice President George Bush, certain to be the Republican
presidential nominee this fall, said the next administration must
be prepared to ``seize the opportunity of change'' in the Soviet
Union. He said the Reagan administration's military buildup had
helped nudge the Soviet Union toward openness but he added, ``The
cold war is not over.''
   Bush made his way from California to Wisconsin as a two new
polls suggested he was closing in his Democratic rival. The surveys
stood in contrast to several polls in recent weeks that put
Dukakis' lead in double digits.
   An ABC-Money Magazine survey of 1,013 adults last week found 45
percent support for Dukakis and 42 percent for Bush _ a tie, given
the margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   Another poll, this one taken over the weekend by the Gallup
organization, indicated Dukakis had 46 percent to Bush's 41
percent. The poll of 1,210 voters, which had a margin of error of 3
percentage points, was published in Wednesday's editions of the San
Francisco Chronicle.
   In another development, New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean announced
that he will deliver the keynote address at the GOP National
Convention in New Orleans in August. Kean, who was overwhelmingly
re-elected governor in 1985 with support from blacks and union
members, said he would use his prime time speech to ``show there is
a tremendous difference between the two parties.''
   But there was also some difference within the party. Sen. Gordon
Humphrey of New Hampshire, saying Kean's selection as keynote
speaker was an ``affront to the right-to-life movement,''
threatened to stage a walkout at the GOP convention if a
right-to-life partisan doesn't get equal time.
   The Republican developments came as Dukakis was spending the
better part of his day in the Capitol in Washington, meeting some
lawmakers in groups and others individually as the search for a
running mate intensified.
   ``I can't say at this point if I'm close or not so close; things
have a way of sorting themselves out,'' Dukakis said after his
series of meetings. ``We're making progress. I'll be talking with
other possible vice presidential candidates.''
   Sen. Sam Nunn, favored by many in Congress for his Southern base
and his conservative political beliefs, said he was never offered
the vice presidency during a hour-long private talk with Dukakis,
but told the likely Democratic presidential nominee he wasn't
interested.
   ``I cherish my independence and the nature of the vice
presidency is a very different job,'' Nunn told reporters after
spending an hour with Dukakis. ``I enjoy making my own decisions.''
He said Dukakis accepted Nunn's desires and ``did it very
graciously.''
   Nunn is the second prominent Democrat to take himself out of the
running for runner-up on the ticket, following New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley.
   Dukakis' aides went to unusual lengths to keep the governor's
agenda private. Reporters were not told in advance who the
Massachusetts governor was meeting, and when a list was circulated
at day's end, it did not say which lawmakers met privately and
which in large groups. Nor were reporters permitted to wait outside
the room just off the Senate floor where Dukakis set up his
temporary office.
   One man prominently mentioned in the vice presidential
speculation, Sen. John Glenn of Ohio, met privately with Dukakis.
The two were scheduled to campaign together in Ohio on Friday.
   Others mentioned as potential running mates include Sens. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas; Bob Graham of Florida and Dale Bumpers of
Arkansas, as well as Reps. Richard Gephardt of Missouri; Lee
Hamilton of Indiana and Tom Foley of Washington _ although sources
said Foley had decided not to provide background information
requested by Dukakis aides.
   Jesse Jackson also has been asked to provide information about
himself, but Dukakis aides widely discount the possibility that he
will be offered a spot on the ticket.
   For his part, Jackson said he will spend much of the next week
in private, deliberating with his family about a possible vice
presidential nomination and working to free U.S. hostages in the
Middle East. Jackson had said previously that he already had made
up his mind about the vice presidency.
   Dukakis worked on completing his ticket for the fall as an
Associated Press survey of the delegates to the Democratic
Convention showed no clear consensus on a vice presidential pick.
   Of 1,200 delegates responding thus far to the survey, 534 said
they had no preference. Nunn had the support of 163, followed by
Jackson with 135, most of whom will go to the convention supporting
him for president. Glenn was supported by 106 delegates.
   In Florda, Reagan entered the campaign with a partisan vigor
unseen since his 1986 bid to re-elect Republican senators.
   ``What the 1988 elections are all about is whether we continue
to build on that progress (of his administration) and move ahead to
an even brighter future, or whether we hesitate and return to those
worn-out policies that bring high taxes, low growth and a loss of
direction and purpose,'' he said as he campaigned for Senate
candidate Connie Mack.
   He added that the man leading the Democratic ticket is a ``true
liberal who, instead of controlling government spending, raises
taxes.''
   Reagan said that Dukakis has ``spent every dime and more of the
revenue generated in his state by the Reagan-Bush (economic)
recovery. And since 1986, while the federal budget deficit has been
cut sharply, his deficit in Massachusetts has ballooned.''
   Despite Reagan's allegation, records show there hasn't been a
deficit in Massachusetts since 1982, when Dukakis inherited one
from outgoing Gov. Edward King.
   ``With all due respect, I think the president's confused,''
Dukakis said on learning of Reagan's remarks. ``It is this
administration that has given us more red ink than all the previous
administrations from George Washington to Jimmy Carter combined. It
is this administration that has raised taxes four times in the last
six years.''
   Bush concentrated on foreign policy in his speech in California,
saying that the sweeping changes proposed on Tuesday by Soviet
General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev were ``revolutionary.''
   Bush said the changes taking place in the Soviet Union ``didn't
take place in a vacuum but in the context of reinvigorated American
strength.''
   He added, ``my point is this, it was eight years of American
strength that confronted the Soviet Union with the true costs of
aggression and necessity of reform.''
   Bush said the proposals forwarded by Gorbachev on Wednesday
should be watched with ``guarded optimism.''
   But, he said, ``We've got to remember that the cold war is not
over.''
</TEXT>
