<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AMARdp 1stLd-Writethru a0766 06-29 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AMA Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0766,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Approves Drug Policy Overhaul</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with AMA calling for testing of
new category of hospital worker, pickup 4th pvs, `Several doctors
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association voted Wednesday
to test creation of a new type of hospital worker who would handle
chores such as taking vital signs, bathing patients and changing
bandages.
   The proposal for the new category of workers, called registered
care technologists, comes in response to the nationwide shortage of
nurses, but the plan drew strong opposition from a major nursing
group.
   The AMA's 420-member House of Delegates also called for major
changes in the nation's war on drugs and approved a detailed plan
for reforming the nation's Medicaid health insurance program for
the poor.
   The decisions by the policy-making arm of the nation's largest
doctors organization, with 295,000 members, were made by voice vote.
   The plan for the new type of worker was opposed by the American
Nurses' Association, which maintains that the answer to the nursing
shortage is higher salaries and better working conditions.
   ``I really am appalled that in the face of opposition from all
of organized nursing that medicine has gone ahead with this
decision,'' said Judith Ryan, executive director of the American
Nurses' Association.
   The House of Delegates rejected an attempt to delay the pilot
project to allow more time for study.
   The new workers would receive from two months to 18 months of
training.
   Nurses argued that isn't enough training and said the
technologists would duplicate the role now played by nursing
assistants, licensed practical nurses and technical registered
nurses.
   In regard to drug trafficking, the delegates rejected efforts to
delay action on a report calling for major changes in the war on
drugs. The AMA said the United States is losing the war to rich,
sophisticated drug traffickers.
   The delegates said ``real progress'' will only be made by
shifting the attack from catching smugglers to treating abusers.
   Several doctors complained they hadn't had enough time to study
the proposal, but many more delegates said the problem was too
urgent to delay action.
   ``It is (a) farsighted (report) and it would be a tragedy if it
were not adopted,'' said Dr. Saul Levin of Sacramento, Calif.
   ``This is a major issue before this country,'' said Dr. Lonnie
Bristow, an AMA trustee from Berkeley, Calif. ``We are saying this
nation does have the will to overcome the drug problem, but it
simply has the wrong game plan.
   ``We must approach the demand side of this problem by treating
those who are sick ... and thereby reducing the demand for those
who traffick in this filthy product,'' Bristow said.
   With an estimated $30 billion to $100 billion in annual revenue,
drug traffickers can counteract federal crackdowns, the AMA report
says.
   ``They can acquire sophisticated technology, bribe public
officials and recruit new members,'' it contends. ``Real progress
is likely to come only from a major shift in primary emphasis away
from supply-reduction and enforcement strategies and toward
demand-reduction strategies.''
   Shifting their attention to another pressing social problem _
uneven medical care for the poor _ the AMA policymakers proposed
creating uniform nationwide eligibility standards for Medicaid and
uniform payments for medical care.
   The delegates voted to lobby the federal government to create
the standards and expand Medicaid to cover an additional 27 million
poor people at an increased annual cost of $24 billion at 1988
spending levels. The program, administered by state governments,
covers an estimated 19 million poor people at a projected cost of
$52 billion in 1988.
   An AMA report on Medicaid said the program is ``in desperate
need of reform'' because the lack of national standards has bred
``severe inequities'' in the level of medical care benefits
provided to poor people.
   In other action Wednesday, the House of Delegates:
   _Continued the AMA's war on tobacco, approving a proposal to
lobby Congress to double the federal tax on cigarettes from 16
cents per pack to 32 cents.
   _Called on state and federal governments to reform the court
system to limit the amount of money awarded in product liability
lawsuits. A report approved by the delegates contends that
biomedical companies are holding off on developing new vaccines,
drugs and other ``potentially life-saving technologies'' because
they are afraid of being sued.
   The drug policy approved Wednesday recommends that the federal
government expand drug abuse treatment programs, ease regulations
to permit private doctors to treat opiate addicts with methadone
and increase drug education programs aimed at adolescents.
   The policy also calls on the president to appoint ``a
high-ranking official of the Executive Branch to coordinate federal
drug policy'' to keep rival agencies from working at cross-purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
