<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ArabShopkeepers     06-29 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab Shopkeepers,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Patrols Beefed Up Around Arab-Owned Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have stepped up patrols around
Arab-owned businesses after the slaying of a black man by an Arab
grocery clerk sparked several firebombings, police and community
leaders said Wednesday.
   ``Everybody's got bad feelings, and these come from isolated
incidents,'' said Patricia A. Blackmon, the city's chief prosecutor.
   Ms. Blackmon, who has met with community groups in recent days
seeking to calm racial tensions, said blacks are demanding higher
quality food, lower prices and more courtesy from Arab shopkeepers.
   Arab shopkeepers, representing Egyptians, Lebanese, Iranians and
Palestinians, have complained of repeated thefts and slow response
time by police, Ms. Blackmon said.
   Tensions erupted June 18 when a black man, James Slaughter, 31,
was shot and killed by an Arab clerk, Eiab Taher, 33, who was
charged with involuntary manslaughter. The following night, a crowd
ransacked the store in apparent retaliation.
   The tensions have resulted in a rash of firebombings of
Arab-owned businesses, including one store set afire three times in
as many weeks, authorities said.
   In response, police have increased patrols in black
neighborhoods where Arabs have businesses, and police community
relations specialists are working with community leaders on the
problem, said Detective Robert Bolton, a police spokesman.
   ``We don't want it to escalate to anything. If there are
problems that have to be fixed, that's fine,'' Bolton said.
   City Council member Helen Knipe Smith, whose district includes
the neighborhood where an Arab store was firebombed, said most of
the grocers and small delis in the area are operated by Arabs.
   She said the Arabs follow the Jews, Irish, Italians and blacks
who in succession operated family-run businesses in the city's
ghettoes.
   She blamed tensions on a need by ghetto businesses to charge
higher prices than larger chain stores operating in the suburbs and
a concern by Arabs about crime.
   Mayor George V. Voinovich said the city has increased health
inspections at groceries.
   ``Neither the proprietors of stores or any member of our
community should take the law into their own hands,'' he said.
   In response to the tensions, the Cleveland Community Relations
Board has formed a joint Arab-black committee to improve relations,
executive director Earl Williams said.
</TEXT>
