<DOCNO> AP880629-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Somalia-Rebels     06-29 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Somalia-Rebels,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Somali Guerrilla Chief Pleads with U.N. To Probe Massacre Reports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Amnesty-Somalia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Somali rebels have appealed to the United
Nations to investigate purported government massacres in the
war-torn north and organize massive relief aid for other victims, a
guerrilla spokesman said Wednesday.
   Ahmed Mohamed Silanyo, Somali National Movement chairman, wrote
to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Saturday
urging him to seek an ``independent evaluation'' of drugs and food
needed by civilians caught in the cross fire in the past month,
according to a copy of the four-page letter.
   ``The inhabitants of towns and settlements which have been, and
are still being, indiscriminately shelled and bombed from the air
are currently unable to defend themselves,'' Silanyo said. ``They
look to the United Nations and world opinion to protect them.''
   Silanyo sent the letter from his exile headquarters in London,
and a rebel official delivered a copy to The Associated Press in
Nairobi.
   In it, Silanyo said water and power supplies were cut in many
areas, unburied, decomposing corpses in streets threatened to
trigger a cholera epidemic, food was scarce and medical supplies
virtually exhausted.
   Silanyo renewed rebel claims that they control key northern
centers including Hargeisa, Somalia's second largest city, and the
regional capital of Burao, since mounting a major offensive against
President Siad Barre's army late May.
   In retaliation, he wrote, warplanes bombed civilians in villages
and troops massacred suspected rebel sympathizers, many through
``summary executions'' in public.
   Barre's government repeatedly has denied atrocity charges,
accusing the insurgents of killing civilians and looting. The
government insists that since last week, its troops have been
controlling all northern centers.
   But foreign travelers who arrived this week in Nairobi, the
Kenyan capital, from neighboring Somalia said rebels were holding
on to Burao and other towns while fighting continued for Hargeisa.
   The Westerners, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said a
dusk to dawn curfew was still in force in the capital, Mogadishu.
They said troops there were commandeering vehicles, including those
owned by foreign aid workers.
   Silanyo, a former Cabinet member in Barre's government, helped
form the Somali National Movement seven years ago.
   Barre seized power in a 1969 coup. Since 1977, he has been a
staunch African ally of the United States.
</TEXT>
