<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Drought 1stLd-Writethru a0756 06-29 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Drought, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer ``A Little Embarrassed'' By Dukakis Drought Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with Dukakis visit</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, hoping to underscore the
impact of this year's dry weather, got a firsthand look at a
relatively healthy corn field Wednesday but stressed ``the
importance of pulling together'' to help farmers suffering from
drought.
   ``This is a problem that affects farmers and farm communities
and farm states and consumers,'' Dukakis said. ``We are very much a
part of this. We're one nation and one community and one family.''
   His comments came as Dukakis made a brief stop at the Howard
Hughes farm just south of Des Moines.
   Hughes conceded he was ``a little embarrassed'' to have his farm
be the staging ground for a visit aimed at pointing up drought
problems _ because rain just fell on his 160-acre farm and the corn
is nearly seven feet high.
   ``My corn does look pretty good,'' Hughes said.
   Though Hughes' farm isn't the most hard-hit in the state, it
does have at least one major tactical advantage. It's located about
four miles from the end of the runway at the Des Moines airport and
quickly accessible for Dukakis' motorcade.
   Dukakis spoke to about 250 people under threatening skies and in
chilly weather that caused many to don sweaters.
   ``I don't know whether those storm clouds overhead mean Dukakis
brings good fortune,'' he said. ``I hope so.''
   Dukakis was accompanied on the tour by Illinois Sen. Paul Simon,
a former rival for the nomination, who appealed for party unity.
   ``There is a time to fight and a time to heal,'' Simon said.
   After a brief round of speeches, Dukakis was led on a tour of
the farm and told by Hughes that the apparently healthy corn
wouldn't last long without rain, although he conceded it has a lush
appearance.
   Just under an inch of rain fell on the Hughes' farm overnight,
and that comes on top of a 2.5 inch downpour earlier in the month.
   ``What this does is, it's kind of a tantalizing rain,'' Hughes
said. ``It prolongs things and it makes my corn look better.''
   Simon warned reporters not to jump to any quick conclusions
about the status of the crop simply because it looked good.
   ``Don't get any false impressions, even though that corn looks
better,'' Simon said.
   Vice President George Bush, the certain Republican nominee, had
a similar farm visit in Wisconsin on Wednesday.
   Hughes said his farm presents a fairly lush backdrop for a
drought tour. ``Really, I'm a little embarrassed by it,'' he said.
   But he said even crops which look good now will soon be
threatened by dry weather.
   ``This is a point that we're going to have to drive home real
hard with people who aren't familiar with farming,'' Hughes said.
``My corn is six or seven feet high and getting ready to tassel,
but if we have some more searing heat and no rain I don't have
stalks with enough vigor to produce ears.''
   Hughes said recent rainfalls are far too little and too
scattered to do much about ending this year's drought.
   ``It gives me a few more days over the farmer who didn't get
any,'' he said.
   ``To illustrate how fickle these rains are, I have a dear friend
just north of here who only got two-hundredths while Indianola just
south of here got an inch. It's just in a little pocket,'' Hughes
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0851 06-29 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0851,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Searches for Veep Candidates in Congress; Nunn Says Count
Me Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs with farm visit</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis met with senators
Wednesday in his search for a vice presidential candidate, and was
told by one _ Sam Nunn of Georgia _ to count him out.
   ``I can't say at this point if I'm close or not so close; things
have a way of sorting themselves out,'' Dukakis said after his
series of meetings. ``We're making progress. I'll be talking with
other possible vice presidential candidates.''
   The all-but-certain presidential nominee spent an hour in
private with Nunn, a favorite of southern and conservative
Democrats, during a day filled with private meetings on Capitol
Hill _ including individual sessions with at least three other
possible running mates.
   ``I told Governor Dukakis that I was honored to be considered,
to be on the list,'' Nunn said. ``I told him I was still not
interested in the vice presidency.''
   Dukakis also met privately with Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas and Bob Graham of Florida, he told reporters while
leaving the Capitol.
   He said he would be back in a week or so to meet with other
potential candidates.
   Nunn had previously indicated a lack of interest in the post,
but he had been pushed by conservative Democrats who want a
geographic and ideological balance on the ticket. The meeting with
the likely nominee enabled Nunn to relay his decision in person.
   ``He accepted the decision and he did it very graciously,'' Nunn
said.
   The two then discussed ``seven or eight'' other potential vice
presidential candidates, Nunn said.
   The Georgia senator is the second major prospective candidate to
take himself out of the running. Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.,
recently withdrew from consideration.
   Nunn said his move should not be taken as a reflection of
Dukakis. ``My feeling on the subject had absolutely nothing to do
with Governor Dukakis,'' he said.
   Despite the rejection, Dukakis said he had ``a good day, a very
helpful day.''
   ``I cannot emphasize too much the kind of cooperation and
response that I've gotten. It's been terrific,'' he said.
   The Massachusetts governor met with 29 senators and nine House
members, including some of the lawmakers often mentioned as
potential running mates: Bentsen, Glenn, Graham, and Rep. Tom
Foley, D-Wash.
   Glenn, who figures high in the vice presidential speculation,
declined to comment. He was flying home to Ohio to appear Friday
with Dukakis, who was stopping in Dayton on a Midwest campaign
swing, said a spokesman, who declined to be identified.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, whose Democratic presidential
campaign failed to catch fire outside the South, was not invited to
meet with Dukakis, said Gore press secretary Mike Kopp.
   Foley met with Dukakis during the governor's lunch with a group
of agriculture committee members. He said they did not discuss the
vice presidency, but added that he would meet again with Dukakis in
a week or so. Foley declined to comment when asked if he had turned
over background information to the Dukakis campaign.
   Dukakis shuttled from meeting to meeting through corridors
cleared of bystanders by Capitol Police, and he said nothing on the
few occasions reporters caught glimpses of him.
   Dukakis later departed on a five-state campaign swing through
the Midwest.
   Accompanying Dukakis was his senior adviser Paul Brountas, who
is leading the campaign's search for a running mate and is heading
a team of lawyers who are reviewing financial records and other
information about prospective candidates. Brountas and other aides
left the room during the Nunn meeting.
   Nunn told reporters after his meeting with Dukakis that he had
taken himself out of the running because he prefers his Senate job
to the vice presidency.
   ``I cherish my independence and the nature of the vice
presidency is a very different job. I enjoy making my own
decisions,'' Nunn said.
   Nunn was among the Democrats asked by the Dukakis campaign to
supply personal and financial disclosure information. He declined.
   ``I considered filling out forms to be essentially a job
application and there's no reason to do that if you're not
interested in the job,'' Nunn said.
   He said that although Dukakis ``urged me to keep my hat in the
ring,'' he did not engage in any form of pressure or arm-twisting.
``He made no move for my arm,'' Nunn said.
   He said that at no point did Dukakis ever directly ask him to be
his running mate. ``I would not have put him in that position,''
Nunn said.
   Dukakis press secretary Dayton Duncan said that Dukakis did not
have a deadline for selecting the running mate, and planned to
return July 13 for meetings with House members. That would be five
days before the Democratic National Convention opens in Atlanta.
   ``He doesn't feel like he's under any timetable or deadline,''
Duncan said.
   Dukakis met first with a group including most of the 16 Senate
Democrats facing re-election races this year, a group that included
Bentsen.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said they discussed the vice
presidency without mentioning names.
   ``He said the process is still open, and he's enjoying the
process,'' Kerry said. He said Dukakis invited suggestions on a
running mate.
   Dukakis also held a lunch with nine Democratic members of the
Senate Agriculture Committee and 10 members of the House
Agriculture Committee to discuss the drought in farm states.
   Later, Dukakis toured the farm of Howard Hughes near Norwalk,
Iowa. The farm actually got some rain the night before, but Hughes
said even if his corn crop looks healthy now, it won't produce ears
if it doesn't rain some more _ and soon.
   Hughes said some farms in the state were much harder hit by the
drought than his. But his farm is only about four miles from the
Des Moines airport, and lent itself to a quick campaign-style stop.
   ``This is a problem that affects farmers and farm communities
and farm states and consumers,'' Dukakis said after a brief tour.
``We are very much a part of this. We're one nation and one
community and one family.''
   Dukakis spoke in chilly weather, under skies threatening rain.
   ``I don't know whether those storm clouds overhead mean Dukakis
brings good fortune,'' he said. ``I hope so.''
</TEXT>
