<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador-Bucaram     06-29 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Bucaram,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate Flees Ecuadorean Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUAYAQUIL, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abdala Bucaram, a fiery politician who
lost a presidential runoff in May, fled Ecuador for Miami Wednesday
to avoid arrest, his wife said.
   If would mark the second time in three years that the leader of
the populist Roldosista Party went into self-exile.
   Judge Luis Herreria ordered the 36-year-old Bucaram arrested
Tuesday after he failed to appear in court in mid-June.
   The politician was to make statements regarding alleged
diversions of Guayaquil city funds, which were said to have
occurred when he was mayor in 1984-85.
   ``He left the country because the judicial action had become
politicized,'' his wife, Maria Rosa Bucaram, told a news conference
in this port city, 180 miles southwest of the capital city of Quito.
   Mrs. Bucaram said her husband left Guayaquil on a 10 a.m. (11
a.m. EDT) flight aboard a plane owned by the cargo company AECA.
The flight could not be confirmed by late Wednesday.
   Bucaram lost the May 9 runoff to Rodrigo Borja, Social Democrat
and leader of the Democratic Left party, who replaces President
Leon Febres Cordero in August.
   Bucaram went into exile in Panama while still mayor in late 1985
to escape imprisonment for having allegedly slandered the armed
forces, a criminal offense in Ecuador. He said the military was
good only for wasting money on parades.
   While in Panama he was arrested for possession of five pounds of
cocaine. He claimed it was a frame-up arranged by Febres Cordero, a
political enemy. Ecuador's Congress granted him amnesty on the
military offense and Panama eventually dropped the charges.
   He returned in August 1987 to a hero's welcome from his
followers in Guayaquil's shantytowns and almost immediately
launched his presidential campaign.
   Analysts said Bucaram's presence as a strong presidential
contender sparked repeated rumors of a military coup during the
campaign.
</TEXT>
