<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Massacre     06-29 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Massacre,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maoist Guerrillas Kill 25 Peasants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas raided four farm
settlements, killing 25 men in revenge attacks against peasant
self-defense patrols, the military said Wednesday.
   Thirty Shining Path guerrillas, six wearing police and army
uniforms, carried out the attacks Monday and Tuesday, the military
said in a communique released in this highland capital, 235 miles
southeast of Lima.
   The military said the Maoist rebels left messages in the
villages, all in the Acon River valley about 55 miles northeast of
Ayacucho, which warned villagers against taking part in the patrols
organized by the army.
   Six men and two women were wounded in the attacks, the military
said.
   The communique did not describe the violence, but rebels have
held mock trials and shot or stabbed to death hundreds of patrol
members in dozens of attacks.
   The government says more than 10,000 people have died since the
Shining Path launched its insurgency from the impoverished Ayacucho
highlands eight years ago.
   Most of the dead have been peasants caught up in the struggle
between the Mao-inspired rebels and government forces, officials
say.
</TEXT>
