<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbusiveCalls     06-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abusive Calls,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abusive Calls Traced To Council Member's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police investigating abusive phone calls received
by a woman said Wednesday they traced some of the calls to the home
of a City Council member with whom she had clashed over monitoring
of the Police Department.
   The council member, Deputy Mayor Pro Tem Diane Ragsdale, denied
making the calls, labeling the charges as a ``set up'' by police.
   Ms. Ragsdale is a vocal critic of the Police Department and its
use of deadly force against minorities.
   Carrie Delano, an ardent supporter of the Police Department,
said that she received abusive calls and a death threat after a
shouting match with Ms. Ragsdale at a council meeting June 8, and
that she asked police to trace the calls.
   Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. traced four of the calls to Ms.
Ragsdale's home, four to the home of her sister, Charlotte
Ragsdale, and one to a number listed to an R. Benson, said police
Capt. Dolan Hargrove.
   Diane and Charlotte Ragsdale said neither they nor other members
of their households would have made such calls.
   No charges have been filed. The Dallas County district
attorney's office is investigating.
   ``I will not be sidetracked by this electronic provocation,''
Ms. Ragsdale said. ``All of these allegations reinforces the fact
that there are bad apples in the Police Department.''
   Ms. Ragsdale, the city's highest-ranking elected black official,
had argued with Mrs. Delano over an effort to weaken a citizens'
police review board. The two called each other racists. Ms. Delano
is white.
   Acting Police Chief Lou Caudell confirmed police are
investigating calls made to Mrs. Delano and that authorities had
placed a ``trap'' on her phone.
   Ms. Ragsdale, 35, lives with her 74-year-old mother and her
12-year-old nephew.
</TEXT>
