<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday upheld the
power of independent counsels to prosecute illegal acts by
high-ranking government officials, a momentous constitutional
decision and a defeat for a handful of former White House aides
such as Oliver L. North and Michael K. Deaver.
   By a 7-1 vote, the justices said a 1978 law inspired by the
Watergate scandal does not violate the Constitution's command that
the powers of the executive, legislative and judicial branches be
separate and balanced.
   The ruling clears away a potential stumbling block in the
prosecution of North, the former National Security Council aide;
John M. Poindexter, President Reagan's former national security
adviser; and two arms dealers indicted in the Iran-Contra arms and
money affair.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonian delegates to the Communist Party
conference said Wednesday they expect the Kremlin to back their
Baltic republic's demand for autonomy from Moscow as the ``only
chance'' to keep the Soviet Union strong.
   In interviews with The Associated Press, three Estonian
delegates described what they said were efforts dating back to last
fall to work out a political and economic program giving the
republic independence over its economy, ecology, education and
culture.
   The program has been summarized in the platform of Estonia's 32
delegates to the party conference, who said it has been well
received by influential reformers in Moscow.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like millions of other Soviets touched by the
terror of Josef Stalin, Dmitri A. Volkogonov still remembers the
day his father disappeared.
   More than 50 years later, that personal tragedy is foremost in
Volkogonov's mind as he finishes the first comprehensive Soviet
biography of Stalin, the man he blames for the death of his father
and those of millions of others.
   Volkogonov, a military historian, said he has spent 10 years
culling Soviet archives and talking to people who knew Stalin for a
two-volume biography, ``Triumph and Tragedy,'' scheduled to appear
next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government weather forecasters offered scant
cheer to drought-plagued areas Wednesday, issuing a series of
forecasts that call for more of the same, at least for the next
month.
   ``It's likely to get worse before it gets better,'' said Dr.
Michael Hudlow, director of hydrology for the National Weather
Service.
   The overall outlook calls for little change in the weather for
the next week or two. Hot, dry weather will continue but shift its
emphasis eastward and southward over the next one to three months,
said Dr. Donald L. Gilman, head of the agency's Long Range
Predictions Group.
</TEXT>
