<TEXT>
   Delegates to the Democratic National
Convention have not rallied behind any potential vice presidential
candidate, including Jesse Jackson, and apparently are content to
leave the choice to Michael Dukakis, an Associated Press survey
found.
   Roughly half the delegates surveyed by the AP said they had no
preference for the No. 2 spot on the party's ticket, while the
other half scattered their support among nearly three dozen
potential candidates, mostly favorite sons.
   Many of those responding to the survey said they were willing to
go along with whomever Dukakis asks to join him on the ticket. The
delegates will be asked to ratify Dukakis' choice on the final
night of the four-day convention.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medicine widely used for gout appears to
dramatically slow the lethal destruction of cirrhosis, but doctors
disagree over whether it should become routine treatment for this
major killer.
   In a report published Thursday, a team of Mexican researchers
said they found ``a striking, consistent, statistically significant
benefit'' of the drug colchicine. After 10 years, more than half of
those who got the medicine were alive, compared with less than a
quarter of the people in an untreated comparison group.
   Earlier versions of the 14-year study have been published and
presented at medical meetings over the years, and many U.S. experts
are familiar with the work. Despite the impressive results,
however, opinion is divided.
</TEXT>
