<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   06-29 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0636</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wed June 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Something To Worry About</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the economic scene calming down after a
succession of crises _ trade imbalance, falling dollar, recession
threat _ the current big concern of economic worry warts is a
familiar one: inflation.
   From researchers at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. comes an
``economic flash'' about ``early signs of wage acceleration.''
Service sector wages, it states, have accelerated significantly in
the past three months.
   The pervasive drought adds urgency to the inflation message,
since commodity prices could force increases in the consumer price
index.
   Jack Lavery of Merrill Lynch & Co. comments that ``enough damage
has already been done to corn, wheat and soybean crops to
accelerate food-price increases this year, although the full extent
of the damage remains to be seen.''
   At Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette, it isn't only drought that
produces worries. ``Our concerns about inflation have never been
based on the weather,'' say researchers there.
   Instead, they observe that apparel prices are higher than they
were a year ago, gasoline and fuel-oil prices have risen for
several months, and medical care costs have continued to set
records, as they have for years.
   The worriers fall into two distinct camps. Those who fear
inflation via higher commodity prices or wages are citing a
cost-push scenario. Others fear the threat is from demand-pull, as
from high levels of consumer demand.
   While the worriers might not be growing in number they are
shouting louder, and in the otherwise quieter economic setting that
has evolved in the past month their voices are carrying farther.
   Are they worth listening to?
   Other commentators observe that there is always an inflation
threat. It is ever present, ready to end any economic expansion if
allowed to gain headway. You can always cite it as a threat, they
say. It is always available for duty.
   ``Cost-push inflation scenarios don't make economic sense,''
according to a paper released a few days ago by the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce. It explains:
   ``Sellers to the final consumer can only raise prices if
competitors and consumers are willing to go along. Otherwise,
sellers must absorb cost increases by cutting other costs or
accepting lower profits.''
   Right now, it states, competition is intense among sellers. The
latter are more concerned about meeting competitor prices than they
are about raising margins. They are fighting for a limited number
of consumer dollars.
   It is true that wages show signs of rising, but there are few
indications that they are rising faster than productivity.
   Offsetting the wage pressure, the anti-inflationists contend, is
growth in the nation's capacity to produce as well as an increase
in productivity. Money is being spent on enlarging capacity, and on
making it more efficient.
   ``The core rate of inflation has been remarkably stable,'' says
Edward Yardeni, economist at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. Since
1985, he states, it has hovered between 4 percent and 4.5 percent.
Some things have risen; others have fallen.
   He attributes this partly to investment in new facilities, and
demographics as well. He asserts that the nation's problems with
baby-boomers have ended, at least in the production of goods.
   In retrospect those problems were enormous. Youngsters flooded
the labor markets. They were inexperienced. They were inefficient
producers. And, because there were so many available, business
didn't bother with efficiencies.
   Now it's different. Says Yardeni: ``The shortage of young job
seekers will force businesses to invest in labor-saving and
productivity-enhancing plants and equipment.'' And efficient
production is anti-inflationary.
   Will that stop the inflation worries? Not likely, at least until
something bigger seizes the stage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed., June 29.</NOTE>
</DOC>
