<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Pascal Adv30   06-29 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Pascal, Adv 30,0795</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, June 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mary Ann Pascal Became Actress Because She Looked Like One</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of June 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Ann Pascal had never given acting a
thought, but because of her voluptuous beauty people kept assuming
she was an actress.
   ``I never trained as an actress. I never thought about it until
I was 26,'' said Pascal, who stars on the Showtime comedy series
``Brothers.''
   ``I was working in a boutique, learning the business so I could
open my own place. But when you look like I do, people always
assume you're an actress. Anywhere else, I suppose, they'd think
you were somebody's mistress. A man who later became one of my
managers said I really should try acting.''
   It quickly fell into place for her. She got a job on her first
interview, which got her into the Screen Actors Guild. She was cast
as a ``Hammerettes,'' one of the women executive producer Jay
Bernstein hired to walk through ``Mickey Spillane's Mike Hammer.''
   ``Obviously, these women are not brain surgeons,'' said Pascal.
``I went to Frederick's of Hollywood and bought a push-up bra. I
looked exactly like what I was supposed to look. Afterward, I
burned the bra and told my agent I didn't want any more parts like
that.''
   She did guest shots on ``Hotel,'' ``Knight Rider'' and
``Remington Steele.''
   ``Brothers'' was her first comedy and her first time before an
audience.
   ``When Tuesday night came around I was trembling,'' she said.
``There'd be 600 eyes on me. They say that after a while it becomes
like nothing, and it does. Now it gives me adrenalin and energy,
but in the beginning it was terrifying.
   ``Now that I've done drama and comedy, I'd pick comedy every
time. The hours are so much better. You can lead a normal life
around it.''
   Since then, she's also had roles on ``Night Court,'' ``Crime
Story'' and the TV movie ``Blood Vows: A Mafia Wife's Story.''
   Pascal is married to Michael Pascal, marketing executive of the
Golden Nugget Hotel and Casino. She lives in Las Vegas and is
unofficial hostess of the casino. She commutes to Los Angeles for
filming.
   Because of some unsavory fan mail she is taking pistol lessons
and practicing her marksmanship. ``I play this very sexy person,''
she said, ``and people who don't have a good grip on reality
confuse me with the character. I'm a happily married woman and have
been for almost 10 years.''
   Pascal stars on ``Brothers'' as Sam, the girlfriend of Joe
Waters (Robert Walden). The show focuses on three brothers, played
by Walden, Brandon Maggart and Paul Regina. Regina's character is
gay, as is a family friend played by Philip Charles MacKenzie.
Hallie Todd plays Walden's college-age daughter.
   ``Brothers'' opened its fifth season on Showtime last Friday
with Sam announcing she was pregnant.
   ``My character is so full of herself,'' said Pascal. ``She can't
believe that no one would drop dead to marry her. But she and Joe
decide to get married. On the next show they're already married.''
   The baby will be born on the 10th episode of the season, which
will be the 100th episode for the series.
   The fly in the ointment, however, is that only three shows were
taped for the new season before the writers' strike. If the show is
forced to go into reruns after the third show, the producers will
select best shows from the past seasons.
   ``Brothers'' will go into syndication in the fall of 1989.
``They're getting into more boy-girl relationships so it will have
broader appeal for syndication,'' said Pascal. ``They're diluting
the gay theme.''
   Pascal, who was born in New York and grew up there and in
Florida, said acting is work but that being hostess at the Golden
Nugget is play.
   After she was persuaded to become an actress, she said, ``I had
visions of what I would be. I thought of `Dynasty.' I imagined I'd
be Alexis. And I end up as Lucy. When I was a kid all I wanted to
be was a nun.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BALLOTS IN THE MAIL...Ballots for the 40th Annual Prime Time
Emmy Awards have been mailed to qualified voters of the Academy of
Television Arts & Sciences. Deadline for the return is July 15. The
nominees will be announced at 5:30 a.m. Thursday, July 28, at the
Registry Hotel next door to Universal Studios. The presentation
will be Sunday, Aug. 28, on Fox Broadcasting Co. from the Pasadena
Civic Auditorium.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, June 30</NOTE>
