<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Anderson Adv04   06-29 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Anderson, Adv 04,0643</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, July 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Stage And Screen ``Orphan'' Finds Himself a ``Home''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Anderson came to fame as the wild,
youthful kidnapper in the play and film, ``Orphans.'' However, his
new movie, ``Miles From Home,'' shows the actor's more taciturn
side.
   ``This guy is so quiet,'' the 28-year-old Anderson said. ``Most
of the time I just had to try to exist, to be there and to listen.''
   Anderson talked about the movie in an interview at the recent
Cannes Film Festival, where the $6 million movie had its world
premiere in May.
   Scheduled for an American release in October from Cinecom, the
film co-stars Anderson and Richard Gere as two brothers on a family
farm in Iowa who destroy their property rather than face
foreclosure on it.
   Gere is the impulsive older brother, Frank Roberts, a man quick
to take action regardless of the consequences. Anderson is the
shyer, more tentative Terry, who comes to respect his brother as
they become joint outlaws on the run.
   The film drew mixed reviews at Cannes for its somewhat dogged
earnestness. But there was general acclaim for Anderson's ability
to make passivity engaging in a film that puts two brothers
center-screen, as ``Orphans'' did.
   ``(Maybe) there's some brother hang-up I need to work out,''
joked the soft-spoken actor, himself the youngest of three brothers
from Gurnee, Ill.
   However, there are differences between the parts: ``It was
difficult to find the arc of Terry because he is largely silent,''
he said of ``Miles From Home,'' which marks the film directing
debut of Gary Sinise, a long-time colleague of Anderson from their
days at Chicago's Steppenwolf Theater Company.
   ``In `Orphans,' I was so soundly rooted in the character, I
didn't have to worry about nerves,'' he said of the earlier film,
which began life as a Lyle Kessler play for Steppenwolf, directed
by Sinise and acclaimed in Chicago, New York and London.
   The film, directed by Alan Pakula and co-starring Matthew Modine
and Albert Finney, fared less well. Reviews were mixed-to-good but
the box office was low, contrary to the hopes of its star, whose
prior movie credits were limited to one line in the popular comedy
``Risky Business.''
   ``I received a lot of attention for `Orphans' on-stage so I
really wanted the movie to be special,'' Anderson said. ``I was
very disappointed; the studio kind of gave up on it.''
   Anderson will also be seen this year in Ray Silver's ``A Walk on
the Moon,'' playing a peace corps volunteer in Ecuador in 1969. His
co-star, Terry Kinney, is a Steppenwolf alumnus who has a
supporting role in ``Miles From Home'' alongside other Chicago
talents such as Moira Harris, Francis Guinan and, in a vivid cameo,
John Malkovich.
   Despite his increased screen exposure, Anderson remains attached
to the stage. Last December, he headed an exemplary company of
young New York actors in an off-Broadway revival of Michael
Weller's ``Moonchildren.''
   He is currently playing the celebrated gigolo of the title in a
revival of the musical ``Pal Joey'' at Chicago's Goodman Theater.
The Richard Rodgers and Lorenz Hart classic, co-starring Carlin
Glynn, runs through Aug. 7 with the chance of an extension.
   Anderson said he was enjoying reprising one of Broadway's most
famous cads in a bitter and pungent show considered ahead of its
time when it opened in 1940. What the stage can't offer in salary,
it makes up for in quality, he said.
   ``You have to work on something,'' he said, ``and for me there
are so many lousy movie scripts that you might as soon do a decent
play than some lousy movie.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, July 4</NOTE>
