<1ST_LINE>a a BC-PersonalFile-Peltz Adv01   06-29 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Peltz, Adv 01,0814</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday July 1 and Thereafer</NOTE>
<HEAD>Peltz Uses `Junk' To Build Packaging Empire; Attention Turned
Toward Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12 of June 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the surface, Nelson Peltz might seem like
just another corporate raider.
   He got where he is today _ heading the world's largest consumer
packaging concern, Triangle Industries Inc. _ through a series of
acquisitions financed largely through the personal services of
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s junk-bond whiz, Michael Milken.
   Milken also has provided much-needed leverage for many other
takeover strategists like Carl C. Icahn, who, incidentally, lives
near Peltz in the verdant Westchester County suburbs of New York.
   But Peltz parts company from Icahn and others who sell off parts
of their newly acquired companies for quick profits and displace
many of the target company's workers.
   ``Our goal is to buy companies and build it up,'' the
46-year-old Peltz said in a recent interview. ``I invest in a
business, make it grow and make sure it competes.
   ``We don't like to strip a company ... to tear it apart.''
   Since Peltz and long-time associate Peter May gained control of
Triangle in 1983, after working for Peltz's family-owned
food-supply business in New Jersey, the company has expanded from a
copper-wire and cable manufacturer with annual sales of $264
million to a packaging giant with more than $4 billion in sales.
   In fact, most people can barely go a day without coming in
contact with a Triangle-made beer bottle, soda can, toothpaste tube
or potato chip bag.
   When Peltz took the helm at Triangle, ``The company was low in
money ... It didn't have too bright a future and needed direction.
   ``The previous management had promised to liquidate the wire and
cable division. That would have meant 1,000 people out of work. We
didn't liquidate the business. We kept it going and rebuilt it.''
   Peltz was determined to rebuild the entire company. He amassed
his packaging empire by gobbling up National Can Corp. in 1985 and
purchasing American Can Co.'s packaging business a year later.
Peltz and May are now in the process of increasing to 80 percent
their voting shares of Triangle by having a smaller subsidiary, CJI
Industries Inc., buy the parent.
   ``It's like watching a baby grow,'' he said with a touch of
pride, admitting that he'd like another addition to his business
family. ``We're always looking at all kinds of things.''
   It is with that same vision and gusto that Peltz has approached
his latest ``rebuilding'' project _ helping the nation's homeless
get back on their feet through transitional housing financed by big
business.
   Peltz was recruited more than a year ago by Tipper Gore, wife of
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, to help fund a nationwide tour
for an exhibit of photographs aimed at raising the public's
awareness of America's homeless.
   His own interest piqued, he decided to go a step further with
the building proposal.
   Such a civic-minded task might seem a bit out of character for a
wealthy industrialist like Peltz, who is used to the good things in
life: posh New York offices decorated with expensive antiques and
paintings; a private corporate chef; a large homestead outside of
New York City and a second home in Florida shared with his
former-model wife, Claudia, and four children.
   But the Brooklyn-born Peltz said he is touched by the plight of
the homeless. And besides, his keen business sense tells him that
if something isn't done now to stem this growing social problem,
big businesses will undoubtedly have to pay somewhere down the line
through higher taxes.
   ``The government clearly is not going to spend the money. I
don't know if the government is capable of doing enough,'' Peltz
said. ``They (big corporations) have to take an active role because
it's a problem we face.''
   Peltz's goal is to eventually build transitional multifamily
homes for the homeless in major U.S. cities, with each facility
housing between 30 to 40 families. He estimates each building would
cost half a million dollars.
   Although still in its fact-finding stage, Peltz has been
circulating a slick ``coffee-table'' book, based on the ``Homeless
in America'' exhibit, to big corporations to garner their support.
   Peltz has even tapped the same Washington-based lobbying group
involved in his efforts to promote high-yield, high-risk junk bonds
to further his cause. The group, National Strategies and Marketing
Group, is helping move Peltz's housing dream off the drawing board
by formulating specific plans for building and financing.
   ``No one has taken an active role in this fight. We would like
to be a catalyst,'' Peltz said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday editions, July 1</NOTE>
