<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-29 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0600</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities pros say the latest insider trading
scheme alleged by the government against a Morgan Stanley & Co.
analyst and a client raises big questions about whether Wall Street
has been properly policing itself in the aftermath of the Ivan
Boesky scandal.
   Securities lawyers and professionals say they are shocked that
Morgan trainee Stephen Wang Jr. could have obtained access to
secrets about corporate takeovers and systematically misused them.
   Washington attorney Paul Fischer said Tuesday that the scheme
``seems to suggest that even the real threat of criminal
prosecution and jail sentences isn't enough to eradicate insider
trading.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street felon Ivan F. Boesky, center of a
massive insider trading scandal, has been transferred from a U.S.
prison in California to a detention facility in New York, federal
prison officials said.
   The move immediately raised speculation that he would testify
against others implicated in the scandal, although officials said
they didn't know the exact reason for the temporary transfer.
   Boesky was moved from a minimum-security prison camp in Lompoc,
Calif., to the Metropolitan Correctional Facility in Manhattan June
23, said Joseph Fitzmaurice, a Lompoc correctional officer reached
by telephone.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The suffocating drought in mid-America is taking its toll on
scores of smaller crops _ from cherries to honey _ that could
result in huge losses for thousands of growers.
   Although the spotlight about the drought's impact has focused on
the enormous grain and livestock industries, analysts say the
drought will affect just about everything grown from the Rocky
Mountains east to Ohio.
   The result could be a change in diets and higher prices at
grocery stores, restaurants and taverns.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices plummeted by
their daily limits on the Chicago Board of Trade in a wild reversal
based on concerns that rain may fall across the Midwest and bring
relief to drought-stricken crops.
   Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
said Tuesday that talk of rain ``caused massive liquidation'' among
buyers in the corn and soybean pits who had been anticipating the
drought would continue to damage crops and tighten supplies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers are putting off buying tractors
and delaying equipment repairs because of the drought, just as farm
equipment manufacturers were beginning to enjoy a rebound from an
eight-year slump.
   Although some say it's too early to gauge the drought's impact
on the industry, others say the uncertainty comes at a bad time.
   George Dahlman, an analyst who follows the farm equipment
industry for the Minneapolis securities firm of Piper Jaffrey &
Hopwood Inc., said Tuesday that the drought will mean a significant
backwards slide for farm equipment sales but won't push
manufacturers into bankruptcy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials have extended the
negotiating deadline for Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass in his
effort to take over troubled American Savings and Loan Association,
the nation's second largest thrift.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates the S&L
industry, had announced on April 21 that it would negotiate
exclusively with the Robert M. Bass Group for a period of 75 days,
ending on July 5.
   But the bank board said the ``complexity of the transaction''
warranted the extension until Aug. 1. for the Stockton,
Calif.-based American Savings, the main unit of Financial Corp. of
America of Irvine, Calif.
</TEXT>
