<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-29 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0586</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines' parent says it has
entered an agreement to acquire Simmons Airlines, the
fourth-largest regional carrier in the country.
   AMR Corp. said Tuesday its subsidiary, AMR Eagle-Central, has
signed an agreement to purchase Chicago-based Simmons for $17.50 a
share, or a total of about $78 million.
   Under the agreement, AMR Eagle-Central will commence a cash
tender offer within five days for all of the outstanding shares of
Simmons. The board of directors of Simmons has unanimously approved
the agreement, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris USA, the nation's biggest tobacco
maker, has launched a multimillion-dollar advertising campaign
touting the economic contributions of smokers.
   The first full-page ad, placed Tuesday in 19 daily newspapers
across the country, carried the headline ``$1 trillion is too much
financial power to ignore,'' referring to the combined household
income of smokers.
   However, Irving Rimer of the American Cancer Society, said the
campaign leaves out smoking's costs to the economy _ an estimated
$65 billion a year in terms of lost productivity and treatment of
smoking-related diseases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican senators have won several minor
amendments to a plant closing notification bill but appeared unable
to stop a Democratic juggernaut for putting the legislation on
President Reagan's desk by July 4.
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., promised his colleagues
an extended Fourth of July holiday lasting all next week if they
vote on final passage before recessing Wednesday.
   But he vowed to bring back the senators _ one-third of them up
for re-election and eager to spend next week campaigning in their
home states _ on July 6 if Republicans delay a final vote until
after the Independence Day break.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of new construction projects rose 9
percent in May, reversing a declining trend.
   But the improvement, which translated to an annualized $246.4
billion in new construction projects, was dominated by a cluster of
major, non-building projects, said the F.W. Dodge Division of
McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
   General construction activity, which includes housing and
commercial buildings, was up only slightly from the previous month
and still held below last year's levels, according to Tuesday's
report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motown Records, the company that boosted such
black singers as Michael Jackson and Stevie Wonder to stardom, has
been sold to MCA Inc. and an investment banking firm for $61
million.
   The long-rumored purchase of the nation's best-known black-owned
business gives MCA the Motown record label, Motown spokeswoman
Rosalind Stevenson said Tuesday.
   Berry Gordy Jr., the former Detroit autoworker who built the
label into a huge force in pop music, retains the company's sheet
music and film businesses, Ms. Stevenson said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a rally in subdued trading Tuesday. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 34.50 points on Monday,
rebounded 22.41 to 2,130.87.
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen but as
restrained against European currencies by the dollar sales of
central banks. Gold prices fell to their lowest levels since early
March.
   Corn and soybean futures prices fell by their daily limits due
to a forecast for rain and possible relief for drought-stricken
crops.
   Bond prices advanced broadly. Yields on the bellwether 30-year
Treasury bond fell to 8.85 percent from 8.96 percent late Monday.
</TEXT>
