<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-29 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Futures Higher In Dull Energy Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracts for unleaded gasoline, spurred by the
summer driving season, posted the only gains in an otherwise dull
oil market.
   While contracts for other products fell on Tuesday, the July
contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.48 to 51.53 cents a gallon.
Most longer term contracts were lower, however.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, fell 8 cents to $15.78 per barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Among other refined products traded on the exchange, the July
contract for home heating oil slipped 0.28 cent to 42.31 cents a
gallon.
   Traders said activity was somewhat dull on Tuesday. ``There's
not a whole lot going on,'' said William Byers of futures research
at Bear Stearns & Co.
   The gains posted in near-term contracts for unleaded gasoline
are typical of the summer driving season, particularly ahead of the
long Independence Day weekend, traders said.
   ``This is a gas-oriented market,'' said Madison Galbraith, a
trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Galbraith also said traders were awaiting the release of the
latest statistics from the American Petroleum Institute, issued
after the market closed, to see if supplies had declined enough to
justify the rising price in the near-term gasoline contract.
   The API report showed a larger-than-expected drop in gasoline
stocks, and a decline in crude oil stocks.
   Among other contracts, traders noted there was a late wave of
profit-taking that brought both crude and heating oil down shortly
before the market closed.
   ``People don't see what will happen to make the market go up,
but they're not overwhelmingly negative, either,'' Byers said.
</TEXT>
