<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MotownSale     06-29 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Motown Sale,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pop Music Powerhouse of '60s and '70s sold to MCA Inc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motown Records, which launched the careers of
such singers as Diana Ross, Michael Jackson and Stevie Wonder and
won a huge and enduring white audience for black pop music, has
been sold to a unit of entertainment conglomerate MCA Inc.
   The $61 million deal announced Tuesday gives MCA Records the
famed Motown label and rights to a string of hit songs dating back
to the early 1960s, such as ``I Heard it Through the Grapevine''
and ``Baby Love.''
   MCA also will assume Motown's current recording contracts with
such stars as Lionel Richie, Smokey Robinson and Wonder.
   Berry Gordy Jr., the former Detroit auto worker who founded
Motown and built it into what was once the nation's biggest
black-owned business, retains the company's sheet music and film
divisions, said Motown spokeswoman Rosalind Stevenson.
   MCA Inc. put up 20 percent of the purchase price and Boston
Ventures, an investment banking firm, will supply the remainder,
Ms. Stevenson said. The deal calls for MCA to buy out Boston
Ventures' share in the future, she said.
   MCA officials announced the long-rumored deal had been completed
but refused to discuss the terms. Ms. Stevenson and another source
familiar with the talks who refused to be identified confirmed the
$61 million purchase price.
   ``In today's economy, the big get bigger and the small get
extinct,'' Gordy said, explaining the necessity for the sale in
Tuesday's editions of the entertainment paper Daily Variety.
   ``In order to prevent that from happening, and to ensure the
perpetuation of Motown and its heritage, I decided to clasp hands
with one of the most formidable giants in our business, MCA,''
Gordy said.
   In the 1960s, Motown, named for its ``Motor Town'' roots in
Detroit, discovered and molded a lineup of black recording artists
and churned out a line of songs that topped pop charts for both
black and white audiences.
   For many, the harmonies and images of Motown's acts are woven
into the cultural backdrop of the 1960s: Diana Ross and the
Supremes singing ``Baby Love,'' ``Love Child'' and ``Stop! In the
Name of Love;'' the Temptations' ``My Girl;'' the Four Tops' ``I
Can't Help Myself;'' and Marvin Gaye's ``I Heard it Through the
Grapevine.''
   Michael Jackson began his musical career with Motown as a child
member of the Jackson Five.
   Wonder, whose hits on Motown-allied labels include the 1973
chart-toppers ``Superstition'' and ``You Are the Sunshine of My
Life,'' agreed to stay on under MCA before the sale went through,
said the source familiar with the negotiations.
   Diana Ross, who in her solo career has recorded with RCA, signed
with MCA previous to the deal and will return to the Motown label,
Ms. Stevenson said.
   Gordy formed Motown in 1960 and moved it to Los Angles 1971.
Gordy, who worked as talent scout, arranger and producer, ran the
company like a stern father, demanding loyalty and also encouraging
his performers to finish high school, though he made it only
through 11th grade.
   Privately-owned Motown was the nation's most visible black
business and at one time its biggest. Last year, Motown was the
nation's fifth-largest black owned business, with $100 million in
sales, according to Black Enterprise magazine.
   Without specifying how it would be done, MCA and Boston Ventures
said they ``have provided an opportunity for continued black
ownership in the company.''
   Gordy retains Motown's sheet music arm, Jobete Music Co., and
its film and television arm, Motown Productions, which will be
known as The Gordy Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Congress-Transportation     06-29 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Transportation,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Debates $10.8 Billion Transportation Spending Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: House debate resumes at 10 a.m. EDT; time for final passage
uncertain. A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House is moving toward final passage of a
bill providing $10.8 billion in new spending for the government's
transportation programs for fiscal 1989, despite a Reagan
administration veto threat.
   Approval of the legislation was expected today, even though
administration officials say rejection of the measure by President
Reagan is possible because it is too expensive.
   The legislation would provide $2 billion above the amount Reagan
requested for transportation programs for the fiscal year that
begins Oct. 1, and $182 million over the amount provided for this
year. It contains large increases for the Federal Aviation
Administration and the Coast Guard.
   The bill would also allow the government to spend up to an
additional $15.4 billion out of revenues collected each year
specifically for aviation, highway and mass transit programs.
   As usual, the bill also contains a number of highway projects
and other items aimed at particular districts.
   Altogether, the measure would allow $3.1 billion in spending for
the Coast Guard, a 16 percent increase over 1988 levels. At least
$492 million would have to be spent on drug interdiction efforts.
   The Federal Aviation Administration would be entitled to spend
more than $6.6 billion, 15 percent more than this year. Most of the
money would be for the salaries of air traffic controllers and
other workers, new equipment such as radar, and grants to airports
for construction.
   Amtrak, the federally subsidized passenger railroad, would
receive $590 million and mass transit programs would get $3.3
billion.
   It was for those programs that lawmakers differed most radically
from Reagan's proposed budget. The president wanted to terminate
all federal aid to Amtrak, which expects to carry 34 million
passengers next year, and provide mass transit programs with barely
half the amount the House approved.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee approved a $10.6 billion
version of the bill last Friday. When the full Senate passes that
legislation, the two chambers will have to agree to a compromise
bill before it is sent to Reagan for his signature.
   When debate on the House bill began Tuesday, lawmakers removed
provisions that might have blocked federal aid to Boston's Logan
International Airport.
   Officials at Logan plan to increase landing fees July 1 for
small aircraft, which they say would reduce delays for airline
passengers by encouraging private and commuter planes to use nearby
airfields. The program is supported by Boston-area legislators.
   Opponents inserted a provision that would have withheld federal
assistance to Logan until the Department of Transportation
completes an investigation of Logan's plan, and until the courts
rule on challenges filed by small aircraft industry groups.
   The provision was removed on procedural grounds, however, after
Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, D-Mass., complained that by House rules,
it should not have been included in a spending bill. Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif., who was presiding over the House at the time,
upheld Kennedy's objection. There was no vote.
   Similar provisions blocking aid to Logan remain in the Senate
version of the transportation bill.
   The House bill would also attempt to block a private developer's
plans to build a shopping mall in Manassas, Va., on part of what
was the scene of the Second Battle of Bull Run, a Confederate
victory during the Civil War. The provision, introduced by Civil
War buff Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., would forbid the government to
approve the construction of exits from highways that serve the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
