<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Penney-Ayres     06-29 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penney-Ayres,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney Purchases Former Ayres Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. has purchased the three
suburban Cincinnati stores vacated earlier this month by L.S. Ayres
& Co., a move that Penney says will double its presence in the
Cincinnati area.
   ``Cincinnati has long represented a really stable economic
market, the kind of market that has been good for J.C. Penney,''
Hank Rusman, a Penney's spokesman, said Tuesday.
   Agreement on the sale was reached Tuesday between Penney and May
Department Stores Co., Ayres' parent company. Terms of the sale
were not disclosed.
   May officials shut the three suburban stores June 6 after the
downtown Ayres store was closed in April. Ayres has 14 other stores
in Indiana.
   Dallas-based Penney also announced it will close its 68-year-old
store in Hamilton this fall shortly before the three suburban
stores are expected to open.
   All displaced employees will be offered jobs in Penney's new
stores, which the company said will employ an estimated 400 people.
</TEXT>
