<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 0852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMMoves     06-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Moves,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Executive Reshuffling Helps Prepare New Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith says a
major reshuffling of top-level management will help train and
prepare a new generation to run the world's largest automaker in
the next century.
   Smith announced promotions Tuesday of more than a dozen top
executives, including three new executive vice presidents, in the
wake of Monday's resignation of Elmer Johnson, a GM director and
executive vice president in charge of GM's operating, legal and
public affairs staffs.
   Johnson, a rare high-level outsider who joined GM just five
years ago, once was considered a contender to replace Smith when
the chairman retires in 1990.
   Smith said Tuesday GM had been planning the moves for more than
a year but accelerated the changes when Johnson resigned. Smith
disputed reports that Johnson was frustrated in efforts to lighten
GM's ponderous bureaucracy and in his ambition to succeed Smith.
   The moves, which widened the pool of Smith's potential
successors, affected 14 GM executives.
   ``We have elected three new executive vice presidents which we
think will significantly strengthen our organization and prepare us
better for the 21st century as we move forward,'' Smith said.
   ``One of our corporation's greatest strengths has been the depth
of our people ... but people always need broader assignments,
different training,'' he said.
   Smith also announced the formation of the new Power Products and
Defense Operations Group, which will centralize direction of
several non-automotive divisions that build diesel and locomotive
engines and defense vehicles.
   Johnson's executive assignments were divided among several top
executives, but he was not replaced on the board of directors.
   The three new executive vice presidents are William E. Hoglund,
53; John F. Smith Jr., 50; and Robert T. O'Connell, 49.
   Hoglund, who was vice president and group executive in charge of
GM's Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac Group, is now in charge of GM's
Automotive Components Groups and the new Power Products and Defense
Operations Group.
   ``It's just a typical round of management changes,'' said Chris
Cedergren, analyst with J.D. Power and Associates in Agoura Hills,
Calif.
   ``(Hoglund) did a really fine job in that particular area. I'm
kind of saddened, because I like to see people who are real good in
the car business stay in the business.''
   But, Cedergren said, in order to move up, Hoglund and others
``have to go through the various ranks and various divisions.''
   ``It's kind of interesting because it widens the field up a
little bit and falls in line with a strategy GM used to have that
they have three people to replace any key job,'' said analyst
Thomas O'Grady, a former GM economist.
   Hoglund is succeeded in his old job by J.T. Battenberg III, 45,
who was manager of the B-O-C Flint Automotive Division and is now a
vice president.
   John Smith, who was a GM vice president and president of General
Motors Europe, is now in charge of all GM overseas operations _ the
first time GM has had an executive vice president whose sole
responsibility is overseas business, the primary source of GM's
1987 profits.
   Smith is succeeded as president of GM Europe by Robert J. Eaton,
48, a vice president and group executive of GM's Technical Staffs
Group.
   The responsibilities of O'Connell, who was vice president and
group executive of GM's Finance Group, were expanded with his new
title. He now also is in charge of General Motors Acceptance Corp.,
GM's lending arm.
   Two of Johnson's executive assignments were given to F. Alan
Smith, 57, who had been the executive vice president in charge of
the Finance Group and GMAC. Smith is now in charge of GM's
operating and public affairs staffs.
   Other executives were moved up to fill vacancies left by the
promotions.
</TEXT>
