<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Singapore-Economy     06-29 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Singapore-Economy,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore Economy To Remain Fairly Strong: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singapore's economy will probably maintain its
8 percent annual growth rate this year despite problems posed by
labor shortages, according to a U.S. Embassy report released
Wednesday.
   The nation's economy is dependent on foreign trade and continues
to recover due to strong export demand in the United States and
other industrialized countries, the report said.
   The economy stumbled into recession in 1985 and partially
recovered with a 1.8 percent growth rate in 1986, which surged to
8.8 percent last year.
   Domestic demand, an increase in tourism and the recovery of the
neighboring Indonesian and Malaysian economies boosted the island's
trade and economic growth last year, according to the embassy
report.
   But ``despite a favorable demand outlook for Singapore's goods
and services for the rest of 1988, persistent labor shortages are
causing many manufacturers to consider delaying new investment
projects,'' the report said.
   ``The outlook for the economy beyond 1988 depends heavily on the
health of Singapore's trading partners,'' it said. ``Global
economic uncertainties, the threat of protectionism and strained
political relations could cloud Singapor's investment climate.''
</TEXT>
