<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-29 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0272</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today in a bid to
extend Tuesday's rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.87 to 2,136.74 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 557 up, 331 down and
505 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.88 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said the market continued to benefit from expectations
of a continuing rally by the dollar in foreign exchange.
   A steady to stronger dollar would presumably attract money from
overseas investors to both stocks and bonds traded in the United
States.
   Worries over upward pressure on commodity prices eased,
meanwhile, after Tuesday's rain in much of the Midwest.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up ~ at 127~; DuPont, up { at 91[; American Telephone &
Telegraph, up [ at 26~, and General Electric, up [ at 43{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.33 to 154.10. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .09 at 308.51.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 22.41 to
2,130.87.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 966 up, 515 down and 482 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 152.37 million shares, against 264.41 million Monday, when
the total was inflated by dividend-related activity in several
high-yielding issues.
</TEXT>
