<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Citicorp-FirstRepublic     06-29 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citicorp-First Republic,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First RepublicBank's Restructuring Plan Best, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp. has told shareholders it
will suffer another substantial loss in the current quarter because
the Texas real estate market has not bottomed out.
   Meanwhile, the bank holding company was waiting to see if it
would receive a buyout bid from Citicorp. First RepublicBank
Chairman Albert Casey said Citicorp might submit a restructuring
plan for the company with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   ``(Citicorp) won't tell me if they're going to submit (a
proposal),'' First RepublicBank Chairman Albert Casey said.
   First RepublicBank submitted its own restructuring proposal June
9. The deadline for submission of a proposal is Thursday, and Casey
said the FDIC should select a plan shortly after July 8.
   A First RepublicBank internal memo distributed Monday indicated
Citicorp officials were examining First RepublicBank's books and
financial condition. Citicorp officials declined to comment on
whether they plan to purchase First RepublicBank, the state's
largest bank holding company.
   Citicorp, which held $203 billion of assets at March 31, earned
$358 million during the first quarter of 1988. Citicorp lost $1.14
billion in 1987, largely as the result of large provision for
possible losses on its $12.9 billion portfolio of Latin American
loans.
   First RepublicBank lost $1.5 billion in the first quarter,
prompting a $1 billion bailout earlier this year from the FDIC. The
company has been hit by a string of real estate loans that turned
sour.
   ``The complete disappearance of the real estate market was
unforeseen by anybody,'' Casey said in discussing the company's
problems.
   ``On the second (quarter), we're going to continue to record
further losses,'' Casey said. ``Those losses are primarily made up
of additional loan loss provisions and reductions in the assets by
reasons of continuing new appraisals of the collateral. Both of
those items are still hitting us.''
   Hundreds of loan reappraisals now under way made it impossible
for him to estimate second quarter results in dollar figures,
although the loss would be less than the first quarter, he said.
   ``We have not bottomed out in the real estate market yet, as far
as I can tell,'' Casey said.
   Under First RepublicBank's reorganization proposal, shareholders
would be compensated with a modest but as-yet undetermined amount
of stock in the bank that emerged from the restructuring, Casey
said.
   Casey said a First RepublicBank plan will seek to repay the
FDIC's $1 billion loan.
   If First RepublicBank's reorganization plan is accepted, it
would file registration papers for new securities offerings with
the Securities and Exchange Commission in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
