<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Rubber     06-29 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rubber,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Forecasts Rubber Deficit, Due Partly To AIDS Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World consumption of natural rubber is expected to
grow much faster than production in 1988, leading to the biggest
deficit this decade, the International Rubber Study Group said
Wednesday.
   The producer-consumer statistical group put consumption at a
record 4.935 million metric tons in 1988, which would be 140,000
tons more than the forecast for record production of 4.795 million.
   Last year, consumption exceeded production by 55,000 tons. The
group also is projecting a deficit of 125,000 tons for 1989, based
on a production forecast of 4.965 million and consumption of 5.090
million.
   Traders said the increasing shortfall in world supplies has
pushed average world natural rubber prices up to their highest
level for about eight years, with the latex grade trading at record
levels of above $1,000 a ton.
   Demand for latex, which is used for surgical gloves and condoms,
has been stimulated by the AIDS crisis, analysts said. ``Dentists
now more and more use a new pair of rubber-dipped gloves for every
patient examined,'' said one analyst.
</TEXT>
