<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoIncentives     06-29 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Incentives,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugo Maker Offering Incentives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugo American said starting today it is offering
buyers almost a dollar back on every $5 spent on the country's
lowest priced car.
   Yugo American President William E. Prior said buyers will
receive $750, either in cash or toward down payments on the
Yugoslavian-made automobiles.
   That is a 17 percent rebate on the basic $4,349 Yugo GV and 16
percent on the $4,599 GVL version.
   ``Certainly there are lots of rebates out there. But we
certainly maintain an edge,'' Yugo spokeswoman Fran Jacobs said
said from headquarters in Upper Saddle River, N.J. ``We think it's
a wonderful way to relaunch.''
   Sales of the Yugo, which climbed after introduction in the
United States in August 1985 at a base price of $3,990, have sagged
this year.
   Yugo reported selling 2,510 cars in May, a 39 percent drop from
4,111 a year ago. For the year through May 31, the company sold
14,531 cars, down 35 percent from 22,272 in the first five months
of 1987.
