<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PlantClosing 1stLd-Writethru f0020 06-29 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0761</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new, subbing for top 3 grafs pvs, to UPDATE with
vote on ending debate; DELETES grafs 7-8 pvs: bgng: ``Democratic
leaders ...''; Picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: Byrd had ...; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans today thwarted an initial
attempt by supporters of mandatory advance notice of layoffs and
plant closings to force a showdown with the Reagan administration
before the Democratic National Convention.
   On a 58-39 largely party-line vote, the Senate refused to bring
to a halt six days of debate on the measure, which President Reagan
cited last month as his primary reason for vetoing a massive
overhaul of the nation's trade laws. Sixty votes are necessary to
cut off Senate debate on a bill.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., acknowledged the
setback even before falling two votes short of the number needed to
end debate, telling reporters that Republicans intend to ``drag
this thing on awhile.''
   However, Byrd said he would call lawmakers back into session on
July 6 instead of giving them all next week off to campaign for
re-election in their home states if Democrats do not win final
Senate passage of the bill tonight.
   GOP opponents concede that Congress will pass the legislation,
but they are trying to deny Democrats possible victory on a
congressional override of an expected veto from Reagan before the
Democratic convention opens July 18 in Atlanta.
   The bill would require employers of 150 people or more to give
60 days advance notice to both workers and local community
officials before closing a plant or laying off 50 people or more.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said Tuesday he could
not explain all the myriad amendments Republicans have offered to
the bill in six days of debate on the Senate floor.
   ``I don't know precisely what's happening myself; it's not a
requirement around here,'' he said. ``But I know what the game plan
is on the other side and it's to get a bill passed before the
Democratic National Convention.''
   Byrd had planned to adjourn the Senate today, giving the House
an opportunity to act on it Thursday before it recesses. That would
give Reagan just 10 working days to veto the bill, enabling an
override attempt the week before the Democratic convention.
   ``It's hard-ball politics,'' said Dole. ``I'm not sure of its
importance beyond that.''
   With recent polls showing that more than 80 percent of Americans
favor early notices, Democrats and union leaders are more confident
of winning the three Senate votes they lacked last month to
override Reagan's veto then.
   Dole won an amendment Tuesday exempting businesses affected by
the drought that is parching most of the Farm Belt and other
natural disasters from having to provide the early layoff notices.
   ``I don't think we ought to get carried away by the demands from
organized labor,'' he said. ``If we're serious about alleviating
the effects of the drought on the economy, then we ought not to be
hitting businesses with both barrels.''
   The Senate unanimously approved Dole's amendment after farm
state lawmakers said they have been told by bakeries, flour mills
and meatpacking, poultry, egg, ethanol and farm equipment plants
they anticipate future layoffs because of the drought.
   Also approved Tuesday were four amendments offered by
Republicans _ including one to exempt employers from having to give
60-day layoff notices to strikers who have been replaced.
   Rejected was an amendment to extend that exemption to
non-strikers whose jobs might be lost from a plant closing or
layoff resulting from a strike. Also rejected was an amendment
limiting the layoff notices only to workers losing their jobs as a
result of a hostile corporate takeover.
   Fulfilling a promise to the nation's labor leaders, top
Democracts have agreed to delay final congressional action on a
revised trade bill until after first acting on the plant closing
and layoff notices.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, a chief author of the trade
measure, said Tuesday he doesn't anticipate that Senate action on
it until August _ after Congress has had a chance to override
Reagan's expected veto of the plant-closing bill but before the
Republican National Convention.
   Without a separate plant-closing law, AFL-CIO officials have
vowed to withdraw what backers of the trade bill agree is organized
labor's pivotal support for it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
