<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-29 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Plummet As Rain Spreads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
dramatically lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, weakened by
the spread of steady rains over much of the drought-stricken Farm
Belt.
   ``Basically, you're seeing a very sudden shift from very dry
conditions to a cooler, rainier situation,'' said Walter Spilka, an
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Most contracts for future delivery of corn, oats and soybeans
plunged their daily limits at the opening.
   But the limits on contracts for July delivery of grains and
soybeans were routinely removed today pending the expiration of
those contracts in three weeks.
   Without limits, prices for July delivery went into a free-fall,
despite forecasts for another month of hot, dry weather in the
Midwest.
   The July contracts expire at noon on July 20.
   The Agriculture Department, in its daily weather update, said
cooler temperatures and some additional showers were expected for
the region through Thursday.
   In early trading, wheat was 14 cents to 23\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.50 a bushel; corn was 14\ cents
to 22{ cents lower with July at $3.15 a bushel; oats were 15 cents
to 38 cents lower with July at $3.25 a bushel; soybeans were 45
cents to 74{ cents lower with July at $9.40 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were 1.50 cents lower to .40 cent higher with August
at 65.02 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to 1.50
cents higher with August at 74.55 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50
cents lower to .43 cent higher with July at 46 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies werer .90 cent to 2 cents lower with July at
36.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
