<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DefenseProbe-Congress 2ndLd-Writethru f0066 06-29 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Congress, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0066,0885</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Procurement Chief Blames ``One Word _ Greed''
^EDs: Subs lead and adds new graf 7 to include Costello ``greed''
quote; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's top procurement official said
today the criminal investigation into fraud and bribery in weapons
buying arises from ``one word _ greed'' but he said the probe shows
the strength _ not the weaknesses _ of Reagan administration
defense policies.
   ``So, if we have accomplished so much, why have there been so
many cases of procurement fraud?'' Robert B. Costello asked at a
packed hearing of the House Armed Services Committee. ``Is there
more corruption now?''
   ``We don't think so. Due to our improvements we can conduct
viable enforcement to apprehend, prosecute and jail procurement
fraud perpetrators,'' he answered.
   Added the witness:
   ``We are firmly committed to insuring the integrity of the
acquisition process and are continually improving it. Our
acquisition system works. Otherwise, we wouldn't be able to
identify persons who attempt to circumvent it. They may elude us
for a while, but in the end, we will prevail.''
   Costell is the undersecretary of defense for acquisition and
oversees the vast Pentagon purchasing system.
   When Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the panel, asked
Costello why ``we're seeing this case now,'' Costello answered,
``in one word _ greed.''
   The hearing was the first formal meeting of a congressional
committee to review the Pentagon acquisition since the ongoing
investigation became public two weeks ago.
   An hour before today's session started, well over 100 people
were lined up along the corridors in hopes of getting into the
hearing room.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee will also hold hearings into
military purchasing starting next month, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
chairman of the panel, said Tuesday.
   Neither committee's hearings will delve into the current
criminal investigation so as not to interfere with it. Prosecutor
Henry Hudson says has said it may not be before the end of the year
until indictments are returned.
   The probe focuses on allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former military men, bribed Pentagon
officials for contracting details.
   Costello declined to discuss specifics of the current case, but
said, ``we cannot and will not tolerate illegal acts that undermine
the department's acquisition process.''
   ``As the investigation's results become available, we will take
all appropriate actions, on a case by case basis,'' Costello said.
``But let's not judge suspects in an ongoing investigation through
innuendo. Let's await the facts and allow the investigators, our
administrative processes, and the courts to do their jobs.''
   He said the Pentagon has taken a number of steps to improve the
way its billions of dollars are spent.
   ``We have substantially improved the acquisition system,'' he
said, outlining a series of steps, including more reviews of
contracts, more use of commercial products rather than products
designed specifically for the military and increased competition.
   ``Although not part of the acquisition system, our enforcement
agencies contribute as much to the acqusition system as the Defense
Acqusition Board or the Defense Logistics Agency,'' he said.
   Aspin noted that the investigation involves about 85 contractors
worth tens of billions of dollars and warned that those contracts
may be compromised.
   ``This uncertainty raises a number of critical legal issues that
_ until resolved _ will cloud the day-to-day operations of the DoD
acquisition system,'' said Aspin.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., noted that Congress has tried
to reform the Pentagon procurement system for years.
   ``Quite frankly,'' he told Costello, ``many of us are
disappointed to see defense procurement problems again in the
headlines. In fact, many in Congres and much of the public at large
are more than disappointed, they are tired of hearing about a
defense acqusition systems that cannot seem to iron out its
systemic problems.''
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, which will conduct its own hearings next month, said
Tuesay that ``I think we need to look at the procurement process.
We have to re-examine it to find out where it can be improved.''
   ``But we don't want to interfere with the current
investigation,'' he said. ``We've got to get to the systemic part
of the procurement problem and correct that, but we should not use
those problems to excuse pure old fraud, waste and greed.''
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger believes there's no
way to insure against fraud and he said he doesn't feel bad about
the current situation.
   Appearing Sunday on ABC-TV, Weinberger said even his working
every day ``cannot guarantee that there's going to be a total,
complete, 100 percent honesty in the chain of people ... I don't
have any basis whatever for saying I didn't do enough, and I
certainly don't feel culpable.''
   No changes in Pentagon policy have yet been proposed in
Congress, but several plans are likely to be offered.
   For example, Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., a frequent critic of
current Pentagon spending practices, has said he may try again to
win approval of a law which he says would restrict the so-called
``revolving door'' between government and private sector employment.
</TEXT>
