<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GM-TruckProduction     06-29 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM-Truck Production,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM to Move Certain Light-Duty Truck Production to Flint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Only version planned.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. announced Wednesday that
some light-duty truck production will be moved from Janesville,
Wis., to Flint, Mich., to make way for production of a new
medium-duty truck in Janesville.
   GM said production of cab chassis and crew cab models will move
in the spring of 1989 from Janesville's Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac
Group plant to the Flint Truck & Bus plant.
   The car line at Janesville is unaffected by the change. In
Flint, the trucks will be assembled on one shift, GM said in a
written statement.
   Approximately 650 Flint assembly employees are expected to be
recalled from layoff when the move takes place. About 300 of those
recalled will be laid off when cab chassis production ends,
probably in December 1989, the company said. Crew cab production is
expected to continue through the 1992 model year.
   In Janesville, employees building the components will be laid
off temporarily during the plant's retooling for medium-duty trucks.
</TEXT>
