<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground today after an
early advance faded.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up about 7 points in
the early going, was down 10.32 at 2,120.55 by 3 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 9 to 5 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 501 up, 952
down and 499 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders still were expecting a continuing rally by
the dollar in foreign exchange. A steady to stronger dollar would
presumably attract money from overseas investors to both stocks and
bonds traded in the United States.
   Worries over upward pressure on commodity prices eased,
meanwhile, after Tuesday's rain in much of the Midwest.
   However, the bond market turned in an uninspired showing today,
leaving interest rates slightly higher on the day.
   Brokers said many investors were reluctant to chase after stocks
at levels near the high point of the range in which they have
fluctuated since the crash last fall.
   Pullman Co. jumped 1} to 7~ in active trading. The company said
top executives were considering a proposal to acquire the company
for $7.50 a share.
   Losers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, down ~ at 52{;
General Electric, down { at 42~; DuPont, down ~ at 89}, and Philip
Morris, down \ at 83}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.83 to 152.94. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.39 at 307.03.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 134.57 million shares with an
hour to go.
