<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pennzoil-Tenneco     06-29 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennzoil-Tenneco,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennzoil Considering Buying Tenneco Oil and Gas Division</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Randal in 5th graf is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co., cash-rich after receiving a $3
billion settlement from Texaco Inc., is eyeing the oil and gas
operations being sold by neighboring Tenneco Inc., a Pennzoil
spokesman said Wednesday.
   Tenneco, headquartered a few blocks from Pennzoil's main office
in downtown Houston, announced in May that it would sell off its
Tenneco Oil Co. division, which includes vast oil and gas
properties and refining and marketing divisions, to reduce its $8.5
billion debt. Analysts said the division could fetch $5 billion to
$7 billion.
   A Pennzoil spokesman said the company has not yet requested any
information in preparation for making a bonafide offer for Tenneco
Oil.
   ``We haven't gotten anywhere near that point yet,'' spokesman
Robert G. Harper said. ``We're looking at a number of investment
situations. Since Tenneco has put its oil operation on the market,
that's one of those we're looking at. We're kind of analyzing the
situation.''
   Harper downplayed a report quoting Pennzoil Chairman Randal
McDonald as saying the company is interested in buying Tenneco Oil
and would use the $3 billion legal settlement from its protracted
legal battle with Texaco.
   McDonald was quoted as saying the company is looking at the
Tenneco assets but has not decided if it will make a bid.
   Tenneco has received a number of quieries on the properties,
company officials said.
   Analysts have speculated that Pennzoil probably doesn't have the
financing to buy all of Tenneco Oil, although it could combine with
one or more partners or make a limited bid for some of the
company's producing properties.
   McDonald said the company is particularly interested in oil and
gas properties but would consider buying everything, including the
refining and marketing division.
   Pennzoil received a $3 billion payment from Texaco as settlement
for a lawsuit in which Texaco was ruled to have interfered with
Pennzoil's plan to buy oil and gas properties held by Getty Oil Co.
</TEXT>
