<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-29 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Dramatically Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed dramatically
lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as showers in the
drought-stricken Farm Belt spurred some of the steepest losses in
exchange history.
   Most contracts for future deliveries of corn, oats and soybeans
plunged their daily limits at the opening.
   But the limits on contracts for July delivery of grains and
soybeans were routinely removed Wednesday pending the July 20
expiration of those contracts. Without limits, prices for July
delivery went into a free fall, despite forecasts for another month
of hot, dry weather in the Midwest.
   July soybeans closed 85{ cents a bushel below Tuesday's
settlement price while all other soybean contracts were limited to
losses of 45 cents. July corn plunged 29{ cents a bushel and July
oats dropped 33 cents. Other corn and oat contracts were permitted
to fall only 15 cents.
   ``It was just panic liquidation,'' said Jay Homan, an
independent oat trader.
   Mario Balletto, soybean analyst with Merrill Lynch Captial
Markets Inc. in New York, said the markets had overreacted to the
rain.
   ``You always see some rain somewhere in the middle of a
drought,'' he said. ``But everybody wants it to be bone dry or else
they get nervous.''
   At the close, wheat was 17 cents to 19\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.54 a bushel; corn was 15 cents
to 29{ cents lower with July at $3.08 a bushel; oats were 14 cents
to 33 cents lower with July at $3.30 a bushel; soybeans were 29\
cents to 85{ cents lower with July at $9.29 a bushel.
</TEXT>
