<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InsiderTrading-Lee Bjt   06-29 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading-Lee, Bjt,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insider Trading Suspect Said to Be Well-Connected Taiwanese
Businessman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of making millions on
insider trading in the United States is said to be a rich Taiwanese
socialite divorcee with a doctorate degree, a penchant for buddhism
and a history of stock-dabbling.
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filed a civil
complaint Monday accusing Fred C. Lee of making $19 million by
trading on tips about impending corporate takeovers given by a
junior analyst at the Morgan Stanley and Co. brokerage firm,
Stephen Wang Jr.
   Wall Street and SEC sources in the United States have described
Lee, 38, as a wealthy member of a Taiwanese family who had several
trading and bank accounts, interests in real estate, import-export
operations and public utilities. He has homes in Hong Kong and
McLean, Va., a Washington suburb.
   Taiwan newspapers identified the man as Lee Chuan-hong and said
he was a major investor in the Taiwan stock market several years
ago.
   The mass-circulation China Times reported Wednesday that Lee's
``contacts with high-leval political and financial circles made him
somewhat famous. Lee himself and his story are legendary.''
   The mass-circulation United Daily News said Lee's acquaintances
included Tsiang Yien-si, former secretary general of Taiwan's
ruling Nationalist Party, and former Taipei mayor Yang Ching-tsun.
It did not elaborate on the nature of the relationships.
   An official at the government-run Taiwan Power Co., speaking on
condition of anonymity, confirmed that Lee Chuan-hong has been a
director of the utility since 1978. A City Bank of Taipei official,
also requesting anonymity, told The Associated Press that Lee had
previously been on the bank's board.
   Lee became general manager of the Taiwan Tea Corp. in 1984 but
quit two years later, telling friends and associates he wanted to
preach Buddhism in the United States, newspapers said. He
reportedly has returned to the United States only on rare occasions
since.
   An account in the Wall Street Journal quoted unidentified
acquaintances of Lee as saying he enjoyed dabbling in the Hong Kong
and Taipei stock markets, where insider trading is believed to be
widespread.
   The acquaintances also were quoted as describing Lee as a ``bon
vivant'' divorced father of two, who held largely honorary
positions on the boards of some prominent Taiwan businesses.
   Lee attended elementary school and college in Taiwan, but went
to post-graduate school in the United States. In June 1983, he
received a doctorate in education policy and management from the
University of Oregon in Eugene, according to Gunvor McWilliams, an
official of the school's registrar office.
   Other elements of Lee's background remain unclear. While he was
apparently well known among business and political circles in
Taiwan, he wasn't prominent in Hong Kong, according to press
accounts there.
   The SEC has been investigating Lee's trading activities for some
time, but it was when the commission's attorneys interviewed him in
Hong Kong last Friday that a break in the investigation came,
according to SEC officials. After denying he knew Wang, Lee
admitted using information supplied by Wang to profit from stocks,
SEC documents show.
   In Hong Kong, U.S. Consulate spokesman Daniel Sreebny said
Wednesday he had no information on Lee. The local branch of Morgan
Stanley also said they knew nothing of the businessman.
   No reports have surfaced indicating Lee has left Hong Kong.
   Michael Perlis, Lee's attorney, said in a telephone interview
from his San Francisco office on Wednesday that Lee was either in
Hong Kong or Taiwan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880629-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 1543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy Bjt   06-29 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Off, But Economists Unfazed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday its chief
economic forecasting gauge dipped slightly in May, the first
setback since January, but analysts shrugged off the tiny downturn
as no threat to prospects for the rest of the year.
   The Commerce Department reported a 0.1 percent decline last
month in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, primarily
reflecting weakness in the stock market, manufacturing orders and
the labor market. But at the same time, the department revised
upward, from 0.2 percent to 0.5 percent, the gain it had initially
reported for April.
   Economists dismissed the May estimate's small decline, the first
since a 0.2 percent decrease in January, and said it did nothing to
shake their belief that growth would continue at least through the
remainder of 1988 with no danger of recession.
   ``This tiny one-month decline in the leading index will likely
turn out to be an isolated event. The message is that we have an
economy that should be expanding throughout 1988 and into 1989,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co.
   In a second report Wednesday, the Commerce Department said that
new home sales edged down a small 0.3 percent in May to an annual
sales rate of 658,000 units. While it was the first drop in sales
since January, analysts said the decrease was so tiny it indicated
that demand for homes was holding firm despite increases in
mortgage rates.
   Analysts said the June leading index figure, from what is
already known about the performance of the economy during the
month, should show a resumption of the string of gains.
   The current economic expansion is in its 67th month, a record
for peacetime. While many analysts originally feared that the
economy could topple into a recession following the October stock
market collapse, they have jettisoned those forecasts in light of
stronger-than-expected growth in the first three months of the year.
   The Reagan administration last week issued a revised forecast
predicting that the overall economy, as measured by the gross
national product, will climb 3 percent this year, a significant
revision from the administration's original 2.4 percent GNP
forecast made at the beginning of the year.
   This estimate is in line with the expectations of many private
economists who now say that the stock market downturn had no impact
on the real economy.
   ``We are expecting steady growth this year with the strength
coming from exports and capital spending,'' said Richard Peach,
senior economist for the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   The GNP grew at a robust annual rate of 3.6 percent from January
through March, and Peach said he expected the current April-June
quarter would show similarly strong growth of around 3 percent. He
said this rate was likely to hold for the rest of the year.
   But Lawrence Chimerine, president of the WEFA Group, an economic
consulting firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said he was expecting some
slowing of economic activity as the year progresses, in part
because of the fact that farm production will be curtailed by the
severe drought in the Midwest.
   ``We have a mixed economy where some parts are doing well and
others are slowing. That is one reason we have seen the leading
index flatten out in recent months,'' Chimerine said.
   In May, five of nine available indicators registered declines.
The biggest factor holding the index back was a 2.5 percent drop in
the value of the Standard & Poor 500-stock compilation. Without the
drop in stock prices, the index would have registered a 0.1 percent
increase for the month.
   The four other business barometers which registered weakness
were a drop in plant and equipment orders, a rise in initial
unemployment claims, a decline in the average workweek and a fall
in building permits.
   Analysts said the small labor market weakness only represented a
pause following a period of exceptional strength and should not be
cause for alarm.
   Four of the nine indicators made positive contributions to the
index. The biggest positive force was a slowdown in business
deliveries from suppliers. This is seen as a sign of rising demand
and is thus viewed as a good sign for future economic activity.
   Other positive forces were a rise in manufacturers' orders for
consumer goods, a rise in raw materials prices, also viewed as a
positive for the index, and in increase in the money supply.
   The various changes left the index at 192.6 percent of its 1967
base of 100.
</TEXT>
