<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Westinghouse     06-29 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westinghouse,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Announce Job Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. on Wednesday said
it would cut 380 jobs from its energy systems business, which now
employs about 7,000 people, because of stiffening worldwide
competition.
   All but 100 of the jobs to be cut are in the Pittsburgh area,
where 4,000 of the 7,000 energy systems jobs are located. Most of
the cuts will be made by year's end.
   ``Worldwide competition is the major force affecting our
businesses,'' said Richard J. Slember, vice president and general
manager of the segment. ``The business has changed from supplying
large commercial nuclear plants to supplying smaller fossil-fueled
plants, waste-to-energy plants, and engineering and field
services.''
   Slember said a growing number of small competitors with lower
overhead costs are ``making it necessary for us to streamline our
organization to compete successfully and grow in these markets.''
</TEXT>
