<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HomeSales Bjt   06-29 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales, Bjt,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Sales Post First Decline in Four Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes edged down 0.3 percent in
May, the first decline in four months, the government reported
Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said new single-family homes were sold
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 658,000 units last month,
following an increase of 1.1 percent in April.
   The decline was the first since a 1.2 percent fall in January,
but analysts said they were relieved that the setback wasn't worse,
especially in light of a report last week that housing starts
plummeted 12.2 percent in May.
   That drop had raised fears that builders were sharply cutting
back on construction plans in light of worse-than-expected sales
activity.
   Analysts said last month's small dip in sales should reassure
builders that the housing industry is not facing a disastrous year,
although activity will be lower than in 1987.
   ``This lessens the concerns raised by the big drop in housing
starts. It tells us that people are still buying homes so there is
reason to believe that builders will pick up the pace in June,''
said Mark Obrinsky, senior economist at the U.S. League of Savings
Instituions.
   For the first five months of the year, home sales have been
running 7.8 percent below the pace of the same period in 1987.
Analysts blamed higher interest rates for much of the slowdown.
   For all of 1988, Obrinsky predicted sales would total 650,000
units, down about 5 percent from the 1987 level.
   ``This forecast is achievable assuming we don't have a sharp
runup in mortgage rates,'' he said.
   Mortgage rates, which dipped into the single-digit range briefly
in February and March, have been rising in recent months and now
stand at 10.4 percent for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages.
   David Seiders, chief economist for the National Association of
Home Builders, predicted that rates would hit 11 percent or higher
by the end of the year, pushed upward by tighter credit conditions
imposed by the Federal Reserve in an effort to fight inflationary
pressures.
   Seiders said he believed sales hit their peak in the just-ending
April-June quarter and will be headed lower for the rest of the
year.
   The median price of a new home edged down 0.9 percent to
$110,000 in May compared with April. The median price is the point
where half the homes sold for less and half sold for more. The
average sales price during the month rose 0.2 percent to $135,900.
   The small sales decline was led by a 7.3 percent drop in sales
in the Northeast, where new homes were purchased at an annual rate
of 101,000 units last month.
   Sales fell 0.7 percent in the South to an annual rate of 271,000
units. Sales were up 6.4 percent in the Midwest to a rate of
100,000 units, while sales in the West edged up 0.5 percent to
185,000 units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
