<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CBSRadio     06-29 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Radio,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hosking To Retire as Head of CBS Radio, Widmann Named as
Replacement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the CBS Radio division, Robert
L. Hosking, has decided to take CBS's early retirement offer and
will leave the company at the end of July, the company announced
Wednesday.
   Hosking will be suceeded by Nancy C. Widmann, who has been with
CBS Radio for 16 years and will be the first woman to head the
division. Her appointment is effective Aug. 1.
   Hosking, 56, joined CBS as a financial management trainee in
1958. He became vice president and general manager at WCBS-TV in
New York in 1970 and was appointed to the same post at WCAU-TV in
Philadelphia three years later.
   He became vice president of affilate relations for the CBS
Television network in 1978, and two years later joined CBS Radio as
executive vice president. He became president of the radio division
in 1981.
   Hosking is taking early retirement under a special incentive
plan that CBS announced in March. Employees age 55 or over and with
at least 10 years of experience were offered significantly improved
pension benefits provided they notified the company by July 1 of
their intention to accept the proposal.
   CBS said about 800 employees were eligible. A CBS spokeswoman,
Alice Henderson, said she had no information on how many people had
signed up. When a similar early retirement plan was offered in the
fall of 1985, the company said about 32 percent of the eligible
employees signed up.
   Hosking said he is leaving CBS with good feelings for the
company.
   ``It was a matter of did I want to continue to be in
broadcasting for another 10 years or try something else,'' he said
in an interview.
   He said he and his wife ``decided to both leave our jobs, spend
a lot of time together and go teach.'' His wife is a lawyer.
   Ms. Widmann, 44, began with CBS as an account executive for CBS
radio advertising sales in 1972 and was named its New York sales
manager four years later.
   She has been vice president for the CBS-owned radio stations
since 1987.
   The CBS Radio division owns and operates 18 radio stations, two
radio networks with a combined total of 600 affiliates, a
syndicated programming service with an additional 250 affiliates
and a national sales organization.
</TEXT>
