<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-29 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly higher against
foreign currencies in U.S. trading Wednesday despite a late selloff
incited by rumors of aggressive central bank intervention, currency
brokers said.
   Gold prices eased further in New York after falling sharply in
Europe. At of 4 p.m. EDT, Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$435.30 a troy ounce, down from $437.20 at the same time Tuesday.
   Money traders have attributed the dollar's persistent rise in
value over the past several days to an increasing perception that
the major industrialized democracies are willing to tolerate a more
expensive U.S. currency.
   But the dollar's growing attractiveness in foreign exchange
markets was dampened somewhat Wednesday after Japan's central bank
governor Satoshi Sumita said Tuesday in Tokyo that he was ready to
stem the rise if necessary.
   Rumors also spread that other central banks sold dollars late
Wednesday, concerned that the U.S. currency quickly was becoming
overvalued. The rumors sent some money traders scurrying to sell
dollars.
   ``Today was kind of a mixed day,'' said Arthur Liming, money
market analyst at LNS Financial Group Inc. in Chicago. ``Most
people kind of took a chance to sit back and look at what's been
transpiring. They're trying to decide whether the central banks are
trying to stem rise of dollar or make sure the rise doesn't get out
of hand.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar broke the 133-yen level for the first time
in nearly seven months before retreating to 132.40 yen, up 1.45 yen
from Tuesday. In London, it was quoted later at 133.70 yen. Later
in New York the dollar closed at 132.93 yen, up from its 132.74-yen
close on Tuesday.
   The British pound fell sharply in London to $1.7060 from $1.7200
late Tuesday but recovered partly in the United States. The pound
fetched $1.7132 in late New York trading, up from $1.7085 late
Tuesday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.8225 West German marks, up from
1.8220; 1.5118 Swiss francs, up from 1.5080; 1.2147 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2097; 6.1375 French francs, up from 6.1340; and
1,351.00 Italian lire, down from 1,352.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's rates,
included: 1.8290 West German marks, up from 1.8070; 1.5155 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4960; 6.1635 French francs, up from 6.0885;
2.0545 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0210; 1,350.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,337.00; and 1.2173 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2105.
   Dealers said the dollar's resilient strength was the main reason
for the slide in gold prices.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled down $2.30 a troy ounce to $435.70.
   Earlier in London, gold tumbled nearly $10 an ounce to $433.30,
against $443.20 late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold dropped to $433.50 an
ounce $443.20 late Tuesday. In Hong Kong, gold fell $6.26 to close
at $440.04.
   Silver bullion prices fell in tandem with gold. Silver traded at
$6.66 a troy ounce in London, down from $6.92 Tuesday. On New
York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell 13.8 cents
an ounce to $6.622.
</TEXT>
