<2ND_LINE>AM-Trinova Purchase,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trinova To Acquire West German Plastics Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAUMEE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sterling Engineered Products, a subsidiary
of Trinova Corp., will purchase a West German plastics company,
Trinova's president and chief executive officer said Wednesday.
   Darryl Allen said Sterling's acquisition of Gotthilf Roth GmbH &
Co. KG, based in Frankfurt, is another step in making Sterling a
global supplier of plastic automotive components.
   Trinova did not disclose a purchase price.
   Roth is a leading plastic components supplier to the West German
automotive market. Allen said Roth manufactures parts for BMW and
Volkswagen-Audi as well as Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.
   ``West Germany is the number three vehicle-producing company in
the world and produces 34 percent of the vehicles in Europe,''
Allen said.
   ``With operations in the United States, a new major automotive
joint venture with Japan and a growing operation in the United
Kingdom...Sterling is well-positioned to serve the major automotive
markets of the world,'' he said.
   Roth manufactures products such as plastic wheel covers, sun
visors, glove boxes, body side moldings and metal window frames. It
operates two plants in West Germany and employs 1,100 people.
   For the year ending Dec. 31, 1987, Roth recorded sales of about
$70 million dollars.
   During the same period, Sterling reported sales of $358 million.
   Trinova, which makes power and motion control systems for the
aerospace, defense, building and construction markets, reported
1987 sales of $1.68 billion.
</TEXT>
