<2ND_LINE>AM-Macmillan-Bass, 1st Ld-Writethru,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Decision on Macmillan Injunction Request</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with court hearing, final stock
price; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge delayed decision Wednesday on
the Robert M. Bass Group's request for a preliminary injunction to
block Macmillan Inc.'s planned restructuring.
   Jack B. Jacobs, the Delaware Chancery Court judge who earlier
this month temporarily blocked Macmillan from proceeding with the
restructuring, heard four hours of arguments from both sides. A
Bass spokeswoman said the judge said he would rule as promptly as
possible.
   The Bass group has made an unsolicitied $1.9 billion takeover
bid for the publishing giant.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Macmillan finished unchanged at
$75.12{.
   Separately on Tuesday, Macmillan disclosed that its chairman,
Edward P. Evans, had told Security Pacific National Bank in a
letter that it felt the bank had improperly agreed to provide
financing for both the Macmillan restructuring and the Bass bid.
   Macmillan said Security Pacific had been given confidential
materials about Macmillan in mid-June so it could consider the
possibility of providing financing for Macmillan's restructuring
plan. On June 17, Security Pacific said it would commit $200
million for Macmillan's restructuring.
   But Evans said Macmillan was ``surprised and outraged'' when the
Bass group announced its own financing plans for its tender offer
on June 23 that Security Pacific was listed as committing $500
million in financing for the Bass group's offer.
   In the letter, Evans said Macmillan was offering Security
Pacific ``an opportunity to correct breaches of confidentiality
undertakings and fiduciary duty'' before pursuing a legal remedy.
   In Los Angeles, Richard Warner, an executive vice president for
Security Pacific, said Wednesday he had no comment on Macmillan's
request that the bank withdraw its commitment to the Bass group,
but said ``the charge of breach of confidentiality is absolutely
untrue.''
   ``The two pieces of business that came in came in through two
different offices, and our policy of client confidentiality was
maintained throughout the process,'' Warner said.
   He said Security Pacific's New York office made the financing
commitment to Macmillan while the Chicago office handled the
commitment to the Bass group.
   The Bass group proposed paying $64 a share for Macmillan in May.
   Macmillan responded with a restructuring valued at $64.15 a
share that included splitting the company into separate publishing
and information services companies and paying shareholders a cash
dividend of $52.35.
   The Bass group subsequently said it would offer $73 a share in
cash or, alternatively, a restructuring plan comparable to the
Macmillan package but including a dividend of $58 a share.
   Earlier this week, Macmillan said a special committee of its
board had again considered and rejected the Bass offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
