<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid 1stLd-Writethru   06-29 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of New York Threatens To Withdraw Irving Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf pvs with 2 grafs to UPDATE with contents of
Irving letter; uppicks 4th graf pvs: Bank of ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. threatened Wednesday to
abandon its hostile $1.4 billion bid for Irving Bank Corp. unless
it receives a favorable court ruling within two days or reaches an
amicable settlement with Irving.
   Bank of New York said in a statement that it submitted a written
request to the New York State Supreme Court for a ruling by Friday
on the validity of Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill'' and
numerous other pending legal issues.
   Irving, in its own letter to State Supreme Court Justice Herman
Cahn, said ``it is not up to BNY to attempt to dictate deadlines
and ultimatums either to this court or the Irving board.''
   The letter noted that top Irving executives will be unavailable
until the middle of next week. ``We would anticipate the scheduling
of a meeting of the Irving board on Tuesday or Wednesday to
consider BNY's revised proposal,'' the letter said.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady denied the bank was
issuing an ultimatum. ``It's just pointing out the realities of the
situation that if we don't get an answer, we're running out of
time.''
   Bank of New York's deadline for conditional merger approval from
the Federal Reserve Board expires on July 9, and Brady said the
bank needs time to prepare a request for an extension. ``We believe
we can't go to the Fed unless we can point to some progress,'' he
said.
   Bank of New York also is seeking to overturn the results of a
proxy battle in which shareholders chose Irving's incumbent board
over Bank of New York's nominees.
   Bank of New York presently is offering 1.575 shares of its stock
and $15 in cash for each outstanding Irving share, or a total of
about $1.1 billion.
   The company said it would reinstate a June 15 offer that would
give Irving sharesholders 1.675 Bank of New York shares, $15 in
cash and $5 in special dividends if the state Supreme Court removes
the takeover obstacles.
   That offer, for all of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding,
is valued at about $76 a share, or $1.4 billion, which is about 25
percent higher than the existing hostile $1.1 billion tender offer.
   Bank of New York also would revive the offer if requested to do
so by Irving's board ``as the basis for an amicable resolution of
all outstanding matters.''
   The offer also would be revived if Irving's board favors a
merger with Banca Commerciale SpA, Italy's second largest bank,
which is offering $80 a share for 51 percent of Irving, or about
$760 million. The proposal is part of a complex defensive
restructuring plan approved by Irving's board. The plan includes,
among other things, sale of Irving assets, cost-cutting measures
and a special cash dividend.
   Separately, a Florida bank regulator said Banca Commerciale
might have to seek separate approval from the state to acquire
Irving's Florida subsidiary.
</TEXT>
