<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RadioShuffle     06-29 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radio Shuffle,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$156 Million Ownership Shuffle of Stations in N.Y., L.A.,
Elsewhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ownership of nine big-city radio stations is
being shuffled in a complex transaction announced Wednesday.
   The deal was designed to accommodate New York investor Robert
F.X. Sillerman's pending purchase of Metropolitan Broadcasting and
involves four companies.
   Among the transaction's larger provisions is the sale of KJOI-FM
in Los Angeles for $75 million.
   The deal was set in motion by Sillerman's agreement in April to
buy Metropolitan Broadcasting for $300 million.
   Metropolitan owns KTWV-FM in Los Angeles, while another company
in which Sillerman owns a major stake, Legacy Broadcasting, also
has a Los Angeles station, KJOI-FM. Federal Communications
Commission regulations against concentration of ownership required
that at least one be sold.
   Under the agreement:
   _Legacy, a privately held Los Angeles company in which Sillerman
holds 49 percent of the voting stock, will acquire 49 percent of
Metropolitan. Legacy, under a consulting agreement, will take over
management of Metropolitan's remaining stations, which are WNEW-AM
and FM in New York, KTWV-FM in Los Angeles and WMMR-FM in
Philadelphia.
   Legacy, in which Carl Hirsch owns 51 percent, will continue to
operate its own stations _ KDWB-AM and FM in Minneapolis-St. Paul,
KILT-AM and FM in Houston, WCXR-FM and WCPT-AM in Washington, D.C.,
and WLLZ-FM in Detroit.
   _Carl C. Brazell Jr., the current president of Metropolitan,
will leave to form his own company, Command Communications, which
will pay Legacy $95 million for KJOI-FM in Los Angeles and sister
station KSYY-FM and KHOW-AM in Denver. Brazell also will buy
Metropolitan's KRLD-AM and the Texas State Networks in Dallas for
$50 million.
   _Westwood One, which is a publicly owned radio company based in
Culver City, Calif., signed a letter of intent to buy 50 percent of
Metropolitan's WNEW-AM in New York for $11 million and to operate
the station. The station, which has experimented unsuccessfully
with daytime talk shows, already uses much Westwood One programming.
   Sillerman, who has extensive investments in communications, said
in a telephone interview that the diverse formats of the stations
would be unchanged, except for WNEW-AM.
   Sillerman said he would have a ``substantial'' interest in
Brazell's Command Communications as a lender and investor, but
wouldn't have a voice in management.
</TEXT>
