<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-KiawahIslandSale     06-29 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kiawah Island Sale,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resort Island Bought For $105 Million From Kuwaiti Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by Charleston businessman
Charles Way has purchased the Kiawah Island resort for $105
million, in one of the largest real estate transactions in South
Carolina history.
   The 10,000-acre island southwest of Charleston was purchased
Wednesday from the Kiawah Island Co., which is owned by Kuwaiti
business interests.
   Way, who signed a contract for the purchase in March, said at a
news conference that he closed the deal Wednesday.
   Vicki Jinnette of the South Carolina Tax Commission said the
sale was among the largest in state history, but there was no way
to immediately confirm whether it was the single largest.
   Purchasers include Way and members of the Way, Long and Darby
families of Charleston. Other principals include Frank Brumley and
Pat McKinney of Charleston, Henry Holliday III of Atlanta and an
institutional investment group including the investment firm Mabon,
Nugent & Co. and Imperial Corp. of America of San Diego.
   Way said the purchase includes three championship golf courses,
the 150-room Kiawah Island Inn, three swimming pools and two tennis
centers and commercial facilities on the island. It also includes
undeveloped land on a barrier island.
   The sale was financed with a $118.5 million bank loan. The
additional $13.5 million over the purchase price will be used to
make improvements at the island, Way said.
   In addition, he said, the new owners will work to bring in a
commercial hotel to the island.
   Kuwait Investment Co., the parent of Kiawah Island Co., bought
the island in 1974 for $17.4 million from C.C. Royal of Aiken, who
had purchased it in 1952 for lumbering for about $125,000.
   Royal purchased the island from the Vanderhorst family of
Charleston, which had held the island for a century before then.
</TEXT>
