<FILEID>AP-NR-06-29-88 2309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DefenseProbe 2ndLd-Writethru f0269 06-29 1064</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0269,1098</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Purchasing Chief Backs Away from Defense of Memo</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 5 grafs after 6th graf pvs bgng, `You drive,' to
UPDATE with other developments Wednesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's top purchasing official, faced
with hostile questions from congressmen Wednesday, backed away from
a proposal he made just last month to give Defense Department
officials the power to prevent searches of contractors' facilities
by fraud investigators.
   Under blistering questioning, Robert B. Costello, undersecretary
of defense for acquisition policy, said he had changed his mind and
would not now write the same memo he had written May 5 outlining
the plan.
   Costello asserted, however, that current Reagan administration
policies work in uncovering misdeeds in military equipment
procurement and that there is less corruption in the process now
than before.
   ``Our acquisition system works,'' he told the packed hearing
room at the first congressional hearing into defense procurement
problems since the disclosure that investigators have issued 275
subpoenas, conducted more than 40 searches and listened in on more
than 4,000 wiretapped conversations in the probe of fraud and
bribery in sales to the Pentagon.
   Among the Congress members clearly frustrated by Costello's
defense of present policies was Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.
   ``You drive me crazy. ... You're in an absolutely protective
mode,'' she told him at the House Armed Services Committee hearing.
   In other developments Wednesday:
   _Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney who is heading the
investigation, said in court papers filed in Brooklyn, N.Y., that
he has learned of several instances of documents being destroyed by
people under investigation in the probe.
   Neither Hudson nor Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica, who
wrote an attached affidavit, provided details on who destroyed
documents or how they might be related to the investigation.
   _Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., asked the FBI to give Congress its
file on Melvyn Paisley, a former Pentagon procurement official
under investigation in connection with alleged fraud and bribery in
defense purchasing.
   The current chairman and ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, Sens. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and John Warner, R-Va.,
said in a statement Wednesday night that the committee has
researched the records it currently holds on Paisley's nomination.
The only records it has, the senators said, are financial
disclosure forms and associated memoranda and the standard letter
from him required by the committee concerning his financial
situation.
   Although Costello defended his plan for Pentagon decision-making
on searches of contractors' facilities during most of the
questioning, he backed down as the hearing wore on into the
afternoon.
   Rep. J. Roy Rowland, D-Ga., told Costello his proposal ``is not
appropriate. ... It doesn't look good; it doesn't smell good.''
   Costello declined to agree the memo was inappropriate, but added
that he wouldn't write it now.
   ``I can change my mind,'' he explained to Rowland. He said that
he and June Gibbs Brown, the Defense Department's inspector
general, ``had a discussion and I listened to her and I said,
`June, you're right.'''
   He noted that Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci rejected the
proposal after Brown complained.
   ``In the worst case, such a policy could be interpreted as
placing constraints on or interfering with the criminal
investigative process,'' Brown wrote in her own memo. ``Such an
approval would be unprecedented within federal law enforcement and
unwise as a matter of law enforcement and procurement policy.''
   Costello's May 5 memo suggested that he and other top Pentagon
officials be given power to veto searches of the private
contractors who supply military equipment. The Associated Press
obtained a copy of the memo Tuesday.
   He said he wrote the memo after a contractor's office in St.
Louis was searched. He explained he didn't object to the search,
but that it should not have been conducted without a prior review
at the upper levels of the Pentagon.
   ``The system at that point had been short-circuited...,''
Costello said. ``If the system had been allowed to function as it
was constructed to function ... the access to the information could
have been achieved without resort to the use of force.''
   Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., told Costello that ``the
memo itself sends the wrong signal'' to defense contractors. ``The
whole tenor of that (the memo) is awfully sympathetic to defense
contractors,'' he said.
   Carlucci, talking to reporters during a visit to the State
Department, said he disagreed with Aspin. ``I don't think this
sends any signal at all that we are letting up on our monitoring
activities or on inspection activities,'' he said.
   In Costello's defense of Reagan administration policies, he said
military procurement changes had reduced fraud and waste in the
government's largest department.
   ``So, if we have accomplished so much, why have there been so
many cases of procurement fraud?'' Costello asked rhetorically.
``Is there more corruption now?''
   ``We don't think so. Due to our improvements we can conduct
viable enforcement to apprehend, prosecute and jail procurement
fraud perpetrators,'' he said.
   At one point, Aspin interrupted to ask, ``How come we're seeing
this now?'' in reference to the widespread investigation.
   ``In one word _ greed,'' Costello replied.
   An another occasion, Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, said, ``Every
time we suggest legislation, you're opposed.''
   Later, Rep. Andy Ireland, R-Fla., told Costello, ``I simply
don't agree we have all the laws and regulations we need.''
   Another Defense Department witness, General Counsel Kathleen
Buck, agreed with Costello that no new laws may be needed. ``This
is something that's pretty old-fashioned after all. It's bribery,''
she said.
   When Mrs. Schroeder said the current investigation may show
``we've been overcharged'' for some weapons, Costello answered that
``we may have been undercharged'' and explained that the
investigation is still incomplete.
   At that point, Mrs. Schroeder said, ``You drive me crazy.''
   She told Costello, ``I want you to be a pit bull,'' and he
answered by saying, ``I do have a Great Dane.''
   Mrs. Schroeder shot back, ``I don't want you to have a Great
Dane. I want you to be one.''
   When Aspin noted that 85 contracts worth billions of dollars may
be involved in the current investigation, Buck answered that ``we
will revisit every single contract involved here ... on a
case-by-case basis.''
   If contracts are found to be tainted, she and Costello said, the
Pentagon has several options, including rebidding or reletting the
contracts, or barring contractors from bidding on future contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
