<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0303,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher At Midmorning; Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Nikkei morning closing,
details, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher early Thursday against
the Japanese yen, although it declined from its opening highs,
while stock prices rose in active trading in Tokyo.
   The dollar opened at 132.90 yen, up from Wednesday's close of
132.40 yen, but retreated to the 132.45-132.55 yen level by
midmorning.
   The dollar fell because market participants were closing their
positions prior to the long Fourth of July holiday weekend in the
United States, said a dealer with a major securities firm, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Financial markets will be closed Monday in the United States.
   ``Those who were buying the currency at the 133-yen level at the
start of trading moved down to 132 yen because of the upcoming
holiday,'' he said.
   The dealer also attributed the dollar's decline to bullish
movement overnight in New York, where the dollar briefly shattered
the 134-yen level.
   ``The market today (Thursday) is taking a break,'' the dealer
said.
   But he added that he expected the dollar to bounce back against
the yen as soon as the U.S. holiday weekend was over, ``so long as
the Bank of Japan does not intervene in the market.''
   Lack of intervention by Japan's central bank since last week has
fueled the dollar's surge on the Tokyo foreign exchange market.
During a regular press conference earlier this week, Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa ruled out the possibility of intervention
and dismissed the current market gyrations as ordinary fluctuations.
   However, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a news
conference Wednesday the nation's central bank was ready to take
``appropriate'' action to brake the dollar's rise, depending on how
the U.S. currency moves in the future.
   The dollar has risen 3.45 yen in the past two trading days in
Tokyo.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, up 209.24 points on Wednesday, rose another 123.03
points to 27,730.36 by the end of the morning trading session.
   The main market barometer's climb was led mainly by heavy
electricals, shipping issues and shipbuilders. Traders said
automakers also managed to move higher during the morning dealings.
</TEXT>
